Unified Strong's Dictionaries of Hebrew and Greek in XML (alpha release)

Hebrew

  1. 'ab a primitive word; father, in a literal and immediate, or figurative and remote application): chief, (fore-)father(-less), X patrimony, principal. Compare names in "Abi-".
  2. 'ab (Aramaic) corresponding to 'ab: father.
  3. 'eb from the same as 'abiyb; a green plant: greenness, fruit.
  4. 'eb (Aramaic) corresponding to 'eb: fruit.
  5. 'Abagtha' of foreign origin; Abagtha, a eunuch of Xerxes: Abagtha.
  6. 'abad a primitive root; properly, to wander away, i.e. lose oneself; by implication to perish (causative, destroy): break, destroy(- uction), + not escape, fail, lose, (cause to, make) perish, spend, X and surely, take, be undone, X utterly, be void of, have no way to flee.
  7. 'abad (Aramaic) corresponding to 'abad: destroy, perish.
  8. 'obed active of participle of 'abad; (concrete) wretched or (abstract) destructin: perish.
  9. 'abedah from 'abad; concrete, something lost; abstract, destruction, i.e. Hades: lost. Compare 'abaddoh.
  10. 'abaddoh the same as 'abedah, miswritten for 'abaddown; a perishing: destruction.
  11. 'abaddown intensive from 'abad; abstract, a perishing; concrete, Hades: destruction.
  12. 'abdan from 'abad; a perishing: destruction.
  13. 'obdan from 'abad; a perishing: destruction.
  14. 'abah a primitive root; to breathe after, i.e. (figuratively) to be acquiescent: consent, rest content will, be willing.
  15. 'abeh from 'abah; longing: desire.
  16. 'ebeh from 'abah (in the sense of bending toward); the papyrus: swift.
  17. 'abowy from 'abah (in the sense of desiring); want: sorrow.
  18. 'ebuwc from 'abac; a manger or stall: crib.
  19. 'ibchah from an unused root (apparently meaning to turn); brandishing of a sword: point.
  20. 'abattiyach of uncertain derivation; a melon (only plural): melon.
  21. 'Abiy from 'ab; fatherly; Abi, Hezekiah's mother: Abi.
  22. 'Abiy'el from 'ab and 'el; father (i.e. possessor) of God; Abiel, the name of two Israelites: Abiel.
  23. 'Abiy'acaph from 'ab and 'acaph; father of gathering (i.e. gatherer); Abiasaph, an Israelite: Abiasaph.
  24. 'abiyb from an unused root (meaning to be tender); green, i.e. a young ear of grain; hence, the name of the month Abib or Nisan: Abib, ear, green ears of corn (not maize).
  25. 'Abiy Gib`own from 'ab and Gib`own; father (i.e. founder) of Gibon; Abi-Gibon, perhaps an Israelite: father of Gibeon.
  26. 'Abiygayil or shorter Abiygal; from 'ab and giyl; father (i.e. source) of joy; Abigail or Abigal, the name of two Israelitesses: Abigal.
  27. 'Abiydan from 'ab and diyn; father of judgment (i.e. judge); Abidan, an Israelite: Abidan.
  28. 'Abiyda` from 'ab and yada`; father of knowledge (i.e. knowing); Abida, a son of Abraham by Keturah: Abida, Abidah.
  29. 'Abiyah or prolonged Abiyahuw; from 'ab and Yahh; father (i.e. worshipper) of Jah; Abijah, the name of several Israelite men and two Israelitesses: Abiah, Abijah.
  30. 'Abiyhuw' from 'ab and huw'; father (i.e. worshipper) of Him (i.e. God); Abihu, a son of Aaron: Abihu.
  31. 'Abiyhuwd from 'ab and howd; father (i.e. possessor) of renown; Abihud, the name of two Israelites: Abihud.
  32. 'Abiyhayil or (more correctly) Abiychayil; from 1 and chayil; father (i.e. possessor) of might; Abihail or Abichail, the name of three Israelites and two Israelitesses: Abihail.
  33. 'Abiy ha-`Ezriy from 'Abiy`ezer with the article inserted; father of the Ezrite; an Abiezrite or descendant of Abiezer; -- Abiezrite.
  34. 'ebyown from 'abah, in the sense of want (especially in feeling); destitute: beggar, needy, poor (man).
  35. 'abiyownah from 'abah; provocative of desire; the caper berry (from its stimulative taste): desire.
  36. 'Abiytuwb from 'ab and tuwb; father of goodness (i.e. good); Abitub, an Israelite: Abitub.
  37. 'Abiytal from 'ab and tal; father of dew (i.e. fresh); Abital, a wife of King David: Abital.
  38. 'Abiyam from 'ab and yam; father of (the) sea (i.e. seaman); Abijam (or Abijah), a king of Judah: Abijam.
  39. 'Abiyma'el from 'ab and an elsewhere unused (probably foreign) word; father of Mael (apparently some Arab tribe); Abimael, a son of Joktan: Abimael.
  40. 'Abiymelek from 'ab and melek; father of (the) king; Abimelek, the name of two Philistine kings and of two Israelites: Abimelech.
  41. 'Abiynadab from 'ab and nadab; father of generosity (i.e. liberal); Abinadab, the name of four Israelites: Abinadab.
  42. 'Abiyno`am from 'ab and no`am; father of pleasantness (i.e. gracious); Abinoam, an Israelite: Abinoam.
  43. 'Ebyacaph contracted from 'Abiy'acaph; Ebjasaph, an Israelite: Ebiasaph.
  44. 'Abiy`ezer from 'ab and `Ezer; father of help (i.e. helpful); Abiezer, the name of two Israelites: Abiezer.
  45. 'Abiy-`albown from 'ab and and an unused root of uncertain. derivation; probably, father of strength (i.e. valiant); Abialbon, an Israelite: Abialbon.
  46. 'abiyr from 'abar; mighty (spoken of God): mighty (one).
  47. 'abbiyr for 'abiyr; --angel, bull, chiefest, mighty (one), stout(-hearted), strong (one), valiant.
  48. 'Abiyram from 'ab and ruwm; father of height (i.e. lofty); Abiram, the name of two Israelites: Abiram.
  49. 'Abiyshag from 'ab and shagah; father of error (i.e. blundering); Abishag, a concubine of David: Abishag.
  50. 'Abiyshuwae from 'ab and showa`; father of plenty (i.e. prosperous); Abishua, the name of two Israelites: Abishua.
  51. 'Abiyshuwr from 'ab and shuwr; father of (the) wall (i.e. perhaps mason); Abishur, an Israelite: Abishur.
  52. 'Abiyshay or (shorter) Abshay; from 'ab and shay; father of a gift (i.e. probably generous); Abishai, an Israelite: Abishai.
  53. 'Abiyshalowm or (shortened) Abshalowm; from 'ab and shalowm; father of peace (i.e. friendly); Abshalom, a son of David; also (the fuller form) a later Israelite: Abishalom, Absalom.
  54. 'Ebyathar contracted from 'ab and yathar; father of abundance (i.e. liberal); Ebjathar, an Israelite: Abiathar.
  55. 'abak a primitive root; probably to coil upward: mount up.
  56. 'abal a primitive root; to bewail: lament, mourn.
  57. 'abel from 'abal; lamenting: mourn(-er, -ing).
  58. 'abel from an unused root (meaning to be grassy); a meadow: plain. Compare also the proper names beginning with Abel-.
  59. 'Abel from 'abel; a meadow; Abel, the name of two places in Palestine.: Abel.
  60. 'ebel from 'abal; lamentation: mourning.
  61. 'abal apparently from 'abal through the idea of negation; nay, i.e. truly or yet: but, indeed, nevertheless, verily.
  62. 'Abel Beyth-Ma`akah from 'abel and bayith and Ma`akah; meadow of Beth-Maakah; Abel of Beth-maakah, a place in Palestine:--Abel-beth-maachah, Abel of Beth-maachah,
  63. 'Abel hash-Shittiym from 'abel and the plural of shittah, with the article inserted; meadow of the acacias; Abel hash- Shittim, a place in Palestine: Abel-shittim.
  64. 'Abel Kramiym from 'abel and the plural of kerem; meadow of vineyards; Abel-Keramim, a place in Palestine: plain of the vineyards.
  65. 'Abel Mchowlah from 'abel and mchowlah; meadow of dancing; Abel-Mecholah, a place in Palestine: Abel-meholah.
  66. 'Abel Mayim from 'abel and mayim; meadow of water; Abel-Majim, a place in Palestine: Abel-maim.
  67. 'Abel Mitsrayim from 'abel and Mitsrayim; meadow of Egypt; Abel-Mitsrajim, a place in Palestine: Abel-mizraim.
  68. 'eben from the root of banah through the meaning to build; a stone: + carbuncle, + mason, + plummet, (chalk-, hail-, head-, sling-)stone(-ny), (divers) weight(-s).
  69. 'eben (Aramaic) corresponding to 'eben: stone.
  70. 'oben from the same as 'eben; a pair of stones (only dual); a potter's wheel or a midwife's stool (consisting alike of two horizontal disks with a support between): wheel, stool.
  71. 'Abanah perhaps feminine of 'eben; stony; Abanah, a river near Damascus: Abana. Compare 'Amanah.
  72. 'Eben ha-`ezer from 'eben and `ezer with the article inserted; stone of the help; Eben-ha-Ezer, a place in Palestine: Ebenezer.
  73. 'abnet of uncertain derivation; a belt: girdle.
  74. 'Abner or (fully) Abiyner; from 'ab and niyr; father of light (i.e. enlightening); Abner, an Israelite: Abner.
  75. 'abac a primitive root; to fodder: fatted, stalled.
  76. 'aba`bu`ah (by reduplication) from an unused root (meaning to belch forth); an inflammatory pustule (as eruption): blains.
  77. 'Ebets from an unused root probably meaning to gleam; conspicuous; Ebets, a place in Palestine: Abez.
  78. 'Ibtsan from the same as 'aba`bu`ah; splendid; Ibtsan, an Israelite: Ibzan.
  79. 'abaq a primitive root, probably to float away (as vapor), but used only as denominative from 'abaq; to bedust, i.e. grapple: wrestle.
  80. 'abaq from root of 'abaq; light particles (as volatile): (small) dust, powder.
  81. 'abaqah feminine of 'abaq: powder.
  82. 'abar a primitive root; to soar: fly.
  83. 'eber from 'abar; a pinion: (long-)wing(-ed).
  84. 'ebrah feminine of 'eber: feather, wing.
  85. 'Abraham contracted from 'ab and an unused root (probably meaning to be populous); father of a multitude; Abraham, the later name of Abram: Abraham.
  86. 'abrek probably an Egyptian word meaning kneel: bow the knee.
  87. 'Abram contracted from 'Abiyram; high father; Abram, the original name of Abraham: Abram.
  88. 'oboth plural of 'owb; water-skins; Oboth, a place in the Desert: Oboth.
  89. 'Age' of uncertain derivation (compare 'Agag); Age, an Israelite: Agee.
  90. 'Agag or Agag; of uncertain derivation (compare 'Age'); flame; Agag, a title of Amalekitish kings: Agag.
  91. 'Agagiy patrial or patronymic from 'Agag; an Agagite or descendent (subject) of Agag: Agagite.
  92. 'aguddah feminine passive participle of an unused root (meaning to bind); a band, bundle, knot, or arch: bunch, burden, troop.
  93. 'egowz prob of Persian origin; a nut: nut.
  94. 'Aguwr passive participle of 'agar; gathered (i.e. received among the sages); Agur, a fanciful name for Solomon: Agur.
  95. 'agowrah from the same as 'Aguwr; properly, something gathered, i.e. perhaps a grain or berry; used only of a small (silver) coin: piece (of) silver.
  96. 'egel from an unused root (meaning to flow down or together as drops); a reservoir: drop.
  97. 'Eglayim dual of 'egel.; a double pond; Eglajim, a place in Moab: Eglaim.
  98. 'agam from an unused root (meaning to collect as water); a marsh; hence a rush (as growing in swamps); hence a stockade of reeds: pond, pool, standing (water).
  99. 'agem probably from the same as 'agam (in the sense of stagnant water); figuratively, sad: pond.
  100. 'agmown from the same as 'agam; a marshy pool (others from a different root, a kettle); by implication a rush (as growing there); collectively a rope of rushes: bulrush, caldron, hook, rush.
  101. 'aggan probably from nagan; a bowl (as pounded out hollow): basin, cup, goblet.
  102. 'aggaph probably from nagaph (through the idea of impending); a cover or heap; i.e. (only plural) wings of an army, or crowds of troops: bands.
  103. 'agar a primitive root; to harvest: gather.
  104. 'iggra' (Aramaic) of Persian origin; an epistle (as carried by a state courier or postman): letter.
  105. 'agartal of uncertain derivation; a basin: charger.
  106. 'egroph from garaph (in the sense of grasping); the clenched hand: fist.
  107. 'iggereth feminine of 'iggra'; an epistle: letter.
  108. 'ed from the same as 'uwd (in the sense of enveloping); a fog: mist, vapor.
  109. 'adab a primitive root; to languish: grieve.
  110. 'Adb'el probably from 'adab (in the sense of chastisement) and 'el; disciplined of God; Adbeel, a son of Ishmael: Adbeel.
  111. 'Adad probably an orthographical variation for Chadad; Adad (or Hadad), an Edomite: Hadad.
  112. 'Iddow of uncertain derivation; Iddo, an Israelite: Iddo.
  113. 'adown or (shortened) adon; from an unused root (meaning to rule); sovereign, i.e. controller (human or divine): lord, master, owner. Compare also names beginning with "Adoni-".
  114. 'Addown probably intensive for 'adown; powerful; Addon, apparently an Israelite: Addon.
  115. 'Adowrayim dual from 'adar (in the sense of eminence); double mound; Adorajim, a place in Palestine: Adoraim.
  116. 'edayin (Aramaic) of uncertain derivation; then (of time): now, that time, then.
  117. 'addiyr from 'adar; wide or (generally) large; figuratively, powerful: excellent, famous, gallant, glorious, goodly, lordly, mighty(- ier one), noble, principal, worthy.
  118. 'Adalya' of Persian derivation; Adalja, a son of Haman: Adalia.
  119. 'adam to show blood (in the face), i.e. flush or turn rosy: be (dyed, made) red (ruddy).
  120. 'adam from 'adam; ruddy i.e. a human being (an individual or the species, mankind, etc.): X another, + hypocrite, + common sort, X low, man (mean, of low degree), person.
  121. 'Adam the same as 'adam; Adam the name of the first man, also of a place in Palestine: Adam.
  122. 'adom from 'adam; rosy: red, ruddy.
  123. 'Edom or (fully) Edowm; from 'adom; red (see Gen. 25:25); Edom, the elder twin-brother of Jacob; hence the region (Idumaea) occupied by him: Edom, Edomites, Idumea.
  124. 'odem from 'adam; redness, i.e. the ruby, garnet, or some other red gem: sardius.
  125. 'adamdam reduplicated from 'adam; reddish: (somewhat) reddish.
  126. 'Admah contracted for 'adamah; earthy; Admah, a place near the Dead Sea: Admah.
  127. 'adamah from 'adam; soil (from its general redness): country, earth, ground, husband(-man) (-ry), land.
  128. 'Adamah the same as 'adamah; Adamah, a place in Palestine: Adamah.
  129. 'Adamiy from 'adamah; earthy; Adami, a place in Palestine: Adami.
  130. 'Edomiy or (fully) Edowmiy; patronymic from 'Edom; an Edomite, or descendants from (or inhabitants of) Edom: Edomite. See 'Arowmiy.
  131. 'Adummiym plural of 'Adam; red spots; Adummim, a pass in Palestine: Adummim.
  132. 'admoniy or (fully) admowniy; from 'adam; reddish (of the hair or the complexion): red, ruddy.
  133. 'Admatha' probably of Persian derivation: Admatha, a Persian nobleman: Admatha.
  134. 'eden from the same as 'adown (in the sense of strength); a basis (of a building, a column, etc.): foundation, socket.
  135. 'Addan intensive from the same as 'eden; firm; Addan, an Israelite: Addan.
  136. 'Adonay am emphatic form of 'adown; the Lord (used as a proper name of God only): (my) Lord.
  137. 'Adoniy-Bezeq from 'adown and Bezeq; lord of Bezek; Adoni-Bezek; a Canaanitish king: Adoni-bezek.
  138. 'Adoniyah original (prolonged) Adoniyahuw; from 'adown and Yahh; lord (i.e. worshipper) of Jah; Adonijah, the name of three Israelites: Adonijah.
  139. 'Adoniy-Tsedeq from 'adown and tsedeq; lord of justice; Adoni-Tsedek, a Canaanitish king: Adonizedec.
  140. 'Adoniyqam from 'adown and quwm; lord of rising (i.e. high); Adonikam, the name of one or two Israelites: Adonikam.
  141. 'Adoniyram from 'adown and ruwm; lord of height; Adoniram, an Israelite: Adoniram.
  142. 'adar a primitive root; to expand, i.e. be great or (figuratively) magnificent: (become) glorious, honourable.
  143. 'Adar probably of foreign derivation; perhaps meaning fire; Adar, the 12th Hebrew month: Adar.
  144. 'Adar (Aramaic) corresponding to 'Adar: Adar.
  145. 'eder from 'adar; amplitude, i.e. (concrete) a mantle; also (figuratively) splendor: goodly, robe.
  146. 'Addar intensive from 'adar; ample; Addar, a place in Palestine; also an Israelite: Addar.
  147. 'iddar (Aramaic) intensive, from a root corresponding to 'adar; ample, i.e. a threshing-floor: threshingfloor.
  148. 'adargazer (Aramaic) from the same as 'iddar, and gzar; a chief diviner, or astrologer: judge.
  149. 'adrazda' (Aramaic) probably of Persian origin; quickly or carefully: diligently.
  150. 'adarkon of Persian origin; a daric or Persian coin: dram.
  151. 'Adoram contracted for 'Adoniyram; Adoram (or Adoniram), an Israelite: Adoram.
  152. 'Adrammelek from 'adar and melek; splendor of (the) king; Adrammelek, the name of an Assyrian idol, also of a son of Sennacherib: Adrammelech.
  153. 'edra` (Aramaic) an orthographical variation for dra`; an arm, i.e. (figuratively) power: force.
  154. 'edre`iy from the equivalent of 'edra`; mighty; Edrei, the name of two places in Palestine: Edrei.
  155. 'addereth feminine of 'addiyr; something ample (as a large vine, a wide dress); also the same as 'eder: garment, glory, goodly, mantle, robe.
  156. 'adash a primitive root; to tread out (grain): thresh.
  157. 'ahab or raheb; a primitive root; to have affection for (sexually or otherwise): (be-)love(-d, -ly, -r), like, friend.
  158. 'ahab from 'ahab; affection (in a good or a bad sense): love(-r).
  159. 'ohab from 'adash; meaning the same as 'ahab: love.
  160. 'ahabah feminine of 'ahab and meaning the same: love.
  161. 'Ohad from an unused root meaning to be united; unity; Ohad, an Israelite: Ohad.
  162. 'ahahh apparently a primitive word expressing pain exclamatorily; Oh!: ah, alas.
  163. 'Ahava' probably of foreign origin; Ahava, a river of Babylonia: Ahava.
  164. 'Ehuwd from the same as 'Ohad; united; Ehud, the name of two or three Israelites: Ehud.
  165. 'ehiy apparently an orthographical variation for 'ayeh; where: I will be (Hos. 13:10, 14) (which is often the rendering of the same Hebrew form from hayah).
  166. 'ahal a primitive root; to be clear: shine.
  167. 'ahal a denominative from 'ohel; to tent: pitch (remove) a tent.
  168. 'ohel from 'ahal; a tent (as clearly conspicuous from a distance): covering, (dwelling)(place), home, tabernacle, tent.
  169. 'Ohel the same as 'ohel; Ohel, an Israelite: Ohel.
  170. 'Oholah in form a feminine of 'ohel, but in fact for.Oholahh; from 'ohel; her tent (i.e. idolatrous sanctuary); Oholah, a symbol. name for Samaria: Aholah.
  171. 'Oholiy'ab from 'ohel and 'ab; tent of (his) father; Oholiab, an Israelite: Aholiab.
  172. 'Oholiybah (similarly with 'Oholah) for Oholiybahh; from 'ohel; my tent (is) in her; Oholibah, a symbolic name for Judah: Aholibah.
  173. 'Oholiybamah from 'ohel and bamah; tent of (the) height; Oholibamah, a wife of Esau: Aholibamah.
  174. 'ahaliym or (feminine) ahalowth (only used thus in the plural); of foreign origin; aloe wood (i.e. sticks): (tree of lign-) aloes.
  175. 'Aharown of uncertain derivation; Aharon, the brother of Moses: Aaron.
  176. 'ow presumed to be the "constructive" or genitival form of -av; short for 'avvah; desire (and so probably in Prov. 31:4); hence (by way of alternative) or, also if: also, and, either, if, at the least, X nor, or, otherwise, then, whether.
  177. 'Uw'el from 'ow and 'el; wish of God; Uel, and Israelite: Uel.
  178. 'owb from the same as 'ab (apparently through the idea of prattling a father's name); properly, a mumble, i.e. a water skin (from its hollow sound); hence a necromancer (ventriloquist, as from a jar): bottle, familiar spirit.
  179. 'owbiyl probably from 'abal; mournful; Obil, an Ishmaelite: Obil.
  180. 'uwbal or (shortened) ubal; from yabal (in the sense of yabal); a stream: river.
  181. 'uwd from an unused root meaning to rake together; a poker (for turning or gathering embers): (fire-)brand.
  182. 'owdowth or (shortened) rodowth (only thus in the plural); from the same as 'uwd; turnings (i.e. occasions); (adverb) on account of: (be-)cause, concerning, sake.
  183. 'avah a primitive root; to wish for: covet, (greatly) desire, be desirous, long, lust (after).
  184. 'avah a primitive root; to extend or mark out: point out.
  185. 'avvah from 'avah; longing: desire, lust after, pleasure.
  186. 'Uwzay perhaps by permutation for `Uzziy, strong; Uzai, an Israelite: Uzai.
  187. 'Uwzal of uncertain derivation; Uzal, a son of Joktan: Uzal.
  188. 'owy probably from 'avah (in the sense of crying out after); lamentation; also interjectionally Oh!: alas, woe.
  189. 'Eviy probably from 'avah; desirous; Evi, a Midianitish chief: Evi.
  190. 'owyah feminine of 'owy: woe.
  191. 'eviyl from an unused root (meaning to be perverse); (figuratively) silly: fool(-ish) (man).
  192. 'Eviyl Mrodak of Aramaic derivation and probably meaning soldier of Merodak; Evil-Merodak, a Babylonian king: Evil-merodach.
  193. 'uwl from an unused root meaning to twist, i.e. (by implication) be strong; the body (as being rolled together); also powerful: mighty, strength.
  194. 'uwlay or (shortened) rulay; from 'ow; if not; hence perhaps: if so be, may be, peradventure, unless.
  195. 'Uwlay of Persian derivation; the Ulai (or Eulaeus), a river of Persia: Ulai.
  196. 'eviliy from 'eviyl; silly, foolish; hence (morally) impious: foolish.
  197. 'uwlam or (shortened) ulam; from 'alam (in the sense of tying); a vestibule (as bound to the building): porch.
  198. 'Uwlam appar, from 'alam (in the sense of dumbness); solitary; Ulam, the name of two Israelites: Ulam.
  199. 'uwlam apparently a variation of 'uwlay; however or on the contrary: as for, but, howbeit, in very deed, surely, truly, wherefore.
  200. 'ivveleth from the same as 'eviyl; silliness: folly, foolishly(-ness).
  201. 'Owmar from 'amar; talkative; Omar, a grandson of Esau: Omar.
  202. 'own probably from the same as 'aven (in the sense of effort, but successful); ability, power, (figuratively) wealth: force, goods, might, strength, substance.
  203. 'Own the same as 'own; On, an Israelite: On.
  204. 'Own or (shortened) On; of Egyptian derivation; On, a city of Egypt: On.
  205. 'aven from an unused root perhaps meaning properly, to pant (hence, to exert oneself, usually in vain; to come to naught); strictly nothingness; also trouble. vanity, wickedness; specifically an idol: affliction, evil, false, idol, iniquity, mischief, mourners(-ing), naught, sorrow, unjust, unrighteous, vain, vanity, wicked(-ness). Compare 'ayin.
  206. 'Aven the same as 'aven; idolatry; Aven, the contemptuous synonym of three places, one in Coele-Syria, one in Egypt (On), and one in Palestine (Bethel): Aven. See also 'Own, Beyth 'Aven.
  207. 'Ownow or (shortened) ;Onow; prolonged from 'own; strong; Ono, a place in Palestine: Ono.
  208. 'Ownam a variation of 'Ownan; strong; Onam, the name of an Edomite and of an Israelite: Onam.
  209. 'Ownan a variation of 'Ownow; strong; Onan, a son of Judah: Onan.
  210. 'Uwphaz perhaps a corruption of 'Owphiyr; Uphaz, a famous gold region: Uphaz.
  211. 'Owphiyr or (shortened) Ophiyr; and Owphir; of uncertain derivation; Ophir, the name of a son of Joktan, and of a gold region in the East: Ophir.
  212. 'owphan or (shortened) pophan; from an unused root meaning to revolve; a wheel: wheel.
  213. 'uwts a primitive root; to press; (by implication) to be close, hurry, withdraw: (make) haste(-n, -y), labor, be narrow.
  214. 'owtsar from 'atsar; a depository: armory, cellar, garner, store(-house), treasure(-house) (-y).
  215. 'owr a primitive root; to be (causative, make) luminous (literally and metaphorically): X break of day, glorious, kindle, (be, en-, give, show) light (-en, -ened), set on fire, shine.
  216. 'owr from 'owr; illumination or (concrete) luminary (in every sense, including lightning, happiness, etc.): bright, clear, + day, light (-ning), morning, sun.
  217. 'uwr from 'owr; flame; hence (in the plural) the East (as being the region of light): fire, light. See also 'Uwriym.
  218. 'Uwr the same as 'uwr; Ur, a place in Chaldaea; also an Israelite: Ur.
  219. 'owrah feminine of 'owr; luminousness, i.e. (figuratively) prosperity; also a plant (as being bright): herb, light.
  220. 'averah by transposition for 'urvah; a stall: cote.
  221. 'Uwriy from 'uwr; fiery; Uri, the name of three Israelites: Uri.
  222. 'Uwriy'el from 'uwr and 'el; flame of God; Uriel, the name of two Israelites: Uriel.
  223. 'Uwriyah or (prolonged) Uwriyahuw; from 'uwr and Yahh; flame of Jah; Urijah, the name of one Hittite and five Israelites: Uriah, Urijah.
  224. 'Uwriym plur of 'uwr; lights; Urim, the oracular brilliancy of the figures in the high-priest's breastplate: Urim.
  225. 'uwth a primitive root; properly, to come, i.e. (implied) to assent: consent.
  226. 'owth probably from 'uwth (in the sense of appearing); a signal (literally or figuratively), as a flag, beacon, monument, omen, prodigy, evidence, etc.: mark, miracle, (en-)sign, token.
  227. 'az a demonstrative adverb; at that time or place; also as a conjunction, therefore: beginning, for, from, hitherto, now, of old, once, since, then, at which time, yet.
  228. 'aza' (Aramaic) or iazah (Aramaic); to kindle; (by implication) to heat: heat, hot.
  229. 'Ezbay probably from 'ezowb; hyssop-like; Ezbai, an Israelite: Ezbai.
  230. 'azad (Aramaic) of uncertain derivation; firm: be gone.
  231. 'ezowb probably of foreign derivation; hyssop: hyssop.
  232. 'ezowr from 'aziqqiym; something girt; a belt, also a band: girdle.
  233. 'azay probably from 'az; at that time: then.
  234. 'azkarah from zakar; a reminder; specifically remembrance- offering: memorial.
  235. 'azal a primitive root; to go away, hence, to disappear: fail, gad about, go to and fro (but in Ezek. 27:19 the word is rendered by many "from Uzal," by others "yarn"), be gone (spent).
  236. 'azal (Aramaic) the same as 'azal; to depart: go (up).
  237. 'ezel from 'azal; departure; Ezel, a memorial stone in Palestine: Ezel.
  238. 'azan a primitive root; probably to expand; but used only as a denominative from 'ozen; to broaden out the ear (with the hand), i.e. (by implication) to listen: give (perceive by the) ear, hear(-ken). See 'azan.
  239. 'azan a primitive root (rather identical with 'azan through the idea of scales as if two ears); to weigh, i.e. (figuratively) ponder: give good head.
  240. 'azen from 'azan; a spade or paddle (as having a broad end): weapon.
  241. 'ozen from 'azan; broadness. i.e. (concrete) the ear (from its form in man): + advertise, audience, + displease, ear, hearing, + show.
  242. 'Uzzen She'erah from 'azan and She'erah; plat of Sheerah (i.e. settled by him); Uzzen-Sheerah, a place in Palestine: Uzzen-sherah.
  243. 'Aznowth Tabowr from 'azan and Tabowr; flats (i.e. tops) of Tabor (i.e. situated on it); Aznoth-Tabor, a place in Palestine: Aznoth-tabor.
  244. 'Ozniy from 'ozen; having (quick) ears; Ozni, an Israelite; also an Oznite (collectively), his descendant: Ozni, Oznites.
  245. 'Azanyah from 'azan and Yahh; heard by Jah; Azanjah, an Israelite: Azaniah.
  246. 'aziqqiym a variation for ziyqah; manacles: chains.
  247. 'azar a primitive root; to belt: bind (compass) about, gird (up, with).
  248. 'ezrowa` a variation for zrowa`; the arm: arm.
  249. 'ezrach from zarach (in the sense of springing up); a spontaneous growth, i.e. native (tree or persons): bay tree, (home-)born (in the land), of the (one's own) country (nation).
  250. 'Ezrachiy patronymic from Chobab; an Ezrachite or descendant of Zerach: Ezrahite.
  251. 'ach a primitive word; a brother (used in the widest sense of literal relationship and metaphorical affinity or resemblance (like 'ab)): another, brother(-ly); kindred, like, other. Compare also the proper names beginning with "Ah-" or "Ahi-".
  252. 'ach (Aramaic) corresponding to 'ach: brother.
  253. 'ach a variation for 'ahahh; Oh! (expressive of grief or surprise): ah, alas.
  254. 'ach of uncertain derivation; a fire-pot or chafing dish: hearth.
  255. 'oach probably from 'ach; a howler or lonesome wild animal: doleful creature.
  256. 'Ach'ab once (by contraction) Echab (Jer. 29:22); from 'ach and 'ab; brother (i.e. friend) of (his) father; Achab, the name of a king of Israel and of a prophet at Babylon: Ahab.
  257. 'Achban from 'ach and biyn; brother (i.e. possessor) of understanding; Achban, an Israelite: Ahban.
  258. 'achad perhaps a primitive root; to unify, i.e. (figuratively) collect (one's thoughts): go one way or other.
  259. 'echad a numeral from 'achad; properly, united, i.e. one; or (as an ordinal) first:--a, alike, alone, altogether, and, any(-thing), apiece, a certain, (dai-)ly, each (one), + eleven, every, few, first, + highway, a man, once, one, only, other, some, together,
  260. 'achuw of uncertain (perhaps Egyptian) derivation; a bulrush or any marshy grass (particularly that along the Nile): flag, meadow.
  261. 'Echuwd from 'achad; united; Echud, the name of three Israelites: Ehud.
  262. 'achvah from chavah (in the sense of chava'); an utterance: declaration.
  263. 'achavah (Aramaic) corresponding to 'achvah; solution (of riddles): showing.
  264. 'achavah from 'ach; fraternity: brotherhood.
  265. 'Achowach by reduplication from 'ach; brotherly; Achoach, an Israelite: Ahoah.
  266. 'Achowchiy patronymic from 'achavah; an Achochite or descendant of Achoach: Ahohite.
  267. 'Achuwmay perhaps from 'ach and mayim; brother (i.e. neighbour) of water; Achumai, an Israelite: Ahumai.
  268. 'achowr or (shortened) achor; from 'Achiyra`; the hinder part; hence (adverb) behind, backward; also (as facing north) the West: after(-ward), back (part, -side, -ward), hereafter, (be-)hind(-er part), time to come, without.
  269. 'achowth irregular feminine of 'ach; a sister (used very widely (like 'Ezrachiy), literally and figuratively): (an-)other, sister, together.
  270. 'achaz a primitive root; to seize (often with the accessory idea of holding in possession): + be affrighted, bar, (catch, lay, take) hold (back), come upon, fasten, handle, portion, (get, have or take) possess(-ion).
  271. 'Achaz from 'achaz; possessor; Achaz, the name of a Jewish king and of an Israelite: Ahaz.
  272. 'achuzzah feminine passive participle from 'achaz; something seized, i.e. a possession (especially of land): possession.
  273. 'Achzay from 'achaz; seizer; Achzai, an Israelite: Ahasai.
  274. 'Achazyah or (prolonged) Achazyahuw; from 'achaz and Yahh; Jah has seized; Achazjah, the name of a Jewish and an Israelite king: Ahaziah.
  275. 'Achuzzam from 'achaz; seizure; Achuzzam, an Israelite: Ahuzam.
  276. 'Achuzzath a variation of 'achuzzah; possession; Achuzzath, a Philistine: Ahuzzath.
  277. 'Achiy from 'ach; brotherly; Achi, the name of two Israelites: Ahi.
  278. 'Echiy probably the same as 'Achiy; Echi, an Israelite: Ehi.
  279. 'Achiyam from 'ach and 'em; brother of the mother (i.e. uncle); Achiam, an Israelite: Ahiam.
  280. 'achiydah (Aramaic) corresponding to chiydah, an enigma: hard sentence.
  281. 'Achiyah or (prolonged) Achiyahuw; from 'ach and Yahh; brother (i.e. worshipper) of Jah; Achijah, the name of nine Israelites: Ahiah, Ahijah.
  282. 'Achiyhuwd from 'ach and howd; brother (i.e. possessor) of renown; Achihud, an Israelite: Ahihud.
  283. 'Achyow prolonged from 'ach; brotherly; Achio, the name of three Israelites: Ahio.
  284. 'Achiychud from 'ach and chuwd; brother of a riddle (i.e. mysterious); Achichud, an Israelite: Ahihud.
  285. 'Achiytuwb from 'ach and tuwb; brother of goodness; Achitub, the name of several priests: Ahitub.
  286. 'Achiyluwd from 'ach and yalad; brother of one born; Achilud, an Israelite: Ahilud.
  287. 'Achiymowth from 'ach and muwth; brother of death; Achimoth, an Israelite: Ahimoth.
  288. 'Achiymelek from 'ach and melek; brother of (the) king; Achimelek, the name of an Israelite and of a Hittite: Ahimelech.
  289. 'Achiyman or Achiyman; from 'ach and min; brother of a portion (i.e. gift); Achiman, the name of an Anakite and of an Israelite: Ahiman.
  290. 'Achiyma`ats from 'ach and the equivalent of Ma`ats; brother of anger; Achimaats, the name of three Israelites: Ahimaaz.
  291. 'Achyan from 'ach; brotherly; Achjan, an Israelite: Ahian.
  292. 'Achiynadab from 'ach and nadab; brother of liberality; Achinadab, an Israelite: Ahinadab.
  293. 'Achiyno`am from 'ach and no`am; brother of pleasantness; Achinoam, the name of two Israelitesses: Ahinoam.
  294. 'Achiycamak from 'ach and camak; brother of support; Achisamak, an Israelite: Ahisamach.
  295. 'Achiy`ezer from 'ach and `ezer; brother of help; Achiezer, the name of two Israelites: Ahiezer.
  296. 'Achiyqam from 'ach and quwm; brother of rising (i.e. high); Achikam, an Israelite: Ahikam.
  297. 'Achiyram from 'ach and ruwm; brother of height (i.e. high); Achiram, an Israelite: Ahiram.
  298. 'Achiyramiy patronymic from 'Achiyram; an Achiramite or descendant (collectively) of Achiram: Ahiramites.
  299. 'Achiyra` from 'ach and ra`; brother of wrong; Achira, an Israelite: Ahira.
  300. 'Achiyshachar from 'ach and shachar; brother of (the) dawn; Achishachar, an Israelite: Ahishar.
  301. 'Achiyshar from 'ach and shiyr; brother of (the) singer; Achishar, an Israelite: Ahishar.
  302. 'Achiythophel from 'ach and taphel; brother of folly; Achithophel, an Israelite: Ahithophel.
  303. 'Achlab from the same root as cheleb; fatness (i.e. fertile); Achlab, a place in Palestine: Ahlab.
  304. 'Achlay the same as 'achalay; wishful; Achlai, the name of an Israelitess and of an Israelite: Ahlai.
  305. 'achalay or achaley; prob from 'ach and a variation of luw'; would that!: O that, would God.
  306. 'achlamah perhaps from chalam (and thus dream-stone); a gem, probably the amethyst: amethyst.
  307. 'Achmtha' of Persian derivation; Achmetha (i.e. Ecbatana), the summer capital of Persia: Achmetha.
  308. 'Achacbay of uncertain derivation; Achasbai, an Israelite: Ahasbai.
  309. 'achar a primitive root; to loiter (i.e. be behind); by implication to procrastinate: continue, defer, delay, hinder, be late (slack), stay (there), tarry (longer).
  310. 'achar from 'achar; properly, the hind part; generally used as an adverb or conjunction, after (in various senses): after (that, -ward), again, at, away from, back (from, -side), behind, beside, by, follow (after, -ing), forasmuch, from, hereafter, hinder end, + out (over) live, + persecute, posterity, pursuing, remnant, seeing, since, thence(-forth), when, with.
  311. 'achar (Aramaic) corresponding to 'achar; after: (here-)after.
  312. 'acher from 'achar; properly, hinder; generally, next, other, etc.: (an-)other man, following, next, strange.
  313. 'Acher the same as 'acher; Acher, an Israelite: Aher.
  314. 'acharown or (shortened) ;acharon; from 'achar; hinder; generally, late or last; specifically (as facing the east) western: after (-ward), to come, following, hind(-er, -ermost, -most), last, latter, rereward, ut(ter)most.
  315. 'Achrach from 'achar and 'ach; after (his) brother: Achrach, an Israelite: Aharah.
  316. 'Acharchel from 'achar and cheyl; behind (the) intrenchment (i.e. safe); Acharchel, an Israelite:--Aharhel,
  317. 'ochoriy (Aramaic) from 'achar; other: (an-)other.
  318. 'ochoreyn (Aramaic) or (shortened) :ochoren (Aramaic); from 'ochoriy; last: at last.
  319. 'achariyth from 'achar; the last or end, hence, the future; also posterity: (last, latter) end (time), hinder (utter) -most, length, posterity, remnant, residue, reward.
  320. 'achariyth (Aramaic) from 'achar; the same as 'achariyth; later: latter.
  321. 'ochoran (Aramaic) from 'achar; the same as 'ochoriy; other: (an-)other.
  322. 'achoranniyth prolonged from 'achowr; backwards: back (-ward, again).
  323. 'achashdarpan of Persian derivation; a satrap or governor of a main province (of Persia): lieutenant.
  324. 'achashdarpan (Aramaic) corresponding to 'achashdarpan: prince.
  325. 'Achashverowsh or (shortened) Achashrosh (Esth. 10:1); of Persian origin; Achashverosh (i.e. Ahasuerus or Artaxerxes, but in this case Xerxes), the title (rather than name) of a Persian king: Ahasuerus.
  326. 'achashtariy probably of Persian derivation; an achastarite (i.e. courier); the designation (rather than name) of an Israelite: Haakashtari (includ. the article).
  327. 'achastaran of Persian origin; a mule: camel.
  328. 'at from an unused root perhaps meaning to move softly; (as a noun) a necromancer (from their soft incantations), (as an adverb) gently: charmer, gently, secret, softly.
  329. 'atad from an unused root probably meaning to pierce or make fast; a thorn-tree (especially the buckthorn): Atad, bramble, thorn.
  330. 'etuwn from an unused root (probably meaning to bind); properly, twisted (yarn), i.e. tapestry: fine linen.
  331. 'atam a primitive root; to close (the lips or ears); by analology to contract (a window by bevelled jambs): narrow, shut, stop.
  332. 'atar a primitive root; to close up: shut.
  333. 'Ater from 'atar; maimed; Ater, the name of three Israelites: Ater.
  334. 'itter from 'atar; shut up, i.e. impeded (as to the use of the right hand): + left-handed.
  335. 'ay perhaps from 'aiyn; where? hence how?: how, what, whence, where, whether, which (way).
  336. 'iy probably identical with 'ay (through the idea of a query); not: island (Job 22:30).
  337. 'iy short from 'owy; alas!: woe.
  338. 'iy probably identical with 'iy (through the idea of a doleful sound); a howler (used only in the plural), i.e. any solitary wild creature; --wild beast of the islands.
  339. 'iy from 'avah; properly, a habitable spot (as desirable); dry land, a coast, an island: country, isle, island.
  340. 'ayab a primitive root; to hate (as one of an opposite tribe or party); hence to be hostile: be an enemy.
  341. 'oyeb or (fully) owyeb; active participle of 'ayab; hating; an adversary: enemy, foe.
  342. 'eybah from 'ayab; hostility: emnity, hatred.
  343. 'eyd from the same as 'uwd (in the sense of bending down); oppression; by implication misfortune, ruin: calamity, destruction.
  344. 'ayah perhaps from 'iy; the screamer, i.e. a hawk: kite, vulture.
  345. 'Ayah the same as 'ayah; Ajah, the name of two Israelites: Aiah, Ajah.
  346. 'ayeh prolonged from 'ay; where?: where.
  347. 'Iyowb from 'ayab; hated (i.e. persecuted); Ijob, the patriarch famous for his patience: Job.
  348. 'Iyzebel from 'iy and Zbul; Izebel, the wife of king Ahab: Jezebel.
  349. 'eyk also eykah; and teykakah; prolonged from 'ay; how? or how!; also where: how, what.
  350. 'Iy-kabowd from 'iy and kabowd; (there is) no glory, i.e. inglorious; Ikabod, a son of Phineas: I-chabod.
  351. 'eykoh probably a variation for 'eyk, but not as an interogative; where: where.
  352. 'ayil from the same as 'uwl; properly, strength; hence, anything strong; specifically a chief (politically); also a ram (from his strength); a pilaster (as a strong support); an oak or other strong tree: mighty (man), lintel, oak, post, ram, tree.
  353. 'eyal a variation of 'ayil; strength: strength.
  354. 'ayal an intensive form of 'ayil (in the sense of ram); a stag or male deer: hart.
  355. 'ayalah feminine of 'ayal; a doe or female deer: hind.
  356. 'Eylown or (shortened) ;Elown; or Eylon; from 'ayil; oak-grove; Elon, the name of a place in Palestine, and also of one Hittite, two Israelites: Elon.
  357. 'Ayalown from 'ayal; deer-field; Ajalon, the name of five places in Palestine: Aijalon, Ajalon.
  358. 'Eylown Beyth Chanan from 'Eylown, bayith, and chanan; oak-grove of (the) house of favor; Elon of Beth-chanan, a place in Palestine: Elon-beth-hanan.
  359. 'Eylowth or Eylath; from 'ayil; trees or a grove (i.e. palms); Eloth or Elath, a place on the Red Sea: Elath, Eloth.
  360. 'eyaluwth feminine of 'eyal; power; by implication, protection: strength.
  361. 'eylam or (shortened) ;elam; or (feminine) ielammah; probably from 'ayil; a pillar-space (or colonnade), i.e. a pale (or portico): arch.
  362. 'Eylim plural of 'ayil; palm-trees; Elim, a place in the Desert: Elim.
  363. 'iylan (Aramaic) corresponding to 'Eylown; a tree: tree.
  364. 'Eyl Pa'ran from 'ayil and Pa'ran; oak of Paran; El- Paran, a portion of the district of Paran: El-paran.
  365. 'ayeleth the same as 'ayalah; a doe: hind, Aijeleth.
  366. 'ayom from an unused root (meaning to frighten); frightful: terrible.
  367. 'eymah or (shortened) remah; from the same as 'ayom; fright; concrete, an idol (as a bugbear): dread, fear, horror, idol, terrible, terror.
  368. 'Eymiym plural of 'eymah; terrors; Emim, an early Canaanitish (or Maobitish) tribe: Emims.
  369. 'ayin as if from a primitive root meaning to be nothing or not exist; a non-entity; generally used as a negative particle: else, except, fail, (father-)less, be gone, in(-curable), neither, never, no (where), none, nor, (any, thing), not, nothing, to nought, past, un(-searchable), well-nigh, without. Compare 'aiyn.
  370. 'aiyn probably identical with 'ayin in the sense of query (compare 'iy); --where? (only in connection with prepositional prefix, whence): whence, where.
  371. 'iyn apparently a shortened form of 'ayin; but (like 'aiyn) an interrogative: is it not?: not.
  372. 'Iy`ezer from 'iy and `ezer; helpless; Iezer, an Israelite: Jeezer.
  373. 'Iy`ezriy patronymic from 'Iy`ezer; an Iezrite or descendant of Iezer: Jezerite.
  374. 'eyphah or (shortened) ephah; of Egyptian derivation; an ephah or measure for grain; hence, a measure in general: ephah, (divers) measure(-s).
  375. 'eyphoh from 'ay and poh; what place?; also (of time) when?; or (of means) how?; --what manner, where.
  376. 'iysh contracted for 'enowsh (or perhaps rather from an unused root meaning to be extant); a man as an individual or a male person; often used as an adjunct to a more definite term (and in such cases frequently not expressed in translation): also, another, any (man), a certain, + champion, consent, each, every (one), fellow, (foot-, husband-)man, (good-, great, mighty) man, he, high (degree), him (that is), husband, man(-kind), + none, one, people, person, + steward, what (man) soever, whoso(-ever), worthy. Compare 'ishshah.
  377. 'iysh denominative from 'iysh; to be a man, i.e. act in a manly way: show (one) self a man.
  378. 'Iysh-Bosheth from 'iysh and bosheth; man of shame; Ish- Bosheth, a son of King Saul: Ish-bosheth.
  379. 'Iyshhowd from 'iysh and howd; man of renown; Ishod, an Israelite: Ishod.
  380. 'iyshown diminutive from 'iysh; the little man of the eye; the pupil or ball; hence, the middle (of night): apple (of the eye), black, obscure.
  381. 'Iysh-Chayil from 'iysh and chayil; man of might; by defect. transcription (2 Sam. 23:20) Iysh-Chay; as if from 'iysh and chay; living man; Ish-chail (or Ish-chai), an Israelite: a valiant man.
  382. 'Iysh-Towb from 'iysh and Towb; man of Tob; Ish-Tob, a place in Palestine: Ish-tob.
  383. 'iythay (Aramaic) corresponding to yesh; properly, entity; used only as a particle of affirmation, there is: art thou, can, do ye, have, it be, there is (are), X we will not.
  384. 'Iythiy'el perhaps from 'osher and 'el; God has arrived; Ithiel, the name of an Israelite, also of a symbolical person: Ithiel.
  385. 'Iythamar from 'iy and tamar; coast of the palm-tree; Ithamar, a son of Aaron: Ithamar.
  386. 'eythan or (shortened) ethan; from an unused root (meaning to continue); permanence; hence (concrete) permanent; specifically a chieftain: hard, mighty, rough, strength, strong.
  387. 'Eythan the same as 'eythan; permanent; Ethan, the name of four Israelites: Ethan.
  388. 'Eythaniym plural of 'eythan; always with the article; the permanent brooks; Ethanim, the name of a month: Ethanim.
  389. 'ak akin to 'aken; a particle of affirmation, surely; hence (by limitation) only: also, in any wise, at least, but, certainly, even, howbeit, nevertheless, notwithstanding, only, save, surely, of a surety, truly, verily, + wherefore, yet (but).
  390. 'Akkad from an unused root probably meaning to strengthen; a fortress; Accad, a place in Babylon: Accad.
  391. 'akzab from kazab; falsehood; by implication treachery: liar, lie.
  392. 'Akziyb from 'akzab; deceitful (in the sense of a winter- torrent which fails in summer); Akzib, the name of two places in Palestine: Achzib.
  393. 'akzar from an unused root (apparently meaning to act harshly); violent; by implication deadly; also (in a good sense) brave: cruel, fierce.
  394. 'akzariy from 'akzar; terrible: cruel (one).
  395. 'akzriyuwth from 'akzariy; fierceness: cruel.
  396. 'akiylah feminine from 'akal; something eatable, i.e. food: meat.
  397. 'Akiysh of uncertain derivation; Akish, a Philistine king: Achish.
  398. 'akal a primitive root; to eat (literally or figuratively): X at all, burn up, consume, devour(-er, up), dine, eat(-er, up), feed (with), food, X freely, X in...wise(-deed, plenty), (lay) meat, X quite.
  399. 'akal (Aramaic) corresponding to 'akal: + accuse, devour, eat.
  400. 'okel from 'akal; food: eating, food, meal(-time), meat, prey, victuals.
  401. 'Ukal or Ukkal; apparently from 'akal; devoured; Ucal, a fancy name: Ucal.
  402. 'oklah feminine of 'Ukal; food: consume, devour, eat, food, meat.
  403. 'aken from kuwn (compare ken); firmly; figuratively, surely; also (advers.) but: but, certainly, nevertheless, surely, truly, verily.
  404. 'akaph a primitive root; apparently meaning to curve (as with a burden); to urge: crave.
  405. 'ekeph from 'akaph; a load; by implication, a stroke (others dignity): hand.
  406. 'ikkar from an unused root meaning to dig; a farmer: husbandman, ploughman.
  407. 'Akshaph from kashaph; fascination; Acshaph, a place in Palestine: Achshaph.
  408. 'al a negative particle (akin to lo'); not (the qualified negation, used as a deprecative); once (Job 24:25) as a noun, nothing: nay, neither, + never, no, nor, not, nothing (worth), rather than.
  409. 'al (Aramaic) corresponding to 'al: not.
  410. 'el shortened from 'ayil; strength; as adjective, mighty; especially the Almighty (but used also of any deity): God (god), X goodly, X great, idol, might(-y one), power, strong. Compare names in "-el."
  411. 'el a demonstrative particle (but only in a plural sense) these or those: these, those. Compare 'el-leh.
  412. 'el (Aramaic) corresponding to 'el: these.
  413. 'el (but only used in the shortened constructive form sel); a primitive particle; properly, denoting motion towards, but occasionally used of a quiescent position, i.e. near, with or among; often in general, to: about, according to, after, against, among, as for, at, because(-fore, -side), both...and, by, concerning, for, from, X hath, in(- to), near, (out) of, over, through, to(-ward), under, unto, upon, whether, with(-in).
  414. 'Ela' a variation of 'elah; oak; Ela, an Israelite: Elah.
  415. 'El 'elohey Yisra'el from 'el and 'elohiym and Yisra'el; the mighty god if Jisrael; El-Elohi-Jisrael, the title given to a consecrated spot by Jacob: El-elohe-israel.
  416. 'El Beyth-'El from 'el and Beyth-'El; the God of Bethel; El-Bethel, the title given to a consecrated spot by Jacob: El-beth-el.
  417. 'elgabiysh from 'el and gabiysh; hail (as if a great pearl): great hail(-stones).
  418. 'alguwmmiym by transposition for 'almuggiym; sticks of algum wood: algum (trees).
  419. 'Eldad from 'el and dowd; God has loved; Eldad, an Israelite: Eldad.
  420. 'Elda`ah from 'el and yada`; God of knowledge; Eldaah, a son of Midian: Eldaah.
  421. 'alah a primitive root (rather identical with 'alah through the idea of invocation); to bewail: lament.
  422. 'alah a primitive root; properly, to adjure, i.e. (usually in a bad sense) imprecate: adjure, curse, swear.
  423. 'alah from 'alah; an imprecation: curse, cursing, execration, oath, swearing.
  424. 'elah feminine of 'ayil; an oak or other strong tree: elm, oak, teil-tree.
  425. 'Elah the same as 'elah; Elah, the name of an Edomite, of four Israelites, and also of a place in Palestine: Elah.
  426. 'elahh (Aramaic) corresponding to 'elowahh; God: God, god.
  427. 'allah A variation of 'elah: oak.
  428. 'el-leh prolonged from 'el; these or those: an- (the) other; one sort, so, some, such, them, these (same), they, this, those, thus, which, who(-m).
  429. 'elleh (Aramaic) corresponding to 'el-leh: these.
  430. 'elohiym plural of 'elowahh; gods in the ordinary sense; but specifically used (in the plural thus, especially with the article) of the supreme God; occasionally applied by way of deference to magistrates; and sometimes as a superlative: angels, X exceeding, God (gods)(-dess, -ly), X (very) great, judges, X mighty.
  431. 'aluw (Aramaic) probably prolonged from 'el; lo!: behold.
  432. 'illuw probably from 'al; nay, i.e. (softened) if: but if, yea though.
  433. 'elowahh, rarely (shortened) >eloahh probably prolonged (emphat.) from 'el; a deity or the Deity: God, god. See 'elohiym.
  434. 'eluwl for 'eliyl; good for nothing: thing of nought.
  435. 'Eluwl probably of foreign derivation; Elul, the sixth Jewish month: Elul.
  436. 'elown prolonged from 'ayil; an oak or other strong tree: plain. See also 'Eylown.
  437. 'allown a variation of 'elown: oak.
  438. 'Allown the same as 'allown; Allon, an Israelite, also a place in Palestine: Allon.
  439. 'Allown Bakuwth from 'allown and a variation of bkiyth; oak of weeping; Allon-Bakuth, a monumental tree: Allon-bachuth.
  440. 'Elowniy or rather (shortened) Eloniy; patron from 'Allown; an Elonite or descendant (collectively) of Elon: Elonites.
  441. 'alluwph or (shortened) talluph; from 'alph; familiar; a friend, also gentle; hence, a bullock (as being tame; applied, although masculine, to a cow); and so, a chieftain (as notable, like neat cattle): captain, duke, (chief) friend, governor, guide, ox.
  442. 'Aluwsh of uncertain derivation; Alush, a place in the Desert: Alush.
  443. 'Elzabad from 'el and zabad; God has bestowed; Elzabad, the name of two Israelites: Elzabad.
  444. 'alach a primitive root; to muddle, i.e. (figuratively and intransitive) to turn (morally) corrupt: become filthy.
  445. 'Elchanan from 'el and chanan; God (is) gracious; Elchanan, an Israelite: Elkanan.
  446. 'Eliy'ab from 'el and 'ab; God of (his) father; Eliab, the name of six Israelites: Eliab.
  447. 'Eliy'el from 'el repeated; God of (his) God; Eliel, the name of nine Israelites: Eliel.
  448. 'Eliy'athah or (contraction) ;Eliyathah; from 'el and 'uwth; God of (his) consent; Eliathah, an Israelite: Eliathah.
  449. 'Eliydad from the same as 'Eldad; God of (his) love; Elidad, an Israelite: Elidad.
  450. 'Elyada` from 'el and yada`; God (is) knowing; Eljada, the name of two Israelites and of an Aramaean leader: Eliada.
  451. 'alyah from 'alah (in the original sense of strength); the stout part, i.e. the fat tail of the Oriental sheep: rump.
  452. 'Eliyah or prolonged Eliyahuw; from 'el and Yahh; God of Jehovah; Elijah, the name of the famous prophet and of two other Israelites: Elijah, Eliah.
  453. 'Eliyhuw or (fully) Eliyhuwh; from 'el and huw'; God of him; Elihu, the name of one of Job's friends, and of three Israelites: Elihu.
  454. 'Elyhow`eynay or (shortened) Elyow`eynay; from 'el and Yhovah and `ayin; towards Jehovah (are) my eyes; Eljehoenai or Eljoenai, the name of seven Israelites: Elihoenai, Elionai.
  455. 'Elyachba' from 'el and chaba'; God will hide; Eljachba, an Israelite: Eliahbah.
  456. 'Eliychoreph from 'el and choreph; God of autumn; Elichoreph, an Israelite: Elihoreph.
  457. 'eliyl apparently from 'al; good for nothing, by anal. vain or vanity; specifically an idol: idol, no value, thing of nought.
  458. 'Eliymelek from 'el and melek; God of (the) king; Elimelek, an Israelite: Elimelech.
  459. 'illeyn (Aramaic) or shorter oillen; prolonged from 'el; these: the, these.
  460. 'Elyacaph from 'el and yacaph; God (is) gatherer; Eljasaph, the name of two Israelites: Eliasaph.
  461. 'Eliy`ezer from 'el and `ezer; God of help; Eliezer, the name of a Damascene and of ten Israelites: Eliezer.
  462. 'Eliy`eynay probably contracted for 'Elyhow`eynay; Elienai, an Israelite: Elienai.
  463. 'Eliy`am from 'el and `am; God of (the) people; Eliam, an Israelite: Eliam.
  464. 'Eliyphaz from 'el and paz; God of gold; Eliphaz, the name of one of Job's friends, and of a son of Esau: Eliphaz.
  465. 'Eliyphal from 'el and palal; God of judgment; Eliphal, an Israelite: Eliphal.
  466. 'Eliyphlehuw from 'el and palah; God of his distinction; Eliphelehu, an Israelite: Elipheleh.
  467. 'Eliyphelet or (shortened) Elpelet; from 'el and pallet; God of deliverance; Eliphelet or Elpelet, the name of six Israelites: Eliphalet, Eliphelet, Elpalet.
  468. 'Eleytsuwr from 'el and tsuwr; God of (the) rock; Elitsur, an Israelite: Elizur.
  469. 'Eliytsaphan or (shortened) Eltsaphan; from 'el and tsaphan; God of treasure; Elitsaphan or Eltsaphan, an Israelite: Elizaphan, Elzaphan.
  470. 'Eliyqa' from 'el and qow'; God of rejection; Elika, an Israelite: Elika.
  471. 'Elyaqiym' from 'el and quwm; God of raising; Eljakim, the name of four Israelites: Eliakim.
  472. 'Eliysheba` from 'el and sheba` (in the sense of shaba`); God of (the) oath; Elisheba, the wife of Aaron: Elisheba.
  473. 'Eliyshah probably of foreign derivation; Elishah, a son of Javan: Elishah.
  474. 'Eliyshuwa` from 'el and shuwa`; God of supplication (or of riches); Elishua, the son of King David: Elishua.
  475. 'Elyashiyb from 'el and shuwb; God will restore; Eljashib, the name of six Israelites: Eliashib.
  476. 'Eliyshama` from 'el and shama`; God of hearing; Elishama, the name of seven Israelites: Elishama.
  477. 'Eliysha` contracted for 'Eliyshuwa`.; Elisha, the famous prophet: Elisha.
  478. 'Eliyshaphat from 'el and shaphat; God of judgment; Elishaphat, an Israelite: Elishaphat.
  479. 'illek (Aramaic) prolonged from 'el; these: these, those.
  480. 'allay by reduplication from 'alah; alas!: woe.
  481. 'alam a primitive root; to tie fast; hence (of the mouth) to be tongue-tied: bind, be dumb, put to silence.
  482. 'elem from 'alam; silence (i.e. mute justice): congregation. Compare yownath 'elem rchoqiym.
  483. 'illem from 'alam; speechless: dumb (man).
  484. 'almuggiym probably of foreign derivation (used thus only in the plural); almug (i.e. probably sandle-wood) sticks: almug trees. Compare 'alguwmmiym.
  485. 'alummah or (masculine) ealum; passive participle of 'alam; something bound; a sheaf: sheaf.
  486. 'Almowdad probably of foreign derivation: Almodad, a son of Joktan:--Almodad.
  487. 'Allammelek from 'allah and melek; oak of (the) king; Allammelek, a place in Palestine: Alammelech.
  488. 'alman prolonged from 'alam in the sense of bereavement; discarded (as a divorced person): forsaken.
  489. 'almon from 'alam as in 'alman; bereavement: widowhood.
  490. 'almanah fem of 'alman; a widow; also a desolate place: desolate house (palace), widow.
  491. 'almanuwth feminine of 'alman; concrete, a widow; abstract, widowhood: widow, widowhood.
  492. 'almoniy from 'almon in the sense of concealment; some one (i.e. so and so, without giving the name of the person or place): one, and such.
  493. 'Elna`am from 'el and na`em; God (is his) delight; Elnaam, an Israelite: Elnaam.
  494. 'Elnathan from 'el and nathan; God (is the) giver; Elnathan, the name of four Israelites: Elnathan.
  495. 'Ellacar probably of foreign derivation; Ellasar, an early country of Asia: Ellasar.
  496. 'El`ad from 'el and `uwd; God has testified; Elad, an Israelite: Elead.
  497. 'El`adah from 'el and `adah; God has decked; Eladah, an Israelite: Eladah.
  498. 'El`uwzay from 'el and `uwz (in the sense of `oz); God (is) defensive; Eluzai, an Israelite: Eluzai.
  499. 'El`azar from 'el and `azar; God (is) helper; Elazar, the name of seven Israelites: Eleazar.
  500. 'El`ale' or (more properly) GEl aleh; from 'el and `alah; God (is) going up; Elale or Elaleh, a place east of the Jordan: Elealeh.
  501. 'El`asah from 'el and `asah; God has made; Elasah, the name of four Israelites: Elasah, Eleasah.
  502. 'alph a primitive root, to associate with; hence, to learn (and causatively to teach): learn, teach, utter.
  503. 'alaph denominative from 'eleph; causative, to make a thousandfold: bring forth thousands.
  504. 'eleph from 'alph; a family; also (from the sense of yoking or taming) an ox or cow: family, kine, oxen.
  505. 'eleph prop, the same as 'eleph; hence (the ox's head being the first letter of the alphabet, and this eventually used as a numeral) a thousand: thousand.
  506. 'alaph (Aramaic) or meleph (Aramaic); corresponding to 'eleph: thousand.
  507. 'Eleph the same as 'eleph; Eleph, a place in Palestine: Eleph.
  508. 'Elpa`al from 'el and pa`al; God (is) act; Elpaal, an Israelite: Elpaal.
  509. 'alats a primitive root; to press: urge.
  510. 'alquwm probably from 'al and quwm; a non-rising (i.e. resistlessness): no rising up.
  511. 'Elqanah from 'el and qanah; God has obtained; Elkanah, the name of several Israelites: Elkanah.
  512. 'Elqoshiy patrial from a name of uncertain derivation; an Elkoshite or native of Elkosh: Elkoshite.
  513. 'Eltowlad probably from 'el and a masculine form of towldah (compare Towlad); God (is) generator; Eltolad, a place in Palestine: Eltolad.
  514. 'Eltqe or (more properly) Eltqeh; of uncertain derivation; Eltekeh or Elteke, a place in Palestine: Eltekeh.
  515. 'Eltqon from 'el and taqan; God (is) straight; Eltekon, a place in Palestine: Eltekon.
  516. 'Al tashcheth from 'al and shachath; Thou must not destroy; probably the opening words to a popular song: Al-taschith.
  517. 'em a primitive word; a mother (as the bond of the family); in a wide sense (both literally and figuratively (like 'ab): dam, mother, X parting.
  518. 'im a primitive particle; used very widely as demonstrative, lo!; interrog., whether?; or conditional, if, although; also Oh that!, when; hence, as a negative, not: (and, can-, doubtless, if, that) (not), + but, either, + except, + more(-over if, than), neither, nevertheless, nor, oh that, or, + save (only, -ing), seeing, since, sith, + surely (no more, none, not), though, + of a truth, + unless, + verily, when, whereas, whether, while, + yet.
  519. 'amah apparently a primitive word; a maid-servant or female slave: (hand-)bondmaid(-woman), maid(-servant).
  520. 'ammah prolonged from 'em; properly, a mother (i.e. unit of measure, or the fore-arm (below the elbow), i.e. a cubit; also a door-base (as a bond of the entrance): cubit, + hundred (by exchange for me'ah), measure, post.
  521. 'ammah (Aramaic) corresponding to 'ammah: cubit.
  522. 'Ammah the same as 'ammah; Ammah, a hill in Palestine: Ammah.
  523. 'ummah from the same as 'em; a collection, i.e. community of persons: nation, people.
  524. 'ummah (Aramaic) corresponding to 'ummah: nation.
  525. 'amown from 'aman, probably in the sense of training; skilled, i.e. an architect (like 'aman): one brought up.
  526. 'Amown the same as 'amown; Amon, the name of three Israelites: Amon.
  527. 'amown a variation for hamown; a throng of people: multitude.
  528. 'Amown of Egyptian derivation; Amon (i.e. Ammon or Amn), a deity of Egypt (used only as an adjunct of No'): multitude, populous.
  529. 'emuwn from 'aman; established, i.e. (figuratively) trusty; also (abstractly) trustworthiness: faith(-ful), truth.
  530. 'emuwnah, or (shortened) >emunah feminine of 'emuwn; literally firmness; figuratively security; morally fidelity: faith(-ful, -ly, -ness, (man)), set office, stability, steady, truly, truth, verily.
  531. 'Amowts from 'amats; strong; Amots, an Israelite: Amoz.
  532. 'Amiy an abbrev. for 'Amown; Ami, an Israelite: Ami.
  533. 'ammiyts or (shortened) ammits; from 'amats; strong or (abstractly) strength: courageous, mighty, strong (one).
  534. 'amiyr apparently from 'amar (in the sense of self- exaltation); a summit (of a tree or mountain: bough, branch.
  535. 'amal a primitive root; to droop; by implication to be sick, to mourn: languish, be weak, wax feeble.
  536. 'umlal from 'amal; sick: weak.
  537. 'amelal from 'amal; languid: feeble.
  538. 'Amam from 'em; gathering-spot; Amam, a place in Palestine: Amam.
  539. 'aman a primitive root; properly, to build up or support; to foster as a parent or nurse; figuratively to render (or be) firm or faithful, to trust or believe, to be permanent or quiet; morally to be true or certain; once (Isa. 30:21; interchangeable with 'aman) to go to the right hand: hence, assurance, believe, bring up, establish, + fail, be faithful (of long continuance, stedfast, sure, surely, trusty, verified), nurse, (-ing father), (put), trust, turn to the right.
  540. 'aman (Aramaic) corresponding to 'aman: believe, faithful, sure.
  541. 'aman denominative from yamiyn; to take the right hand road: turn to the right. See 'aman.
  542. 'aman from 'aman (in the sense of training); an expert: cunning workman.
  543. 'amen from 'aman; sure; abstract, faithfulness; adverb, truly: Amen, so be it, truth.
  544. 'omen from 'aman; verity: truth.
  545. 'omnah feminine of 'omen (in the specific sense of training); tutelage: brought up.
  546. 'omnah feminine form of 'omen (in its usual sense); adverb, surely: indeed.
  547. 'omnah feminine active participle of 'omen (in the original sense of supporting); a column: pillar.
  548. 'amanah feminine of 'amen; something fixed, i.e. a covenant. an allowance: certain portion, sure.
  549. 'Amanah the same as 'amanah; Amanah, a mountain near Damascus: Amana.
  550. 'Amnown or Amiynown; from 'aman; faithful; Amnon (or Aminon), a son of David: Amnon.
  551. 'omnam adverb from 'omen; verily: indeed, no doubt, surely, (it is, of a) true(-ly, -th).
  552. 'umnam an orthographical variation of 'omnam: in (very) deed; of a surety.
  553. 'amats a primitive root; to be alert, physically (on foot) or mentally (in courage): confirm, be courageous (of good courage, stedfastly minded, strong, stronger), establish, fortify, harden, increase, prevail, strengthen (self), make strong (obstinate, speed).
  554. 'amots probably from 'amats; of a strong color, i.e. red (others fleet): bay.
  555. 'omets from 'amats; strength: stronger.
  556. 'amtsah from 'amats; force: strength.
  557. 'Amtsiy from 'amats; strong; Amtsi, an Israelite: Amzi.
  558. 'Amatsyah or Amatsyahuw; from 'amats and Yahh; strength of Jah; Amatsjah, the name of four Israelites: Amaziah.
  559. 'amar a primitive root; to say (used with great latitude): answer, appoint, avouch, bid, boast self, call, certify, challenge, charge, + (at the, give) command(-ment), commune, consider, declare, demand, X desire, determine, X expressly, X indeed, X intend, name, X plainly, promise, publish, report, require, say, speak (against, of), X still, X suppose, talk, tell, term, X that is, X think, use (speech), utter, X verily, X yet.
  560. 'amar (Aramaic) corresponding to 'amar: command, declare, say, speak, tell.
  561. 'emer from 'amar; something said: answer, X appointed unto him, saying, speech, word.
  562. 'omer the same as 'emer: promise, speech, thing, word.
  563. 'immar (Aramaic) perhaps from 'amar (in the sense of bringing forth); a lamb: lamb.
  564. 'Immer from 'amar; talkative; Immer, the name of five Israelites: Immer.
  565. 'imrah or memrah; feminine of 'emer, and meaning the same: commandment, speech, word.
  566. 'Imriy from 'Immer; wordy; Imri, the name of two Israelites: Imri.
  567. 'Emoriy probably a patronymic from an unused name derived from 'amar in the sense of publicity, i.e. prominence; thus, a mountaineer; an Emorite, one of the Canaanitish tribes: Amorite.
  568. 'Amaryah or prolonged Amaryahuw; from 'amar and Yahh; Jah has said (i.e. promised); Amarjah, the name of nine Israelites: Amariah.
  569. 'Amraphel of uncertain (perhaps foreign) derivation; Amraphel, a king of Shinar: Amraphel.
  570. 'emesh time past, i.e. yesterday or last night:--former time, yesterday(-night)
  571. 'emeth contracted from 'aman; stability; (figuratively) certainty, truth, trustworthiness: assured(-ly), establishment, faithful, right, sure, true (-ly, -th), verity.
  572. 'amtachath from mathach; properly, something expansive, i.e. a bag: sack.
  573. 'Amittay from 'emeth; veracious; Amittai, an Israelite: Amittai.
  574. 'emtaniy (Aramaic) from a root corresponding to that of mothen; well-loined (i.e. burly) or mighty: terrible.
  575. 'an or manah; contracted from 'aiyn; where?; hence, whither?, when?; also hither and thither: + any (no) whither, now, where, whither(-soever).
  576. 'ana' (Aramaic) or .anah (Aramaic); corresponding to 'aniy; I: I, as for me.
  577. 'anna' or mannah; apparent contracted from 'ahabah and na'; oh now!: I (me) beseech (pray) thee, O.
  578. 'anah a primitive root; to groan: lament, mourn.
  579. 'anah a primitive root (perhaps rather identical with 'anah through the idea of contraction in anguish); to approach; hence, to meet in various senses: befall, deliver, happen, seek a quarrel.
  580. 'anuw contracted for 'anachnuw; we: we.
  581. 'innuwn (Aramaic) or (feminine) inniyn (Aramaic); corresponding to hem; they: X are, them, these.
  582. 'enowsh from 'anash; properly, a mortal (and thus differing from the more dignified 'adam); hence, a man in general (singly or collectively): another, X (blood-)thirsty, certain, chap(-man); divers, fellow, X in the flower of their age, husband, (certain, mortal) man, people, person, servant, some ( X of them), + stranger, those, + their trade. It is often unexpressed in the English versions, especially when used in apposition with another word. Compare 'iysh.
  583. 'Enowsh the same as 'enowsh; Enosh, a son of Seth; --Enos.

  594. 'anak probably from an unused root meaning to be narrow; according to most a plumb-line, and to others a hook: plumb-line.
  595. 'anokiy; a primitive pro.; I: I, me, X which.

  597. 'anac to insist: compel.
  598. 'anac (Aramaic) corresponding to 'anac; figuratively, to distress: trouble.
  599. 'anaph a primitive root; to breathe hard, i.e. be enraged: be angry (displeased).
  600. 'anaph (Aramaic) corresponding to 'aph (only in the plural as a singular); the face: face, visage.
  601. 'anaphah from 'anaph; an unclean bird, perhaps the parrot (from its irascibility): heron.

  604. 'anaqah the same as 'anaqah; some kind of lizard, probably the gecko (from its wail): ferret.
  605. 'anash a primitive root; to be frail, feeble, or (figuratively) melancholy: desperate(-ly wicked), incurable, sick, woeful.
  606. 'enash (Aramaic) or renash (Aramaic); corresponding to 'enowsh; a man: man, + whosoever.

  611. 'acown of uncertain derivation; hurt: mischief.
  612. 'ecuwr from 'acar; a bond (especially manacles of a prisoner): band, + prison.
  613. 'ecuwr (Aramaic) corresponding to 'ecuwr: band, imprisonment.
  614. 'aciyph or maciph; from 'acaph; gathered, i.e. (abstractly) a gathering in of crops: ingathering.

  617. 'Acciyr the same as 'acciyr; prisoner; Assir, the name of two Israelites: Assir.
  618. 'acam from an unused root meaning to heap together; a storehouse (only in the plural): barn, storehouse.
  619. 'Acnah of uncertain derivation; Asnah, one of the Nethinim: Asnah.
  620. 'Ocnappar of foreign derivation; Osnappar, an Assyrian king: Asnapper.
  621. 'Acnath of Egyptian derivation; Asenath, the wife of Joseph: Asenath.
  622. 'acaph a primitive root; to gather for any purpose; hence, to receive, take away, i.e. remove (destroy, leave behind, put up, restore, etc.): assemble, bring, consume, destroy, felch, gather (in, together, up again), X generally, get (him), lose, put all together, receive, recover (another from leprosy), (be) rereward, X surely, take (away, into, up), X utterly, withdraw.
  623. 'Acaph from 'acaph; collector; Asaph, the name of three Israelites, and of the family of the first: Asaph.
  624. 'acuph passive participle of 'acaph; collected (only in the plural), i.e. a collection of offerings): threshold, Asuppim.
  625. 'oceph from 'acaph; a collection (of fruits): gathering.
  626. 'acephah from 'acaph; a collection of people (only adverbial): X together.
  627. 'acuppah fem of 'acuph.; a collection of (learned) men (only in the plural): assembly.
  628. 'acpcuph by reduplication from 'acuph; gathered up together, i.e. a promiscuous assemblage (of people): mixt multitude.
  629. 'ocparna' (Aramaic) of Persian derivation; diligently: fast, forthwith, speed(-ily).
  630. 'Acpatha' of Persian derivation; Aspatha, a son of Haman: Aspatha.
  631. 'acar a primitive root; to yoke or hitch; by analogy, to fasten in any sense, to join battle: bind, fast, gird, harness, hold, keep, make ready, order, prepare, prison(-er), put in bonds, set in array, tie.
  632. 'ecar or riccar; from 'acar; an obligation or vow (of abstinence): binding, bond.
  633. 'ecar (Aramaic) corresponding to 'ecar in a legal sense; an interdict: decree.
  634. 'Ecar-Chaddown of foreign derivation; Esar- chaddon, an Assyrian king: Esar-haddon.
  635. 'Ecter of Persian derivation; Ester, the Jewish heroine: Esther.
  636. 'a` (Aramaic) corresponding to `ets; a tree or wood: timber, wood.
  637. 'aph a primitive particle; meaning accession (used as an adverb or conjunction); also or yea; adversatively though: also, + although, and (furthermore, yet), but, even, + how much less (more, rather than), moreover, with, yea.
  638. 'aph (Aramaic) corresponding to 'aph: also.
  639. 'aph from 'anaph; properly, the nose or nostril; hence, the face, and occasionally a person; also (from the rapid breathing in passion) ire: anger(-gry), + before, countenance, face, + forebearing, forehead, + (long-)suffering, nose, nostril, snout, X worthy, wrath.
  640. 'aphad a primitive root (rather a denominative from 'ephowd); to gird on (the ephod): bind, gird.
  641. 'Ephod the same as 'ephowd shortened; Ephod, an Israelite: Ephod.

  645. 'ephow or hephowe; from poh; strictly a demonstrative particle, here; but used of time, now or then:--here, now, where?
  646. 'ephowd rarely oephod; probably of foreign derivation; a girdle; specifically the ephod or high-priest's shoulder- piece; also generally, an image: ephod.

  657.   680. 'atsal a primitive root; properly, to join; used only as a denominative from 'etsel; to separate; hence, to select, refuse, contract: keep, reserve, straiten, take.

  834. 'aher a primitive relative pronoun (of every gender and number); who, which, what, that; also (as an adverb and a conjunction) when, where, how, because, in order that, etc.: X after, X alike, as (soon as), because, X every, for, + forasmuch, + from whence, + how(-soever), X if, (so) that ((thing) which, wherein), X though, + until, + whatsoever, when, where (+ -as, -in, -of, -on, -soever, -with), which, whilst, + whither(- soever), who(-m, -soever, -se). As it is indeclinable, it is often accompanied by the personal pronoun expletively, used to show the connection.
  835. 'esher from 'ashar; happiness; only in masculine plural construction as interjection, how happy!: blessed, happy.

  854. 'eth probably from 'anah; properly, nearness (used only as a preposition or an adverb), near; hence, generally, with, by, at, among, etc.: against, among, before, by, for, from, in(-to), (out) of, with. Often with another prepositional prefix.

  857. 'athah or matha; a primitive root (collateral to 225 contraction); to arrive: (be-, things to) come (upon), bring.
  858. 'athah (Aramaic) or wathaw (Aramaic); corresponding to 'athah: (be-)come, bring.
  859. 'attah or (shortened) aatta; or wath; feminine (irregular) sometimes nattiy; plural masculine attem; feminine atten; or oattenah; or fattennah; a primitive pronoun of the second person; thou and thee, or (plural) ye and you: thee, thou, ye, you.

  869. 'Ethnan the same as 'ethnan in the sense of 'Ethniy; Ethnan, an Israelite: Ethnan.
  870. 'athar (Aramaic) from a root corresponding to that of 'Athariym; a place; (adverb) after: after, place.

  872. b'ah from bow'; an entrance to a building: entry.

  874. ba'ar a primitive root; to dig; by analogy, to engrave; figuratively, to explain: declare, (make) plain(-ly).
  875. 'er from ba'ar; a pit; especially a well: pit, well.

  886. B'erothiy patrial from B'erowth; a Beerothite or inhabitant of Beeroth: Beerothite.
  887. ba'ash a primitive root; to smell bad; figuratively, to be offensive morally: (make to) be abhorred (had in abomination, loathsome, odious), (cause a, make to) stink(-ing savour), X utterly.

  898. bagad a primitive root; to cover (with a garment); figuratively, to act covertly; by implication, to pillage: deal deceitfully (treacherously, unfaithfully), offend, transgress(-or), (depart), treacherous (dealer, -ly, man), unfaithful(-ly, man), X very.

  929. bhemah from an unused root (probably meaning to be mute); properly, a dumb beast; especially any large quadruped or animal (often collective): beast, cattle.

  1069. bakar a primitive root; properly, to burst the womb, i.e. (causatively) bear or make early fruit (of woman or tree); also (as denominative from bikkuwr) to give the birthright: make firstborn, be firstling, bring forth first child (new fruit).
  1070. beker from bakar (in the sense of youth); a young camel: dromedary.

  1077. bal from balah; properly, a failure; by implication nothing; usually (adverb) not at all; also lest: lest, neither, no, none (that...), not (any), nothing.

  1079. bal (Aramaic) from bla'; properly, anxiety, i.e. (by implication) the heart (as its seat): heart.

  1088. Balah feminine of baleh; failure; Balah, a place in Palestine: Balah.

  1090. Bilhah from balahh; timid; Bilhah, the name of one of Jacob's concubines; also of a place in Palestine: Bilhah.

  1287. boriyth feminine of bor; vegetable alkali: sope.
  1288. barak a primitive root; to kneel; by implication to bless God (as an act of adoration), and (vice-versa) man (as a benefit); also (by euphemism) to curse (God or the king, as treason): X abundantly, X altogether, X at all, blaspheme, bless, congratulate, curse, X greatly, X indeed, kneel (down), praise, salute, X still, thank.

  1350. ga'al a primitive root, to redeem (according to the Oriental law of kinship), i.e. to be the next of kin (and as such to buy back a relative's property, marry his widow, etc.): X in any wise, X at all, avenger, deliver, (do, perform the part of near, next) kinsfolk(-man), purchase, ransom, redeem(-er), revenger.

  1496. gaziyth from gazah; something cut, i.e. dressed stone: hewed, hewn stone, wrought.

  1498. gazel from gazal; robbery, or (concretely) plunder: robbery, thing taken away by violence.

  1505. gzar (Aramaic) corresponding to gazar; to quarry; determine: cut out, soothsayer.
  1506. gezer from gazar; something cut off; a portion: part, piece.
  1507. Gezer the same as gezer; Gezer, a place in Palestine: Gazer, Gezer.
  1508. gizrah feminine of gezer; the figure or person (as if cut out); also an inclosure (as separated): polishing, separate place.

  1512. gachown probably from giyach; the external abdomen, belly (as the source of the faetus (compare Giychown)): belly.
  1513. gechel or (feminine) gacheleth; from an unused root meaning to glow or kindle; an ember: (burning) coal.
  1514. Gacham from an unused root meaning to burn; flame; Gacham, a son of Nahor: Gaham.
  1515. Gachar from an unused root meaning to hide; lurker; Gachar, one of the Nethinim: Gahar.
  1516. gay' or (shortened) gay; probably (by transmutation) from the same root as gevah (abbreviated); a gorge (from its lofty sides; hence, narrow, but not a gully or winter-torrent): valley.
  1517. giyd probably from guwd; a thong (as compressing); by analogy, a tendon: sinew.
  1518. giyach or (shortened) goach; a primitive root; to gush forth (as water), generally to issue: break forth, labor to bring forth, come forth, draw up, take out.
  1519. giyach (Aramaic) or (shortened) guwach (Aramaic); corresponding to giyach; to rush forth: strive.
  1520. Giyach from giyach; a fountain; Giach, a place in Palestine: Giah.
  1521. Giychown or (shortened) Gichown; from giyach; stream; Gichon, a river of Paradise; also a valley (or pool) near Jerusalem: Gihon.
  1522. Geychaziy or Gechaziy; apparently from gay' and chazah; valley of a visionary; Gechazi, the servant of Elisha: Gehazi.
  1523. giyl or (by permutation) guwl; a primitive root; properly, to spin round (under the influence of any violent emotion), i.e. usually rejoice, or (as cringing) fear: be glad, joy, be joyful, rejoice.
  1524. giyl from giyl; a revolution (of time, i.e. an age); also joy: X exceedingly, gladness, X greatly, joy, rejoice(-ing), sort.

  1530. gal from galal; something rolled, i.e. a heap of stone or dung (plural ruins), by analogy, a spring of water (plural waves): billow, heap, spring, wave.

  1570. galash a primitive root; probably to caper (as a goat): appear.
  1571. gam by contraction from an unused root meaning to gather; properly, assemblage; used only adverbially also, even, yea, though; often repeated as correl. both...and: again, alike, also, (so much) as (soon), both (so)...and, but, either...or, even, for all, (in) likewise (manner), moreover, nay...neither, one, then(-refore), though, what, with, yea.
  1572. gama' a primitive root (literally or figuratively) to absorb: swallow, drink.

  1576. gmuwl from gamal; treatment, i.e. an act (of good or ill); by implication, service or requital: + as hast served, benefit, desert, deserving, that which he hath given, recompense, reward.

  1579. Gimzow of uncertain derivation; Gimzo, a place in Palestine: Gimzo.
  1580. gamal a primitive root; to treat a person (well or ill), i.e. benefit or requite; by implication (of toil), to ripen, i.e. (specifically) to wean: bestow on, deal bountifully, do (good), recompense, requite, reward, ripen, + serve, mean, yield.
  1581. gamal apparently from gamal (in the sense of labor or burden-bearing); a camel: camel.

  1604. go`al from ga`al; abhorrence: loathing.

  1639. gara` a primitive root; to scrape off; by implication, to shave, remove, lessen, withhold: abate, clip, (di-)minish, do (take) away, keep back, restrain, make small, withdraw.

  1719. Ddan or (prolonged) Ddaneh (Ezek. 25:13); of uncertain derivation; Dedan, the name of two Cushites and of their territory: Dedan.

  1730. dowd or (shortened) dod; from an unused root meaning properly, to boil, i.e. (figuratively) to love; by implication, a love- token, lover, friend; specifically an uncle: (well-)beloved, father's brother, love, uncle.
  1731. duwd from the same as dowd; a pot (for boiling); also (by resemblance of shape) a basket: basket, caldron, kettle, (seething) pot.
  1732. David rarely (fully); Daviyd; from the same as dowd; loving; David, the youngest son of Jesse: David.
  1733. dowdah feminine of dowd; an aunt: aunt, father's sister, uncle's wife.
  1734. Dowdow from dowd; loving; Dodo, the name of three Israelites: Dodo.

  1738. davah a primitive root; to be sick (as if in menstruation): infirmity.

  1742. davvay from daveh; sick; figuratively, troubled: faint.

  1744. duwkiyphath of uncertain derivation; the hoopoe or else the grouse: lapwing.

  1746. Duwmah the same as duwmah; Dumah, a tribe and region of Arabia: Dumah.

  1749. downag of uncertain derivation; wax; -wax.
  1750. duwts a primitive root; to leap: be turned.
  1751. duwq (Aramaic) corresponding to daqaq; to crumble: be broken to pieces.
  1752. duwr a primitive root; properly, to gyrate (or move in a circle), i.e. to remain: dwell.
  1753. duwr (Aramaic) corresponding to duwr; to reside: dwell.

  1756. Dowr or (by permutation) Dorr (Josh. 17:11; 1 Kings 4:11); from dowr; dwelling; Dor, a place in Palestine: Dor.

  1758. duwsh or dowsh; or diysh; a primitive root; to trample or thresh: break, tear, thresh, tread out (down), at grass (Jer. 50:11, by mistake for deshe').
  1759. duwsh (Aramaic) corresponding to duwsh; to trample: tread down.

  1761. dachavah (Aramaic) from the equivalent of dachah; probably a musical instrument (as being struck): instrument of music.

  1766. dachaq a primitive root; to press, i.e. oppress: thrust, vex.
  1767. day of uncertain derivation; enough (as noun or adverb), used chiefly with preposition in phrases: able, according to, after (ability), among, as (oft as), (more than) enough, from, in, since, (much as is) sufficient(-ly), too much, very, when.
  1768. diy (Aramaic) apparently for da'; that, used as relative conjunction, and especially (with a preposition) in adverbial phrases; also as preposition of: X as, but, for(-asmuch +), + now, of, seeing, than, that, therefore, until, + what (-soever), when, which, whom, whose.

  1800. dal from dalal; properly, dangling, i.e. (by implication) weak or thin: lean, needy, poor (man), weaker.

  1815. dlaq (Aramaic) corresponding to dalaq: burn.
