  5736. `adaph a primitive root; to be (causatively, have) redundant: be more, odd number, be (have) over (and above), overplus, remain.
  5737. `adar a primitive root; to arrange, as a battle, a vineyard (to hoe); hence, to muster and so to miss (or find wanting): dig, fail, keep (rank), lack.
  5738. `Eder from `adar; an arrangement (i.e. drove); Eder, an Israelite: Ader.
  5739. `eder from `adar; an arrangement, i.e. muster (of animals): drove, flock, herd.

  5741. `Adriy'el from `eder and 'el; flock of God; Adriel, an Israelite: Adriel.
  5742. `adash from an unused root of uncertain meaning; a lentil: lentile.
  5743. `uwb a primitive root; to be dense or dark, i.e. to becloud: cover with a cloud.
  5744. `Owbed active participle of `abad; serving; Obed, the name of five Israelites: Obed.
  5745. `Owbal of foreign derivation; Obal, a son of Joktan: Obal.
  5746. `uwg a primitive root; properly, to gyrate; but used only as a denominative from `uggah, to bake (round cakes on the hearth): bake.
  5747. `Owg probably from `uwg; round; Og, a king of Bashan: Og.
  5748. `uwgab or buggab; from `agab in the original sense of breathing; a reed-instrument of music: organ.
  5749. `uwd a primitive root; to duplicate or repeat; by implication, to protest, testify (as by reiteration); intensively, to encompass, restore (as a sort of reduplication): admonish, charge, earnestly, lift up, protest, call (take) to record, relieve, rob, solemnly, stand upright, testify, give warning, (bear, call to, give, take to) witness.
  5750. `owd or rod; from `uwd; properly, iteration or continuance; used only adverbially (with or without preposition), again, repeatedly, still, more: again, X all life long, at all, besides, but, else, further(-more), henceforth, (any) longer, (any) more(-over), X once, since, (be) still, when, (good, the) while (having being), (as, because, whether, while) yet (within).
  5751. `owd (Aramaic) corresponding to `owd: while.
  5752. `Owded or Oded; from `uwd; reiteration; Oded, the name of two Israelites: Oded.
  5753. `avah a primitive root; to crook, literally or figuratively (as follows): do amiss, bow down, make crooked, commit iniquity, pervert, (do) perverse(-ly), trouble, X turn, do wickedly, do wrong.
  5754. `avvah intensive from `avah abbreviated; overthrow: X overturn.

  5764. `uwl from `uwl; a babe: sucking child, infant.
  5765. `aval a primitive root; to distort (morally): deal unjustly, unrighteous.
  5766. `evel or lavel; and (feminine) lavlah; or owlah; or .olah; from `aval; (moral) evil: iniquity, perverseness, unjust(-ly), unrighteousness(-ly); wicked(-ness).
  5767. `avval intensive from `aval; evil (morally): unjust, unrighteous, wicked.
  5768. `owlel or lolal; from `uwl; a suckling: babe, (young) child, infant, little one.
  5769. `owlam or lolam; from `alam; properly, concealed, i.e. the vanishing point; generally, time out of mind (past or future), i.e. (practically) eternity; frequentatively, adverbial (especially with prepositional prefix) always: alway(-s), ancient (time), any more, continuance, eternal, (for, (n-))ever(-lasting, -more, of old), lasting, long (time), (of) old (time), perpetual, at any time, (beginning of the) world (+ without end). Compare netsach, `ad.
  5770. `avan denominative from `ayin; to watch (with jealosy): eye.

  5772. `ownah from an unused root apparently meaning to dwell together; sexual (cohabitation): duty of marriage.

  5774. `uwph a primitive root; to cover (with wings or obscurity); hence (as denominative from `owph) to fly; also (by implication of dimness) to faint (from the darkness of swooning): brandish, be (wax) faint, flee away, fly (away), X set, shine forth, weary.
  5775. `owph from `uwph; a bird (as covered with feathers, or rather as covering with wings), often collectively: bird, that flieth, flying, fowl.
  5776. `owph (Aramaic) corresponding to `owph: fowl.
  5777. `owphereth or mophereth; feminine participle active of `aphar; lead (from its dusty color): lead.

  5779. `uwts a primitive root; to consult: take advice ((counsel) together).
  5780. `Uwts apparently from `uwts; consultation; Uts, a son of Aram, also a Seirite, and the regions settled by them.: Uz.
  5781. `uwq a primitive root; to pack: be pressed.

  5921. `al properly, the same as `al used as a preposition (in the singular or plural often with prefix, or as conjunction with a particle following); above, over, upon, or against (yet always in this last relation with a downward aspect) in a great variety of applications (as follow): above, according to(-ly), after, (as) against, among, and, X as, at, because of, beside (the rest of), between, beyond the time, X both and, by (reason of), X had the charge of, concerning for, in (that), (forth, out) of, (from) (off), (up-)on, over, than, through(-out), to, touching, X with.

  5927. `alah a primitive root; to ascend, intransitively (be high) or actively (mount); used in a great variety of senses, primary and secondary, literal and figurative (as follow): arise (up), (cause to) ascend up, at once, break (the day) (up), bring (up), (cause to) burn, carry up, cast up, + shew, climb (up), (cause to, make to) come (up), cut off, dawn, depart, exalt, excel, fall, fetch up, get up, (make to) go (away, up); grow (over) increase, lay, leap, levy, lift (self) up, light, (make) up, X mention, mount up, offer, make to pay, + perfect, prefer, put (on), raise, recover, restore, (make to) rise (up), scale, set (up), shoot forth (up), (begin to) spring (up), stir up, take away (up), work.

  7139. qarach a primitive root; to depilate: make (self) bald.

  7194. qashar a primitive root: to tie, physically (gird, confine, compact) or mentally (in love, league): bind (up), (make a) conspire(-acy, -ator), join together, knit, stronger, work (treason).

  7757. shuwl from an unused root meaning to hang down; a skirt; by implication, a bottom edge: hem, skirt, train.
  7758. showlal or sheylal (Micah 1:8); from shalal; nude (especially bare-foot); by implication, captive: spoiled, stripped.
  7759. Shuwlammiyth from shalam; peaceful (with the article always prefixed, making it a pet name); the Shulammith, an epithet of Solomon's queen: Shulamite.
  7760. suwm or siym; a primitive root; to put (used in a great variety of applications, literal, figurative, inferentially, and elliptically): X any wise, appoint, bring, call (a name), care, cast in, change, charge, commit, consider, convey, determine, + disguise, dispose, do, get, give, heap up, hold, impute, lay (down, up), leave, look, make (out), mark, + name, X on, ordain, order, + paint, place, preserve, purpose, put (on), + regard, rehearse, reward, (cause to) set (on, up), shew, + stedfastly, take, X tell, + tread down, ((over-))turn, X wholly, work.
  7761. suwm (Aramaic) corresponding to suwm: + command, give, lay, make, + name, + regard, set.
  7762. shuwm from an unused root meaning to exhale; garlic (from its rank odor): garlic.
  7763. Showmer or Shomer; active participle of shamar; keeper; Shomer, the name of two Israelites: Shomer.
  7764. Shuwniy from an unused root meaning to rest; quiet; Shuni, an Israelite: Shuni.
  7765. Shuwniy patronymic from Shuwniy; a Shunite (collectively) or descendants of Shuni: Shunites.
  7766. Shuwnem probably from the same as Shuwniy; quietly; Shunem, a place in Pal: Shunem.
  7767. Shuwnammiyth patrial from Shuwnem; a Shunammitess, or female inhabitant of Shunem: Shunamite.
  7768. shava` a primitive root; properly, to be free; but used only causatively and reflexively, to halloo (for help, i.e. freedom from some trouble): cry (aloud, out), shout.
  7769. shuwa` from shava`; a halloo: cry, riches.
  7770. Shuwa` the same as shuwa`; Shua, a Canaanite: Shua, Shuah.
  7771. showa` from shava` in the original sense of freedom; a noble, i.e. liberal, opulent; also (as noun in the derived sense) a halloo: bountiful, crying, rich.
  7772. Showa` the same as showa`; rich; Shoa, an Oriental people: Shoa.
  7773. sheva` from shava`; a halloo: cry.
  7774. Shuwa`a' from shava`; wealth; Shua, an Israelitess: Shua.
  7775. shav`ah feminine of sheva`; a hallooing: crying.
  7776. shuw`al or shunal; from the same as sho`al; a jackal (as a burrower): fox.
  7777. Shuw`al the same as shuw`al; Shual, the name of an Israelite and of a place in Palestine: Shual.
  7778. show`er or shomer : active participle of sha`ar (as denominative from sha`ar); a janitor: doorkeeper, porter.
  7779. shuwph a primitive root; properly, to gape, i.e. snap at; figuratively, to overwhelm: break, bruise, cover.
  7780. Showphak from shaphak; poured; Shophak, a Syrian: Shophach.
  7781. Shuwphamiy patronymic from Shphuwpham; a Shuphamite (collectively) or descendants of Shephupham: Shuphamite.
  7782. showphar or shophar; from shaphar in the original sense of incising; a cornet (as giving a clear sound) or curved horn: cornet, trumpet.
  7783. shuwq a primitive root; to run after or over, i.e. overflow: overflow, water.
  7784. shuwq from shuwq; a street (as run over): street.
  7785. showq from shuwq; the (lower) leg (as a runner): hip, leg, shoulder, thigh.
  7786. suwr a primitive root; properly, to vanquish; by implication, to rule (causatively, crown): make princes, have power, reign. See cuwr.
  7787. suwr a primitive root (identical with suwr through the idea of reducing to pieces; compare massowr); to saw: cut.
  7788. shuwr a primitive root; properly, to turn, i.e. travel about (as a harlot or a merchant): go, singular See also shiyr.
  7789. shuwr a primitive root (identical with shuwr through the idea of going round for inspection); to spy out, i.e. (generally) survey, (for evil) lurk for, (for good) care for: behold, lay wait, look, observe, perceive, regard, see.
  7790. shuwr from Shiymown; a foe (as lying in wait): enemy.
  7791. shuwr from shuwr; a wall (as going about): wall.

  7793. Shuwr the same as shuwr; Shur, a region of the Desert: Shur.
  7794. showr from shuwr; a bullock (as a traveller): bull(-ock), cow, ox, wall (by mistake for shuwr).
  7795. sowrah from suwr in the primitive sense of cuwr; properly, a ring, i.e. (by analogy) a row (adverbially): principal.
  7796. Sowreq the same as soreq; a vine; Sorek, a valley in Palestine: Sorek.
  7797. suws or siys; a primitive root; to be bright, i.e. cheerful: be glad, X greatly, joy, make mirth, rejoice.

  7799. shuwshan or showshan; or shoshan; and (feminine) showshannah; from suws; a lily (from its whiteness), as a flower of arch. ornament; also a (straight) trumpet (from the tubular shape): lily, Shoshannim.
  7800. Shuwshan the same as shuwshan; Shushan, a place in Persia: Shushan.

  7802. Shuwshan `Eduwth or (plural of former) Showshanniym Eduwth; from shuwshan and `eduwth; lily (or trumpet) of assemblage; Shushan-Eduth or Shoshannim-Eduth, the title of a popular song: Shoshannim-Eduth, Shushan-eduth.

  7804. shzab (Aramaic) corresponding to `azab; to leave, i.e. (causatively) free: deliver.
  7805. shazaph a primitive root; to tan (by sun-burning); figuratively (as if by a piercing ray) to scan: look up, see.
  7806. shazar a primitive root; to twist (a thread of straw): twine.

  7809. shachad a primitive root; to donate, i.e. bribe: hire, give a reward.

  7811. sachah a primitive root; to swim; causatively, to inundate: (make to) swim.
  7812. shachah a primitive root; to depress, i.e. prostrate (especially reflexive, in homage to royalty or God): bow (self) down, crouch, fall down (flat), humbly beseech, do (make) obeisance, do reverence, make to stoop, worship.
  7813. sachuw from sachah; a pond (for swimming): to swim in.
  7814. schowq or schoq; from sachaq; laughter (in merriment or defiance): derision, laughter(-ed to scorn, -ing), mocked, sport.

  7816. shchuwth from shachah; pit: pit.

  7819. shachat a primitive root; to slaughter (in sacrifice or massacre): kill, offer, shoot out, slay, slaughter.

  7821. shchiytah from shachat; slaughter: killing.
  7822. shchiyn from an unused root probably meaning to burn; inflammation, i.e. an ulcer; --boil, botch.
  7823. shachiyc or cachiysh; from an unused root apparently meaning to sprout; after-growth: (that) which springeth of the same.
  7824. shachiyph from the same as shachaph; a board (as chipped thin): cieled with.
  7825. shchiyth from shachah; a pit-fall (literally or figuratively): destruction, pit.

  7830. shachats from an unused root apparently meaning to strut; haughtiness (as evinced by the attitude): X lion, pride.
  7831. Shachatsowm from the same as shachats; proudly; Shachatsom, a place in Palestine: Shahazimah (from the margin).
  7832. sachaq a primitive root; to laugh (in pleasure or detraction); by implication, to play: deride, have in derision, laugh, make merry, mock(-er), play, rejoice, (laugh to) scorn, be in (make) sport.
  7833. shachaq a primitive root; to comminate (by trituration or attrition): beat, wear.
  7834. shachaq from shachaq; a powder (as beaten small): by analogy, a thin vapor; by extension, the firmament: cloud, small dust, heaven, sky.
  7835. shachar a primitive root (identical with shachar through the idea of the duskiness of early dawn); to be dim or dark (in color): be black.
  7836. shachar a primitive root; properly, to dawn, i.e. (figuratively) be (up) early at any task (with the implication of earnestness); by extension, to search for (with painstaking): (do something) betimes, enquire early, rise (seek) betimes, seek diligently) early, in the morning).
  7837. shachar from shachar; dawn (literal, figurative or adverbial): day(-spring), early, light, morning, whence riseth.
  7838. shachor or shachowr; from shachar; properly, dusky, but also (absol.) jetty: black.
  7839. shacharuwth from shachar; a dawning, i.e. (figuratively) juvenescence: youth.
  7840. shcharchoreth from shachar; swarthy: black.
  7841. Shcharyah from shachar and Yahh; Jah has sought; Shecharjah, an Israelite: Shehariah.
  7842. Shacharayim dual of shachar; double dawn; Shacharajim, an Israelite: Shaharaim.
  7843. shachath a primitive root; to decay, i.e. (causatively) ruin (literally or figuratively): batter, cast off, corrupt(-er, thing), destroy(-er, -uction), lose, mar, perish, spill, spoiler, X utterly, waste(-r).
  7844. shchath (Aramaic) corresponding to shachath: corrupt, fault.
  7845. shachath from shuwach; a pit (especially as a trap); figuratively, destruction: corruption, destruction, ditch, grave, pit.
  7846. set or cet; from suwt; a departure from right, i.e. sin: revolter, that turn aside.

  7848. shittah feminine of a derivative (only in the plural shittiym; meaning the sticks of wood) from the same as shotet; the acacia (from its scourging thorns): shittah, shittim. See also Beyth hash-Shittah.
  7849. shatach a primitive root; to expand: all abroad, enlarge, spread, stretch out.

  7851. Shittiym the same as the plural of shittah; acacia trees; Shittim, a place East of the Jordan: Shittim.
  7852. satam a primitive root; properly, to lurk for, i.e. persecute: hate, oppose self against.
  7853. satan a primitive root; to attack, (figuratively) accuse: (be an) adversary, resist.
  7854. satan from satan; an opponent; especially (with the article prefixed) Satan, the arch-enemy of good: adversary, Satan, withstand.
  7855. sitnah from satan; opposition (by letter): accusation.
  7856. Sitnan the same as sitnah; Sitnah, the name of a well in Pal: Sitnah.
  7857. shataph a primitive root; to gush; by implication, to inundate, cleanse; by analogy, to gallop, conquer: drown, (over-)flow(- whelm, rinse, run, rush, (throughly) wash (away).

  7863. siy' from the same as sow' by permutation; elevation: excellency.

  7873. siyg from suwg; a withdrawal (into a private place): pursuing.

  7875. siyd from siyd; lime (as boiling when slacked): lime, plaister.
  7876. shayah a primitive root; to keep in memory: be unmindful. (Render Deuteronomy 32:18, "A Rock bore thee, thou must recollect; and (yet) thou hast forgotten," etc.)
  7877. Shiyza' of unknown derivation; Shiza, an Is.: Shiza.

  7879. siyach from siyach; a contemplation; by implication, an utterance: babbling, communication, complaint, meditation, prayer, talk.

  7899. sek from cakak in the sense of suwk; a brier (as of a hedge): prick.
  7900. sok from cakak in the sense of suwk; a booth (as interlaced): tabernacle.
  7901. shakab a primitive root; to lie down (for rest, sexual connection, decease or any other purpose): X at all, cast down, ((lover-))lay (self) (down), (make to) lie (down, down to sleep, still with), lodge, ravish, take rest, sleep, stay.
  7902. shkabah from shakab; a lying down (of dew, or for the sexual act): X carnally, copulation, X lay, seed.

  7919. sakal a primitive root; to be (causatively, make or act) circumspect and hence, intelligent: consider, expert, instruct, prosper, (deal) prudent(-ly), (give) skill(-ful), have good success, teach, (have, make to) understand(-ing), wisdom, (be, behave self, consider, make) wise(- ly), guide wittingly.

  7921. shakol a primitive root; properly, to miscarry, i.e. suffer abortion; by analogy, to bereave (literally or figuratively): bereave (of children), barren, cast calf (fruit, young), be (make) childless, deprive, destroy, X expect, lose children, miscarry, rob of children, spoil.

  7925. shakam a primitive root; properly, to incline (the shoulder to a burden); but used only as denominative from shkem; literally, to load up (on the back of man or beast), i.e. to start early in the morning: (arise, be up, get (oneself) up, rise up) early (betimes), morning.

  7938. seker from sakar; wages: reward, sluices.

  7949. shalag a primitive root; properly, meaning to be white; used only as denominative from sheleg; to be snow-white (with the linen clothing of the slain): be as snow.
  7950. sheleg from shalag; snow (probably from its whiteness): snow(-y).
  7951. shalah or shalav (Job 3:26); a primitive root; to be tranquil, i.e. secure or successful: be happy, prosper, be in safety.
  7952. shalah a primitive root (probably identical with shalah through the idea of educing); to mislead: deceive, be negligent.
  7953. shalah a primitive root (rather cognate (by contraction) to the base of nashal, shalal and their congeners through the idea of extracting); to draw out or off, i.e. remove (the soul by death): take away.

  7955. shalah (Aramaic) from a root corresponding to shalah; a wrong: thing amiss.

  7957. shalhebeth from the same as lahab with sibilant prefix; a flare of fire: (flaming) flame.

  7959. shelev from shalah; security: prosperity.
  7960. shaluw (Aramaic) or shaluwth (Aramaic); from the same as shalah; a fault: error, X fail, thing amiss.

  7963. shlevah (Aramaic) corresponding to shalvah; safety: tranquillity. See also shalev.
  7964. shilluwach or shilluach; from shalach; (only in plural) a dismissal, i.e. (of a wife) divorce (especially the document); also (of a daughter) dower: presents, have sent back.
  7965. shalowm or shalom; from shalam; safe, i.e. (figuratively) well, happy, friendly; also (abstractly) welfare, i.e. health, prosperity, peace: X do, familiar, X fare, favour, + friend, X great, (good) health, (X perfect, such as be at) peace(-able, -ably), prosper(-ity, -ous), rest, safe(-ty), salute, welfare, (X all is, be) well, X wholly.
  7966. shilluwm or shillum; from shalam; a requital, i.e. (secure) retribution, (venal) a fee: recompense, reward.
  7967. Shalluwm or (shorter) Shallum; the same as shilluwm; Shallum, the name of fourteen Israelites: Shallum.
  7968. Shalluwn probably for Shalluwm; Shallun, an Israelite: Shallum.
  7969. shalowsh or shalosh; masculine shlowshah; or shloshah; a primitive number; three; occasionally (ordinal) third, or (multipl.) thrice: + fork, + often(-times), third, thir(-teen, -teenth), three, + thrice. Compare shaliysh.
  7970. shlowshiym or shloshiym; multiple of shalowsh; thirty; or (ordinal) thirtieth: thirty, thirtieth. Compare shaliysh.
  7971. shalach a primitive root; to send away, for, or out (in a great variety of applications): X any wise, appoint, bring (on the way), cast (away, out), conduct, X earnestly, forsake, give (up), grow long, lay, leave, let depart (down, go, loose), push away, put (away, forth, in, out), reach forth, send (away, forth, out), set, shoot (forth, out), sow, spread, stretch forth (out).
  7972. shlach (Aramaic) corresponding to shalach: put, send.
  7973. shelach from shalach; a missile of attack, i.e. spear; also (figuratively) a shoot of growth; i.e. branch: dart, plant, X put off, sword, weapon.
  7974. Shelach the same as shelach; Shelach, a postdiluvian patriarch: Salah, Shelah. Compare Shiloach.
  7975. Shiloach or (in imitation of Shelach) Shelach (Neh. 3:15); from shalach; rill; Shiloach, a fountain of Jerusalem: Shiloah, Siloah.
  7976. shilluchah feminine of shilluwach; a shoot: branch.
  7977. Shilchiy from shelach; missive, i.e. armed; Shilchi, an Israelite: Shilhi.
  7978. Shilchiym plural of shelach; javelins or sprouts; Shilchim, a place in Palestine: Shilhim.
  7979. shulchan from shalach; a table (as spread out); by implication, a meal: table.
  7980. shalat a primitive root; to dominate, i.e. govern; by implication, to permit: (bear, have) rule, have dominion, give (have) power.
  7981. shlet (Aramaic) corresponding to shalat: have the mastery, have power, bear rule, be (make) ruler.
  7982. shelet from shalat; probably a shield (as controlling, i.e. protecting the person): shield.

  7984. shiltown (Aramaic) or shilton (Aramaic); corresponding to shiltown: ruler.

  7986. shalleteth feminine from shalat; a vixen: imperious.
  7987. shliy from shalah; privacy: + quietly.
  7988. shilyah feminine from shalah; a fetus or babe (as extruded in birth): young one.
  7989. shalliyt from shalat; potent; concretely, a prince or warrior: governor, mighty, that hath power, ruler.
  7990. shalliyt (Aramaic) corresponding to shalliyt; mighty; abstractly, permission; concretely, a premier: captain, be lawful, rule(- r).
  7991. shaliysh or shalowsh ( 1 Chron. 11:11; 12:18); or shalosh (2 Sam. 23:13); from shalowsh; a triple, i.e. (as a musical instrument) a triangle (or perhaps rather three-stringed lute); also (as an indefinite, great quantity) a three-fold measure (perhaps a treble ephah); also (as an officer) a general of the third rank (upward, i.e. the highest): captain, instrument of musick, (great) lord, (great) measure, prince, three (from the margin).
  7992. shliyshiy ordinal from shalowsh; third; feminine a third (part); by extension, a third (day, year or time); specifically, a third-story cell): third (part, rank, time), three (years old).
  7993. shalak a primitive root; to throw out, down or away (literally or figuratively): adventure, cast (away, down, forth, off, out), hurl, pluck, throw.
  7994. shalak from shalak; bird of prey, usually thought to be the pelican (from casting itself into the sea): cormorant.
  7995. shalleketh from shalak; a felling (of trees): when cast.
  7996. Shalleketh the same as shalleketh; Shalleketh, a gate in Jerusalem: Shalleketh.
  7997. shalal a primitive root; to drop or strip; by implication, to plunder: let fall, make self a prey, X of purpose, (make a, (take)) spoil.
  7998. shalal from shalal; booty: prey, spoil.
  7999. shalam a primitive root; to be safe (in mind, body or estate); figuratively, to be (causatively, make) completed; by implication, to be friendly; by extension, to reciprocate (in various applications): make amends, (make an) end, finish, full, give again, make good, (re-)pay (again), (make) (to) (be at) peace(-able), that is perfect, perform, (make) prosper(-ous), recompense, render, requite, make restitution, restore, reward, X surely.

  8033. sham a primitive particle (rather from the relative pronoun, 'aher); there (transferring to time) then; often thither, or thence: in it, + thence, there (-in, + of, + out), + thither, + whither.
  8034. shem a primitive word (perhaps rather from suwm through the idea of definite and conspicuous position; compare shamayim); an appellation, as a mark or memorial of individuality; by implication honor, authority, character: + base, (in-)fame(-ous), named(-d), renown, report.

  8040. smo'wl or smosl; a primitive word (rather perhaps from the same as simlah (by insertion of the aleph) through the idea of wrapping up); properly, dark (as enveloped), i.e. the north; hence (by orientation), the left hand: left (hand, side).

  8055. samach a primitive root; probably to brighten up, i.e. (figuratively) be (causatively, make) blithe or gleesome: cheer up, be (make) glad, (have, make) joy(-ful), be (make) merry, (cause to, make to) rejoice, X very.
  8056. sameach from samach; blithe or gleeful: (be) glad, joyful, (making) merry((-hearted), -ily), rejoice(-ing).

  8066. shmiyniy from shmoneh; eight: eight.

  8070. Shmiyramowth or Shmariymowth; probably from shem and plural of ramah; name of heights; Shemiramoth, the name of two Israelites: Shemiramoth.

  8085. shama` a primitive root; to hear intelligently (often with implication of attention, obedience, etc.; causatively, to tell, etc.): X attentively, call (gather) together, X carefully, X certainly, consent, consider, be content, declare, X diligently, discern, give ear, (cause to, let, make to) hear(-ken, tell), X indeed, listen, make (a) noise, (be) obedient, obey, perceive, (make a) proclaim(-ation), publish, regard, report, shew (forth), (make a) sound, X surely, tell, understand, whosoever (heareth), witness.

  8602. taphel from an unused root meaning to smear; plaster (as gummy) or slime; (figuratively) frivolity: foolish things, unsavoury, untempered.

  8608. taphaph a primitive root; to drum, i.e. play (as) on the tambourine: taber, play with timbrels.
  8609. taphar a primitive root; to sew: (women that) sew (together).
  8610. taphas a primitive root; to manipulate, i.e. seize; chiefly to capture, wield, specifically, to overlay; figuratively, to use unwarrantably: catch, handle, (lay, take) hold (on, over), stop, X surely, surprise, take.
  8611. topheth from the base of taphaph; a smiting, i.e. (figuratively) contempt: tabret.
  8612. Topheth the same as topheth; Topheth, a place near Jerusalem: Tophet, Topheth.
