  8614. tiphtay (Aramaic) perhaps from shaphat; judicial, i.e. a lawyer: sheriff.
  8615. tiqvah from qavah; literally, a cord (as an attachment (compare qaveh)); figuratively, expectancy: expectation ((-ted)), hope, live, thing that I long for.
  8616. Tiqvah the same as tiqvah; Tikvah, the name of two Israelites: Tikvah.
  8617. tquwmah from quwm; resistfulness: power to stand.
  8618. tqowmem from quwm; an opponent: rise up against.
  8619. taqowa` from taqa` (in the musical sense); a trumpet: trumpet.
  8620. Tqowa` a form of taqowa`; Tekoa, a place in Palestine: Tekoa, Tekoah.
  8621. Tqow`iy or Tqo iy; patronymically from Tqowa`; a Tekoite or inhabitant of Tekoah: Tekoite.
  8622. tquwphah or tquphah; from naqaph; a revolution, i.e. (of the sun) course, (of time) lapse: circuit, come about, end.
  8623. taqqiyph from taqaph; powerful: mightier.
  8624. taqqiyph (Aramaic) corresponding to taqqiyph: mighty, strong.
  8625. tqal (Aramaic) corresponding to shaqal; to balance: Tekel, be weighed.
  8626. taqan a primitive root; to equalize, i.e. straighten (intransitive or transitive); figuratively, to compose: set in order, make straight.
  8627. tqan (Aramaic) corresponding to taqan; to straighten up, i.e. confirm: establish.
  8628. taqa` a primitive root; to clatter, i.e. slap (the hands together), clang (an instrument); by analogy, to drive (a nail or tent-pin, a dart, etc.); by implication, to become bondsman by handclasping): blow ((a trumpet)), cast, clap, fasten, pitch (tent), smite, sound, strike, X suretiship, thrust.
  8629. teqa` from taqa`; a blast of a trumpet: sound.
  8630. taqaph a primitive root; to overpower: prevail (against).
  8631. tqeph (Aramaic) corresponding to taqaph; to become (causatively, make) mighty or (figuratively) obstinate: make firm, harden, be(-come) strong.
  8632. tqoph (Aramaic) corresponding to toqeph; power: might, strength.
  8633. toqeph from taqaph; might or (figuratively) positiveness: authority, power, strength.
  8634. Tar'alah probably for tar`elah; a reeling; Taralah, a place in Palestine: Taralah.
  8635. tarbuwth from rabah; multiplication, i.e. progeny: increase.
  8636. tarbiyth from rabah; multiplication, i.e. percentage or bonus in addition to principal: increase, unjust gain.
  8637. tirgal a denominative from ragal; to cause to walk: teach to go.
  8638. tirgam a denominative from ragam in the sense of throwing over; to transfer, i.e. translate: interpret.
  8639. tardemah from radam; a lethargy or (by implication) trance: deep sleep.
  8640. Tirhaqah of foreign derivation; Tirhakah, a king of Kush: Tirhakah.
  8641. truwmah or trumah (Deut. 12:11); from ruwm; a present (as offered up), especially in sacrifice or as tribute: gift, heave offering ((shoulder)), oblation, offered(-ing).
  8642. truwmiyah formed as truwmah; a sacrificial offering: oblation.
  8643. truw`ah from ruwa`; clamor, i.e. acclamation of joy or a battle-cry; especially clangor of trumpets, as an alarum: alarm, blow(- ing) (of, the) (trumpets), joy, jubile, loud noise, rejoicing, shout(-ing), (high, joyful) sound(-ing).
  8644. truwphah from ruwph in the sense of its congener rapha'; a remedy: medicine.
  8645. tirzah probably from razah; a species of tree (apparently from its slenderness), perhaps the cypress: cypress.
  8646. Terach of uncertain derivation; Terach, the father of Abraham; also a place in the Desert: Tarah, Terah.
  8647. Tirchanah of uncertain derivation; Tirchanah, an Israelite: Tirhanah.
  8648. treyn (Aramaic) feminine tarteyn (Aramaic); corresponding to shnayim; two: second, + twelve, two.
  8649. tormah and tarmuwth; or tarmiyth; from ramah; fraud: deceit(-ful), privily.
  8650. toren probably for 'oren; a pole (as a mast or flag-staff): beacon, mast.
  8651. tra` (Aramaic) corresponding to sha`ar; a door; by implication, a palace: gate mouth.
  8652. tara` (Aramaic) from tra`; a doorkeeper: porter.
  8653. tar`elah from ra`al; reeling: astonishment, trembling.
  8654. Tir`athiy patrial from an unused name meaning gate; a Tirathite or inhabitant of an unknown Tirah: Tirathite.
  8655. traphiym plural from rapha'; a healer; Teraphim (singular or plural) a family idol: idols(-atry), images, teraphim.
  8656. Tirtsah from ratsah; delightsomeness; Tirtsah, a place in Palestine; also an Israelitess: Tirzah.
  8657. Teresh of foreign derivation; Teresh, a eunuch of Xerxes: Teresh.
  8658. tarshiysh probably of foreign derivation (compare Tarshiysh); a gem, perhaps the topaz: beryl.
  8659. Tarshiysh probably the same as tarshiysh (as the region of the stone, or the reverse); Tarshish, a place on the Mediterranean, hence, the ephithet of a merchant vessel (as if for or from that port); also the name of a Persian and of an Israelite: Tarshish, Tharshish.
  8660. Tirshatha' of foreign derivation; the title of a Persian deputy or governor: Tirshatha.
  8661. Tartan of foreign derivation; Tartan, an Assyrian: Tartan.
  8662. Tartaq of foreign derivation; Tartak, a deity of the Avvites: Tartak.
  8663. tshu'ah from show'; a crashing or loud clamor: crying, noise, shouting, stir.
  8664. Tishbiy patrial from an unused name meaning recourse; a Tishbite or inhabitant of Tishbeh (in Gilead): Tishbite.
  8665. tashbets from shabats; checkered stuff (as reticulated): broidered.
  8666. tshuwbah or tshubah; from shuwb; a recurrence (of time or place); a reply (as returned): answer, be expired, return.
  8667. tsuwmeth from suwm; a deposit, i.e. pledging: + fellowship.
  8668. tshuw`ah or tshuah; from shava` in the sense of yasha`; rescue (literal or figurative, pers., national or spir.): deliverance, help, safety, salvation, victory.
  8669. tshuwqah from shuwq in the original sense of stretching out after; a longing: desire.
  8670. tshuwrah from shuwr in the sense of arrival; a gift: present.
  8671. tshiy`iy ord. from tesha`; ninth: ninth.
  8672. tesha` or (masculine) tishtah; perhaps from sha`ah through the idea of a turn to the next or full number ten; nine or (ord.) ninth: nine (+ -teen, + -teenth, -th).
  8673. tish`iym multiple from tesha`; ninety: ninety.
  8674. Tattnay of foreign derivation; Tattenai, a Persian: Tatnai.

Greek

  1. a of Hebrew origin; the first letter of the alphabet; figuratively, only (from its use as a numeral) the first: Alpha. Often used (usually an, before a vowel) also in composition (as a contraction from aneu) in the sense of privation; so, in many words, beginning with this letter; occasionally in the sense of union (as a contraction of hama).
  2. Aaron of Hebrew origin ('Aharown); Aaron, the brother of Moses: Aaron.
  3. Abaddon of Hebrew origin ('abaddown); a destroying angel: Abaddon.
  4. abares from a (as a negative particle) and baros; weightless, i.e. (figuratively) not burdensome: from being burdensome.
  5. Abba of Chaldee origin ('ab); father as a vocative: Abba.
  6. Abel of Hebrew origin (Hebel); Abel, the son of Adam: Abel.
  7. Abia of Hebrew origin ('Abiyah); Abijah, the name of two Israelites: Abia.
  8. Abiathar of Hebrew origin ('Ebyathar); Abiathar, an Israelite: Abiathar.
  9. Abilene of foreign origin (compare 'abel); Abilene, a region of Syria: Abilene.
  10. Abioud of Hebrew origin ('Abiyhuwd); Abihud, an Israelite: Abiud.
  11. Abraam of Hebrew origin ('Abraham); Abraham, the Hebrew patriarch: Abraham. (In Acts 7:16 the text should probably read Jacob.)
  12. abussos from a (as a negative particle) and a variation of buthos; depthless, i.e. (specially) (infernal) "abyss": deep, (bottomless) pit.
  13. Agabos of Hebrew origin (compare Chagab); Agabus, an Israelite: Agabus.
  14. agathoergeo from agathos and ergon; to work good: do good.
  15. agathopoieo from agathopoios; to be a well-doer (as a favor or a duty): (when) do good (well).
  16. agathopolia from agathopoios; well-doing, i.e. virtue: well-doing.
  17. agathopoios from agathos and poieo; a well-doer, i.e. virtuous: them that do well.
  18. agathos a primary word; "good" (in any sense, often as noun): benefit, good(-s, things), well. Compare kalos.
  19. agathosune from agathos; goodness, i.e. virtue or beneficence: goodness.
  20. agalliasis from agalliao; exultation; specially, welcome: gladness, (exceeding) joy.
  21. agalliao from agan (much) and hallomai; properly, to jump for joy, i.e. exult: be (exceeding) glad, with exceeding joy, rejoice (greatly).
  22. agamos from a (as a negative particle) and gamos; unmarried: unmarried.
  23. aganakteo from agan (much) and achthos (grief; akin to the base of agkale); to be greatly afflicted, i.e. (figuratively) indignant: be much (sore) displeased, have (be moved with, with) indignation.
  24. aganaktesis from aganakteo; indignation: indignation.
  25. agapao perhaps from agan (much) (or compare `agab); to love (in a social or moral sense): (be-)love(-ed). Compare phileo.
  26. agape from agapao; love, i.e. affection or benevolence; specially (plural) a love-feast: (feast of) charity(-ably), dear, love.
  27. agapetos from agapao; beloved: (dearly, well) beloved, dear.
  28. Agar of Hebrew origin (Hagar); Hagar, the concubine of Abraham: Hagar.
  29. aggareuo of foreign origin (compare 'iggra'); properly, to be a courier, i.e. (by implication) to press into public service: compel (to go).
  30. aggeion from aggos (a pail, perhaps as bent; compare the base of agkale); a receptacle: vessel.
  31. aggelia from aggelos; an announcement, i.e. (by implication) precept: message.
  32. aggelos from aggello (probably derived from ago; compare agele) (to bring tidings); a messenger; especially an "angel"; by implication, a pastor: angel, messenger.
  33. age imperative of ago; properly, lead, i.e. come on: go to.
  34. agele from ago (compare aggelos); a drove: herd.
  35. agenealogetos from a (as negative particle) and genealogeo; unregistered as to birth: without descent.
  36. agenes from a (as negative particle) and genos; properly, without kin, i.e. (of unknown descent, and by implication) ignoble: base things.
  37. hagiazo from hagios; to make holy, i.e. (ceremonially) purify or consecrate; (mentally) to venerate: hallow, be holy, sanctify.
  38. hagiasmos from hagiazo; properly, purification, i.e. (the state) purity; concretely (by Hebraism) a purifier: holiness, sanctification.
  39. hagion neuter of hagios; a sacred thing (i.e. spot): holiest (of all), holy place, sanctuary.
  40. hagios from hagos (an awful thing) (compare hagnos, thalpo); sacred (physically, pure, morally blameless or religious, ceremonially, consecrated): (most) holy (one, thing), saint.
  41. hagiotes from hagios; sanctity (i.e. properly, the state): holiness.
  42. hagiosune from hagios; sacredness (i.e. properly, the quality): holiness.
  43. agkale from agkos (a bend, "ache"); an arm (as curved): arm.
  44. agkistron from the same as agkale; a hook (as bent): hook.
  45. agkura from the same as agkale; an "anchor" (as crooked): anchor.
  46. agnaphos from a (as a negative particle) and the same as gnapheus; properly, unfulled, i.e. (by implication) new (cloth): new.
  47. hagneia from hagnos; cleanliness (the quality), i.e. (specially) chastity: purity.
  48. hagnizo from hagnos; to make clean, i.e. (figuratively) sanctify (ceremonially or morally): purify (self).
  49. hagnismos from hagnizo; a cleansing (the act), i.e. (ceremonially) lustration: purification.
  50. agnoeo from a (as a negative particle) and noieo; not to know (through lack of information or intelligence); by implication, to ignore (through disinclination): (be) ignorant(-ly), not know, not understand, unknown.
  51. agnoema from agnoeo; a thing ignored, i.e. shortcoming: error.
  52. agnoia from agnoeo; ignorance (properly, the quality): ignorance.
  53. hagnos from the same as hagios; properly, clean, i.e. (figuratively) innocent, modest, perfect: chaste, clean, pure.
  54. hagnotes from hagnos; cleanness (the state), i.e. (figuratively) blamelessness: pureness.
  55. hagnos adverb from hagnos; purely, i.e. honestly: sincerely.
  56. agnosia from a (as negative particle) and gnosis; ignorance (properly, the state): ignorance, not the knowledge.
  57. agnostos from a (as negative particle) and gnostos; unknown: unknown.
  58. agora from ageiro (to gather; probably akin to egeiro); properly, the town-square (as a place of public resort); by implication, a market or thoroughfare: market(-place), street.
  59. agorazo from agora; properly, to go to market, i.e. (by implication) to purchase; specially, to redeem: buy, redeem.
  60. agoraios from agora; relating to the market-place, i.e. forensic (times); by implication, vulgar: baser sort, low.
  61. agra from ago; (abstractly) a catching (of fish); also (concretely) a haul (of fish): draught.
  62. agrammatos from a (as negative particle) and gramma; unlettered, i.e. illiterate: unlearned.
  63. agrauleo from agros and auleo (in the sense of aule); to camp out: abide in the field.
  64. agreuo from agra; to hunt, i.e. (figuratively) to entrap: catch.
  65. agrielaios from agrios and elaia; an oleaster: olive tree (which is) wild.
  66. agrios from agros; wild (as pertaining to the country), literally (natural) or figuratively (fierce): wild, raging.
  67. Agrippas apparently from agrios and hippos; wild-horse tamer; Agrippas, one of the Herods: Agrippa.
  68. agros from ago; a field (as a drive for cattle); genitive case, the country; specially, a farm, i.e. hamlet: country, farm, piece of ground, land.
  69. agrupneo ultimately from a (as negative particle) and hupnos; to be sleepless, i.e. keep awake: watch.
  70. agrupnia from agrupneo; sleeplessness, i.e. a keeping awake: watch.
  71. ago a primary verb; properly, to lead; by implication, to bring, drive, (reflexively) go, (specially) pass (time), or (figuratively) induce: be, bring (forth), carry, (let) go, keep, lead away, be open.
  72. agoge reduplicated from ago; a bringing up, i.e. mode of living: manner of life.
  73. agon from ago; properly, a place of assembly (as if led), i.e. (by implication) a contest (held there); figuratively, an effort or anxiety: conflict, contention, fight, race.
  74. agonia from agon; a struggle (properly, the state), i.e. (figuratively) anguish: agony.
  75. agonizomai from agon; to struggle, literally (to compete for a prize), figuratively (to contend with an adversary), or genitive case (to endeavor to accomplish something): fight, labor fervently, strive.
  76. Adam of Hebrew origin ('Adam); Adam, the first man; typically (of Jesus) man (as his representative): Adam.
  77. adapanos from a (as negative particle); and dapane; costless, i.e. gratuitous: without expense.
  78. Addi probably of Hebrew origin (compare `adiy); Addi, an Israelite: Addi.
  79. adelphe feminine of adephos; a sister (naturally or ecclesiastically): sister.
  80. adephos from a (as a connective particle) and delphus (the womb); a brother (literally or figuratively) near or remote (much like a): brother.
  81. adelphotes from adephos; brotherhood (properly, the feeling of brotherliness), i.e. the (Christian) fraternity: brethren, brotherhood.
  82. adelos from a (as a negative particle) and delos; hidden, figuratively, indistinct: appear not, uncertain.
  83. adelotes from adelos; uncertainty: X uncertain.
  84. adelos adverb from adelos; uncertainly: uncertainly.
  85. ademoneo from a derivative of adeo (to be sated to loathing); to be in distress (of mind): be full of heaviness, be very heavy.
  86. haides from a (as negative particle) and eido; properly, unseen, i.e. "Hades" or the place (state) of departed souls: grave, hell.
  87. adiakritos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of diakrino; properly, undistinguished, i.e. (actively) impartial: without partiality.
  88. adialeiptos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a compound of dia and leipo; unintermitted, i.e. permanent: without ceasing, continual.
  89. adialeiptos adverb from adialeiptos; uninterruptedly, i.e. without omission (on an appropriate occasion): without ceasing.
  90. adiaphthoria from a derivative of a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of diaphtheiro; incorruptibleness, i.e. (figuratively) purity (of doctrine): uncorruptness.
  91. adikeo from adikos; to be unjust, i.e. (actively) do wrong (morally, socially or physically): hurt, injure, be an offender, be unjust, (do, suffer, take) wrong.
  92. adikema from adikeo; a wrong done: evil doing, iniquity, matter of wrong.
  93. adikia from adikos; (legal) injustice (properly, the quality, by implication, the act); morally, wrongfulness (of character, life or act): iniquity, unjust, unrighteousness, wrong.
  94. adikos from a (as a negative particle) and dike; unjust; by extension wicked; by implication, treacherous; specially, heathen: unjust, unrighteous.
  95. adikos adverb from adikos; unjustly: wrongfully.
  96. adokimos from a (as a negative particle) and dokimos; unapproved, i.e. rejected; by implication, worthless (literally or morally): castaway, rejected, reprobate.
  97. adolos from a (as a negative particle); and dolos; undeceitful, i.e. (figuratively) unadulterated: sincere.
  98. Adramuttenos from Adramutteion (a place in Asia Minor); Adramyttene or belonging to Adramyttium: of Adramyttium.
  99. Adrias from Adria (a place near its shore); the Adriatic sea (including the Ionian): Adria.
  100. hadrotes from hadros (stout); plumpness, i.e. (figuratively) liberality: abundance.
  101. adunateo from adunatos; to be unable, i.e. (passively) impossible: be impossible.
  102. adunatos from a (as a negative particle) and dunatos; unable, i.e. weak (literally or figuratively); passively, impossible: could not do, impossible, impotent, not possible, weak.
  103. aido a primary verb; to sing: sing.
  104. aei from an obsolete primary noun (apparently meaning continued duration); "ever," by qualification regularly; by implication, earnestly: always, ever.
  105. aetos from the same as aer; an eagle (from its wind-like flight): eagle.
  106. azumos from a (as a negative particle) and zume; unleavened, i.e. (figuratively) uncorrupted; (in the neutral plural) specially (by implication) the Passover week: unleavened (bread).
  107. Azor of Hebrew origin (compare `Azzuwr); Azor, an Israelite: Azorigin.
  108. Azotos of Hebrew origin ('Ashdowd); Azotus (i.e. Ashdod), a place in Palestine: Azotus.
  109. aer from aemi (to breathe unconsciously, i.e. respire; by analogy, to blow); "air" (as naturally circumambient): air. Compare psucho.
  110. athanasia from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and thanatos; deathlessness: immortality.
  111. athemitos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of themis (statute; from the base of tithemi); illegal; by implication, flagitious: abominable, unlawful thing.
  112. atheos from a (as a negative particle) and theos; godless: without God.
  113. athesmos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of tithemi (in the sense of enacting); lawless, i.e. (by implication) criminal: wicked.
  114. atheteo from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of tithemi; to set aside, i.e. (by implication) to disesteem, neutralize or violate: cast off, despise, disannul, frustrate, bring to nought, reject.
  115. athetesis from atheteo; cancellation (literally or figuratively): disannulling, put away.
  116. Athenai plural of Athene (the goddess of wisdom, who was reputed to have founded the city); Athen, the capitol of Greece: Athens.
  117. Athenaios from Athenai; an Athenan or inhabitant of Athen: Athenian.
  118. athleo from athlos (a contest in the public lists); to contend in the competitive games: strive.
  119. athlesis from athleo; a struggle (figuratively): fight.
  120. athumeo from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and thumos; to be spiritless, i.e. disheartened: be dismayed.
  121. athoos from a (as a negative particle) and probably a derivative of tithemi (meaning a penalty); not guilty: innocent.
  122. aigeos from aix (a goat); belonging to a goat: goat.
  123. aigialos from aisso (to rush) and hals (in the sense of the sea; a beach (on which the waves dash): shore.
  124. Aiguptios from Aiguptos; an gyptian or inhabitant of gyptus: Egyptian.
  125. Aiguptos of uncertain derivation; gyptus, the land of the Nile: Egypt.
  126. aidios from aei; everduring (forward and backward, or forward only): eternal, everlasting.
  127. aidos perhaps from a (as a negative particle) and eido (through the idea of downcast eyes); bashfulness, i.e. (towards men), modesty or (towards God) awe: reverence, shamefacedness.
  128. Aithiops from aitho (to scorch) and ops (the face, from optanomai); an thiopian (as a blackamoor): Ethiopian.
  129. haima of uncertain derivation; blood, literally (of men or animals), figuratively (the juice of grapes) or specially (the atoning blood of Christ); by implication, bloodshed, also kindred: blood.
  130. haimatekchusia from haima and a derivative of ekcheo; an effusion of blood: shedding of blood.
  131. haimorrheo from haima and rheo; to flow blood, i.e. have a hmorrhage: diseased with an issue of blood.
  132. Aineas of uncertain derivation; nas, an Israelite: neas.
  133. ainesis from aineo; a praising (the act), i.e. (specially) a thank(-offering): praise.
  134. aineo from ainos; to praise (God): praise.
  135. ainigma from a derivative of ainos (in its primary sense); an obscure saying ("enigma"), i.e. (abstractly) obscureness: X darkly.
  136. ainos apparently a prime word; properly, a story, but used in the sense of epainos; praise (of God): praise.
  137. Ainon of Hebrew origin (a derivative of `ayin, place of springs); non, a place in Palestine: non.
  138. haireomai probably akin to airo; to take for oneself, i.e. to prefer: choose. Some of the forms are borrowed from a cognate hellomai hel'-lom-ahee; which is otherwise obsolete.
  139. hairesis from haireomai; properly, a choice, i.e. (specially) a party or (abstractly) disunion: heresy (which is the Greek word itself), sect.
  140. hairetizo from a derivative of haireomai; to make a choice: choose.
  141. hairetikos from the same as hairetizo; a schismatic: heretic (the Greek word itself).
  142. airo a primary root; to lift up; by implication, to take up or away; figuratively, to raise (the voice), keep in suspense (the mind), specially, to sail away (i.e. weigh anchor); by Hebraism (compare nasa') to expiate sin: away with, bear (up), carry, lift up, loose, make to doubt, put away, remove, take (away, up).
  143. aisthanomai of uncertain derivation; to apprehend (properly, by the senses): perceive.
  144. aisthesis from aisthanomai; perception, i.e. (figuratively) discernment: judgment.
  145. aistheterion from a derivative of aisthanomai; properly, an organ of perception, i.e. (figuratively) judgment: senses.
  146. aischrokerdes from aischros and kerdos (gain); sordid: given to (greedy of) filthy lucre.
  147. aischrokerdos adverb from aischrokerdes; sordidly: for filthy lucre's sake.
  148. aischrologia from aischros and logos; vile conversation: filthy communication.
  149. aischron neuter of aischros; a shameful thing, i.e. indecorum: shame.
  150. aischros from the same as aischunomai; shameful, i.e. base (specially, venal): filthy.
  151. aischrotes from aischros; shamefulness, i.e. obscenity: filthiness.
  152. aischune from aischunomai; shame or disgrace (abstractly or concretely): dishonesty, shame.
  153. aischunomai from aischos (disfigurement, i.e. disgrace); to feel shame (for oneself): be ashamed.
  154. aiteo of uncertain derivation; to ask (in genitive case): ask, beg, call for, crave, desire, require. Compare punthanomai.
  155. aitema from aiteo; a thing asked or (abstractly) an asking: petition, request, required.
  156. aitia from the same as aiteo; a cause (as if asked for), i.e. (logical) reason (motive, matter), (legal) crime (alleged or proved): accusation, case, cause, crime, fault, (wh-)ere(-fore).
  157. aitiama from a derivative of aitia; a thing charged: complaint.
  158. aition neuter of aitios; a reason or crime (like aitia): cause, fault.
  159. aitios from the same as aiteo; causative, i.e. (concretely) a causer: author.
  160. aiphnidios from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and phaino (compare exaiphnes) (meaning non-apparent); unexpected, i.e. (adverbially) suddenly: sudden, unawares.
  161. aichmalosia from aichmalotos; captivity: captivity.
  162. aichmaloteuo from aichmalotos; to capture (like aichmalotizo): lead captive.
  163. aichmalotizo from aichmalotos; to make captive: lead away captive, bring into captivity.
  164. aichmalotos from aichme (a spear) and a derivative of the same as halosis; properly, a prisoner of war, i.e. (genitive case) a captive: captive.
  165. aion from the same as aei; properly, an age; by extension, perpetuity (also past); by implication, the world; specially (Jewish) a Messianic period (present or future): age, course, eternal, (for) ever(-more), (n-)ever, (beginning of the, while the) world (began, without end). Compare chronos.
  166. aionios from aion; perpetual (also used of past time, or past and future as well): eternal, for ever, everlasting, world (began).
  167. akatharsia from akathartos; impurity (the quality), physically or morally: uncleanness.
  168. akathartes from akathartos; impurity (the state), morally: filthiness.
  169. akathartos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of kathairo (meaning cleansed); impure (ceremonially, morally (lewd) or specially, (demonic)): foul, unclean.
  170. akaireomai from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and kairos (meaning unseasonable); to be inopportune (for oneself), i.e. to fail of a proper occasion: lack opportunity.
  171. akairos adverb from the same as akaireomai; inopportunely: out of season.
  172. akakos from a (as a negative particle) and kakos; not bad, i.e. (objectively) innocent or (subjectively) unsuspecting: harmless, simple.
  173. akantha probably from the same as akmen; a thorn: thorn.
  174. akanthinos from akantha; thorny: of thorns.
  175. akarpos from a (as a negative particle) and karpos; barren (literally or figuratively): without fruit, unfruitful.
  176. akatagnostos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of kataginosko; unblamable: that cannot be condemned.
  177. akatakaluptos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a compound of kata and kalupto; unveiled: uncovered.
  178. akatakritos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of katakrino; without (legal) trial: uncondemned.
  179. akatalutos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of kataluo; indissoluble, i.e. (figuratively) permanent: endless.
  180. akatapaustos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of katapauo; unrefraining: that cannot cease.
  181. akatastasia from akatastatos; instability, i.e. disorder: commotion, confusion, tumult.
  182. akatastatos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of kathistemi; inconstant: unstable.
  183. akataschetos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of katecho; unrestrainable: unruly.
  184. Akeldama of Chaldee origin (meaning field of blood; corresponding to cheleq and dam); Akeldama, a place near Jerusalem: Aceldama.
  185. akeraios from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of kerannumi; unmixed, i.e. (figuratively) innocent: harmless, simple.
  186. aklines from a (as a negative particle) and klino; not leaning, i.e. (figuratively) firm: without wavering.
  187. akmazo from the same as akmen; to make a point, i.e. (figuratively) mature: be fully ripe.
  188. akmen accusative case of a noun ("acme") akin to ake (a point) and meaning the same; adverbially, just now, i.e. still: yet.
  189. akoe from akouo; hearing (the act, the sense or the thing heard): audience, ear, fame, which ye heard, hearing, preached, report, rumor.
  190. akoloutheo from a (as a particle of union) and keleuthos (a road); properly, to be in the same way with, i.e. to accompany (specially, as a disciple): follow, reach.
  191. akouo a primary verb; to hear (in various senses): give (in the) audience (of), come (to the ears), (shall) hear(-er, -ken), be noised, be reported, understand.
  192. akrasia from akrates; want of self-restraint: excess, incontinency.
  193. akrates from a (as a negative particle) and kratos; powerless, i.e. without self-control: incontinent.
  194. akratos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of kerannumi; undiluted: without mixture.
  195. akribeia from the same as akribestatos; exactness: perfect manner.
  196. akribestatos superlative of akribes (a derivative of the same as akron); most exact: most straitest.
  197. akribesteron neuter of the comparative of the same as akribestatos; (adverbially) more exactly: more perfect(-ly).
  198. akriboo from the same as akribestatos; to be exact, i.e. ascertain: enquire diligently.
  199. akribos adverb from the same as akribestatos; exactly: circumspectly, diligently, perfect(-ly).
  200. akris apparently from the same as akron; a locust (as pointed, or as lighting on the top of vegetation): locust.
  201. akroaterion from akroates; an audience-room: place of hearing.
  202. akroates from akroaomai (to listen; apparently an intensive of akouo); a hearer (merely): hearer.
  203. akrobustia from akron and probably a modified form of posthe (the penis or male sexual organ); the prepuce; by implication, an uncircumcised (i.e. gentile, figuratively, unregenerate) state or person: not circumcised, uncircumcised (with echo), uncircumcision.
  204. akrogoniaios from akron and gonia; belonging to the extreme corner: chief corner.
  205. akrothinion from akron and this (a heap); properly (in the plural) the top of the heap, i.e. (by implication) best of the booty: spoils.
  206. akron neuter of an adjective probably akin to the base of akmen; the extremity: one end other, tip, top, uttermost participle.
  207. Akulas probably for Latin aquila (an eagle); Akulas, an Israelite: Aquila.
  208. akuroo from a (as a negative particle) and kuroo; to invalidate: disannul, make of none effect.
  209. akolutos adverb from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of koluo; in an unhindered manner, i.e. freely: no man forbidding him.
  210. akon from a (as a negative particle) and hekon; unwilling: against the will.
  211. alabastron neuter of alabastros (of uncertain derivation), the name of a stone; properly, an "alabaster" box, i.e. (by extension) a perfume vase (of any material): (alabaster) box.
  212. alazoneia from alazon; braggadocio, i.e. (by implication) self-confidence: boasting, pride.
  213. alazon from ale (vagrancy); braggart: boaster.
  214. alalazo from alale ( a shout, "halloo"); to vociferate, i.e. (by implication) to wail; figuratively, to clang: tinkle, wail.
  215. alaletos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of laleo; unspeakable: unutterable, which cannot be uttered.
  216. alalos from a (as a negative particle) and laleo; mute: dumb.
  217. halas from hals; salt; figuratively, prudence: salt.
  218. aleipho from a (as particle of union) and the base of liparos; to oil (with perfume): anoint.
  219. alektorophonia from alektor and phone; cock-crow, i.e. the third night-watch: cockcrowing.
  220. alektor from aleko (to ward off); a cock or male fowl: cock.
  221. Alexandreus from Alexandreia (the city so called); an Alexandreian or inhabitant of Alexandria: of Alexandria, Alexandrian.
  222. Alexandrinos from the same as Alexandreus; Alexandrine, or belonging to Alexandria: of Alexandria.
  223. Alexandros from the same as (the first part of) alektor and aner; man-defender; Alexander, the name of three Israelites and one other man: Alexander.
  224. aleuron from aleo (to grind); flour: meal.
  225. aletheia from alethes; truth: true, X truly, truth, verity.
  226. aletheuo from alethes; to be true (in doctrine and profession): speak (tell) the truth.
  227. alethes from a (as a negative particle) and lanthano; true (as not concealing): true, truly, truth.
  228. alethinos from alethes; truthful: true.
  229. aletho from the same as aleuron; to grind: grind.
  230. alethos adverb from alethes; truly: indeed, surely, of a surety, truly, of a (in) truth, verily, very.
  231. halieus from hals; a sailor (as engaged on the salt water), i.e. (by implication) a fisher: fisher(-man).
  232. halieuo from halieus; to be a fisher, i.e. (by implication) to fish: go a-fishing.
  233. halizo from hals; to salt: salt.
  234. alisgema from alisgeo (to soil); (ceremonially) defilement: pollution.
  235. alla neuter plural of allos; properly, other things, i.e. (adverbially) contrariwise (in many relations): and, but (even), howbeit, indeed, nay, nevertheless, no, notwithstanding, save, therefore, yea, yet.
  236. allasso from allos; to make different: change.
  237. allachothen from allos; from elsewhere: some other way.
  238. allegoreo from allos and agoreo (to harangue (compare agora)); to allegorize: be an allegory (the Greek word itself).
  239. allelouia of Hebrew origin (imperative of halal and Yahh); praise ye Jah!, an adoring exclamation: alleluiah.
  240. allelon Genitive plural from allos reduplicated; one another: each other, mutual, one another, (the other), (them-, your-)selves, (selves) together (sometimes with meta or pros).
  241. allogenes from allos and genos; foreign, i.e. not a Jew: stranger.
  242. hallomai middle voice of apparently a primary verb; to jump; figuratively, to gush: leap, spring up.
  243. allos a primary word; "else," i.e. different (in many applications): more, one (another), (an-, some an-)other(-s, -wise).
  244. allotriepiskopos from allotrios and episkopos; overseeing others' affairs, i.e. a meddler (specially, in Gentile customs): busybody in other men's matters.
  245. allotrios from allos; another's, i.e. not one's own; by extension foreign, not akin, hostile: alien, (an-)other (man's, men's), strange(-r).
  246. allophulos from allos and phule; foreign, i.e. (specially) Gentile: one of another nation.
  247. allos adverb from allos; differently: otherwise.
  248. aloao from the same as halon; to tread out grain: thresh, tread out the corn.
  249. alogos from a (as a negative particle) and logos; irrational: brute, unreasonable.
  250. aloe of foreign origin (compare akanthinos); aloes (the gum): aloes.
  251. hals a primary word; "salt": salt.
  252. halukos from hals; briny: salt.
  253. alupoteros comparative of a compound of a (as a negative particle) and lupe; more without grief: less sorrowful.
  254. halusis of uncertain derivation; a fetter or manacle: bonds, chain.
  255. alusiteles from a (as a negative particle) and the base of lusitelei; gainless, i.e. (by implication) pernicious: unprofitable.
  256. Alphaios of Hebrew origin (compare Cheleph); Alphus, an Israelite: Alpheus.
  257. halon probably from the base of heilisso; a threshing-floor (as rolled hard), i.e. (figuratively) the grain (and chaff, as just threshed): floor.
  258. alopex of uncertain derivation; a fox, i.e. (figuratively) a cunning person: fox.
  259. halosis from a collateral form of haireomai; capture, be taken.
  260. hama a primary particle; properly, at the "same" time, but freely used as a preposition or adverb denoting close association: also, and, together, with(-al).
  261. amathes from a (as a negative particle) and manthano; ignorant: unlearned.
  262. amarantinos from amarantos; "amaranthine", i.e. (by implication) fadeless: that fadeth not away.
  263. amarantos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of maraino; unfading, i.e. (by implication) perpetual: that fadeth not away.
  264. hamartano perhaps from a (as a negative particle) and the base of meros; properly, to miss the mark (and so not share in the prize), i.e. (figuratively) to err, especially (morally) to sin: for your faults, offend, sin, trespass.
  265. hamartema from hamartano; a sin (properly concrete): sin.
  266. hamartia from hamartano; a sin (properly abstract): offence, sin(-ful).
  267. amarturos from a (as a negative particle) and a form of martus; unattested: without witness.
  268. hamartolos from hamartano; sinful, i.e. a sinner: sinful, sinner.
  269. amachos from a (as a negative particle) and mache; peaceable: not a brawler.
  270. amao from hama; properly, to collect, i.e. (by implication) reap: reap down.
  271. amethustos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of methuo; the "amethyst" (supposed to prevent intoxication): amethyst.
  272. ameleo from a (as a negative particle) and melo; to be careless of: make light of, neglect, be negligent, no regard.
  273. amemptos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of memphomai; irreproachable: blameless, faultless, unblamable.
  274. amemptos adverb from amemptos; faultlessly: blameless, unblamably.
  275. amerimnos from a (as a negative particle) and merimna; not anxious: without care(-fulness), secure.
  276. ametathetos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of metatithemi; unchangeable, or (neuter as abstract) unchangeability: immutable(-ility).
  277. ametakinetos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of metakineo; immovable: unmovable.
  278. ametameletos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of metamellomai; irrevocable: without repentance, not to be repented of.
  279. ametanoetos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of metanoeo; unrepentant: impenitent.
  280. ametros from a (as a negative particle) and metron; immoderate: (thing) without measure.
  281. amen of Hebrew origin ('amen); properly, firm, i.e. (figuratively) trustworthy; adverbially, surely (often as interjection, so be it): amen, verily.
  282. ametor from a (as a negative particle) and meter; motherless, i.e. of unknown maternity: without mother.
  283. amiantos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of miaino; unsoiled, i.e. (figuratively) pure: undefiled.
  284. Aminadab of Hebrew origin (`Ammiynadab); Aminadab, an Israelite: Aminadab.
  285. ammos perhaps from hama; sand (as heaped on the beach): sand.
  286. amnos apparently a primary word; a lamb: lamb.
  287. amoibe from ameibo (to exchange); requital: requite.
  288. ampelos probably from the base of amphoteros and that of halon; a vine (as coiling about a support): vine.
  289. ampelourgos from ampelos and ergon; a vine-worker, i.e. pruner: vine-dresser.
  290. ampelon from ampelos; a vineyard: vineyard.
  291. Amplias contracted for Latin ampliatus (enlarged); Amplias, a Roman Christian: Amplias.
  292. amunomai middle voice of a primary verb; to ward off (for oneself), i.e. protect: defend.
  293. amphiblestron from a compound of the base of amphoteros and ballo; a (fishing) net (as thrown about the fish): net.
  294. amphiennumi from the base of amphoteros and hennumi (to invest); to enrobe: clothe.
  295. Amphipolis from the base of amphoteros and polis; a city surrounded by a river; Amphipolis, a place in Macedonia: Amphipolis.
  296. amphodon from the base of amphoteros and hodos; a fork in the road: where two ways meet.
  297. amphoteros comparative of amphi (around); (in plural) both: both.
  298. amometos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of momaomai; unblamable: blameless.
  299. amomos from a (as a negative particle) and momos; unblemished (literally or figuratively): without blame (blemish, fault, spot), faultless, unblamable.
  300. Amon of Hebrew origin ('Amown); Amon, an Israelite: Amon.
  301. Amos of Hebrew origin ('Amowts); Amos, an Israelite: Amos.
  302. an a primary particle, denoting a supposition, wish, possibility or uncertainty: (what-, where-, wither-, who-)soever. Usually unexpressed except by the subjunctive or potential mood. Also contracted for ean.
  303. ana a primary preposition and adverb; properly, up; but (by extension) used (distributively) severally, or (locally) at (etc.): and, apiece, by, each, every (man), in, through. In compounds (as a prefix) it often means (by implication) repetition, intensity, reversal, etc.
  304. anabathmos from anabaino (compare bathmos); a stairway: stairs.
  305. anabaino from ana and the base of basis; to go up (literally or figuratively): arise, ascend (up), climb (go, grow, rise, spring) up, come (up).
  306. anaballomai middle voice from ana and ballo; to put off (for oneself): defer.
  307. anabibazo from ana and a derivative of the base of basis; to cause to go up, i.e. haul (a net): draw.
  308. anablepo from ana and blepo; to look up; by implication, to recover sight: look (up), see, receive sight.
  309. anablepsis from anablepo; restoration of sight: recovery of sight.
  310. anaboao from ana and boao; to halloo: cry (aloud, out).
  311. anabole from anaballomai; a putting off: delay.
  312. anaggello from ana and the base of aggelos; to announce (in detail): declare, rehearse, report, show, speak, tell.
  313. anagennao from ana and gennao; to beget or (by extension) bear (again): beget, (bear) X (again).
  314. anaginosko from ana and ginosko; to know again, i.e. (by extension) to read: read.
  315. anagkazo from anagke; to necessitate: compel, constrain.
  316. anagkaios from anagke; necessary; by implication, close (of kin): near, necessary, necessity, needful.
  317. anagkastos adverb from a derivative of anagkazo; compulsorily: by constraint.
  318. anagke from ana and the base of agkale; constraint (literally or figuratively); by implication, distress: distress, must needs, (of) necessity(-sary), needeth, needful.
  319. anagnorizomai middle voice from ana and gnorizo; to make (oneself) known: be made known.
  320. angnosis from anaginosko; (the act of) reading: reading.
  321. anago from ana and ago; to lead up; by extension to bring out; specially, to sail away: bring (again, forth, up again), depart, launch (forth), lead (up), loose, offer, sail, set forth, take up.
  322. anadeiknumi from ana and deiknuo; to exhibit, i.e. (by implication) to indicate, appoint: appoint, shew.
  323. anadeixis from anadeiknumi; (the act of) exhibition: shewing.
  324. anadechomai from ana and dechomai; to entertain (as a guest): receive.
  325. anadidomi from ana and didomi; to hand over: deliver.
  326. anazao from ana and zao; to recover life (literally or figuratively): (be a-)live again, revive.
  327. anazeteo from ana and zeteo; to search out: seek.
  328. anazonnumi from ana and zonnumi; to gird afresh: gird up.
  329. anazopureo from ana and a compound of the base of zoon and pur; to re-enkindle: stir up.
  330. anathallo from ana and thallo (to flourish); to revive: flourish again.
  331. anathema from anatithemai; a (religious) ban or (concretely) excommunicated (thing or person): accused, anathema, curse, X great.
  332. anathematizo from anathema; to declare or vow under penalty of execration: (bind under a) curse, bind with an oath.
  333. antheoreo from ana and theoreo; to look again (i.e. attentively) at (literally or figuratively): behold, consider.
  334. anathema from anatithemai (like anathema, but in a good sense); a votive offering: gift.
  335. anaideia from a compound of a (as a negative particle (compare aneu)) and aidos; impudence, i.e. (by implication) importunity: importunity.
  336. anairesis from anaireo; (the act of) killing: death.
  337. anaireo from ana and (the active of) haireomai; to take up, i.e. adopt; by implication, to take away (violently), i.e. abolish, murder: put to death, kill, slay, take away, take up.
  338. anaitios from a (as a negative particle) and aitios (in the sense of aitia); innocent: blameless, guiltless.
  339. anakathizo from ana and kathizo; properly, to set up, i.e. (reflexively) to sit up: sit up.
  340. anakainizo from ana and a derivative of kainos; to restore: renew.
  341. anakainoo from ana and a derivative of kainos; to renovate: renew.
  342. anakainosis from anakainoo; renovation: renewing.
  343. anakalupto from ana (in the sense of reversal) and kalupto; to unveil: open, (un-)taken away.
  344. anakampto from ana and kampto; to turn back: (re-)turn.
  345. anakeimai from ana and keimai; to recline (as a corpse or at a meal): guest, lean, lie, sit (down, at meat), at the table.
  346. anakephalaiomai from ana and kephalaioo (in its original sense); to sum up: briefly comprehend, gather together in one.
  347. anaklino from ana and klino; to lean back: lay, (make) sit down.
  348. anakopto from ana and kopto; to beat back, i.e. check: hinder.
  349. anakrazo from ana and krazo; to scream up (aloud): cry out.
  350. anakrino from ana and krino; properly, to scrutinize, i.e. (by implication) investigate, interrogate, determine: ask, question, discern, examine, judge, search.
  351. anakrisis from anakrino; a (judicial) investigation: examination.
  352. anakupto from ana (in the sense of reversal) and kupto; to unbend, i.e. rise; figuratively, be elated: lift up, look up.
  353. analambano from ana and lambano; to take up: receive up, take (in, unto, up).
  354. analepsis from analambano; ascension: taking up.
  355. analisko from ana and a form of the alternate of haireomai; properly, to use up, i.e. destroy: consume.
  356. analogia from a compound of ana and logos; proportion: proportion.
  357. analogizomai middle voice from analogia; to estimate, i.e. (figuratively) contemplate: consider.
  358. analos from a (as a negative particle) and hals; saltless, i.e. insipid: X lose saltness.
  359. analusis from analuo; departure: departure.
  360. analuo from ana and luo; to break up, i.e. depart (literally or figuratively): depart, return.
  361. anamartetos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of hamartano; sinless: that is without sin.
  362. anemeno from ana and meno; to await: wait for.
  363. anamimnesko from ana and mimnesko; to remind; (reflexively) to recollect: call to mind, (bring to, call to, put in), remember(-brance).
  364. anamnesis from anamimnesko; recollection: remembrance (again).
  365. ananeoo from ana and a derivative of neos; to renovate, i.e. reform: renew.
  366. ananepho from ana and nepho; to become sober again, i.e. (figuratively) regain (one's) senses: recover self.
  367. Ananias of Hebrew origin (Chananyah); Ananias, the name of three Israelites: Ananias.
  368. anantirrhetos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of anti and rheo; indisputable: cannot be spoken against.
  369. anantirrhetos adverb from anantirrhetos; promptly: without gainsaying.
  370. anaxios from a (as a negative particle) and axios; unfit: unworthy.
  371. anaxios adverb from anaxios; irreverently: unworthily.
  372. anapausis from anapano; intermission; by implication, recreation: rest.
  373. anapano from ana and pauo; (reflexively) to repose (literally or figuratively (be exempt), remain); by implication, to refresh: take ease, refresh, (give, take) rest.
  374. anapeitho from ana and peitho; to incite: persuade.
  375. anapempo from ana and pempo; to send up or back: send (again).
  376. anaperos from ana (in the sense of intensity) and peros (maimed); crippled: maimed.
  377. anapipto from ana and pipto; to fall back, i.e. lie down, lean back: lean, sit down (to meat).
  378. anapleroo from ana and pleroo; to complete; by implication, to occupy, supply; figuratively, to accomplish (by coincidence ot obedience): fill up, fulfill, occupy, supply.
  379. anapologetos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of apologeomai; indefensible: without an excuse, inexcusable.
  380. anaptusso from ana (in the sense of reversal) and ptusso; to unroll (a scroll or volume): open.
  381. anapto from ana and hapto; to enkindle: kindle, light.
  382. anarithmetos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of arithmeo; unnumbered, i.e. without number: innumerable.
  383. anaseio from ana and seio; figuratively, to excite: move, stir up.
  384. anaskeuazo from ana (in the sense of reversal) and a derivative of skeuos; properly, to pack up (baggage), i.e. (by implication, and figuratively) to upset: subvert.
  385. anaspao from ana and spao; to take up or extricate: draw up, pull out.
  386. anastasis from anistemi; a standing up again, i.e. (literally) a resurrection from death (individual, genitive case or by implication, (its author)), or (figuratively) a (moral) recovery (of spiritual truth): raised to life again, resurrection, rise from the dead, that should rise, rising again.
  387. anastatoo from a derivative of anistemi (in the sense of removal); properly, to drive out of home, i.e. (by implication) to disturb (literally or figuratively): trouble, turn upside down, make an uproar.
  388. anastauroo from ana and stauroo; to recrucify (figuratively): crucify afresh.
  389. anastenazo from ana and stenazo; to sigh deeply: sigh deeply.
  390. anastrepho from ana and strepho; to overturn; also to return; by implication, to busy oneself, i.e. remain, live: abide, behave self, have conversation, live, overthrow, pass, return, be used.
  391. anastrophe from anastrepho; behavior: conversation.
  392. anatassomai from ana and the middle voice of tasso; to arrange: set in order.
  393. anatello from ana and the base of telos; to (cause to) arise: (a-, make to) rise, at the rising of, spring (up), be up.
  394. anatithemai from ana and the middle voice of tithemi; to set forth (for oneself), i.e propound: communicate, declare.
  395. anatole from anatello; a rising of light, i.e. dawn (figuratively); by implication, the east (also in plural): dayspring, east, rising.
  396. anatrepo from ana and the base of trope; to overturn (figuratively): overthrow, subvert.
  397. anatrepho from ana and trepho; to rear (physically or mentally): bring up, nourish (up).
  398. anaphaino from ana and phaino; to show, i.e. (reflexively) appear, or (passively) to have pointed out: (should) appear, discover.
  399. anaphero from ana and phero; to take up (literally or figuratively): bear, bring (carry, lead) up, offer (up).
  400. anaphoneo from ana and phoneo; to exclaim: speak out.
  401. anachusis from a comparative of ana and cheo (to pour); properly, effusion, i.e. (figuratively) license: excess.
  402. anachoreo from ana and choreo; to retire: depart, give place, go (turn) aside, withdraw self.
  403. anapsuxis from anapsucho; properly, a recovery of breath, i.e. (figuratively) revival: revival.
  404. anapsucho from ana and psucho; properly, to cool off, i.e. (figuratively) relieve: refresh.
  405. andrapodistes from a derivative of a compound of aner and pous; an enslaver (as bringing men to his feet): menstealer.
  406. Andreas from aner; manly; Andreas, an Israelite: Andrew.
  407. andrizomai middle voice from aner; to act manly: quit like men.
  408. Andronikos from aner and nikos; man of victory; Andronicos, an Israelite: Adronicus.
  409. androphonos from aner and phonos; a murderer: manslayer.
  410. anegkletos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of egkaleo; unaccused, i.e. (by implication) irreproachable: blameless.
  411. anekdiegetos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ekdiegeomai; not expounded in full, i.e. indescribable: unspeakable.
  412. aneklaletos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of eklaleo; not spoken out, i.e. (by implication) unutterable: unspeakable.
  413. anekleiptos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ekleipo; not left out, i.e. (by implication) inexhaustible: that faileth not.
  414. anektoteros comparative of a derivative of anechomai; more endurable: more tolerable.
  415. aneleemon from a (as a negative particle) and eleemon; merciless: unmerciful.
  416. anemizo from anemos; to toss with the wind: drive with the wind.
  417. anemos from the base of aer; wind; (plural) by implication, (the four) quarters (of the earth): wind.
  418. anendektos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of the same as endechetai; unadmitted, i.e. (by implication) not supposable: impossible.
  419. anexereunetos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of exereunao; not searched out, i.e. (by implication) inscrutable: unsearchable.
  420. anexikakos from anechomai and kakos; enduring of ill, i.e. forbearing: patient.
  421. anexichniastos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of ek and a derivative of ichnos; not tracked out, i.e. (by implication) untraceable: past finding out; unsearchable.
  422. anepaischuntos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of epi and aischunomai; not ashamed, i.e. irreprehensible: that needeth not to be ashamed.
  423. anepileptos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of epilambanomai; not arrested, i.e. (by implication) inculpable: blameless, unrebukeable.
  424. anerchomai from ana and erchomai; to ascend: go up.
  425. anesis from aniemi; relaxation or (figuratively) relief: eased, liberty, rest.
  426. anetazo from ana and etazo (to test); to investigate (judicially): (should have) examined(-d).
  427. aneu a primary particle; without: without. Compare a.
  428. aneuthetos from a (as a negative particle) and euthetos; not well set, i.e. inconvenient: not commodious.
  429. aneurisko from ana and heurisko; to find out: find.
  430. anechomai middle voice from ana and echo; to hold oneself up against, i.e. (figuratively) put up with: bear with, endure, forbear, suffer.
  431. anepsios from a (as a particle of union) and an obsolete nepos (a brood); properly, akin, i.e. (specially) a cousin: sister's son.
  432. anethon probably of foreign origin; dill: anise.
  433. aneko from ana and heko; to attain to, i.e. (figuratively) be proper: convenient, be fit.
  434. anemeros from a (as a negative particle) and hemeros (lame); savage: fierce.
  435. aner a primary word (compare anthropos); a man (properly as an individual male): fellow, husband, man, sir.
  436. anthistemi from anti and histemi; to stand against, i.e. oppose: resist, withstand.
  437. anthomologeomai from anti and the middle voice of homologeo; to confess in turn, i.e. respond in praise: give thanks.
  438. anthos a primary word; a blossom: flower.
  439. anthrakia from anthrax; a bed of burning coals: fire of coals.
  440. anthrax of uncertain derivation; a live coal: coal of fire.
  441. anthropareskos from anthropos and aresko; man-courting, i.e. fawning: men-pleaser.
  442. anthropinos from anthropos; human: human, common to man, man(-kind), (man-)kind, men's, after the manner of men.
  443. anthropoktonos from anthropos and kteino (to kill); a manslayer: murderer. Compare phoneus.
  444. anthropos from aner and ops (the countenance; from optanomai); man-faced, i.e. a human being: certain, man.
  445. anthupateuo from anthupatos; to act as proconsul: be the deputy.
  446. anthupatos from anti and a superlative of huper; instead of the highest officer, i.e. (specially) a Roman proconsul: deputy.
  447. aniemi from ana and hiemi (to send); to let up, i.e. (literally) slacken or (figuratively) desert, desist from: forbear, leave, loose.
  448. anileos from a (as a negative particle) and hileos; inexorable: without mercy.
  449. aniptos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of nipto; without ablution: unwashen.
  450. anistemi from ana and histemi; to stand up (literal or figurative, transitive or intransitive): arise, lift up, raise up (again), rise (again), stand up(-right).
  451. Anna of Hebrew origin (Channah); Anna, an Israelitess: Anna.
  452. Annas of Hebrew origin (Chananyah); Annas (i.e. Ananias), an Israelite: Annas.
  453. anoetos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of noieo; unintelligent; by implication, sensual: fool(-ish), unwise.
  454. anoia from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and nous; stupidity; by implication, rage: folly, madness.
  455. anoigo from ana and oigo (to open); to open up (literally or figuratively, in various applications): open.
  456. anoikodomeo from ana and oikodomeo; to rebuild: build again.
  457. anoixis from anoigo; opening (throat): X open.
  458. anomia from anomos; illegality, i.e. violation of law or (genitive case) wickedness: iniquity, X transgress(-ion of) the law, unrighteousness.
  459. anomos from a (as a negative particle) and nomos; lawless, i.e. (negatively) not subject to (the Jewish) law; (by implication, a Gentile), or (positively) wicked: without law, lawless, transgressor, unlawful, wicked.
  460. anomos adverb from anomos; lawlessly, i.e. (specially) not amenable to (the Jewish) law: without law.
  461. anorthoo from ana and a derivative of the base of orthos; to straighten up: lift (set) up, make straight.
  462. anosios from a (as a negative particle) and hosios; wicked: unholy.
  463. anoche from anechomai; self-restraint, i.e. tolerance: forbearance.
  464. antagonizomai from anti and agonizomai; to struggle against (figuratively) ("antagonize"): strive against.
  465. antallagma from a compound of anti and allasso; an equivalent or ransom: in exchange.
  466. antanapleroo from anti and anapleroo; to supplement: fill up.
  467. antapodidomi from anti and apodidomi; to requite (good or evil): recompense, render, repay.
  468. antapodoma from antapodidomi; a requital (properly, the thing): recompense.
  469. antapodosis from antapodidomi; requital (properly, the act): reward.
  470. antapokrinomai from anti and apokrinomai; to contradict or dispute: answer again, reply against.
  471. antepo from anti and epo; to refute or deny: gainsay, say against.
  472. antechomai from anti and the middle voice of echo; to hold oneself opposite to, i.e. (by implication) adhere to; by extension to care for: hold fast, hold to, support.
  473. anti a primary particle; opposite, i.e. instead or because of (rarely in addition to): for, in the room of. Often used in composition to denote contrast, requital, substitution, correspondence, etc.
  474. antiballo from anti and ballo; to bandy: have.
  475. antidiatithemai from anti and diatithemai; to set oneself opposite, i.e. be disputatious: that oppose themselves.
  476. antidikos from anti and dike; an opponent (in a lawsuit); specially, Satan (as the arch-enemy): adversary.
  477. antithesis from a compound of anti and tithemi; opposition, i.e. a conflict (of theories): opposition.
  478. antikathistemi from anti and kathistemi; to set down (troops) against, i.e. withstand: resist.
  479. antikaleo from anti and kaleo; to invite in return: bid again.
  480. antikeimai from anti and keimai; to lie opposite, i.e. be adverse (figuratively, repugnant) to: adversary, be contrary, oppose.
  481. antikru prolonged from anti; opposite: over against.
  482. antilambanomai from anti and the middle voice of lambano; to take hold of in turn, i.e. succor; also to participate: help, partaker, support.
  483. antilego from anti and lego; to dispute, refuse: answer again, contradict, deny, gainsay(-er), speak against.
  484. antilepsis from antilambanomai; relief: help.
  485. antilogia from a derivative of antilego; dispute, disobedience: contradiction, gainsaying, strife.
  486. antiloidoreo from anti and loidoreo; to rail in reply: revile again.
  487. antilutron from anti and lutron; a redemption-price: ransom.
  488. antimetreo from anti and metreo; to mete in return: measure again.
  489. antimisthia from a compound of anti and misthos; requital, correspondence: recompense.
  490. Antiocheia from Antiochus (a Syrian king); Antiochia, a place in Syria: Antioch.
  491. Antiocheus from Antiocheia; an Antiochian or inhabitant of Antiochia: of Antioch.
  492. antiparerchomai from anti and parerchomai; to go along opposite: pass by on the other side.
  493. Antipas contracted for a compound of anti and a derivative of pater; Antipas, a Christian: Antipas.
  494. Antipatris from the same as Antipas; Antipatris, a place in Palestine: Antipatris.
  495. antiperan from anti and peran; on the opposite side: over against.
  496. antipipto from anti and pipto (including its alternate); to oppose: resist.
  497. antistrateuomai from anti and strateuomai; (figuratively) to attack, i.e. (by implication) destroy: war against.
  498. antitassomai from anti and the middle voice of tasso; to range oneself against, i.e. oppose: oppose themselves, resist.
  499. antitupon neuter of a compound of anti and tupos; corresponding ("antitype"), i.e. a representative, counterpart: (like) figure (whereunto).
  500. antichristos from anti and Christos; an opponent of the Messiah: antichrist.
  501. antleo from antlos (the hold of a ship); to bale up (properly, bilge water), i.e. dip water (with a bucket, pitcher, etc.): draw (out).
  502. antlema from antleo; a baling-vessel: thing to draw with.
  503. antophthalmeo from a compound of anti and ophthalmos; to face: bear up into.
  504. anudros from a (as a negative particle) and hudor; waterless, i.e. dry: dry, without water.
  505. anupokritos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of hupokrinomai; undissembled, i.e. sincere: without dissimulation (hypocrisy), unfeigned.
  506. anupotaktos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of hupotasso; unsubdued, i.e. insubordinate (in fact or temper): disobedient, that is not put under, unruly.
  507. ano adverb from anti; upward or on the top: above, brim, high, up.
  508. anogeon from ano and ge; above the ground, i.e. (properly) the second floor of a building; used for a dome or a balcony on the upper story: upper room.
  509. anothen from ano; from above; by analogy, from the first; by implication, anew: from above, again, from the beginning (very first), the top.
  510. anoterikos from anoteros; superior, i.e. (locally) more remote: upper.
  511. anoteros comparative degree of ano; upper, i.e. (neuter as adverb) to a more conspicuous place, in a former part of the book: above, higher.
  512. anopheles from a (as a negative particle) and the base of ophelimos; useless or (neuter) inutility: unprofitable(-ness).
  513. axine probably from agnumi (to break; compare rhegnumi); an axe: axe.
  514. axios probably from ago; deserving, comparable or suitable (as if drawing praise): due reward, meet, (un-)worthy.
  515. axioo from axios; to deem entitled or fit: desire, think good, count (think) worthy.
  516. axios adverb from axios; appropriately: as becometh, after a godly sort, worthily(-thy).
  517. aoratos from a (as a negative particle) and horatos; invisible: invisible (thing).
  518. apaggello from apo and the base of aggelos; to announce: bring word (again), declare, report, shew (again), tell.
  519. apagchomai from apo and agcho (to choke; akin to the base of agkale); to strangle oneself off (i.e. to death): hang himself.
  520. apago from apo and ago; to take off (in various senses): bring, carry away, lead (away), put to death, take away.
  521. apaideutos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of paideuo; uninstructed, i.e. (figuratively) stupid: unlearned.
  522. apairo from apo and airo; to lift off, i.e. remove: take (away).
  523. apaiteo from apo and aiteo; to demand back: ask again, require.
  524. apalgeo from apo and algeo (to smart); to grieve out, i.e. become apathetic: be past feeling.
  525. apallasso from apo and allasso; to change away, i.e. release, (reflexively) remove: deliver, depart.
  526. apallotrioo from apo and a derivative of allotrios; to estrange away, i.e. (passively and figuratively) to be non-participant: alienate, be alien.
  527. apalos of uncertain derivation; soft: tender.
  528. apantao from apo and a derivative of anti; to meet away, i.e. encounter: meet.
  529. apantesis from apantao; a (friendly) encounter: meet.
  530. hapax probably from hapas; one (or a single) time (numerically or conclusively): once.
  531. aparabatos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of parabaino; not passing away, i.e. untransferable (perpetual): unchangeable.
  532. aparaskeuastos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of paraskeuazo; unready: unprepared.
  533. aparneomai from apo and arneomai; to deny utterly, i.e. disown, abstain: deny.
  534. aparti from apo and arti; from now, i.e. henceforth (already): from henceforth.

  536. aparche from a compound of apo and archomai; a beginning of sacrifice, i.e. the (Jewish) first-fruit (figuratively): first-fruits.
  537. hapas from a (as a particle of union) and pas; absolutely all or (singular) every one: all (things), every (one), whole.
  538. apatao of uncertain derivation; to cheat, i.e. delude: deceive.
  539. apate from apatao; delusion: deceit(-ful, -fulness), deceivableness(-ving).
  540. apator from a (as a negative particle) and pater; fatherless, i.e. of unrecorded paternity: without father.
  541. apaugasma from a compound of apo and augazo; an off-flash, i.e. effulgence: brightness.
  542. apeido from apo and the same as eido; to see fully: see.
  543. apeitheia from apeithes; disbelief (obstinate and rebellious): disobedience, unbelief.
  544. apeitheo from apeithes; to disbelieve (wilfully and perversely): not believe, disobedient, obey not, unbelieving.
  545. apeithes from a (as a negative particle) and peitho; unpersuadable, i.e. contumacious: disobedient.
  546. apeileo of uncertain derivation; to menace; by implication, to forbid: threaten.
  547. apeile from apeileo; a menace: X straitly, threatening.
  548. apeimi from apo and eimi; to be away: be absent. Compare apeimi.
  549. apeimi from apo and eimi (to go); to go away: go. Compare apeimi.
  550. apeipomen reflexive past of a compound of apo and epo; to say off for oneself, i.e. disown: renounce.
  551. apeirastos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of peirao; untried, i.e. not temptable: not to be tempted.
  552. apeiros from a (as a negative particle) and peira; inexperienced, i.e. ignorant: unskilful.
  553. apekdechomai from apo and ekdechomai; to expect fully: look (wait) for.
  554. apekduomai middle voice from apo and ekduo; to divest wholly oneself, or (for oneself) despoil: put off, spoil.
  555. apekdusis from apekduomai; divestment: putting off.
  556. apelauno from apo and elauno; to dismiss: drive.
  557. apelegmos from a compound of apo and elegcho; refutation, i.e. (by implication) contempt: nought.
