  559. Apelles of Latin origin; Apelles, a Christian: Apelles.
  560. apelpizo from apo and elpizo; to hope out, i.e. fully expect: hope for again.
  561. apenanti from apo and enanti; from in front, i.e. opposite, before or against: before, contrary, over against, in the presence of.
  562. aperantos from a (as a negative particle) and a secondary derivative of peran; unfinished, i.e. (by implication) interminable: endless.
  563. aperispastos adverb from a compound of a (as a negative participle) and a presumed derivative of perispao; undistractedly, i.e. free from (domestic) solicitude: without distraction.
  564. aperitmetos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of peritemno; uncircumcised (figuratively): uncircumcised.
  565. aperchomai from apo and erchomai; to go off (i.e. depart), aside (i.e. apart) or behind (i.e. follow), literally or figuratively: come, depart, go (aside, away, back, out, ways), pass away, be past.
  566. apechei third person singular present indicative active of apecho used impersonally; it is sufficient: it is enough.
  567. apechomai middle voice (reflexively) of apecho; to hold oneself off, i.e. refrain: abstain.
  568. apecho from apo and echo; (actively) to have out, i.e. receive in full; (intransitively) to keep (oneself) away, i.e. be distant (literally or figuratively): be, have, receive.
  569. apisteo from apistos; to be unbelieving, i.e. (transitively) disbelieve, or (by implication) disobey: believe not.
  570. apaistia from apistos; faithlessness, i.e. (negatively) disbelief (lack of Christian faith), or (positively) unfaithfulness (disobedience): unbelief.
  571. apistos from a (as a negative particle) and pistos; (actively) disbelieving, i.e. without Christian faith (specially, a heathen); (passively) untrustworthy (person), or incredible (thing): that believeth not, faithless, incredible thing, infidel, unbeliever(-ing).
  572. haplotes from haplous; singleness, i.e. (subjectively) sincerity (without dissimulation or self-seeking), or (objectively) generosity (copious bestowal): bountifulness, liberal(-ity), simplicity, singleness.
  573. haplous probably from a (as a particle of union) and the base of pleko; properly, folded together, i.e. single (figuratively, clear): single.
  574. haplos adverb from haplous (in the objective sense of haplotes); bountifully; --liberally.
  575. apo a primary particle; "off," i.e. away (from something near), in various senses (of place, time, or relation; literal or figurative): (X here-)after, ago, at, because of, before, by (the space of), for(-th), from, in, (out) of, off, (up-)on(-ce), since, with. In composition (as a prefix) it usually denotes separation, departure, cessation, completion, reversal, etc.
  576. apobaino from apo and the base of basis; literally, to disembark; figuratively, to eventuate: become, go out, turn.
  577. apoballo from apo and ballo; to throw off; figuratively, to lose: cast away.
  578. apoblepo from apo and blepo; to look away from everything else, i.e. (figuratively) intently regard: have respect.
  579. apobletos from apoballo; cast off, i.e. (figuratively) such as to be rejected: be refused.
  580. apobole from apoballo; rejection; figuratively, loss: casting away, loss.
  581. apogenomenos past participle of a compound of apo and ginomai; absent, i.e. deceased (figuratively, renounced): being dead.
  582. apographe from apographo; an enrollment; by implication, an assessment: taxing.
  583. apographo from apo and grapho; to write off (a copy or list), i.e. enrol: tax, write.
  584. apodeiknumi from apo and deiknuo; to show off, i.e. exhibit; figuratively, to demonstrate, i.e. accredit: (ap-)prove, set forth, shew.
  585. apodeixis from apodeiknumi; manifestation: demonstration.
  586. apodekatoo from apo and dekatoo; to tithe (as debtor or creditor): (give, pay, take) tithe.
  587. apodektos from apodechomai; accepted, i.e. agreeable: acceptable.
  588. apodechomai from apo and dechomai; to take fully, i.e. welcome (persons), approve (things): accept, receive (gladly).
  589. apodemeo from apodemos; to go abroad, i.e. visit a foreign land: go (travel) into a far country, journey.
  590. apodemos from apo and demos; absent from one's own people, i.e. a foreign traveller: taking a far journey.
  591. apodidomi from apo and didomi; to give away, i.e. up, over, back, etc. (in various applications): deliver (again), give (again), (re-)pay(-ment be made), perform, recompense, render, requite, restore, reward, sell, yield.
  592. apodiorizo from apo and a compound of Alexandros and horizo; to disjoin (by a boundary, figuratively, a party): separate.
  593. apodokimazo from apo and dokimazo; to disapprove, i.e. (by implication) to repudiate: disallow, reject.
  594. apodoche from apodechomai; acceptance: acceptation.
  595. apothesis from apotithemi; a laying aside (literally or figuratively): putting away (off).
  596. apotheke from apotithemi; a repository, i.e. granary: barn, garner.
  597. apothesaurizo from apo and thesaurizo; to treasure away: lay up in store.
  598. apothlibo from apo and thlibo; to crowd (from every side): press.
  599. apothnesko from apo and thnesko; to die off (literally or figuratively): be dead, death, die, lie a-dying, be slain (X with).
  600. apokathistemi from apo and kathistemi; to reconstitute (in health, home or organization): restore (again).
  601. apokalupto from apo and kalupto; to take off the cover, i.e. disclose: reveal.
  602. apokalupsis from apokalupto; disclosure: appearing, coming, lighten, manifestation, be revealed, revelation.
  603. apokaradokia from a comparative of apo and a compound of kara (the head) and dokeo (in the sense of watching); intense anticipation: earnest expectation.
  604. apokatallasso from apo and katallasso; to reconcile fully: reconcile.
  605. apokatastasis from apokathistemi; reconstitution: restitution.
  606. apokeimai from apo and keimai; to be reserved; figuratively, to await: be appointed, (be) laid up.
  607. apokephalizo from apo and kephale; to decapitate: behead.
  608. apokleio from apo and kleio; to close fully: shut up.
  609. apokopto from apo and kopto; to amputate; reflexively (by irony) to mutilate (the privy parts): cut off. Compare katatome.
  610. apokrima from apokrinomai (in its original sense of judging); a judicial decision: sentence.
  611. apokrinomai from apo and krino; to conclude for oneself, i.e. (by implication) to respond; by Hebraism (compare `anah) to begin to speak (where an address is expected): answer.
  612. apokrisis from apokrinomai; a response: answer.
  613. apokrupto from apo and krupto; to conceal away (i.e. fully); figuratively, to keep secret: hide.
  614. apokruphos from apokrupto; secret; by implication, treasured: hid, kept secret.
  615. apokteino from apo and kteino (to slay); to kill outright; figuratively, to destroy: put to death, kill, slay.
  616. apokueo from apo and the base of kuma; to breed forth, i.e. (by transference) to generate (figuratively): beget, produce.
  617. apokulio from apo and kulioo; to roll away: roll away (back).
  618. apolambano from apo and lambano; to receive (specially, in full, or as a host); also to take aside: receive, take.
  619. apolausis from a comparative of apo and lauo (to enjoy); full enjoyment: enjoy(-ment).
  620. apoleipo from apo and leipo; to leave behind (passively, remain); by implication, to forsake: leave, remain.
  621. apoleicho from apo and leicho (to "lick"); to lick clean: lick.
  622. apollumi from apo and the base of olethros; to destroy fully (reflexively, to perish, or lose), literally or figuratively: destroy, die, lose, mar, perish.
  623. Apolluon active participle of apollumi; a destroyer (i.e. Satan): Apollyon.
  624. Apollonia from the pagan deity Apollon (i.e. the sun; from apollumi); Apollonia, a place in Macedonia: Apollonia.
  625. Apollos probably from the same as Apollonia; Apollos, an Israelite: Apollos.
  626. apologeomai middle voice from a compound of apo and logos; to give an account (legal plea) of oneself, i.e. exculpate (self): answer (for self), make defence, excuse (self), speak for self.
  627. apologia from the same as apologeomai; a plea ("apology"): answer (for self), clearing of self, defence.
  628. apolouo from apo and louo; to wash fully, i.e. (figuratively) have remitted (reflexively): wash (away).
  629. apolutrosis from a compound of apo and lutron; (the act) ransom in full, i.e. (figuratively) riddance, or (specially) Christian salvation: deliverance, redemption.
  630. apoluo from apo and luo; to free fully, i.e. (literally) relieve, release, dismiss (reflexively, depart), or (figuratively) let die, pardon or (specially) divorce: (let) depart, dismiss, divorce, forgive, let go, loose, put (send) away, release, set at liberty.
  631. apomassomai middle voice from apo and masso (to squeeze, knead, smear); to scrape away: wipe off.
  632. aponemo from apo and the base of nomos; to apportion, i.e. bestow: give.
  633. aponipto from apo and nipto; to wash off (reflexively, one's own hands symbolically): wash.
  634. apopipto from apo and pipto; to fall off: fall.
  635. apoplanao from apo and planao; to lead astray (figuratively); passively, to stray (from truth): err, seduce.
  636. apopleo from apo and pleo; to set sail: sail away.
  637. apopluno from apo and pluno; to rinse off: wash.
  638. apopnigo from apo and pnigo; to stifle (by drowning or overgrowth): choke.
  639. aporeo from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and the base of poreuomai; to have no way out, i.e. be at a loss (mentally): (stand in) doubt, be perplexed.
  640. aporia from the same as aporeo; a (state of) quandary: perplexity.
  641. aporrhipto from apo and rhipto; to hurl off, i.e. precipitate (oneself): cast.
  642. aporphanizo from apo and a derivative of orphanos; to bereave wholly, i.e. (figuratively) separate (from intercourse): take.
  643. aposkeuazo from apo and a derivative of skeuos; to pack up (one's) baggage: take up carriages.
  644. aposkiasma from a compound of apo and a derivative of skia; a shading off, i.e. obscuration: shadow.
  645. apospao from apo and spao; to drag forth, i.e. (literally) unsheathe (a sword), or relatively (with a degree of force implied) retire (personally or factiously): (with-)draw (away), after we were gotten from.
  646. apostasia feminine of the same as apostasion; defection from truth (properly, the state) ("apostasy"): falling away, forsake.
  647. apostasion neuter of a (presumed) adjective from a derivative of aphistemi; properly, something separative, i.e. (specially) divorce: (writing of) divorcement.
  648. apostegazo from apo and a derivative of stege; to unroof: uncover.
  649. apostello from apo and stello; set apart, i.e. (by implication) to send out (properly, on a mission) literally or figuratively: put in, send (away, forth, out), set (at liberty).
  650. apostereo from apo and stereo (to deprive); to despoil: defraud, destitute, kept back by fraud.
  651. apostole from apostello; commission, i.e. (specially) apostolate: apostleship.
  652. apostolos from apostello; a delegate; specially, an ambassador of the Gospel; officially a commissioner of Christ ("apostle") (with miraculous powers): apostle, messenger, he that is sent.
  653. apostomatizo from apo and a (presumed) derivative of stoma; to speak off-hand (properly, dictate), i.e. to catechize (in an invidious manner): provoke to speak.
  654. apostrepho from apo and strepho; to turn away or back (literally or figuratively): bring again, pervert, turn away (from).
  655. apostugeo from apo and the base of stugnetos; to detest utterly: abhor.
  656. aposunagogos from apo and sunagoge; excommunicated: (put) out of the synagogue(-s).
  657. apotassomai middle voice from apo and tasso; literally, to say adieu (by departing or dismissing); figuratively, to renounce: bid farewell, forsake, take leave, send away.
  658. apoteleo from apo and teleo; to complete entirely, i.e. consummate: finish.
  659. apotithemi from apo and tithemi; to put away (literally or figuratively): cast off, lay apart (aside, down), put away (off).
  660. apotinasso from apo and tinasso (to jostle); to brush off: shake off.
  661. apotino from apo and tino; to pay in full: repay.
  662. apotolmao from apo and tolmao; to venture plainly: be very bold.
  663. apotomia from the base of apotomos; (figuratively) decisiveness, i.e. rigor: severity.
  664. apotomos adverb from a derivative of a comparative of apo and temno (to cut); abruptly, i.e. peremptorily: sharply(-ness).
  665. apotrepo from apo and the base of trope; to deflect, i.e. (reflexively) avoid: turn away.
  666. apousia from the participle of apeimi; a being away: absence.
  667. appohero from apo and phero; to bear off (literally or relatively): bring, carry (away).
  668. apopheugo from apo and pheugo; (figuratively) to escape: escape.
  669. apophtheggomai from apo and phtheggomai; to enunciate plainly, i.e. declare: say, speak forth, utterance.
  670. apophortizomai from apo and the middle voice of phortizo; to unload: unlade.
  671. apochresis from a compound of apo and chraomai; the act of using up, i.e. consumption: using.
  672. apochoreo from apo and choreo; to go away: depart.
  673. apochorizo from apo and chorizo; to rend apart; reflexively, to separate: depart (asunder).
  674. apopsucho from apo and psucho; to breathe out, i.e. faint: hearts failing.
  675. Appios of Latin origin; (in the genitive, i.e. possessive case) of Appius, the name of a Roman: Appii.
  676. aprositos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a comparative of pros and eimi (to go); inaccessible: which no man can approach.
  677. aproskopos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of proskopto; actively, inoffensive, i.e. not leading into sin; passively, faultless, i.e. not led into sin: none (void of, without) offence.
  678. aprosopoleptos adverb from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a presumed compound of prosopon and lambano (compare prosopoleptes); in a way not accepting the person, i.e. impartially: without respect of persons.
  679. aptaistos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of ptaio; not stumbling, i.e. (figuratively) without sin: from falling.
  680. haptomai reflexive of hapto; properly, to attach oneself to, i.e. to touch (in many implied relations): touch.
  681. hapto a primary verb; properly, to fasten to, i.e. (specially) to set on fire: kindle, light.
  682. Apphia probably of foreign origin; Apphia, a woman of Collos: Apphia.
  683. apotheomai or apothomai from apo and the middle voice of otheo or otho (to shove); to push off, figuratively, to reject: cast away, put away (from), thrust away (from).
  684. apoleia from a presumed derivative of apollumi; ruin or loss (physical, spiritual or eternal): damnable(-nation), destruction, die, perdition, X perish, pernicious ways, waste.
  685. ara probably from airo; properly, prayer (as lifted to Heaven), i.e. (by implication) imprecation: curse.
  686. ara probably from airo (through the idea of drawing a conclusion); a particle denoting an inference more or less decisive (as follows): haply, (what) manner (of man), no doubt, perhaps, so be, then, therefore, truly, wherefore. Often used in connection with other particles, especially ge or oun (after) or ei (before). Compare also ara.
  687. ara a form of ara, denoting an interrogation to which a negative answer is presumed: therefore.
  688. Arabia of Hebrew origin (` Arab); Arabia, a region of Asia: Arabia.
  689. Aram of Hebrew origin (Ram); Aram (i.e. Ram), an Israelite: Aram.
  690. Araps from Arabia; an Arab or native of Arabia: Arabian.
  691. argeo from argos; to be idle, i.e. (figuratively) to delay: linger.
  692. argos from a (as a negative particle) and ergon; inactive, i.e. unemployed; (by implication) lazy, useless: barren, idle, slow.
  693. argureos from arguros; made of silver: (of) silver.
  694. argurion neuter of a presumed derivative of arguros; silvery, i.e. (by implication) cash; specially, a silverling (i.e. drachma or shekel): money, (piece of) silver (piece).
  695. argurokopos from arguros and kopto; a beater (i.e. worker) of silver: silversmith.
  696. arguros from argos (shining); silver (the metal, in the articles or coin): silver.
  697. Areios Pagos from Ares (the name of the Greek deity of war) and a derivative of pegnumi; rock of Ares, a place in Athens: Areopagus, Mars' Hill.
  698. Areopagites from Areios Pagos; an Areopagite or member of the court held on Mars' Hill: Areopagite.
  699. areskeia from a derivative of aresko; complaisance: pleasing.
  700. aresko probably from airo (through the idea of exciting emotion); to be agreeable (or by implication, to seek to be so): please.
  701. arestos from aresko; agreeable; by implication, fit: (things that) please(-ing), reason.
  702. Aretas of foreign origin; Aretas, an Arabian: Aretas.
  703. arete from the same as arrhen; properly, manliness (valor), i.e. excellence (intrinsic or attributed): praise, virtue.
  704. aren perhaps the same as arrhen; a lamb (as a male): lamb.
  705. arithmeo from arithmos; to enumerate or count: number.
  706. arithmos from airo; a number (as reckoned up): number.
  707. Arimathaia of Hebrew origin (Ramah); Arimatha (or Ramah), a place in Palestine: Arimatha.
  708. Aristarchos from the same as ariston and archo; best ruling; Aristarchus, a Macedonian: Aristarchus.
  709. aristao from ariston; to take the principle meal: dine.
  710. aristeros apparently a comparative of the same as ariston; the left hand (as second-best): left (hand).
  711. Aristoboulos from the same as ariston and boule; best counselling; Aristoboulus, a Christian: Aristobulus.
  712. ariston apparently neuter of a superlative from the same as arrhen; the best meal (or breakfast; perhaps from eri ("early")), i.e. luncheon: dinner.
  713. arketos from arkeo; satisfactory: enough, suffice (-ient).
  714. arkeo apparently a primary verb (but probably akin to airo through the idea of raising a barrier); properly, to ward off, i.e. (by implication) to avail (figuratively, be satisfactory): be content, be enough, suffice, be sufficient.
  715. arktos probably from arkeo; a bear (as obstructing by ferocity): bear.
  716. harma probably from airo (perhaps with a (as a particle of union) prefixed); a chariot (as raised or fitted together (compare harmos)): chariot.
  717. Armageddon of Hebrew origin (har and Mgiddown); Armageddon (or Har-Meggiddon), a symbolic name: Armageddon.
  718. harmozo from harmos; to joint, i.e. (figuratively) to woo (reflexively, to betroth): espouse.
  719. harmos from the same as harma; an articulation (of the body): joint.
  720. arneomai perhaps from a (as a negative particle) and the middle voice of rheo; to contradict, i.e. disavow, reject, abnegate: deny, refuse.
  721. arnion diminutive from aren; a lambkin: lamb.
  722. arotrioo from arotron; to plow: plough.
  723. arotron from aroo (to till); a plow: plough.
  724. harpage from harpazo; pillage (properly abstract): extortion, ravening, spoiling.
  725. harpagmos from harpazo; plunder (properly concrete): robbery.
  726. harpazo from a derivative of haireomai; to seize (in various applications): catch (away, up), pluck, pull, take (by force).
  727. harpax from harpazo; rapacious: extortion, ravening.
  728. arrhabon of Hebrew origin (`arabown); a pledge, i.e. part of the purchase-money or property given in advance as security for the rest: earnest.
  729. arrhaphos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of the same as rhaphis; unsewed, i.e. of a single piece: without seam.
  730. arrhen or arsen probably from airo; male (as stronger for lifting): male, man.
  731. arrhetos from a (as a negative particle) and the same as rhetos; unsaid, i.e. (by implication) inexpressible: unspeakable.
  732. arrhostos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of rhonnumi; infirm: sick (folk, -ly).
  733. arsenokoites from arrhen and koite; a sodomite: abuser of (that defile) self with mankind.
  734. Artemas contracted from a compound of Artemis and doron; gift of Artemis; Artemas (or Artemidorus), a Christian: Artemas.
  735. Artemis probably from the same as artemon; prompt; Artemis, the name of a Grecian goddess borrowed by the Asiatics for one of their deities: Diana.
  736. artemon from a derivative of arti; properly, something ready (or else more remotely from airo (compare artos); something hung up), i.e. (specially) the topsail (rather foresail or jib) of a vessel: mainsail.
  737. arti adverb from a derivative of airo (compare artos) through the idea of suspension; just now: this day (hour), hence(-forth), here(-after), hither(-to), (even) now, (this) present.
  738. artigennetos from arti and gennetos; just born, i.e. (figuratively) a young convert: new born.
  739. artios from arti; fresh, i.e. (by implication) complete: perfect.
  740. artos from airo; bread (as raised) or a loaf: (shew-)bread, loaf.
  741. artuo from a presumed derivative of airo; to prepare, i.e. spice (with stimulating condiments): season.
  742. Arphaxad of Hebrew origin ('Arpakshad); Arphaxad, a post-diluvian patriarch: Arphaxad.
  743. archaggelos from archo and aggelos; a chief angel: archangel.
  744. archaios from arche; original or primeval: (them of) old (time).
  745. Archelaos from archo and Laodikeus; people-ruling; Archelaus, a Jewish king: Archelaus.
  746. arche from archomai; (properly abstract) a commencement, or (concretely) chief (in various applications of order, time, place, or rank): beginning, corner, (at the, the) first (estate), magistrate, power, principality, principle, rule.
  747. archegos from arche and ago; a chief leader: author, captain, prince.
  748. archieratikos from arche and a derivative of hieros; high-priestly: of the high-priest.
  749. archiereus from arche and hiereus; the high-priest (literally, of the Jews, typically, Christ); by extension a chief priest: chief (high) priest, chief of the priests.
  750. archipoimen from arche and poimen; a head shepherd: chief shepherd.
  751. Archippos from arche and hippos; horse-ruler; Archippus, a Christian: Archippus.
  752. archisunagogos from arche and sunagoge; director of the synagogue services: (chief) ruler of the synagogue.
  753. architekton from arche and tekton; a chief constructor, i.e. "architect": masterbuilder.
  754. architelones from arche and telones; a principle tax-gatherer: chief among the publicans.
  755. architriklinos from arche and a compound of treis and klino (a dinner-bed, because composed of three couches); director of the entertainment: governor (ruler) of the feast.
  756. archomai middle voice of archo (through the implication, of precedence); to commence (in order of time): (rehearse from the) begin(-ning).
  757. archo a primary verb; to be first (in political rank or power): reign (rule) over.
  758. archon present participle of archo; a first (in rank or power): chief (ruler), magistrate, prince, ruler.
  759. aroma from airo (in the sense of sending off scent); an aromatic: (sweet) spice.
  760. Asa of Hebrew origin ('Aca'); Asa, an Israelite: Asa.
  761. asaleutos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of saleuo; unshaken, i.e. (by implication) immovable (figuratively): which cannot be moved, unmovable.
  762. asbestos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of sbennumi; not extinguished, i.e. (by implication) perpetual: not to be quenched, unquenchable.
  763. asebeia from asebes; impiety, i.e. (by implication) wickedness: ungodly(-liness).
  764. asebeo from asebes; to be (by implied act) impious or wicked: commit (live, that after should live) ungodly.
  765. asebes from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of sebomai; irreverent, i.e. (by extension) impious or wicked: ungodly (man).
  766. aselgeia from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a presumed selges (of uncertain derivation, but apparently meaning continent); licentiousness (sometimes including other vices): filthy, lasciviousness, wantonness.
  767. asemos from a (as a negative particle) and the base of semaino; unmarked, i.e. (figuratively) ignoble: mean.
  768. Aser of Hebrew origin ('Asher); Aser (i.e. Asher), an Israelite tribe: Aser.
  769. astheneia from asthenes; feebleness (of mind or body); by implication, malady; morally, frailty: disease, infirmity, sickness, weakness.
  770. astheneo from asthenes; to be feeble (in any sense): be diseased, impotent folk (man), (be) sick, (be, be made) weak.
  771. asthenema from astheneo; a scruple of conscience: infirmity.
  772. asthenes from a (as a negative particle) and the base of sthenoo; strengthless (in various applications, literal, figurative and moral): more feeble, impotent, sick, without strength, weak(-er, -ness, thing).
  773. Asia of uncertain derivation; Asia, i.e. Asia Minor, or (usually) only its western shore: Asia.
  774. Asianos from Asia; an Asian (i.e. Asiatic) or an inhabitant of Asia: of Asia.
  775. Asiarches from Asia and arche; an Asiarch or president of the public festivities in a city of Asia Minor: chief of Asia.
  776. asitia from asitos; fasting (the state): abstinence.
  777. asitos from a (as a negative particle) and sitos; without (taking) food: fasting.
  778. askeo probably from the same as skeuos; to elaborate, i.e. (figuratively) train (by implication, strive): exercise.
  779. askos from the same as askeo; a leathern (or skin) bag used as a bottle: bottle.
  780. asmenos adverb from a derivative of the base of hedone; with pleasure: gladly.
  781. asophos from a (as a negative particle) and sophos; unwise: fool.
  782. aspazomai from a (as a particle of union) and a presumed form of spao; to enfold in the arms, i.e. (by implication) to salute, (figuratively) to welcome: embrace, greet, salute, take leave.
  783. aspasmos from aspazomai; a greeting (in person or by letter): greeting, salutation.
  784. aspilos from a (as a negative particle) and spiloo; unblemished (physically or morally): without spot, unspotted.
  785. aspis of uncertain derivation; a buckler (or round shield); used of a serpent (as coiling itself), probably the "asp": asp.
  786. aspondos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of spendo; literally, without libation (which usually accompanied a treaty), i.e. (by implication) truceless: implacable, truce-breaker.
  787. assarion of Latin origin; an assarius or as, a Roman coin: farthing.
  788. asson neuter comparative of the base of eggus; more nearly, i.e. very near: close.
  789. Assos probably of foreign origin; Assus, a city of Asia MInor: Assos.
  790. astateo from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of histemi; to be non-stationary, i.e. (figuratively) homeless: have no certain dwelling-place.
  791. asteios from astu (a city); urbane, i.e. (by implication) handsome: fair.
  792. aster probably from the base of stronnumi; a star (as strown over the sky), literally or figuratively: star.
  793. asteriktos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of sterizo; unfixed, i.e. (figuratively) vacillating: unstable.
  794. astorgos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of stergo (to cherish affectionately); hard-hearted towards kindred: without natural affection.
  795. astocheo from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and stoichos (an aim); to miss the mark, i.e. (figuratively) deviate from truth: err, swerve.
  796. astrape from astrapto; lightning; by analogy, glare: lightning, bright shining.
  797. astrapto probably from aster; to flash as lightning: lighten, shine.
  798. astron neuter from aster; properly, a constellation; put for a single star (natural or artificial): star.
  799. Asugkritos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of sugkrino; incomparable; Asyncritus, a Christian: Asyncritos.
  800. asumphonos from a (as a negative particle) and sumphonos; inharmonious (figuratively): agree not.
  801. asunetos from a (as a negative particle) and sunetos; unintelligent; by implication, wicked: foolish, without understanding.
  802. asunthetos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of suntithemai; properly, not agreed, i.e. treacherous to compacts: covenant-breaker.
  803. asphaleia from asphales; security (literally or figuratively): certainty, safety.
  804. asphales from a (as a negative particle) and sphallo (to "fail"); secure (literally or figuratively): certain(-ty), safe, sure.
  805. asphalizo from asphales; to render secure: make fast (sure).
  806. asphalos adverb from asphales; securely (literally or figuratively): assuredly, safely.
  807. aschemoneo from askemon; to be (i.e. act) unbecoming: behave self uncomely (unseemly).
  808. aschemosune from askemon; an indecency; by implication, the pudenda: shame, that which is unseemly.
  809. askemon from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of echo (in the sense of its congener schema); properly, shapeless, i.e. (figuratively) inelegant: uncomely.
  810. asotia from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of sozo; properly, unsavedness, i.e. (by implication) profligacy: excess, riot.
  811. asotos adverb from the same as asotia; dissolutely: riotous.
  812. atakteo from ataktos; to be (i.e. act) irregular: behave self disorderly.
  813. ataktos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of tasso; unarranged, i.e. (by implication) insubordinate (religiously): unruly.
  814. ataktos adverb from ataktos, irregularly (morally): disorderly.
  815. ateknos from a (as a negative particle) and teknon; childless: childless, without children.
  816. atenizo from a compound of a (as a particle of union) and teino (to stretch); to gaze intently: behold earnestly (stedfastly), fasten (eyes), look (earnestly, stedfastly, up stedfastly), set eyes.
  817. ater a particle probably akin to aneu; aloof, i.e. apart from (literally or figuratively): in the absence of, without.
  818. atimazo from atimos; to render infamous, i.e. (by implication) contemn or maltreat: despise, dishonour, suffer shame, entreat shamefully.
  819. atimia from atimos; infamy, i.e. (subjectively) comparative indignity, (objectively) disgrace: dishonour, reproach, shame, vile.
  820. atimos from a (as a negative particle) and time; (negatively) unhonoured or (positively) dishonoured: despised, without honour, less honourable (comparative degree).
  821. atimoo from atimos; used like atimazo, to maltreat: handle shamefully.
  822. atmis from the same as aer; mist: vapour.
  823. atomos from a (as a negative particle) and the base of tomoteros; uncut, i.e. (by implication) indivisible (an "atom" of time): moment.
  824. atopos from a (as a negative particle) and topos; out of place, i.e. (figuratively) improper, injurious, wicked: amiss, harm, unreasonable.
  825. Attaleia from Attalos (a king of Pergamus); Attaleia, a place in Pamphylia: Attalia.
  826. augazo from auge; to beam forth (figuratively): shine.
  827. auge of uncertain derivation; a ray of light, i.e. (by implication) radiance, dawn: break of day.
  828. Augoustos from Latin ("august"); Augustus, a title of the Roman emperor: Augustus.
  829. authades from autos and the base of hedone; self-pleasing, i.e. arrogant: self-willed.
  830. authairetos from autos and the same as hairetizo; self-chosen, i.e. (by implication) voluntary: of own accord, willing of self.
  831. authenteo from a compound of autos and an obsolete hentes (a worker); to act of oneself, i.e. (figuratively) dominate: usurp authority over.
  832. auleo from aulos; to play the flute: pipe.
  833. aule from the same as aer; a yard (as open to the wind); by implication, a mansion: court, (sheep-)fold, hall, palace.
  834. auletes from auleo; a flute-player: minstrel, piper.
  835. aulizomai middle voice from aule; to pass the night (properly, in the open air): abide, lodge.
  836. aulos from the same as aer; a flute (as blown): pipe.
  837. auzano a prolonged form of a primary verb; to grow ("wax"), i.e. enlarge (literal or figurative, active or passive): grow (up), (give the) increase.
  838. auxesis from auzano; growth: increase.
  839. aurion from a derivative of the same as aer (meaning a breeze, i.e. the morning air); properly, fresh, i.e. (adverb with ellipsis of hemera) to-morrow: (to-)morrow, next day.
  840. austeros from a (presumed) derivative of the same as aer (meaning blown); rough (properly as a gale), i.e. (figuratively) severe: austere.
  841. autarkeia from autarkes; self-satisfaction, i.e. (abstractly) contentedness, or (concretely) a competence: contentment, sufficiency.
  842. autarkes from autos and arkeo; self-complacent, i.e. contented: content.
  843. autokatakritos from autos and a derivative or katakrino; self-condemned: condemned of self.
  844. automatos from autos and the same as maten; self-moved ("automatic"), i.e. spontaneous: of own accord, of self.
  845. autoptes from autos and optanomai; self-seeing, i.e. an eye-witness: eye-witness.
  846. autos from the particle au (perhaps akin to the base of aer through the idea of a baffling wind) (backward); the reflexive pronoun self, used (alone or in the comparative heautou) of the third person, and (with the proper personal pronoun) of the other persons: her, it(-self), one, the other, (mine) own, said, (self-), the) same, ((him-, my-, thy-)self, (your-)selves, she, that, their(-s), them(-selves), there(-at, - by, -in, -into, -of, -on, -with), they, (these) things, this (man), those, together, very, which. Compare hautou.
  847. autou genitive (i.e. possessive) of autos, used as an adverb of location; properly, belonging to the same spot, i.e. in this (or that) place: (t-)here.
  848. hautou contracted for heautou; self (in some oblique case or reflexively, relation): her (own), (of) him(-self), his (own), of it, thee, their (own), them(-selves), they.
  849. autocheir from autos and cheir; self-handed, i.e. doing personally: with own hands.
  850. auchmeros from auchmos (probably from a base akin to that of aer) (dust, as dried by wind); properly, dirty, i.e. (by implication) obscure: dark.
  851. aphaireo from apo and haireomai; to remove (literally or figuratively): cut (smite) off, take away.
  852. aphanes from a (as a negative particle) and phaino; non-apparent): that is not manifest.
  853. aphanizo from aphanes; to render unapparent, i.e. (actively) consume (becloud), or (passively) disappear (be destroyed): corrupt, disfigure, perish, vanish away.
  854. aphanismos from aphanizo; disappearance, i.e. (figuratively) abrogation: vanish away.
  855. aphantos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of phaino; non-manifested, i.e. invisible: vanished out of sight.
  856. aphedron from a compound of apo and the base of hedraios; a place of sitting apart, i.e. a privy: draught.
  857. apheidia from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and pheidomai; unsparingness, i.e. austerity (asceticism): neglecting.
  858. aphelotes from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and phellos (in the sense of a stone as stubbing the foot); smoothness, i.e. (figuratively) simplicity: singleness.
  859. aphesis from aphiemi; freedom; (figuratively) pardon: deliverance, forgiveness, liberty, remission.
  860. haphe from haptomai; probably a ligament (as fastening): joint.
  861. aphthrsia from aphthartos; incorruptibility; genitive, unending existence; (figuratively) genuineness: immortality, incorruption, sincerity.
  862. aphthartos from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of phtheiro; undecaying (in essence or continuance): not (in-, un-)corruptible, immortal.
  863. aphiemi from apo and hiemi (to send; an intensive form of eimi, to go); to send forth, in various applications (as follow): cry, forgive, forsake, lay aside, leave, let (alone, be, go, have), omit, put (send) away, remit, suffer, yield up.
  864. aphikneomai from apo and the base of hikanos; to go (i.e. spread) forth (by rumor): come abroad.
  865. aphilagathos from a (as a negative particle) and philagathos; hostile to virtue: despiser of those that are good.
  866. aphilarguros from a (as a negative particle) and philarguros; unavaricious: without covetousness, not greedy of filthy lucre.
  867. aphixis from aphikneomai; properly, arrival, i.e. (by implication) departure: departing.
  868. aphistemi from apo and histemi; to remove, i.e. (actively) instigate to revolt; usually (reflexively) to desist, desert, etc.: depart, draw (fall) away, refrain, withdraw self.
  869. aphno adverb from aphanes (contraction); unawares, i.e. unexpectedly: suddenly.
  870. aphobos adverb from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and phobos; fearlessly: without fear.
  871. aphomoioo from apo and homoioo; to assimilate closely: make like.
  872. aphorao from apo and horao; to consider attentively: look.
  873. aphorizo from apo and horizo; to set off by boundary, i.e. (figuratively) limit, exclude, appoint, etc.: divide, separate, sever.
  874. aphorme from a compound of apo and hormao; a starting-point, i.e. (figuratively) an opportunity: occasion.
  875. aphrizo from aphros; to froth at the mouth (in epilepsy): foam.
  876. aphros apparently a primary word; froth, i.e. slaver: foaming.
  877. aphrosune from aphron; senselessness, i.e. (euphemistically) egotism; (morally) recklessness: folly, foolishly(-ness).
  878. aphron from a (as a negative particle) and phren; properly, mindless, i.e. stupid, (by implication) ignorant, (specially) egotistic, (practically) rash, or (morally) unbelieving: fool(-ish), unwise.
  879. aphupnoo from a compound of apo and hupnos; properly, to become awake, i.e. (by implication) to drop (off) in slumber: fall asleep.
  880. aphonos from a (as a negative particle) and phone; voiceless, i.e. mute (by nature or choice); figuratively, unmeaning: dumb, without signification.
  881. Achaz of Hebrew origin ('Achaz); Achaz, an Israelite: Achaz.
  882. Achaia of uncertain derivation; Achaia (i.e. Greece), a country of Europe: Achaia.
  883. Achaikos from Achaia; an Achaian; Achaicus, a Christian: Achaicus.
  884. acharistos from a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of charizomai; thankless, i.e. ungrateful: unthankful.
  885. Acheim probably of Hebrew origin (compare Yowqiym); Achim, an Israelite: Achim.
  886. acheiropoietos from a (as a negative particle) and cheiropoietos; unmanufactured, i.e. inartificial: made without (not made with) hands.
  887. achlus of uncertain derivation; dimness of sight, i.e. (probably) a cataract: mist.
  888. achreios from a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of chre (compare chreia); useless, i.e. (euphemistically) unmeritorious: unprofitable.
  889. achreioo from achreios; to render useless, i.e. spoil: become unprofitable.
  890. achrestos from a (as a negative particle) and chrestos; inefficient, i.e. (by implication) detrimental: unprofitable.
  891. achri or achris akh'-rece; akin to akron (through the idea of a terminus); (of time) until or (of place) up to: as far as, for, in(-to), till, (even, un-)to, until, while. Compare mechri.
  892. achuron perhaps remotely from cheo (to shed forth); chaff (as diffusive): chaff.
  893. apseudes from a (as a negative particle) and pseudos; veracious: that cannot lie.
  894. apsinthos of uncertain derivation; wormwood (as a type of bitterness, i.e. (figuratively) calamity): wormwood.
  895. apsuchos from a (as a negative particle) and psuche; lifeless, i.e. inanimate (mechanical): without life.
  896. Baal of Hebrew origin (Ba`al); Baal, a Phnician deity (used as a symbol of idolatry): Baal.
  897. Babulon of Hebrew origin (Babel); Babylon, the capitol of Chalda (literally or figuratively (as a type of tyranny)): Babylon.
  898. bathmos from the same as bathos; a step, i.e. (figuratively) grade (of dignity): degree.
  899. bathos from the same as bathus; profundity, i.e. (by implication) extent; (figuratively) mystery: deep(-ness, things), depth.
  900. bathuno from bathus; to deepen: deep.
  901. bathus from the base of basis; profound (as going down), literally or figuratively: deep, very early.
  902. baion a diminutive of a derivative probably of the base of basis; a palm twig (as going out far): branch.
  903. Balaam of Hebrew origin (Bil`am); Balaam, a Mesopotamian (symbolic of a false teacher): Balaam.
  904. Balak of Hebrew origin (Balaq); Balak, a Moabite: Balac.
  905. balantion probably remotely from ballo (as a depository); a pouch (for money): bag, purse.
  906. ballo a primary verb; to throw (in various applications, more or less violent or intense): arise, cast (out), X dung, lay, lie, pour, put (up), send, strike, throw (down), thrust. Compare rhipto.
  907. baptizo from a derivative of bapto; to immerse, submerge; to make whelmed (i.e. fully wet); used only (in the New Testament) of ceremonial ablution, especially (technically) of the ordinance of Christian baptism: Baptist, baptize, wash.
  908. baptisma from baptizo; baptism (technically or figuratively): baptism.
  909. baptismos from baptizo; ablution (ceremonial or Christian): baptism, washing.
  910. Baptistes from baptizo; a baptizer, as an epithet of Christ's forerunner: Baptist.
  911. bapto a primary verb; to whelm, i.e. cover wholly with a fluid; in the New Testament only in a qualified or special sense, i.e. (literally) to moisten (a part of one's person), or (by implication) to stain (as with dye): dip.
  912. Barabbas of Chaldee origin (ga'own and 'Abagtha'); son of Abba; Bar-abbas, an Israelite: Barabbas.
  913. Barak of Hebrew origin (Baraq); Barak, an Israelite: Barak.
  914. Barachias of Hebrew origin (Berekyah); Barachias (i.e. Berechijah), an Israelite: Barachias.
  915. barbaros of uncertain derivation; a foreigner (i.e. non-Greek): barbarian(-rous).
  916. bareo from barus; to weigh down (figuratively): burden, charge, heavy, press.
  917. bareos adverb from barus; heavily (figuratively): dull.
  918. Bartholomaios of Chaldee origin (bar and Talmay); son of Tolmai; Bar-tholomus, a Christian apostle: Bartholomeus.
  919. Bariesous of Chaldee origin (bar and Yhowshuwa`); son of Jesus (or Joshua); Bar-jesus, an Israelite: Barjesus.
  920. Barionas of Chaldee origin (bar and Yonah); son of Jonas (or Jonah); Bar-jonas, an Israelite: Bar-jona.
  921. Barnabas of Chaldee origin (bar and nbiy'); son of Nabas (i.e. prophecy); Barnabas, an Israelite: Barnabas.
  922. baros probably from the same as basis (through the notion of going down; compare bathos); weight; in the New Testament only, figuratively, a load, abundance, authority: burden(-some), weight.
  923. Barsabas of Chaldee origin (bar and probably tsba'); son of Sabas (or Tsaba); Bar-sabas, the name of two Israelites: Barsabas.
  924. Bartimaios of Chaldee origin (bar and tame'); son of Timus (or the unclean); Bar-timus, an Israelite: Bartimus.
  925. baruno from barus; to burden (figuratively): overcharge.
  926. barus from the same as baros; weighty, i.e. (fig) burdensome, grave: grievous, heavy, weightier.
  927. barutimos from barus and time; highly valuable: very precious.
  928. basanizo from basanos; to torture: pain, toil, torment, toss, vex.
  929. basanismos from basanizo; torture: torment.
  930. basanistes from basanizo; a torturer: tormentor.
  931. basanos perhaps remotely from the same as basis (through the notion of going to the bottom); a touch-stone, i.e. (by analogy) torture: torment.
  932. basileia from basileus; properly, royalty, i.e. (abstractly) rule, or (concretely) a realm (literally or figuratively): kingdom, + reign.
  933. basileion neuter of basileios; a palace: king's court.
  934. basileios from basileus; kingly (in nature): royal.
  935. basileus probably from basis (through the notion of a foundation of power); a sovereign (abstractly, relatively, or figuratively): king.
  936. basileuo from basileus; to rule (literally or figuratively): king, reign.
  937. basilikos from basileus; regal (in relation), i.e. (literally) belonging to (or befitting) the sovereign (as land, dress, or a courtier), or (figuratively) preeminent: king's, nobleman, royal.
  938. basilissa feminine from basileuo; a queen: queen.
  939. basis from baino (to walk); a pace ("base"), i.e. (by implication) the foot: foot.
  940. baskaino akin to phasko; to malign, i.e. (by extension) to fascinate (by false representations): bewitch.
  941. bastazo perhaps remotely derived from the base of basis (through the idea of removal); to lift, literally or figuratively (endure, declare, sustain, receive, etc.): bear, carry, take up.
  942. batos of uncertain derivation; a brier shrub: bramble, bush.
  943. batos of Hebrew origin (bath); a bath, or measure for liquids: measure.
  944. batrachos of uncertain derivation; a frog: frog.
  945. battologeo from Battos (a proverbial stammerer) and logos; to stutter, i.e. (by implication) to prate tediously: use vain repetitions.
  946. bdelugma from bdelusso; a detestation, i.e. (specially) idolatry: abomination.
  947. bdeluktos from bdelusso; detestable, i.e. (specially) idolatrous: abominable.
  948. bdelusso from a (presumed) derivative of bdeo (to stink); to be disgusted, i.e. (by implication) detest (especially of idolatry): abhor, abominable.
  949. bebaios from the base of basis (through the idea of basality); stable (literally or figuratively): firm, of force, stedfast, sure.
  950. bebaioo from bebaios; to stabilitate (figuratively): confirm, (e-)stablish.
  951. bebaiosis from bebaioo; stabiliment: confirmation.
  952. bebelos from the base of basis and belos (a threshold); accessible (as by crossing the door-way), i.e. (by implication, of Jewish notions) heathenish, wicked: profane (person).
  953. bebeloo from bebelos; to desecrate: profane.
  954. Beelzeboul of Chaldee origin (by parody on Ba`al Zbuwb); dung-god; Beelzebul, a name of Satan: Beelzebub.
  955. Belial of Hebrew origin (bliya`al); worthlessness; Belial, as an epithet of Satan: Belial.
  956. belos from ballo; a missile, i.e. spear or arrow: dart.
  957. beltion neuter of a compound of a derivative of ballo (used for the comparative of agathos); better: very well.
  958. Beniamin of Hebrew origin (Binyamiyn); Benjamin, an Israelite: Benjamin.
  959. Bernike from a provincial form of phero and nike; victorious; Bernice, a member of the Herodian family: Bernice.
  960. Beroia perhaps a provincial from a derivative of peran (Pera, i.e. the region beyond the coast-line); Bera, a place in Macedonia: Berea.
  961. Beroiaios from Beroia; a Beroean or native of Bera: of Berea.
  962. Bethabara of Hebrew origin (bayith and `abarah); ferry-house; Bethabara (i.e. Bethabarah), a place on the Jordan: Bethabara.
  963. Bethania of Chaldee origin; date-house; Beth-any, a place in Palestine: Bethany.
  964. Bethesda of Chaldee origin (compare bayith and checed); house of kindness; Beth-esda, a pool in Jerusalem: Bethesda.
  965. Bethleem of Hebrew origin (Beyth l-`Aphrah); Bethleem (i.e. Beth-lechem), a place in Palestine: Bethlehem.
  966. Bethsaida of Chaldee origin (compare bayith and tsayad); fishing-house; Bethsaida, a place in Palestine: Bethsaida.

  968. bema from the base of basis; a step, i.e. foot-breath; by implication, a rostrum, i.e. a tribunal: judgment-seat, set (foot) on, throne.
  969. berullos of uncertain derivation; a "beryl": beryl.
  970. bia probably akin to bios (through the idea of vital activity); force: violence.
  971. biazo from bios; to force, i.e. (reflexively) to crowd oneself (into), or (passively) to be seized: press, suffer violence.
  972. biaios from bia; violent: mighty.
  973. biastes from biazo; a forcer, i.e. (figuratively) energetic: violent.
  974. bibliaridion a diminutive of biblion; a booklet: little book.

  976. biblos properly, the inner bark of the papyrus plant, i.e. (by implication) a sheet or scroll of writing: book.
  977. bibrosko a reduplicated and prolonged form of an obsolete primary verb (perhaps causative of bosko); to eat: eat.
  978. Bithunia of uncertain derivation; Bithynia, a region of Asia: Bithynia.
  979. bios a primary word; life, i.e. (literally) the present state of existence; by implication, the means of livelihood: good, life, living.
  980. bioo from bios; to spend existence: live.
  981. biosis from bioo; living (properly, the act, by implication, the mode): manner of life.
  982. biotikos from a derivative of bioo; relating to the present existence: of (pertaining to, things that pertain to) this life.
  983. blaberos from blapto; injurious: hurtful.
  984. blapto a primary verb; properly, to hinder, i.e. (by implication) to injure: hurt.
  985. blastano from blastos (a sprout); to germinate; by implication, to yield fruit: bring forth, bud, spring (up).
  986. Blastos perhaps the same as the base of blastano; Blastus, an officer of Herod Agrippa: Blastus.
  987. blasphemeo from blasphemos; to vilify; specially, to speak impiously: (speak) blaspheme(-er, -mously, -my), defame, rail on, revile, speak evil.
  988. blasphemia from blasphemos; vilification (especially against God): blasphemy, evil speaking, railing.
  989. blasphemos from a derivative of blapto and pheme; scurrilious, i.e. calumnious (against men), or (specially) impious (against God): blasphemer(-mous), railing.
  990. blemma from blepo; vision (properly concrete; by implication, abstract): seeing.
  991. blepo a primary verb; to look at (literally or figuratively): behold, beware, lie, look (on, to), perceive, regard, see, sight, take heed. Compare optanomai.
  992. bleteos from ballo; fit to be cast (i.e. applied): must be put.
  993. Boanerges of Chaldee origin (ben and rgaz); sons of commotion; Boanerges, an epithet of two of the apostles: Boanerges.

  996. boetheia from boethos; aid; specially, a rope or chain for frapping a vessel: help.

  1063. gar a primary particle; properly, assigning a reason (used in argument, explanation or intensification; often with other particles): and, as, because (that), but, even, for, indeed, no doubt, seeing, then, therefore, verily, what, why, yet.
  1064. gaster of uncertain derivation; the stomach; by analogy, the matrix; figuratively, a gourmand: belly, + with child, womb.

  1067. geena of Hebrew origin (gay' and Hinnom); valley of (the son of) Hinnom; ge-henna (or Ge-Hinnom), a valley of Jerusalem, used (figuratively) as a name for the place (or state) of everlasting punishment: hell.
  1068. Gethsemane of Chaldee origin (compare gath and shemen); oil-press; Gethsemane, a garden near Jerusalem: Gethsemane.
  1069. geiton from ge; a neighbour (as adjoining one's ground); by implication, a friend: neighbour.
  1070. gelao of uncertain affinity; to laugh (as a sign of joy or satisfaction): laugh.
  1071. gelos from gelao; laughter (as a mark of gratification): laughter.
  1072. gemizo transitive from gemo; to fill entirely: fill (be) full.
  1073. gemo a primary verb; to swell out, i.e. be full: be full.
  1074. genea from (a presumed derivative of) genos; a generation; by implication, an age (the period or the persons): age, generation, nation, time.
  1075. genealogeo from genea and logos; to reckon by generations, i.e. trace in genealogy: count by descent.
  1076. genealogia from the same as genealogeo; tracing by generations, i.e. "genealogy": genealogy.
  1077. genesia neuter plural of a derivative of genesis; birthday ceremonies: birthday.
  1078. genesis from the same as genea; nativity; figuratively, nature: generation, nature(-ral).
  1079. genete feminine of a presumed derivative of the base of genea; birth: birth.
  1080. gennao from a variation of genos; to procreate (properly, of the father, but by extension of the mother); figuratively, to regenerate: bear, beget, be born, bring forth, conceive, be delivered of, gender, make, spring.
  1081. gennema from gennao; offspring; by analogy, produce (literally or figuratively): fruit, generation.
  1082. Gennesaret of Hebrew origin (compare Kinnrowth); Gennesaret (i.e. Kinnereth), a lake and plain in Palestine: Gennesaret.
  1083. gennesis from gennao; nativity: birth.
  1084. gennetos from gennao; born: they that are born.
  1085. genos from ginomai; "kin" (abstract or concrete, literal or figurative, individual or collective): born, country(-man), diversity, generation, kind(-red), nation, offspring, stock.
  1086. Gergesenos of Hebrew origin (Girgashiy); a Gergesene (i.e. Girgashite) or one of the aborigines of Palestine: Gergesene.
  1087. gerousia from geron; the eldership, i.e. (collectively) the Jewish Sanhedrin: senate.
  1088. geron of uncertain affinity (compare geras); aged: old.
  1089. geuomai a primary verb; to taste; by implication, to eat; figuratively, to experience (good or ill): eat, taste.
  1090. georgeo from georgos; to till (the soil): dress.
  1091. georgion neuter of a (presumed) derivative of georgos; cultivable, i.e. a farm: husbandry.
  1092. georgos from ge and the base of ergon; a land-worker, i.e. farmer: husbandman.
  1093. ge contracted from a primary word; soil; by extension a region, or the solid part or the whole of the terrene globe (including the occupants in each application): country, earth(-ly), ground, land, world.
  1094. geras akin to geron; senility: old age.
  1095. gerasko from geras; to be senescent: be (wax) old.
  1096. ginomai a prolongation and middle voice form of a primary verb; to cause to be ("gen"-erate), i.e. (reflexively) to become (come into being), used with great latitude (literal, figurative, intensive, etc.): arise, be assembled, be(-come, -fall, -have self), be brought (to pass), (be) come (to pass), continue, be divided, draw, be ended, fall, be finished, follow, be found, be fulfilled, + God forbid, grow, happen, have, be kept, be made, be married, be ordained to be, partake, pass, be performed, be published, require, seem, be showed, X soon as it was, sound, be taken, be turned, use, wax, will, would, be wrought.
  1097. ginosko a prolonged form of a primary verb; to "know" (absolutely) in a great variety of applications and with many implications (as follow, with others not thus clearly expressed): allow, be aware (of), feel, (have) know(-ledge), perceived, be resolved, can speak, be sure, understand.
  1098. gleukos akin to glukus; sweet wine, i.e. (properly) must (fresh juice), but used of the more saccharine (and therefore highly inebriating) fermented wine: new wine.
  1099. glukus of uncertain affinity; sweet (i.e. not bitter nor salt): sweet, fresh.
  1100. glossa of uncertain affinity; the tongue; by implication, a language (specially, one naturally unacquired): tongue.
  1101. glossokomon from glossa and the base of kosmos; properly, a case (to keep mouthpieces of wind-instruments in) i.e. (by extension) a casket or (specially) purse: bag.
  1102. gnapheus by variation for a derivative from knapto (to tease cloth); a cloth-dresser: fuller.
  1103. gnesios from the same as genesia; legitimate (of birth), i.e. genuine: own, sincerity, true.
  1104. gnesios adverb from gnesios; genuinely, i.e. really: naturally.
  1105. gnophos akin to nephos; gloom (as of a storm): blackness.
  1106. gnome from ginosko; cognition, i.e. (subjectively) opinion, or (objectively) resolve (counsel, consent, etc.): advice, + agree, judgment, mind, purpose, will.
  1107. gnorizo from a derivative of ginosko; to make known; subjectively, to know: certify, declare, make known, give to understand, do to wit, wot.
  1108. gnosis from ginosko; knowing (the act), i.e. (by implication) knowledge: knowledge, science.
  1109. gnostes from ginosko; a knower: expert.
  1110. gnostos from ginosko; well-known: acquaintance, (which may be) known, notable.
  1111. gogguzo of uncertain derivation; to grumble: murmur.
  1112. goggusmos from gogguzo; a grumbling: grudging, murmuring.
  1113. goggustes from gogguzo; a grumbler: murmurer.
  1114. goes from goao (to wail); properly, a wizard (as muttering spells), i.e. (by implication) an imposter: seducer.
  1115. Golgotha of Chaldee origin (compare gulgoleth); the skull; Golgotha, a knoll near Jerusalem: Golgotha.
  1116. Gomorrha of Hebrew origin (`Amorah); Gomorrha (i.e. Amorah), a place near the Dead Sea: Gomorrha.
  1117. gomos from gemo; a load (as filling), i.e. (specially) a cargo, or (by extension) wares: burden, merchandise.
  1118. goneus from the base of ginomai; a parent: parent.
  1119. gonu of uncertain affinity; the "knee": knee(X -l).
  1120. gonupeteo from a compound of gonu and the alternate of pipto; to fall on the knee: bow the knee, kneel down.
  1121. gramma from grapho; a writing, i.e. a letter, note, epistle, book, etc.; plural learning: bill, learning, letter, scripture, writing, written.
  1122. grammateus from gramma. a writer, i.e. (professionally) scribe or secretary: scribe, town-clerk.
  1123. graptos from grapho; inscribed (figuratively): written.
  1124. graphe from grapho; a document, i.e. holy Writ (or its contents or a statement in it): scripture.
  1125. grapho a primary verb; to "grave", especially to write; figuratively, to describe: describe, write(-ing, -ten).
  1126. graodes from graus (an old woman) and eidos; crone-like, i.e. silly: old wives'.
  1127. gregoreuo from egeiro; to keep awake, i.e. watch (literally or figuratively): be vigilant, wake, (be) watch(-ful).
  1128. gumnazo from gumnos; to practise naked (in the games), i.e. train (figuratively): exercise.
  1129. gumnasia from gumnazo; training, i.e. (figuratively) asceticism: exercise.
  1130. gumneteuo from a derivative of gumnos; to strip, i.e. (reflexively) go poorly clad: be naked.
  1131. gumnos of uncertain affinity; nude (absolute or relative, literal or figurative): naked.
  1132. gumnotes from gumnos; nudity (absolute or comparative): nakedness.
  1133. gunaikarion a diminutive from gune; a little (i.e. foolish) woman: silly woman.
  1134. gunaikeios from gune; feminine: wife.
  1135. gune probably from the base of ginomai; a woman; specially, a wife: wife, woman.
  1136. Gog of Hebrew origin (Gowg); Gog, a symbolic name for some future Antichrist: Gog.
  1137. gonia probably akin to gonu; an angle: corner, quarter.
  1138. Dabid of Hebrew origin (David); Dabid (i.e. David), the Israelite king: David.
  1139. daimonizomai middle voice from daimon; to be exercised by a dmon: have a (be vexed with, be possessed with) devil(-s).
  1140. daimonion neuter of a derivative of daimon; a dmonic being; by extension a deity: devil, god.
  1141. daimoniodes from daimonion and daimon; dmon-like: devilish.
  1142. daimon from daio (to distribute fortunes); a dmon or supernatural spirit (of a bad nature): devil.
  1143. dakno a prolonged form of a primary root; to bite, i.e. (figuratively) thwart: bite.
  1144. dakru or dakruon of uncertain affinity; a tear: tear.
  1145. dakruo from dakru; to shed tears: weep. Compare klaio.
  1146. daktulios from daktulos; a finger-ring: ring.
  1147. daktulos probably from deka; a finger: finger.
  1148. Dalmanoutha probably of Chaldee origin; Dalmanutha, a place in Palestine: Dalmanutha.
  1149. Dalmatia probably of foreign derivation; Dalmatia, a region of Europe: Dalmatia.
  1150. damazo a variation of an obsolete primary of the same meaning; to tame: tame.
  1151. damalis probably from the base of damazo; a heifer (as tame): heifer.
  1152. Damaris probably from the base of damazo; perhaps gentle; Damaris, an Athenian woman: Damaris.
  1153. Damaskenos from Damaskos; a Damascene or inhabitant of Damascus: Damascene.
  1154. Damaskos of Hebrew origin (Dammeseq); Damascus, a city of Syria: Damascus.
  1155. daneizo from daneion; to loan on interest; reflexively, to borrow: borrow, lend.
  1156. daneion from danos (a gift); probably akin to the base of didomi; a loan: debt.
  1157. daneistes from daneizo; a lender: creditor.
  1158. Daniel of Hebrew origin (Daniye'l); Daniel, an Israelite: Daniel.
  1159. dapanao from dapane; to expend, i.e. (in a good sense) to incur cost, or (in a bad one) to waste: be at charges, consume, spend.
  1160. dapane from dapto (to devour); expense (as consuming): cost.
  1161. de a primary particle (adversative or continuative); but, and, etc.: also, and, but, moreover, now (often unexpressed in English).
  1162. deesis from deomai; a petition: prayer, request, supplication.
  1163. dei 3rd person singular active present of deo; also deon deh-on'; neuter active participle of the same; both used impersonally; it is (was, etc.) necessary (as binding): behoved, be meet, must (needs), (be) need(-ful), ought, should.
  1164. deigma from the base of deiknuo; a specimen (as shown): example.
  1165. deigmatizo from deigma; to exhibit: make a shew.
  1166. deiknuo a prolonged form of an obsolete primary of the same meaning; to show (literally or figuratively): shew.
  1167. deilia from deilos; timidity: fear.
  1168. deiliao from deilia; to be timid: be afraid.
  1169. deilos from deos (dread); timid, i.e. (by implication) faithless: fearful.
  1170. deina probably from the same as deinos (through the idea of forgetting the name as fearful, i.e. strange); so and so (when the person is not specified): such a man.
  1171. deinos adverb from a derivative of the same as deilos; terribly, i.e. excessively: grievously, vehemently.
  1172. deipneo from deipnon; to dine, i.e. take the principle (or evening) meal: sup (X -er).
  1173. deipnon from the same as dapane; dinner, i.e. the chief meal (usually in the evening): feast, supper.
  1174. deisidaimonesteros the compound of a derivative of the base of deilos and daimon; more religious than others: too superstitious.
  1175. deisidaimonia from the same as deisidaimonesteros; religion: superstition.
  1176. deka a primary number; ten: (eight-)een, ten.
  1177. dekaduo from deka and duo; two and ten, i.e. twelve: twelve.
  1178. dekapente from deka and pente; ten and five, i.e. fifteen: fifteen.
  1179. Dekapolis from deka and polis; the ten-city region; the Decapolis, a district in Syria: Decapolis.
  1180. dekatessares from deka and tessares; ten and four, i.e. fourteen: fourteen.
  1181. dekate feminine of dekatos; a tenth, i.e. as a percentage or (technically) tithe: tenth (part), tithe.
  1182. dekatos ordinal from deka; tenth: tenth.
  1183. dekatoo from dekate; to tithe, i.e. to give or take a tenth: pay (receive) tithes.
  1184. dektos from dechomai; approved; (figuratively) propitious: accepted(-table).
  1185. deleazo from the base of dolos; to entrap, i.e. (figuratively) delude: allure, beguile, entice.
  1186. dendron probably from drus (an oak); a tree: tree.
  1187. dexiolabos from dexios and lambano; a guardsman (as if taking the right) or light-armed soldier: spearman.
  1188. dexios from dechomai; the right side or (feminine) hand (as that which usually takes): right (hand, side).
  1189. deomai middle voice of deo; to beg (as binding oneself), i.e. petition: beseech, pray (to), make request. Compare punthanomai.
  1190. Derbaios from Derbe; a Derban or inhabitant of Derbe: of Derbe.
  1191. Derbe of foreign origin; Derbe, a place in Asia Minor: Derbe.
  1192. derma from dero; a hide: skin.
  1193. dermatinos from derma; made of hide: leathern, of a skin.
  1194. dero a primary verb; properly, to flay, i.e. (by implication) to scourge, or (by analogy) to thrash: beat, smite.
  1195. desmeuo from a (presumed) derivative of desmeo; to be a binder (captor), i.e. to enchain (a prisoner), to tie on (a load): bind.
  1196. desmeo from desmon; to tie, i.e. shackle: bind.
  1197. desme from desmeo; a bundle: bundle.
  1198. desmios from desmon; a captive (as bound): in bonds, prisoner.
  1199. desmon or desmos neuter and masculine respectively from deo; a band, i.e. ligament (of the body) or shackle (of a prisoner); figuratively, an impediment or disability: band, bond, chain, string.
  1200. desmophulax from desmon and phulax; a jailer (as guarding the prisoners): jailor, keeper of the prison.
  1201. desmoterion from a derivative of desmon (equivalent to desmeo); a place of bondage, i.e. a dungeon: prison.
  1202. desmotes from the same as desmoterion; (passively) a captive: prisoner.
  1203. despotes perhaps from deo and posis (a husband); an absolute ruler ("despot"): Lord, master.
  1204. deuro of uncertain affinity; here; used also imperative hither!; and of time, hitherto: come (hither), hither(-to).
  1205. deute from deuro and an imperative form of eimi (to go); come hither!: come, X follow.
  1206. deuteraios from deuteros; secondary, i.e. (specially) on the second day: next day.
  1207. deuteroprotos from deuteros and protos; second-first, i.e. (specially) a designation of the Sabbath immediately after the Paschal week (being the second after Passover day, and the first of the seven Sabbaths intervening before Pentecost): second after the first.
  1208. deuteros as the comparative of duo; (ordinal) second (in time, place, or rank; also adverb): afterward, again, second(-arily, time).
  1209. dechomai middle voice of a primary verb; to receive (in various applications, literally or figuratively): accept, receive, take. Compare lambano.
  1210. deo a primary verb; to bind (in various applications, literally or figuratively): bind, be in bonds, knit, tie, wind. See also dei, deomai.
  1211. de probably akin to de; a particle of emphasis or explicitness; now, then, etc.: also, and, doubtless, now, therefore.
  1212. delos of uncertain derivation; clear: + bewray, certain, evident, manifest.
  1213. deloo from delos; to make plain (by words): declare, shew, signify.
  1214. Demas probably for Demetrios; Demas, a Christian: Demas.
  1215. demexoreo from a compound of demos and agora; to be a people-gatherer, i.e. to address a public assembly: make an oration.
  1216. Demetrios from Demeter (Ceres); Demetrius, the name of an Ephesian and of a Christian: Demetrius.
  1217. demiourgos from demos and ergon; a worker for the people, i.e. mechanic (spoken of the Creator): maker.
  1218. demos from deo; the public (as bound together socially): people.
  1219. demosios from demos; public; (feminine singular dative case as adverb) in public: common, openly, publickly.
  1220. denarion of Latin origin; a denarius (or ten asses): pence, penny(-worth).
  1221. depote from de and pote; a particle of generalization; indeed, at any time: (what-)soever.
  1222. depou from de and pou; a particle of asseveration; indeed doubtless: verily.
  1223. dia a primary preposition denoting the channel of an act; through (in very wide applications, local, causal, or occasional): after, always, among, at, to avoid, because of (that), briefly, by, for (cause) fore, from, in, by occasion of, of, by reason of, for sake, that, thereby, therefore, X though, through(-out), to, wherefore, with (-in). In composition it retains the same general importance.
  1224. diabaino from dia and the base of basis; to cross: come over, pass (through).
  1225. diaballo from dia and ballo; (figuratively) to traduce: accuse.
  1226. diabebaioomai middle voice of a compound of dia and bebaioo; to confirm thoroughly (by words), i.e. asseverate: affirm constantly.
  1227. diablepo from dia and blepo; to look through, i.e. recover full vision: see clearly.
  1228. diabolos from diaballo; a traducer; specially, Satan (compare satan): false accuser, devil, slanderer.
  1229. diaggello from dia and the base of aggelos; to herald thoroughly: declare, preach, signify.
  1230. diaginomai from dia and ginomai; to elapse meanwhile: X after, be past, be spent.
  1231. diaginosko from dia and ginosko; to know thoroughly, i.e. ascertain exactly: (would) enquire, know the uttermost.
  1232. diagnorizo from graptos and gnorizo; to tell abroad: make known.
  1233. diagnosis from diaginosko; (magisterial) examination ("diagnosis"): hearing.
  1234. diagogguzo from dia and gogguzo; to complain throughout a crowd: murmur.
  1235. diagregoreo from dia and gregoreuo; to waken thoroughly: be awake.
  1236. diago from dia and ago; to pass time or life: lead life, living.
  1237. diadechomai from dia and dechomai; to receive in turn, i.e. (figuratively) succeed to: come after.
  1238. diadema from a compound of dia and deo; a "diadem" (as bound about the head): crown. Compare stephanos.
  1239. diadidomai from dia and didomi; to give throughout a crowd, i.e. deal out; also to deliver over (as to a successor): (make) distribute(-ion), divide, give.
  1240. diadochos from diadechomai; a successor in office: room.
  1241. diazonnumi from dia and zonnumi; to gird tightly: gird.
  1242. diatheke from diatithemai; properly, a disposition, i.e. (specially) a contract (especially a devisory will): covenant, testament.
  1243. diairesis from diaireo; a distinction or (concretely) variety: difference, diversity.
  1244. diaireo from dia and haireomai; to separate, i.e. distribute: divide.
  1245. diakatharizo from dia and katharizo; to cleanse perfectly, i.e. (specially) winnow: thoroughly purge.
  1246. diakatelegchomai middle voice from dia and a compound of kata and elegcho; to prove downright, i.e. confute: convince.
  1247. diakoneo from diakonos; to be an attendant, i.e. wait upon (menially or as a host, friend, or (figuratively) teacher); technically, to act as a Christian deacon: (ad-)minister (unto), serve, use the office of a deacon.
  1248. diakonia from diakonos; attendance (as a servant, etc.); figuratively (eleemosynary) aid, (official) service (especially of the Christian teacher, or technically of the diaconate): (ad-)minister(-ing, -tration, -try), office, relief, service(-ing).
  1249. diakonos probably from an obsolete diako (to run on errands; compare dioko); an attendant, i.e. (genitive case) a waiter (at table or in other menial duties); specially, a Christian teacher and pastor (technically, a deacon or deaconess): deacon, minister, servant.
  1250. diakosioi from dis and hekaton; two hundred: two hundred.
  1251. diakouomai middle voice from dia and akouo; to hear throughout, i.e. patiently listen (to a prisoner's plea): hear.
  1252. diakrino from dia and krino; to separate thoroughly, i.e. (literally and reflexively) to withdraw from, or (by implication) oppose; figuratively, to discriminate (by implication, decide), or (reflexively) hesitate: contend, make (to) differ(-ence), discern, doubt, judge, be partial, stagger, waver.
  1253. diakrisis from diakrino; judicial estimation: discern(-ing), disputation.
  1254. diakoluo from dia and koluo; to hinder altogether, i.e. utterly prohibit: forbid.
  1255. dialaleo from dia and laleo; to talk throughout a company, i.e. converse or (genitive case) publish: commune, noise abroad.
  1256. dialegomai middle voice from dia and lego; to say thoroughly, i.e. discuss (in argument or exhortation): dispute, preach (unto), reason (with), speak.
  1257. dialeipo from dia and leipo; to leave off in the middle, i.e. intermit: cease.
  1258. dialektos from dialegomai; a (mode of) discourse, i.e. "dialect": language, tongue.
  1259. diallasso from dia and allasso; to change thoroughly, i.e. (mentally) to conciliate: reconcile.
  1260. dialogizomai from dia and logizomai; to reckon thoroughly, i.e. (genitive case) to deliberate (by reflection or discussion): cast in mind, consider, dispute, muse, reason, think.
  1261. dialogismos from dialogizomai; discussion, i.e. (internal) consideration (by implication, purpose), or (external) debate: dispute, doubtful(-ing), imagination, reasoning, thought.
  1262. dialuo from dia and luo; to dissolve utterly: scatter.
  1263. diamarturomai from dia and martureo; to attest or protest earnestly, or (by implication) hortatively: charge, testify (unto), witness.
  1264. diamachomai from dia and machomai; to fight fiercely (in altercation): strive.
  1265. diameno from dia and meno; to stay constantly (in being or relation): continue, remain.
  1266. diamerizo from dia and merizo; to partition thoroughly (literally in distribution, figuratively in dissension): cloven, divide, part.
  1267. diamerismos from diamerizo; disunion (of opinion and conduct): division.
  1268. dianemo from dia and the base of nomos; to distribute, i.e. (of information) to disseminate: spread.
  1269. dianeuo from dia and neuo; to nod (or express by signs) across an intervening space: beckon.
  1270. dianoema from a compound of dia and noieo; something thought through, i.e. a sentiment: thought.
  1271. dianoia from dia and nous; deep thought, properly, the faculty (mind or its disposition), by implication, its exercise: imagination, mind, understanding.
  1272. dianoigo from dia and anoigo; to open thoroughly, literally (as a first-born) or figuratively (to expound): open.
  1273. dianuktereuo from dia and a derivative of nux; to sit up the whole night: continue all night.
  1274. dianuo from dia and anuo (to effect); to accomplish thoroughly: finish.
  1275. diapantos from dia and the genitive case of pas; through all time, i.e. (adverbially) constantly: alway(-s), continually.
  1276. diaperao from dia and a derivative of the base of peran; to cross entirely: go over, pass (over), sail over.
  1277. diapleo from dia and pleo; to sail through: sail over.
  1278. diaponeo from dia and a derivative of ponos; to toil through, i.e. (passively) be worried: be grieved.
  1279. diaporeuomai from dia and poreuomai; to travel through: go through, journey in, pass by.
  1280. diaporeo from dia and aporeo; to be thoroughly nonplussed: (be in) doubt, be (much) perplexed.
  1281. diapragmateuomai from dia and pragmateuomai; to thoroughly occupy oneself, i.e. (transitively and by implication) to earn in business: gain by trading.
  1282. diaprio from dia and the base of prizo; to saw asunder, i.e. (figuratively) to exasperate: cut (to the heart).
  1283. diarpazo from dia and harpazo; to seize asunder, i.e. plunder: spoil.
  1284. diarrhesso from dia and rhegnumi; to tear asunder: break, rend.
  1285. diasapheo from dia and saphes (clear); to clear thoroughly, i.e. (figuratively) declare: tell unto.
  1286. diaseio from dia and seio; to shake thoroughly, i.e. (figuratively) to intimidate: do violence to.
  1287. diaskorpizo from dia and skorpizo; to dissipate, i.e. (genitive case) to rout or separate; specially, to winnow; figuratively, to squander: disperse, scatter (abroad), strew, waste.
  1288. diaspao from dia and spao; to draw apart, i.e. sever or dismember: pluck asunder, pull in pieces.
  1289. diaspeiro from dia and speiro; to sow throughout, i.e. (figuratively) distribute in foreign lands: scatter abroad.
  1290. diaspora from diaspeiro; dispersion, i.e. (specially and concretely) the (converted) Israelite resident in Gentile countries: (which are) scattered (abroad).
  1291. diastellomai middle voice from dia and stello; to set (oneself) apart (figuratively, distinguish), i.e. (by implication) to enjoin: charge, that which was (give) commanded(-ment).
  1292. diastema from diistemi; an interval: space.
  1293. diastole from diastellomai; a variation: difference, distinction.
  1294. diastrepho from dia and strepho; to distort, i.e. (figuratively) misinterpret, or (morally) corrupt: perverse(-rt), turn away.
  1295. diasozo from dia and sozo; to save thoroughly, i.e. (by implication or analogy) to cure, preserve, rescue, etc.: bring safe, escape (safe), heal, make perfectly whole, save.
  1296. diatage from diatasso; arrangement, i.e. institution: instrumentality.
  1297. diatagma from diatasso; an arrangement, i.e. (authoritative) edict: commandment.
  1298. diatarasso from dia and tarasso; to disturb wholly, i.e. agitate (with alarm): trouble.
  1299. diatasso from dia and tasso; to arrange thoroughly, i.e. (specially) institute, prescribe, etc.: appoint, command, give, (set in) order, ordain.
  1300. diateleo from dia and teleo; to accomplish thoroughly, i.e. (subjectively) to persist: continue.
  1301. diatereo from dia and tereo; to watch thoroughly, i.e. (positively and transitively) to observe strictly, or (negatively and reflexively) to avoid wholly: keep.
  1302. diati from dia and tis; through what cause ?, i.e. why?: wherefore, why.
