  1304. diatribo from dia and the base of tribos; to wear through (time), i.e. remain: abide, be, continue, tarry.
  1305. diatrophe from a compound of dia and trepho; nourishment: food.
  1306. diaugazo from dia and augazo; to glimmer through, i.e. break (as day): dawn.
  1307. diaphanes from dia and phaino; appearing through, i.e. "diaphanous": transparent.
  1308. diaphero from dia and phero; to bear through, i.e. (literally) transport; usually to bear apart, i.e. (objectively) to toss about (figuratively, report); subjectively, to "differ", or (by implication) surpass: be better, carry, differ from, drive up and down, be (more) excellent, make matter, publish, be of more value.
  1309. diapheugo from dia and pheugo; to flee through, i.e. escape: escape.
  1310. diaphemizo from dia and a derivative of pheme; to report thoroughly, i.e. divulgate: blaze abroad, commonly report, spread abroad, fame.
  1311. diaphtheiro from diaballo and phtheiro; to rot thoroughly, i.e. (by implication) to ruin (passively, decay utterly, figuratively, pervert): corrupt, destroy, perish.
  1312. diaphthora from diaphtheiro; decay: corruption.
  1313. diaphoros from diaphero; varying; also surpassing: differing, divers, more excellent.
  1314. diaphulasso from dia and phulasso; to guard thoroughly, i.e. protect: keep.
  1315. diacheirizomai from dia and a derivative of cheir; to handle thoroughly, i.e. lay violent hands upon: kill, slay.
  1316. diachorizomai from dia and the middle voice of chorizo; to remove (oneself) wholly, i.e. retire: depart.
  1317. didaktikos from didaktos; instructive ("didactic"): apt to teach.
  1318. didaktos from didasko; (subjectively) instructed, or (objectively) communicated by teaching: taught, which teacheth.
  1319. didaskalia from didaskalos; instruction (the function or the information): doctrine, learning, teaching.
  1320. didaskalos from didasko; an instructor (genitive case or specially): doctor, master, teacher.
  1321. didasko a prolonged (causative) form of a primary verb dao (to learn); to teach (in the same broad application): teach.
  1322. didache from didasko; instruction (the act or the matter): doctrine, hath been taught.
  1323. didrachmon from dis and drachme; a double drachma (didrachm): tribute.
  1324. Didumos prolongation from dis; double, i.e. twin; Didymus, a Christian: Didymus.
  1325. didomi a prolonged form of a primary verb (which is used as an alternative in most of the tenses); to give (used in a very wide application, properly, or by implication, literally or figuratively; greatly modified by the connection): adventure, bestow, bring forth, commit, deliver (up), give, grant, hinder, make, minister, number, offer, have power, put, receive, set, shew, smite (+ with the hand), strike (+ with the palm of the hand), suffer, take, utter, yield.
  1326. diegeiro from dia and egeiro; to wake fully; i.e. arouse (literally or figuratively): arise, awake, raise, stir up.
  1327. diexodos from dia and exodos; an outlet through, i.e. probably an open square (from which roads diverge): highway.
  1328. diermeneutes from diermeneuo; an explainer: interpreter.
  1329. diermeneuo from dia and hermeneuo; to explain thoroughly, by implication, to translate: expound, interpret(-ation).
  1330. dierchomai from dia and erchomai; to traverse (literally): come, depart, go (about, abroad, everywhere, over, through, throughout), pass (by, over, through, throughout), pierce through, travel, walk through.
  1331. dierotao from dia and erotao; to question throughout, i.e. ascertain by interrogation: make enquiry for.
  1332. dietes from dis and etos; of two years (in age): two years old.

  1334. diegeomai from dia and hegeomai; to relate fully: declare, shew, tell.
  1335. diegesis from diegeomai; a recital: declaration.
  1336. dienekes neuter of a compound of dia and a derivative of an alternate of phero; carried through, i.e. (adverbially with eis and ho prefixed) perpetually: + continually, for ever.
  1337. dithalassos from dis and thalassa; having two seas, i.e. a sound with a double outlet: where two seas meet.
  1338. diikneomai from dia and the base of hikanos; to reach through, i.e. penetrate: pierce.
  1339. diistemi from dia and histemi; to stand apart, i.e. (reflexively) to remove, intervene: go further, be parted, after the space of.

  1341. dikaiokrisia from dikaios and krisis; a just sentence: righteous judgment.

  1343. dikaiosune from dikaios; equity (of character or act); specially (Christian) justification: righteousness.

  1349. dike probably from deiknuo; right (as self-evident), i.e. justice (the principle, a decision, or its execution): judgment, punish, vengeance.
  1350. diktuon probably from a primary verb diko (to cast); a seine (for fishing): net.
  1351. dilogos from dis and logos; equivocal, i.e. telling a different story: double-tongued.
  1352. dio from dia and hos; through which thing, i.e. consequently: for which cause, therefore, wherefore.

  1356. diopetes from the alternate of Zeus and the alternate of pipto; sky-fallen (i.e. an aerolite): which fell down from Jupiter.
  1357. diorthosis from a compound of dia and a derivative of orthos, meaning to straighten thoroughly; rectification, i.e. (specially) the Messianic restauration: reformation.

  1364. dis adverb from duo; twice: again, twice.
  1365. distazo from dis; properly, to duplicate, i.e. (mentally) to waver (in opinion): doubt.

  1368. diulizo from dia and hulizo hoo-lid'-zo (to filter); to strain out: strain at (probably by misprint).

  1370. dichostsis from a derivative of dis and stasis; disunion, i.e. (figuratively) dissension: division, sedition.
  1371. dichotomeo from a compound of a derivative of dis and a derivative of temno (to cut); to bisect, i.e. (by extension) to flog severely: cut asunder (in sunder).
  1372. dipsao from a variation of dipsos; to thirst for (literally or figuratively): (be, be a-)thirst(-y).

  1374. dipsuchos from dis and psuche; two-spirited, i.e. vacillating (in opinion or purpose): double minded.
  1375. diogmos from dioko; persecution: persecution.
  1376. dioktes from dioko; a persecutor: persecutor.
  1377. dioko a prolonged (and causative) form of a primary verb dio (to flee; compare the base of deilos and diakonos); to pursue (literally or figuratively); by implication, to persecute: ensue, follow (after), given to, (suffer) persecute(-ion), press forward.
  1378. dogma from the base of dokeo; a law (civil, ceremonial or ecclesiastical): decree, ordinance.
  1379. dogmatizo from dogma; to prescribe by statute, i.e. (reflexively) to submit to, ceremonially rule: be subject to ordinances.
  1380. dokeo a prolonged form of a primary verb, doko dok'-o (used only in an alternate in certain tenses; compare the base of deiknuo) of the same meaning; to think; by implication, to seem (truthfully or uncertainly): be accounted, (of own) please(-ure), be of reputation, seem (good), suppose, think, trow.
  1381. dokimazo from dokimos; to test (literally or figuratively); by implication, to approve: allow, discern, examine, X like, (ap-)prove, try.
  1382. dokime from the same as dokimos; test (abstractly or concretely); by implication, trustiness: experience(-riment), proof, trial.
  1383. dokimion neuter of a presumed derivative of dokime; a testing; by implication, trustworthiness: trial, trying.
  1384. dokimos from dokeo; properly, acceptable (current after assayal), i.e. approved: approved, tried.
  1385. dokos from dechomai (through the idea of holding up); a stick of timber: beam.
  1386. dolios from dolos; guileful: deceitful.
  1387. dolioo from dolios; to be guileful: use deceit.
  1388. dolos from an obsolete primary verb, dello (probably meaning to decoy; compare deleazo); a trick (bait), i.e. (figuratively) wile: craft, deceit, guile, subtilty.
  1389. doloo from dolos; to ensnare, i.e. (figuratively) adulterate: handle deceitfully.
  1390. doma from the base of didomi; a present: gift.
  1391. doxa from the base of dokeo; glory (as very apparent), in a wide application (literal or figurative, objective or subjective): dignity, glory(-ious), honour, praise, worship.
  1392. doxazo from doxa; to render (or esteem) glorious (in a wide application): (make) glorify(-ious), full of (have) glory, honour, magnify.

  1395. dotes from the base of didomi; a giver: giver.
  1396. doulagogeo from a presumed compound of doulos and ago; to be a slave-driver, i.e. to enslave (figuratively, subdue): bring into subjection.
  1397. douleia from douleuo; slavery (ceremonially or figuratively): bondage.
  1398. douleuo from doulos; to be a slave to (literal or figurative, involuntary or voluntary): be in bondage, (do) serve(-ice).
  1399. doule feminine of doulos; a female slave (involuntarily or voluntarily): handmaid(-en).
  1400. doulon neuter of doulos; subservient: servant.
  1401. doulos from deo; a slave (literal or figurative, involuntary or voluntary; frequently, therefore in a qualified sense of subjection or subserviency): bond(-man), servant.
  1402. douloo from doulos; to enslave (literally or figuratively): bring into (be under) bondage, X given, become (make) servant.
  1403. doche from dechomai; a reception, i.e. convivial entertainment: feast.
  1404. drakon probably from an alternate form of derkomai (to look); a fabulous kind of serpent (perhaps as supposed to fascinate): dragon.
  1405. drassomai perhaps akin to the base of drakon (through the idea of capturing); to grasp, i.e. (figuratively) entrap: take.
  1406. drachme from drassomai; a drachma or (silver) coin (as handled): piece (of silver).
  1407. drepanon from drepo (to pluck); a gathering hook (especially for harvesting): sickle.
  1408. dromos from the alternate of trecho; a race, i.e. (figuratively) career: course.
  1409. Drousilla a feminine diminutive of Drusus (a Roman name); Drusilla, a member of the Herodian family: Drusilla.
  1410. dunamai of uncertain affinity; to be able or possible: be able, can (do, + -not), could, may, might, be possible, be of power.

  1412. dunamoo from dunamis; to enable: strengthen.
  1413. dunastes from dunamai; a ruler or officer: of great authority, mighty, potentate.

  1415. dunatos from dunamai; powerful or capable (literally or figuratively); neuter possible: able, could, (that is) mighty (man), possible, power, strong.
  1416. duno or dumi prolonged forms of an obsolete primary duo (to sink) to go "down": set.
  1417. duo a primary numeral; "two": both, twain, two.
  1418. dus- a primary inseparable particle of uncertain derivation; used only in composition as a prefix; hard, i.e. with difficulty: + hard, + grievous, etc.
  1419. dusbastaktos from dus- and a derivative of bastazo; oppressive: grievous to be borne.

  1421. dusermeneutos from dus- and a presumed derivative of hermeneuo; difficult of explanation: hard to be uttered.
  1422. duskolos from dus- and kolon (food); properly, fastidious about eating (peevish), i.e. (genitive case) impracticable: hard.

  1431. dorea from doron; a gratuity: gift.

  1434. dorema from doreomai; a bestowment: gift.
  1435. doron a present; specially, a sacrifice: gift, offering.
  1436. ea apparent imperative of eao; properly, let it be, i.e. (as interjection) aha!: let alone.
  1437. ean from ei and an; a conditional particle; in case that, provided, etc.; often used in connection with other particles to denote indefiniteness or uncertainty: before, but, except, (and) if, (if) so, (what-, whither-)soever, though, when (-soever), whether (or), to whom, (who-)so(-ever).   1438. heautou from a reflexive pronoun otherwise obsolete and the genitive case (dative case or accusative case) of autos; him- (her-, it-, them-, also (in conjunction with the personal pronoun of the other persons) my-, thy-, our-, your-) self (selves), etc.: alone, her (own, -self), (he) himself, his (own), itself, one (to) another, our (thine) own(-selves), + that she had, their (own, own selves), (of) them(-selves), they, thyself, you, your (own, own conceits, own selves, -selves).

  1440. hebdomekonta from hebdomos and a modified form of deka; seventy: seventy, three score and ten.

  1443. Eber of Hebrew origin (`Eber); Eber, a patriarch: Eber.

  1448. eggizo from eggus; to make near, i.e. (reflexively) approach: approach, be at hand, come (draw) near, be (come, draw) nigh.

  1453. egeiro probably akin to the base of agora (through the idea of collecting one's faculties); to waken (transitively or intransitively), i.e. rouse (literally, from sleep, from sitting or lying, from disease, from death; or figuratively, from obscurity, inactivity, ruins, nonexistence): awake, lift (up), raise (again, up), rear up, (a-)rise (again, up), stand, take up.

  1474. edaphizo from edaphos; to raze: lay even with the ground.

  1485. ethos from etho; a usage (prescribed by habit or law): custom, manner, be wont.
  1486. etho a primary verb; to be used (by habit or conventionality); neuter perfect participle usage: be custom (manner, wont).
  1487. ei a primary particle of conditionality; if, whether, that, etc.: forasmuch as, if, that, (al-)though, whether. Often used in connection or composition with other particles, especially as in eige, ei de me(ge), ei kai, ei me, ei me ti, ei per, ei pos, ei tis, ek. See also ean.
  1488. ei second person singular present of eimi; thou art: art, be.
  1489. eige from ei and ge; if indeed, seeing that, unless, (with negative) otherwise: if (so be that, yet).
  1490. ei de me(ge) from ei, de, and me (sometimes with ge added); but if not: (or) else, if (not, otherwise), otherwise.
  1491. eidos from eido; a view, i.e. form (literally or figuratively): appearance, fashion, shape, sight.
  1492. eido a primary verb; used only in certain past tenses, the others being borrowed from the equivalent optanomai and horao; properly, to see (literally or figuratively); by implication, (in the perfect tense only) to know: be aware, behold, X can (+ not tell), consider, (have) know(-ledge), look (on), perceive, see, be sure, tell, understand, wish, wot.   1493. eidoleion neuter of a presumed derivative of eidolon; an image-fane: idol's temple.
  1494. eidolothuton neuter of a compound of eidolon and a presumed derivative of thuo; an image-sacrifice, i.e. part of an idolatrous offering: (meat, thing that is) offered (in sacrifice, sacrificed) to (unto) idols.
  1495. eidololatreia from eidolon and latreia; image-worship (literally or figuratively): idolatry.
  1496. eidololatres from eidolon and the base of latreuo; an image- (servant or) worshipper (literally or figuratively): idolater.
  1497. eidolon from eidos; an image (i.e. for worship); by implication, a heathen god, or (plural) the worship of such: idol.
  1498. eien optative (i.e. English subjunctive) present of eimi (including the other person); might (could, would, or should) be: mean, + perish, should be, was, were.
  1499. ei kai from ei and kai; if also (or even): if (that), though.
  1500. eike probably from eiko (through the idea of failure); idly, i.e. without reason (or effect): without a cause, (in) vain(-ly).
  1501. eikosi of uncertain affinity; a score: twenty.
  1502. eiko apparently a primary verb; properly, to be weak, i.e. yield: give place.
  1503. eiko apparently a primary verb (perhaps akin to eiko through the idea of faintness as a copy); to resemble: be like.
  1504. eikon from eiko; a likeness, i.e. (literally) statue, profile, or (figuratively) representation, resemblance: image.
  1505. eilikrineia from eilikrines; clearness, i.e. (by implication) purity (figuratively): sincerity.
  1506. eilikrines from heile (the sun's ray) and krino; judged by sunlight, i.e. tested as genuine (figuratively): pure, sincere.
  1507. heilisso a prolonged form of a primary but defective verb heilo (of the same meaning); to coil or wrap: roll together. See also helisso.
  1508. ei me from ei and me; if not: but, except (that), if not, more than, save (only) that, saving, till.
  1509. ei me ti from ei me and the neuter of tis; if not somewhat: except.
  1510. eimi the first person singular present indicative; a prolonged form of a primary and defective verb; I exist (used only when emphatic): am, have been, X it is I, was. See also ei, eien, einai, heis kath heis, en, esomai, esmen, este, esti, kerdos, isthi, o.
  1511. einai present infinitive from eimi; to exist: am, was. come, is, X lust after, X please well, there is, to be, was.
  1512. ei per from ei and per; if perhaps: if so be (that), seeing, though.
  1513. ei pos from ei and pos; if somehow: if by any means.

  1516. eirenikos from eirene; pacific; by implication, salutary: peaceable.

  1519. eis a primary preposition; to or into (indicating the point reached or entered), of place, time, or (figuratively) purpose (result, etc.); also in adverbial phrases: (abundant-)ly, against, among, as, at, (back-)ward, before, by, concerning, + continual, + far more exceeding, for (intent, purpose), fore, + forth, in (among, at, unto, -so much that, -to), to the intent that, + of one mind, + never, of, (up-)on, + perish, + set at one again, (so) that, therefore(-unto), throughout, til, to (be, the end, -ward), (here-)until(-to), ward, (where-)fore, with. Often used in composition with the same general import, but only with verbs (etc.) expressing motion (literally or figuratively).
  1520. heis (including the neuter (etc.) hen); a primary numeral; one: a(-n, -ny, certain), + abundantly, man, one (another), only, other, some. See also heis kath heis, medeis, mia, oudeis.

  1535. eite from ei and te; if too: if, or, whether.

  1537. ek or ex a primary preposition denoting origin (the point whence action or motion proceeds), from, out (of place, time, or cause; literal or figurative; direct or remote): after, among, X are, at, betwixt(-yond), by (the means of), exceedingly, (+ abundantly above), for(- th), from (among, forth, up), + grudgingly, + heartily, X heavenly, X hereby, + very highly, in, ly, (because, by reason) of, off (from), on, out among (from, of), over, since, X thenceforth, through, X unto, X vehemently, with(-out).   1722. en a primary preposition denoting (fixed) position (in place, time or state), and (by implication) instrumentality (medially or constructively), i.e. a relation of rest (intermediate between eis and ek); "in," at, (up-)on, by, etc.: about, after, against, + almost, X altogether, among, X as, at, before, between, (here-)by (+ all means), for ( sake of), + give self wholly to, (here-)in(-to, -wardly), X mightily, (because) of, (up-)on, (open-)ly, X outwardly, one, X quickly, X shortly, (speedi-)ly, X that, X there(-in, -on), through(-out), (un-)to(-ward), under, when, where(-with), while, with(-in).   1735. endechetai third person singular present of a compound of en and dechomai; (impersonally) it is accepted in, i.e. admitted (possible): can (+ not) be.
  1736. endemeo from a compound of en and demos; to be in one's own country, i.e. home (figuratively): be at home (present).
  1737. endidusko a prolonged form of enduo; to invest (with a garment): clothe in, wear.
  1738. endikos from en and dike; in the right, i.e. equitable: just.
  1739. endomesis from a compound of en and a derivative of the base of demos; a housing in (residence), i.e. structure: building.
  1740. edoxazo from endoxos; to glorify: glorify.
  1741. endoxos from en and doxa; in glory, i.e. splendid, (figuratively) noble: glorious, gorgeous(-ly), honourable.
  1742. enduma from enduo; apparel (especially the outer robe): clothing, garment, raiment.
  1743. endunamoo from en and dunamoo; to empower: enable, (increase in) strength(-en), be (make) strong.
  1744. enduno from ennomos and duno; to sink (by implication, wrap (compare enduo) on, i.e. (figuratively) sneak: creep.
  1745. endusis from enduo; investment with clothing: putting on.
  1746. enduo from en and duno (in the sense of sinking into a garment); to invest with clothing (literally or figuratively): array, clothe (with), endue, have (put) on.
  1747. enedra feminine from en and the base of hedraios; an ambuscade, i.e. (figuratively) murderous purpose: lay wait. See also enedron.
  1748. enedreuo from enedra; to lurk, i.e. (figuratively) plot assassination: lay wait for.
  1749. enedron neuter of the same as enedra; an ambush, i.e. (figuratively) murderous design: lying in wait.
  1750. eneileo from ennomos and the base of heilisso; to enwrap: wrap in.
  1751. eneimi from ennomos and eimi; to be within (neuter participle plural): such things as have. See also eni.
  1752. heneka or heneken or heineken of uncertain affinity; on account of: because, for (cause, sake), (where-)fore, by reason of, that.
  1753. energeia from energes; efficiency ("energy"): operation, strong, (effectual) working.
  1754. energeo from energes; to be active, efficient: do, (be) effectual (fervent), be mighty in, shew forth self, work (effectually in).
  1755. energema from energeo; an effect: operation, working.
  1756. energes from en and ergon; active, operative: effectual, powerful.
  1757. eneulogeo from en and eulogeo; to confer a benefit on: bless.
  1758. enecho from en and echo; to hold in or upon, i.e. ensnare; by implication, to keep a grudge: entangle with, have a quarrel against, urge.
  1759. enthade from a prolonged form of en; properly, within, i.e. (of place) here, hither: (t-)here, hither.
  1760. enthumeomai from a compound of en and thumos; to be inspirited, i.e. ponder: think.
  1761. enthumesis from enthumeomai; deliberation: device, thought.
  1762. eni contraction for the third person singular present indicative of eneimi; impersonally, there is in or among: be, (there) is.
  1763. eniautos prolongation from a primary enos (a year); a year: year.
  1764. enistemi from en and histemi; to place on hand, i.e. (reflexively) impend, (participle) be instant: come, be at hand, present.
  1765. enischuo from en and ischuo; to invigorate (transitively or reflexively): strengthen.
  1766. ennatos ordinal from ennea; ninth: ninth.
  1767. ennea a primary number; nine: nine.
  1768. ennenekontaennea from a (tenth) multiple of ennea and ennea itself; ninety-nine: ninety and nine.
  1769. enneos from enneuo; dumb (as making signs), i.e. silent from astonishment: speechless.
  1770. enneuo from en and neuo; to nod at, i.e. beckon or communicate by gesture: make signs.
  1771. ennoia from a compound of en and nous; thoughtfulness, i.e. moral understanding: intent, mind.
  1772. ennomos from en and nomos; (subjectively) legal, or (objectively) subject to: lawful, under law.
  1773. ennuchon neuter of a compound of en and nux; (adverbially) by night: before day.
  1774. enoikeo from en and oikeo; to inhabit (figuratively): dwell in.
  1775. henotes from heis; oneness, i.e. (figuratively) unanimity: unity.
  1776. enochleo from en and ochleo; to crowd in, i.e. (figuratively) to annoy: trouble.
  1777. enochos from enecho; liable to (a condition, penalty or imputation): in danger of, guilty of, subject to.
  1778. entalma from entellomai; an injunction, i.e. religious precept: commandment.
  1779. entaphiazo from a compound of en and taphos; to inswathe with cerements for interment: bury.
  1780. entaphiasmos from entaphiazo; preparation for interment: burying.
  1781. entellomai from en and the base of telos; to enjoin: (give) charge, (give) command(-ments), injoin.
  1782. enteuthen from the same as enthade; hence (literally or figuratively); (repeated) on both sides: (from) hence, on either side.
  1783. enteuxis from entugchano; an interview, i.e. (specially) supplication: intercession, prayer.
  1784. entimos from en and time; valued (figuratively): dear, more honourable, precious, in reputation.
  1785. entole from entellomai; injunction, i.e. an authoritative prescription: commandment, precept.
  1786. entopios from en and topos; a resident: of that place.
  1787. entos from en; inside (adverb or noun): within.
  1788. entrepo from en and the base of trope; to invert, i.e. (figuratively and reflexively) in a good sense, to respect; or in a bad one, to confound: regard, (give) reference, shame.
  1789. entrepho from en and trepho; (figuratively) to educate: nourish up in.
  1790. entromos from en and tromos; terrified: X quake, X trembled.
  1791. entrope from entrepo; confusion: shame.
  1792. entruphao from en and truphao; to revel in: sporting selves.
  1793. entugchano from en and tugchano; to chance upon, i.e. (by implication) confer with; by extension to entreat (in favor or against): deal with, make intercession.
  1794. entulisso from en and tulisso (to twist; probably akin to heilisso); to entwine, i.e. wind up in: wrap in (together).
  1795. entupoo from en and a derivative of tupos; to enstamp, i.e. engrave: engrave.
  1796. enubrizo from en and hubrizo; to insult: do despite unto.
  1797. enupniazomai middle voice from enupnion; to dream: dream(-er).
  1798. enupnion from en and hupnos; something seen in sleep, i.e. a dream (vision in a dream): dream.
  1799. enopion neuter of a compound of en and a derivative of optanomai; in the face of (literally or figuratively): before, in the presence (sight) of, to.
  1800. Enos of Hebrew origin ('Enowsh); Enos (i.e. Enosh), a patriarch: Enos.
  1801. enotizomai middle voice from a compound of en and ous; to take in one's ear, i.e. to listen: hearken.
  1802. Enok of Hebrew origin (Chanowk); Enoch (i.e. Chanok), an antediluvian: Enoch.
  1803. hex a primary numeral; six: six.
  1804. exaggello from ek and the base of aggelos; to publish, i.e. celebrate: shew forth.
  1805. exagorazo from ek and agorazo; to buy up, i.e. ransom; figuratively, to rescue from loss (improve opportunity): redeem.
  1806. exago from ek and ago; to lead forth: bring forth (out), fetch (lead) out.
  1807. exaireo from ek and haireomai; actively, to tear out; middle voice, to select; figuratively, to release: deliver, pluck out, rescue.
  1808. exairo from ek and airo; to remove: put (take) away.
  1809. exaiteomai middle voice from ek and aiteo; to demand (for trial): desire.
  1810. exaiphnes from ek and the base of aiphnidios; of a sudden (unexpectedly): suddenly. Compare exapina.
  1811. exakoloutheo from ek and akoloutheo; to follow out, i.e. (figuratively) to imitate, obey, yield to: follow.
  1812. hexakosioi plural ordinal from hex and hekaton; six hundred: six hundred.
  1813. exaleipho from ek and aleipho; to smear out, i.e. obliterate (erase tears, figuratively, pardon sin): blot out, wipe away.
  1814. exallomai from ek and hallomai; to spring forth : leap up.
  1815. exanastasis from exanistemi; a rising from death: resurrection.
  1816. exanatello from ek and anatello; to start up out of the ground, i.e. germinate: spring up.
  1817. exanistemi from ek and anistemi; objectively, to produce, i.e. (figuratively) beget; subjectively, to arise, i.e. (figuratively) object: raise (rise) up.
  1818. exapatao from ek and apatao; to seduce wholly: beguile, deceive.
  1819. exapina from ek and a derivative of the same as aiphnidios; of a sudden, i.e. unexpectedly: suddenly. Compare exaiphnes.
  1820. exaporeomai middle voice from ek and aporeo; to be utterly at a loss, i.e. despond: (in) despair.
  1821. exapostello from ek and apostello; to send away forth, i.e. (on a mission) to despatch, or (peremptorily) to dismiss: send (away, forth, out).
  1822. exartizo from ek and a derivative of artios; to finish out (time); figuratively, to equip fully (a teacher): accomplish, thoroughly furnish.
  1823. exastrapto from ek and astrapto; to lighten forth, i.e. (figuratively) to be radiant (of very white garments): glistening.
  1824. exautes from ek and the genitive case singular feminine of autos (hora being understood); from that hour, i.e. instantly: by and by, immediately, presently, straightway.
  1825. exegeiro from ek and egeiro; to rouse fully, i.e. (figuratively) to resuscitate (from death), release (from infliction): raise up.
  1826. exeimi from ek and eimi (to go); to issue, i.e. leave (a place), escape (to the shore): depart, get (to land), go out.
  1827. exelegcho from ek and elegcho; to convict fully, i.e. (by implication) to punish: convince.
  1828. exelko from ek and helkuo; to drag forth, i.e. (figuratively) to entice (to sin): draw away.
  1829. exerama from a comparative of ek and a presumed erao (to spue); vomit, i.e. food disgorged: vomit.
  1830. exereunao from ek and ereunao; to explore (figuratively): search diligently.
  1831. exerchomai from ek and erchomai; to issue (literally or figuratively): come (forth, out), depart (out of), escape, get out, go (abroad, away, forth, out, thence), proceed (forth), spread abroad.
  1832. exesti third person singular present indicative of a compound of ek and eimi; so also exon ex-on' neuter present participle of the same (with or without some form of eimi expressed); impersonally, it is right (through the figurative idea of being out in public): be lawful, let, X may(-est).
  1833. exetazo from ek and etazo (to examine); to test thoroughly (by questions), i.e. ascertain or interrogate: ask, enquire, search.
  1834. exegeomai from ek and hegeomai; to consider out (aloud), i.e. rehearse, unfold: declare, tell.
  1835. hexekonta the tenth multiple of hex; sixty: sixty(-fold), threescore.
  1836. hexes from echo (in the sense of taking hold of, i.e. adjoining); successive: after, following, X morrow, next.
  1837. execheomai middle voice from ek and echeo; to "echo" forth, i.e. resound (be generally reported): sound forth.
  1838. hexis from echo; habit, i.e. (by implication) practice: use.
  1839. existemi from ek and histemi; to put (stand) out of wits, i.e. astound, or (reflexively) become astounded, insane: amaze, be (make) astonished, be beside self (selves), bewitch, wonder.
  1840. exischuo from ek and ischuo; to have full strength, i.e. be entirely competent: be able.
  1841. exodos from ek and hodos; an exit, i.e. (figuratively) death: decease, departing.
  1842. exolothreuo from ek and olothreuo; to extirpate: destroy.
  1843. exomologeo from ek and homologeo; to acknowledge or (by implication, of assent) agree fully: confess, profess, promise.
  1844. exorkizo from ek and horkizo; to exact an oath, i.e. conjure: adjure.
  1845. exorkistes from exorkizo; one that binds by an oath (or spell), i.e. (by implication) an "exorcist" (conjurer): exorcist.
  1846. exorusso from ek and orusso; to dig out, i.e. (by extension) to extract (an eye), remove (roofing): break up, pluck out.
  1847. exoudenoo from ek and a derivative of the neuter of oudeis; to make utterly nothing of, i.e. despise: set at nought. See also exoutheneo.
  1848. exoutheneo a variation of exoudenoo and meaning the same: contemptible, despise, least esteemed, set at nought.
  1849. exousia from exesti (in the sense of ability); privilege, i.e. (subjectively) force, capacity, competency, freedom, or (objectively) mastery (concretely, magistrate, superhuman, potentate, token of control), delegated influence: authority, jurisdiction, liberty, power, right, strength.
  1850. exousiazo from exousia; to control: exercise authority upon, bring under the (have) power of.
  1851. exoche from a compound of ek and echo (meaning to stand out); prominence (figuratively): principal.
  1852. exupnizo from exupnos; to waken: awake out of sleep.
  1853. exupnos from ek and hupnos; awake: X out of sleep.
  1854. exo adverb from ek; out(-side, of doors), literally or figuratively: away, forth, (with-)out (of, -ward), strange.
  1855. exothen from exo; external(-ly): out(-side, -ward, - wardly), (from) without.
  1856. exotheo or exotho from ek and otheo (to push); to expel; by implication, to propel: drive out, thrust in.
  1857. exoteros comparative of exo; exterior: outer.
  1858. heortazo from heorte; to observe a festival: keep the feast.
  1859. heorte of uncertain affinity; a festival: feast, holyday.
  1860. epaggelia from epaggello; an announcement (for information, assent or pledge; especially a divine assurance of good): message, promise.
  1861. epaggello from epi and the base of aggelos; to announce upon (reflexively), i.e. (by implication) to engage to do something, to assert something respecting oneself: profess, (make) promise.
  1862. epaggelma from epaggello; a self-committal (by assurance of conferring some good): promise.
  1863. epago from epi and ago; to superinduce, i.e. inflict (an evil), charge (a crime): bring upon.
  1864. epagonizomai from epi and agonizomai; to struggle for: earnestly contend for.
  1865. epathroizo from epi and athroizo (to assemble); to accumulate: gather thick together.
  1866. Epainetos from epaineo; praised; Epnetus, a Christian: Epenetus.
  1867. epaineo from epi and aineo; to applaud: commend, laud, praise.
  1868. epainos from epi and the base of aineo; laudation; concretely, a commendable thing: praise.
  1869. epairo from epi and airo; to raise up (literally or figuratively): exalt self, poise (lift, take) up.
  1870. epaischunomai from epi and aischunomai; to feel shame for something: be ashamed.
  1871. epaiteo from epi and aiteo; to ask for: beg.
  1872. epakoloutheo from epi and akoloutheo; to accompany: follow (after).
  1873. epakouo from epi and akouo; to hearken (favorably) to: hear.
  1874. epakroaomai from epi and the base of akroates; to listen (intently) to: hear.
  1875. epan from epi and an; a particle of indefinite contemporaneousness; whenever, as soon as: when.
  1876. epanagkes neuter of a presumed compound of epi and anagke; (adverbially) on necessity, i.e. necessarily: necessary.
  1877. epanago from epi and anago; to lead up on, i.e. (technical) to put out (to sea); (intransitively) to return: launch (thrust) out, return.
  1878. epanamimnesko from epi and anamimnesko; to remind of: put in mind.
  1879. epanapauomai middle voice from epi and anapano; to settle on; literally (remain) or figuratively (rely): rest in (upon).
  1880. epanerchomai from epi and anerchomai; to come up on, i.e. return: come again, return.
  1881. epanistamai middle voice from epi and anistemi; to stand up on, i.e. (figuratively) to attack: rise up against.
  1882. epanorthosis from a compound of epi and anorthoo; a straightening up again, i.e. (figuratively) rectification (reformation): correction.
  1883. epano from epi and ano; up above, i.e. over or on (of place, amount, rank, etc.): above, more than, (up-)on, over.
  1884. eparkeo from epi and arkeo; to avail for, i.e. help: relieve.
  1885. eparchia from a compound of epi and archo (meaning a governor of a district, "eparch"); a special region of government, i.e. a Roman prfecture: province.
  1886. epaulis from epi and an equivalent of aule; a hut over the head, i.e. a dwelling: habitation.
  1887. epaurion from epi and aurion; occurring on the succeeding day, i.e. (hemera being implied) to-morrow: day following, morrow, next day (after).
  1888. epautophoroi from epi and autos and (the dative case singular of) a derivative of phor (a thief); in theft itself, i.e. (by analogy) in actual crime: in the very act.
  1889. Epaphras contracted from Epaphroditos; Epaphras, a Christian: Epaphras.
  1890. epaphrizo from epi and aphrizo; to foam upon, i.e. (figuratively) to exhibit (a vile passion): foam out.
  1891. Epaphroditos from epi (in the sense of devoted to) and Aphrodite (Venus); Epaphroditus, a Christian: Epaphroditus. Compare Epaphras.
  1892. epegeiro from epi and egeiro; to rouse upon, i.e. (figuratively) to excite against: raise, stir up.
  1893. epei from epi and ei; thereupon, i.e. since (of time or cause): because, else, for that (then, -asmuch as), otherwise, seeing that, since, when.
  1894. epeide from epei and de; since now, i.e. (of time) when, or (of cause) whereas: after that, because, for (that, -asmuch as), seeing, since.
  1895. epeideper from epeide and per; since indeed (of cause): forasmuch.
  1896. epeidon and other moods and persons of the same tense; from epi and eido; to regard (favorably or otherwise): behold, look upon.
  1897. epeiper from epei and per; since indeed (of cause): seeing.
  1898. epeisagoge from a compound of epi and eisago; a superintroduction: bringing in.
  1899. epeita from epi and eita; thereafter: after that(-ward), then.
  1900. epekeina from epi and (the accusative case plural neuter of) ekeinos; upon those parts of, i.e. on the further side of: beyond.
  1901. epekteinomai middle voice from epi and ekteino; to stretch (oneself) forward upon: reach forth.
  1902. ependuomai middle voice from epi and enduo; to invest upon oneself: be clothed upon.
  1903. ependutes from ependuomai; a wrapper, i.e. outer garment: fisher's coat.
  1904. eperchomai from epi and erchomai; to supervene, i.e. arrive, occur, impend, attack, (figuratively) influence: come (in, upon).
  1905. eperotao from epi and erotao; to ask for, i.e. inquire, seek: ask (after, questions), demand, desire, question.
  1906. eperotema from eperotao; an inquiry: answer.
  1907. epecho from epi and echo; to hold upon, i.e. (by implication) to retain; (by extension) to detain; (with implication, of nous) to pay attention to: give (take) heed unto, hold forth, mark, stay.
  1908. epereazo from a comparative of epi and (probably) areia (threats); to insult, slander: use despitefully, falsely accuse.
  1909. epi a primary preposition; properly, meaning superimposition (of time, place, order, etc.), as a relation of distribution (with the genitive case), i.e. over, upon, etc.; of rest (with the dative case) at, on, etc.; of direction (with the accusative case) towards, upon, etc.: about (the times), above, after, against, among, as long as (touching), at, beside, X have charge of, (be-, (where-))fore, in (a place, as much as, the time of, -to), (because) of, (up-)on (behalf of), over, (by, for) the space of, through(-out), (un-)to(-ward), with. In compounds it retains essentially the same import, at, upon, etc. (literally or figuratively).
  1910. epibaino from epi and the base of basis; to walk upon, i.e. mount, ascend, embark, arrive: come (into), enter into, go abroad, sit upon, take ship.
  1911. epiballo from epi and ballo; to throw upon (literal or figurative, transitive or reflexive; usually with more or less force); specially (with heautou implied) to reflect; impersonally, to belong to: beat into, cast (up-)on, fall, lay (on), put (unto), stretch forth, think on.
  1912. epibareo from epi and bareo; to be heavy upon, i.e. (pecuniarily) to be expensive to; figuratively, to be severe towards: be chargeable to, overcharge.
  1913. epibibazo from epi and a reduplicated derivative of the base of basis (compare anabibazo); to cause to mount (an animal): set on.
  1914. epiblepo from epi and blepo; to gaze at (with favor, pity or partiality): look upon, regard, have respect to.
  1915. epiblema from epiballo; a patch: piece.
  1916. epiboao from epi and boao; to exclaim against: cry.
  1917. epiboule from a presumed compound of epi and boulomai; a plan against someone, i.e. a plot: laying (lying) in wait.
  1918. epigambreuo from epi and a derivative of gamos; to form affinity with, i.e. (specially) in a levirate way: marry.
  1919. epigeios from epi and ge; worldly (physically or morally): earthly, in earth, terrestrial.
  1920. epiginomai from epi and ginomai; to arrive upon, i.e. spring up (as a wind): blow.
  1921. epiginosko from epi and ginosko; to know upon some mark, i.e. recognize; by implication, to become fully acquainted with, to acknowledge: (ac-, have, take)know(-ledge, well), perceive.
  1922. epignosis from epiginosko; recognition, i.e. (by implication) full discernment, acknowledgement: (ac-)knowledge(-ing, - ment).
  1923. epigraphe from epigrapho; an inscription: superscription.
  1924. epigrapho from epi and grapho; to inscribe (physically or mentally): inscription, write in (over, thereon).
  1925. epideiknumi from epi and deiknuo; to exhibit (physically or mentally): shew.
  1926. epidechomai from epi and dechomai; to admit (as a guest or (figuratively) teacher): receive.
  1927. epidemeo from a compound of epi and demos; to make oneself at home, i.e. (by extension) to reside (in a foreign country): (be) dwelling (which were) there, stranger.
  1928. epidiatassomai middle voice from epi and diatasso; to appoint besides, i.e. supplement (as a codicil): add to.
  1929. epididomi from epi and didomi; to give over (by hand or surrender): deliver unto, give, let (+ (her drive)), offer.
  1930. epidiorthoo from epi and a derivative of orthos; to straighten further, i.e. (figuratively) arrange additionally: set in order.
  1931. epiduo from epi and duno; to set fully (as the sun): go down.
  1932. epieikeia from epieikes; suitableness, i.e. (by implication) equity, mildness: clemency, gentleness.
  1933. epieikes from epi and eiko; appropriate, i.e. (by implication) mild: gentle, moderation, patient.
  1934. epizeteo from epi and zeteo; to search (inquire) for; intensively, to demand, to crave: desire, enquire, seek (after, for).
  1935. epithanatios from epi and thanatos; doomed to death: appointed to death.
  1936. epithesis from epitithemi; an imposition (of hands officially): laying (putting) on.
  1937. epithumeo from epi and thumos; to set the heart upon, i.e. long for (rightfully or otherwise): covet, desire, would fain, lust (after).
  1938. epithumetes from epithumeo; a craver: + lust after.
  1939. epithumia from epithumeo; a longing (especially for what is forbidden): concupiscence, desire, lust (after).
  1940. epikathizo from epi and kathizo; to seat upon: set on.
  1941. epikaleomai middle voice from epi and kaleo; to entitle; by implication, to invoke (for aid, worship, testimony, decision, etc.): appeal (unto), call (on, upon), surname.
  1942. epikaluma from epikalupto; a covering, i.e. (figuratively) pretext: cloke.
  1943. epikalupto from epi and kalupto; to conceal, i.e. (figuratively) forgive: cover.
  1944. epikataratos from epi and a derivative of kataraomai; imprecated, i.e. execrable: accursed.
  1945. epikeimai from epi and keimai; to rest upon (literally or figuratively): impose, be instant, (be) laid (there-, up-)on, (when) lay (on), lie (on), press upon.
  1946. Epikoureios from Epikouros (compare epikouria) (a noted philosopher); an Epicurean or follower of Epicurus: Epicurean.
  1947. epikouria from a compound of epi and a (prolonged) form of the base of korasion (in the sense of servant); assistance: help.
  1948. epikrino from epi and krino; to adjudge: give sentence.
  1949. epilambanomai middle voice from epi and lambano; to seize (for help, injury, attainment, or any other purpose; literally or figuratively): catch, lay hold (up-)on, take (by, hold of, on).
  1950. epilanthanomai middle voice from epi and lanthano; to lose out of mind; by implication, to neglect: (be) forget(-ful of).
  1951. epilegomai middle voice from epi and lego; to surname, select: call, choose.
  1952. epileipo from epi and leipo; to leave upon, i.e. (figuratively) to be insufficient for: fail.
  1953. epilesmone from a derivative of epilanthanomai; negligence: X forgetful.
  1954. epiloipos from epi and loipoy; left over, i.e. remaining: rest.
  1955. epilusis from epiluo; explanation, i.e. application: interpretation.
  1956. epiluo from epi and luo; to solve further, i.e. (figuratively) to explain, decide: determine, expound.
  1957. epimartureo from epi and martureo; to attest further, i.e. corroborate: testify.
  1958. epimeleia from epimeleomai; carefulness, i.e. kind attention (hospitality): + refresh self.
  1959. epimeleomai middle voice from epi and the same as melo; to care for (physically or otherwise): take care of.
  1960. epimelos adverb from a derivative of epimeleomai; carefully: diligently.
  1961. epimeno from epi and meno; to stay over, i.e. remain (figuratively, persevere): abide (in), continue (in), tarry.
  1962. epineuo from epi and neuo; to nod at, i.e. (by implication) to assent: consent.
  1963. epinoia from epi and nous; attention of the mind, i.e. (by implication) purpose: thought.
  1964. epiorkeo from epiorkos; to commit perjury: forswear self.
  1965. epiorkos from epi and horkos; on oath, i.e. (falsely) a forswearer: perjured person.
  1966. epiousa feminine singular participle of a comparative of epi and eimi (to go); supervening, i.e. (hemera or nux being expressed or implied) the ensuing day or night: following, next.
  1967. epiousios perhaps from the same as epiousa; tomorrow's; but more probably from epi and a derivative of the present participle feminine of eimi; for subsistence, i.e. needful: daily.
  1968. epipipto from epi and pipto; to embrace (with affection) or seize (with more or less violence; literally or figuratively): fall into (on, upon) lie on, press upon.
  1969. epiplesso from epi and plesso; to chastise, i.e. (with words) to upbraid: rebuke.
  1970. epipnigo from epi and pnigo; to throttle upon, i.e. (figuratively) overgrow: choke.
  1971. epipotheo from epi and potheo (to yearn); to dote upon, i.e. intensely crave possession (lawfully or wrongfully): (earnestly) desire (greatly), (greatly) long (after), lust.
  1972. epipothesis from epipotheo; a longing for: earnest (vehement) desire.
  1973. epipothetos from epi and a derivative of the latter part of epipotheo; yearned upon, i.e. greatly loved: longed for.
  1974. epipothia from epipotheo; intense longing: great desire.
  1975. epiporeuomai from epi and poreuomai; to journey further, i.e. travel on (reach): come.
  1976. epirrhapto from epi and the base of rhaphis; to stitch upon, i.e. fasten with the needle: sew on.
  1977. epirrhipto from epi and rhipto; to throw upon (literally or figuratively): cast upon.
  1978. episemos from epi and some form of the base of semaino; remarkable, i.e. (figuratively) eminent: notable, of note.
  1979. episitismos from a compound of epi and a derivative of sitos; a provisioning, i.e. (concretely) food: victuals.
  1980. episkeptomai middle voice from epi and the base of skopos; to inspect, i.e. (by implication) to select; by extension, to go to see, relieve: look out, visit.
  1981. episkenoo from epi and skenoo; to tent upon, i.e. (figuratively) abide with : rest upon.
  1982. episkiazo from epi and a derivative of skia; to cast a shade upon, i.e. (by analogy) to envelop in a haze of brilliancy; figuratively, to invest with preternatural influence: overshadow.
  1983. episkopeo from epi and skopeo; to oversee; by implication, to beware: look diligently, take the oversight.
  1984. episkope from episkeptomai; inspection (for relief); by implication, superintendence; specially, the Christian "episcopate": the office of a "bishop", bishoprick, visitation.
  1985. episkopos from epi and skopos (in the sense of episkopeo); a superintendent, i.e. Christian officer in genitive case charge of a (or the) church (literally or figuratively): bishop, overseer.
  1986. epispaomai from epi and spao; to draw over, i.e. (with akrobustia implied) efface the mark of circumcision (by recovering with the foreskin): become uncircumcised.
  1987. epistamai apparently a middle voice of ephistemi (with nous implied); to put the mind upon, i.e. comprehend, or be acquainted with: know, understand.
  1988. epistates from epi and a presumed derivative of histemi; an appointee over, i.e. commander (teacher): master.
  1989. epistello from epi and stello; to enjoin (by writing), i.e. (genitive case) to communicate by letter (for any purpose): write (a letter, unto).
  1990. epistemon from epistamai; intelligent: endued with knowledge.
  1991. episterizo from epi and sterizo; to support further, i.e. reestablish: confirm, strengthen.
  1992. epistole from epistello; a written message: "epistle," letter.
  1993. epistomizo from epi and stoma; to put something over the mouth, i.e. (figuratively) to silence: stop mouths.
  1994. epistrepho from epi and strepho; to revert (literally, figuratively or morally): come (go) again, convert, (re-)turn (about, again).
  1995. epistrophe from epistrepho; reversion, i.e. morally, revolution: conversion.
  1996. episunago from epi and sunago; to collect upon the same place: gather (together).
  1997. episunagoge from episunago; a complete collection; especially a Christian meeting (for worship): assembling (gathering) together.
  1998. episuntrecho from epi and suntrecho; to hasten together upon one place (or a particular occasion): come running together.
  1999. episustasis from the middle voice of a compound of epi and sunistao; a conspiracy, i.e. concourse (riotous or friendly): that which cometh upon, + raising up.
  2000. episphales from a compound of epi and sphallo (to trip); figuratively, insecure: dangerous.
  2001. episucho from epi and ischuo; to avail further, i.e. (figuratively) insist stoutly: be the more fierce.
  2002. episoreuo from epi and soreuo; to accumulate further, i.e. (figuratively) seek additionally: heap.
  2003. epitage from epitasso; an injunction or decree; by implication, authoritativeness: authority, commandment.
  2004. epitasso from epi and tasso; to arrange upon, i.e. order: charge, command, injoin.
  2005. epiteleo from epi and teleo; to fulfill further (or completely), i.e. execute; by implication, to terminate, undergo: accomplish, do, finish, (make) (perfect), perform(X -ance).
  2006. epitedeios from epitedes (enough); serviceable, i.e. (by implication) requisite: things which are needful.
  2007. epitithemi from epi and tithemi; to impose (in a friendly or hostile sense): add unto, lade, lay upon, put (up) on, set on (up), + surname, X wound.
  2008. epitimao from epi and timao; to tax upon, i.e. censure or admonish; by implication, forbid: (straitly) charge, rebuke.
  2009. epitimia from a compound of epi and time; properly, esteem, i.e. citizenship; used (in the sense of epitimao) of a penalty: punishment.
  2010. epitrepo from epi and the base of trope; to turn over (transfer), i.e. allow: give leave (liberty, license), let, permit, suffer.
  2011. epitrope from epitrepo; permission, i.e. (by implication) full power: commission.
  2012. epitropos from epi and tropos (in the sense of epitrope); a commissioner, i.e. domestic manager, guardian: steward, tutor.
  2013. epitugchano from epi and tugchano; to chance upon, i.e. (by implication) to attain: obtain.
  2014. epiphaino from epi and phaino; to shine upon, i.e. become (literally) visible or (figuratively) known: appear, give light.
  2015. epiphaneia from epiphanes; a manifestation, i.e. (specially) the advent of Christ (past or future): appearing, brightness.
  2016. epiphanes from epiphaino; conspicuous, i.e. (figuratively) memorable: notable.
  2017. epiphauo a form of epiphaino; to illuminate (figuratively): give light.
  2018. epiphero from epi and phero; to bear upon (or further), i.e. adduce (personally or judicially (accuse, inflict)), superinduce: add, bring (against), take.
  2019. epiphoneo from epi and phoneo; to call at something, i.e. exclaim: cry (against), give a shout.
  2020. epiphosko a form of epiphauo; to begin to grow light: begin to dawn, X draw on.
  2021. epicheireo from epi and cheir; to put the hand upon, i.e. undertake: go about, take in hand (upon).
  2022. epicheo from epi and cheo (to pour); --to pour upon: pour in.
  2023. epichoregeo from epi and choregeo; to furnish besides, i.e. fully supply, (figuratively) aid or contribute: add, minister (nourishment, unto).
  2024. epichoregia from epichoregeo; contribution: supply.
  2025. epichrio from epi and chrio; to smear over: anoint.
  2026. epoikodomeo from epi and oikodomeo; to build upon, i.e. (figuratively) to rear up: build thereon (thereupon, on, upon).
  2027. epokello from epi and okello (to urge); to drive upon the shore, i.e. to beach a vessel: run aground.
  2028. eponomazo from epi and onomazo; to name further, i.e. denominate: call.
  2029. epopteuo from epi and a derivative of optanomai; to inspect, i.e. watch: behold.
  2030. epoptes from epi and a presumed derivative of optanomai; a looker-on: eye-witness.
  2031. epos from epo; a word: X say.
  2032. epouranios from epi and ouranos; above the sky: celestial, (in) heaven(-ly), high.
  2033. hepta a primary number; seven: seven.
  2034. heptakis adverb from hepta; seven times: seven times.
  2035. heptakischilioi from heptakis and chilioi; seven times a thousand: seven thousand.
  2036. epo a primary verb (used only in the definite past tense, the others being borrowed from ereo, rheo, and phemi); to speak or say (by word or writing): answer, bid, bring word, call, command, grant, say (on), speak, tell. Compare lego.
  2037. Erastos from erao (to love); beloved; Erastus, a Christian: Erastus.
  2038. ergazomai middle voice from ergon; to toil (as a task, occupation, etc.), (by implication) effect, be engaged in or with, etc.: commit, do, labor for, minister about, trade (by), work.
  2039. ergasia from ergates; occupation; by implication, profit, pains: craft, diligence, gain, work.
  2040. ergates from ergon; a toiler; figuratively, a teacher: labourer, worker(-men).
  2041. ergon from a primary (but obsolete) ergo (to work); toil (as an effort or occupation); by implication, an act: deed, doing, labour, work.
  2042. erethizo from a presumed prolonged form of eris; to stimulate (especially to anger): provoke.
  2043. ereido of obscure affinity; to prop, i.e. (reflexively) get fast: stick fast.
  2044. ereugomai of uncertain affinity; to belch, i.e. (figuratively) to speak out: utter.
  2045. ereunao apparently from ereo (through the idea of inquiry); to seek, i.e. (figuratively) to investigate: search.
  2046. ereo probably a fuller form of rheo; an alternate for epo in certain tenses; to utter, i.e. speak or say: call, say, speak (of), tell.
  2047. eremia from eremos; solitude (concretely): desert, wilderness.
  2048. eremos of uncertain affinity; lonesome, i.e. (by implication) waste (usually as a noun, chora being implied): desert, desolate, solitary, wilderness.
  2049. eremoo from eremos; to lay waste (literally or figuratively): (bring to, make) desolate(-ion), come to nought.
  2050. eremosis from eremoo; despoliation: desolation.
  2051. erizo from eris; to wrangle: strive.
  2052. eritheia perhaps as the same as erethizo; properly, intrigue, i.e. (by implication) faction: contention(-ious), strife.
  2053. erion of obscure affinity; wool: wool.
  2054. eris of uncertain affinity; a quarrel, i.e. (by implication) wrangling: contention, debate, strife, variance.
  2055. eriphion from eriphos; a kidling, i.e. (genitive case) goat (symbolically, wicked person): goat.
  2056. eriphos perhaps from the same as erion (through the idea of hairiness); a kid or (genitive case) goat: goat, kid.
  2057. Hermas probably from Hermes; Hermas, a Christian: Hermas.
  2058. hermeneia from the same as hermeneuo; translation: interpretation.
  2059. hermeneuo from a presumed derivative of Hermes (as the god of language); to translate: interpret.
  2060. Hermes perhaps from ereo; Hermes, the name of the messenger of the Greek deities; also of a Christian: Hermes, Mercury.
  2061. Hermogenes from Hermes and ginomai; born of Hermes; Hermogenes, an apostate Christian: Hermogenes.
  2062. herpeton neuter of a derivative of herpo (to creep); a reptile, i.e. (by Hebraism (compare remes)) a small animal: creeping thing, serpent.
  2063. eruthros of uncertain affinity; red, i.e. (with thalassa) the Red Sea: red.
  2064. erchomai middle voice of a primary verb (used only in the present and imperfect tenses, the others being supplied by a kindred (middle voice) eleuthomai el-yoo'-thom-ahee, or (active) eltho el'-tho, which do not otherwise occur); to come or go (in a great variety of applications, literally and figuratively): accompany, appear, bring, come, enter, fall out, go, grow, X light, X next, pass, resort, be set.
  2065. erotao apparently from ereo (compare ereunao); to interrogate; by implication, to request: ask, beseech, desire, intreat, pray. Compare punthanomai.
  2066. esthes from hennumi (to clothe); dress: apparel, clothing, raiment, robe.
  2067. esthesis from a derivative of esthes; clothing (concretely): government.
  2068. esthio strengthened for a primary edo (to eat); used only in certain tenses, the rest being supplied by phago; to eat (usually literal): devour, eat, live.
  2069. Esli of Hebrew origin (probably for 'Elyhow`eynay); Esli, an Israelite: Esli.
  2070. esmen first person plural indicative of eimi; we are: are, be, have our being, X have hope, + (the gospel) was (preached unto) us.
  2071. esomai future of eimi; will be: shall (should) be (have), (shall) come (to pass), X may have, X fall, what would follow, X live long, X sojourn.
  2072. esoptron from eis and a presumed derivative of optanomai; a mirror (for looking into): glass. Compare katoptrizomai.
  2073. hespera feminine of an adjective hesperos (evening); the eve (hora being implied): evening(-tide).
  2074. Esrom of Hebrew origin (Chetsrown); Esrom (i.e. Chetsron), an Israelite: Esrom.
  2075. este second person plural present indicative of eimi; ye are: be, have been, belong.
  2076. esti third person singular present indicative of eimi; he (she or it) is; also (with neuter plural) they are: are, be(-long), call, X can(-not), come, consisteth, X dure for a while, + follow, X have, (that) is (to say), make, meaneth, X must needs, + profit, + remaineth, + wrestle.
  2077. esto second person singular present imperative of eimi; be thou; also estosan, third person of the same let them be: be.
  2078. eschatos a superlative probably from echo (in the sense of contiguity); farthest, final (of place or time): ends of, last, latter end, lowest, uttermost.
  2079. eschatos adverb from eschatos; finally, i.e. (with echo) at the extremity of life: point of death.
  2080. eso from eis; inside (as preposition or adjective): (with-)in(-ner, -to, -ward).
  2081. esothen from eso; from inside; also used as equivalent to eso (inside): inward(-ly), (from) within, without.
  2082. esoteros comparative of eso; interior: inner, within.
  2083. hetairos from etes (a clansman); a comrade: fellow, friend.
  2084. heteroglossos from heteros and glossa; other- tongued, i.e. a foreigner: man of other tongue.
  2085. heterodidaskaleo from heteros and didaskalos; to instruct differently: teach other doctrine(-wise).
  2086. heterozugeo from a compound of heteros and zugos; to yoke up differently, i.e. (figuratively) to associate discordantly: unequally yoke together with.
  2087. heteros of uncertain affinity; (an-, the) other or different: altered, else, next (day), one, (an-)other, some, strange.
  2088. heteros adverb from heteros; differently: otherwise.
  2089. eti perhaps akin to etos; "yet," still (of time or degree): after that, also, ever, (any) further, (t-)henceforth (more), hereafter, (any) longer, (any) more(-one), now, still, yet.
  2090. hetoimazo from hetoimos; to prepare: prepare, provide, make ready. Compare kataskeuazo.
  2091. hetoimasia from hetoimazo; preparation: preparation.
  2092. hetoimos from an old noun heteos (fitness); adjusted, i.e. ready: prepared, (made) ready(-iness, to our hand).
  2093. hetoimos adverb from hetoimos; in readiness: ready.
  2094. etos apparently a primary word; a year: year.
  2095. eu neuter of a primary eus (good); (adverbially) well: good, well (done).
  2096. Eua of Hebrew origin (Chavvah); Eua (or Eva, i.e. Chavvah), the first woman: Eve.
  2097. euaggelizo from eu and aggelos; to announce good news ("evangelize") especially the gospel: declare, bring (declare, show) glad (good) tidings, preach (the gospel).
  2098. euaggelion from the same as euaggelizo; a good message, i.e. the gospel: gospel.
  2099. euaggelistes from euaggelizo; a preacher of the gospel: evangelist.
  2100. euaresteo from euarestos; to gratify entirely: please (well).
  2101. euarestos from eu and arestos; fully agreeable: acceptable(-ted), wellpleasing.
  2102. euarestos adverb from euarestos; quite agreeably: acceptably, + please well.
  2103. Euboulos from eu and boulomai; good-willer; Eubulus, a Christian: Eubulus.
  2104. eugenes from eu and ginomai; well born, i.e. (literally) high in rank, or (figuratively) generous: more noble, nobleman.
  2105. eudia feminine from eu and the alternate of Zeus (as the god of the weather); a clear sky, i.e. fine weather: fair weather.
  2106. eudokeo from eu and dokeo; to think well of, i.e. approve (an act); specially, to approbate (a person or thing): think good, (be well) please(-d), be the good (have, take) pleasure, be willing.
  2107. eudokia from a presumed compound of eu and the base of dokeo; satisfaction, i.e. (subjectively) delight, or (objectively) kindness, wish, purpose: desire, good pleasure (will), X seem good.
  2108. euergesia from euergetes; beneficence (genitive case or specially): benefit, good deed done.
  2109. euergeteo from euergetes; to be philanthropic: do good.
  2110. euergetes from eu and the base of ergon; a worker of good, i.e. (specially) a philanthropist: benefactor.
  2111. euthetos from eu and a derivative of tithemi; well placed, i.e. (figuratively) appropriate: fit, meet.
  2112. eutheos adverb from euthus; directly, i.e. at once or soon: anon, as soon as, forthwith, immediately, shortly, straightway.
  2113. euthudromeo from euthus and dromos; to lay a straight course, i.e. sail direct: (come) with a straight course.
  2114. euthumeo from euthumos; to cheer up, i.e. (intransitively) be cheerful; neuter comparative (adverbially) more cheerfully: be of good cheer (merry).
  2115. euthumos from eu and thumos; in fine spirits, i.e. cheerful: of good cheer, the more cheerfully.
  2116. euthuno from euthus; to straighten (level); technically, to steer: governor, make straight.
  2117. euthus perhaps from eu and tithemi; straight, i.e. (literally) level, or (figuratively) true; adverbially (of time) at once: anon, by and by, forthwith, immediately, straightway.
  2118. euthutes from euthus; rectitude: righteousness.
  2119. eukaireo from eukairos; to have good time, i.e. opportunity or leisure: have leisure (convenient time), spend time.
  2120. eukairia from eukairos; a favorable occasion: opportunity.
  2121. eukairos from eu and kairos; well-timed, i.e. opportune: convenient, in time of need.
  2122. eukairos adverb from eukairos; opportunely: conveniently, in season.
  2123. eukopoteros comparative of a compound of eu and kopos; better for toil, i.e. more facile: easier.
  2124. eulabeia from eulabes; properly, caution, i.e. (religiously) reverence (piety); by implication, dread (concretely): fear(-ed).
  2125. eulabeomai middle voice from eulabes; to be circumspect, i.e. (by implication) to be apprehensive; religiously, to reverence: (moved with) fear.
  2126. eulabes from eu and lambano; taking well (carefully), i.e. circumspect (religiously, pious): devout.
  2127. eulogeo from a compound of eu and logos; to speak well of, i.e. (religiously) to bless (thank or invoke a benediction upon, prosper): bless, praise.
  2128. eulogetos from eulogeo; adorable: blessed.
  2129. eulogia from the same as eulogeo; fine speaking, i.e. elegance of language; commendation ("eulogy"), i.e. (reverentially) adoration; religiously, benediction; by implication, consecration; by extension, benefit or largess: blessing (a matter of) bounty (X -tifully), fair speech.
  2130. eumetadotos from eu and a presumed derivative of metadidomi; good at imparting, i.e. liberal: ready to distribute.
  2131. Eunike from eu and nike; victorious; Eunice, a Jewess: Eunice.
  2132. eunoeo from a compound of eu and nous; to be well- minded, i.e. reconcile: agree.
  2133. eunoia from the same as eunoeo; kindness; euphemistically, conjugal duty: benevolence, good will.
  2134. eunouchizo from eunouchos; to castrate (figuratively, live unmarried): makeeunuch.
  2135. eunouchos from eune (a bed) and echo; a castrated person (such being employed in Oriental bed-chambers); by extension an impotent or unmarried man; by implication, a chamberlain (state-officer): eunuch.
  2136. Euodia from the same as euodoo; fine travelling; Euodia, a Christian woman: Euodias.
  2137. euodoo from a compound of eu and hodos; to help on the road, i.e. (passively) succeed in reaching; figuratively, to succeed in business affairs: (have a) prosper(-ous journey).
  2138. eupeithes from eu and peitho; good for persuasion, i.e. (intransitively) complaint: easy to be intreated.
  2139. euperistatos from eu and a derivative of a presumed compound of peri and histemi; well standing around, i.e. (a competitor) thwarting (a racer) in every direction (figuratively, of sin in genitive case): which doth so easily beset.
  2140. eupoiia from a compound of eu and poieo; well-doing, i.e. beneficence: to do good.
  2141. euporeo from a compound of hetoimazo and the base of poreia; (intransitively) to be good for passing through, i.e. (figuratively) have pecuniary means: ability.
  2142. euporia from the same as euporeo; pecuniary resources: wealth.
  2143. euprepeia from a compound of eu and prepo; good suitableness, i.e. gracefulness: grace.
  2144. euprosdektos from eu and a derivative of prosdechomai; well-received, i.e. approved, favorable: acceptable(-ted).
  2145. euprosedros from eu and the same as prosedreuo; sitting well towards, i.e. (figuratively) assiduous (neuter, diligent service): X attend upon.
  2146. euprosopeo from a compound of eu and prosopon; to be of good countenance, i.e. (figuratively) to make a display: make a fair show.
  2147. heurisko, a prolonged form of a primary heuro, which (together with another cognate form) heureo is used for it in all the tenses except the present and imperfect; to find (literally or figuratively): find, get, obtain, perceive, see.
  2148. Eurokludon from Euros (the east wind) and kludon; a storm from the East (or southeast), i.e. (in modern phrase) a Levanter: Euroklydon.
  2149. euruchoros from eurus (wide) and chora; spacious: broad.
  2150. eusebeia from eusebes; piety; specially, the gospel scheme: godliness, holiness.
  2151. eusebeo from eusebes; to be pious, i.e. (towards God) to worship, or (towards parents) to respect (support): show piety, worship.
  2152. eusebes from eu and sebomai; well-reverent, i.e. pious: devout, godly.
  2153. eusebos adverb from eusebes; piously: godly.
  2154. eusemos from eu and the base of semaino; well indicated, i.e. (figuratively) significant: easy to be understood.
  2155. eusplagchnos from eu and splagchnon; well compassioned, i.e. sympathetic: pitiful, tender-hearted.
  2156. euschemonos adverb from euschemon; decorously: decently, honestly.
  2157. eushemosune from euschemon; decorousness: comeliness.
  2158. euschemon from eu and schema; well-formed, i.e. (figuratively) decorous, noble (in rank): comely, honourable.
  2159. eutonos adverb from a compound of eu and a derivative of teino (to stretch); in a well-strung manner, i.e. (figuratively) intensely (in a good sense, cogently; in a bad one, fiercely): mightily, vehemently.
  2160. eutrapelia from a compound of eu and a derivative of the base of trope (meaning well-turned, i.e. ready at repartee, jocose); witticism, i.e. (in a vulgar sense) ribaldry: jesting.
  2161. Eutuchos from eu and a derivative of tugchano; well- fated, i.e. fortunate; Eutychus, a young man: Eutychus.
  2162. euphemia from euphemos; good language ("euphemy"), i.e. praise (repute): good report.
  2163. euphemos from eu and pheme; well spoken of, i.e. reputable: of good report.
  2164. euphoreo from eu and phoreo; to bear well, i.e. be fertile: bring forth abundantly.
  2165. euphraino from eu and phren; to put (middle voice or passively, be) in a good frame of mind, i.e. rejoice: fare, make glad, be (make) merry, rejoice.
  2166. Euphrates of foreign origin (compare Prath); Euphrates, a river of Asia: Euphrates.
  2167. euphrosune from the same as euphraino; joyfulness: gladness, joy.
  2168. eucharisteo from eucharistos; to be grateful, i.e. (actively) to express gratitude (towards); specially, to say grace at a meal: (give) thank(-ful, -s).

  2179. Ephesinos from Ephesos; Ephesine, or situated at Ephesus: of Ephesus.

  2181. Ephesos probably of foreign origin; Ephesus, a city of Asia Minor: Ephesus.

  2185. ephikneomai from epi and a cognate of heko; to arrive upon, i.e. extend to: reach.

  2189. echthra feminine of echthros; hostility; by implication, a reason for opposition: enmity, hatred.

  2191. echidna of uncertain origin; an adder or other poisonous snake (literally or figuratively): viper.
  2192. echo; including an alternate form scheo (used in certain tenses only) a primary verb; to hold (used in very various applications, literally or figuratively, direct or remote; such as possession; ability, contiuity, relation, or condition): be (able, X hold, possessed with), accompany, + begin to amend, can(+ -not), X conceive, count, diseased, do + eat, + enjoy, + fear, following, have, hold, keep, + lack, + go to law, lie, + must needs, + of necessity, + need, next, + recover, + reign, + rest, + return, X sick, take for, + tremble, + uncircumcised, use.
  2193. heos of uncertain affinity; a conjunction, preposition and adverb of continuance, until (of time and place): even (until, unto), (as) far (as), how long, (un-)til(-l), (hither-, un-, up) to, while(-s).

  2200. zestos from zeo; boiled, i.e. (by implication) calid (figuratively, fervent): hot.
  2201. zeugos from the same as zugos; a couple, i.e. a team (of oxen yoked together) or brace (of birds tied together): yoke, pair.

  2203. Zeus of uncertain affinity; in the oblique cases there is used instead of it a (probably cognate) name Dis, which is otherwise obsolete; Zeus or Dis (among the Latins, Jupiter or Jove), the supreme deity of the Greeks: Jupiter.
  2204. zeo a primary verb; to be hot (boil, of liquids; or glow, of solids), i.e. (figuratively) be fervid (earnest): be fervent.
  2205. zelos from zeo; properly, heat, i.e. (figuratively) "zeal" (in a favorable sense, ardor; in an unfavorable one, jealousy, as of a husband (figuratively, of God), or an enemy, malice): emulation, envy(-ing), fervent mind, indignation, jealousy, zeal.

  2215. zizanion of uncertain origin; darnel or false grain: tares.

  2218. zugos from the root of zeugnumi (to join, especially by a "yoke"); a coupling, i.e. (figuratively) servitude (a law or obligation); also (literally) the beam of the balance (as connecting the scales): pair of balances, yoke.
  2219. zume probably from zeo; ferment (as if boiling up): leaven.
  2220. zumoo from zume; to cause to ferment: leaven.
  2221. zogreo from the same as zoon and agreuo; to take alive (make a prisoner of war), i.e. (figuratively) to capture or ensnare: take captive, catch.
  2222. zoe from zao; life (literally or figuratively): life(-time). Compare psuche.
  2223. zone probably akin to the base of zugos; a belt; by implication, a pocket: girdle, purse.
  2224. zonnumi from zone; to bind about (especially with a belt): gird.
  2225. zoogoneo from the same as zoon and a derivative of ginomai; to engender alive, i.e. (by analogy) to rescue (passively, be saved) from death: live, preserve.
  2226. zoon neuter of a derivative of zao; a live thing, i.e. an animal: beast.
  2227. zoopoieo from the same as zoon and poieo; to (re-)vitalize (literally or figuratively): make alive, give life, quicken.
  2228. e a primary particle of distinction between two connected terms; disjunctive, or; comparative, than: and, but (either), (n-)either, except it be, (n-)or (else), rather, save, than, that, what, yea. Often used in connection with other particles. Compare especially ede, eper, etoi.
  2229. e an adverb of confirmation; perhaps intensive of e; used only (in the New Testament) before men; assuredly: surely.
  2230. hegemoneuo from hegemon; to act as ruler: be governor.
  2231. hegemonia from hegemon; government, i.e. (in time) official term: reign.
  2232. hegemon from hegeomai; a leader, i.e. chief person (or figuratively, place) of a province: governor, prince, ruler.
  2233. hegeomai middle voice of a (presumed) strengthened form of ago; to lead, i.e. command (with official authority); figuratively, to deem, i.e. consider: account, (be) chief, count, esteem, governor, judge, have the rule over, suppose, think.
  2234. hedeos adverb from a derivative of the base of hedone; sweetly, i.e. (figuratively) with pleasure: gladly.
  2235. ede apparently from e (or possibly e) and de; even now: already, (even) now (already), by this time.
  2236. hedista neuter plural of the superlative of the same as hedeos; with great pleasure: most (very) gladly.

  2240. heko a primary verb; to arrive, i.e. be present (literally or figuratively): come.

  2250. hemera feminine (with hora implied) of a derivative of hemai (to sit; akin to the base of hedraios) meaning tame, i.e. gentle; day, i.e. (literally) the time space between dawn and dark, or the whole 24 hours (but several days were usually reckoned by the Jews as inclusive of the parts of both extremes); figuratively, a period (always defined more or less clearly by the context): age, + alway, (mid-)day (by day, (-ly)), + for ever, judgment, (day) time, while, years.

  2255. hemisu neuter of a derivative from an inseparable prefix akin to hama (through the idea of partition involved in connection) and meaning semi-; (as noun) half: half.
  2256. hemiorion from the base of hemisu and hora; a half-hour: half an hour.
  2257. hemon genitive case plural of ego; of (or from) us: our (company), us, we.

  2260. eper from e and per; than at all (or than perhaps, than indeed): than.
  2261. epios probably from epos; properly, affable, i.e. mild or kind: gentle.

  2263. eremos perhaps by transposition from eremos (through the idea of stillness); tranquil: quiet.

  2301. theatrizo from theatron; to expose as a spectacle: make a gazing stock.

  2308. thelesis from thelo; determination (properly, the act), i.e. option: will.
  2309. thelo or ethelo, in certain tenses theleo, and etheleo, which are otherwise obsolete apparently strengthened from the alternate form of haireomai; to determine (as an active option from subjective impulse; whereas boulomai properly denotes rather a passive acquiescence in objective considerations), i.e. choose or prefer (literally or figuratively); by implication, to wish, i.e. be inclined to (sometimes adverbially, gladly); impersonally for the future tense, to be about to; by Hebraism, to delight in: desire, be disposed (forward), intend, list, love, mean, please, have rather, (be) will (have, -ling, - ling(-ly)).

  2379. thusiasterion from a derivative of thusia; a place of sacrifice, i.e. an altar (special or genitive case, literal or figurative): altar.
  2380. thuo a primary verb; properly, to rush (breathe hard, blow, smoke), i.e. (by implication) to sacrifice (properly, by fire, but genitive case); by extension to immolate (slaughter for any purpose): kill, (do) sacrifice, slay.

  2382. thorax of uncertain affinity; the chest ("thorax"), i.e. (by implication) a corslet: breast-plate.

  2389. Iannes of Egyptian origin; Jannes, an Egyptian: Jannes.

  2398. idios of uncertain affinity; pertaining to self, i.e. one's own; by implication, private or separate: X his acquaintance, when they were alone, apart, aside, due, his (own, proper, several), home, (her, our, thine, your) own (business), private(-ly), proper, severally, their (own).
  2399. idiotes from idios; a private person, i.e. (by implication) an ignoramus (compare "idiot"): ignorant, rude, unlearned.
  2400. idou second person singular imperative middle voice of eido; used as imperative lo!; --behold, lo, see.
  2401. Idoumaia of Hebrew origin ('Edom); Iduma (i.e. Edom), a region East (and South) of Palestine: Iduma.
  2402. hidros a strengthened form of a primary idos (sweat); perspiration: sweat.
  2403. Iezabel of Hebrew origin ('Iyzebel); Jezabel (i.e. Jezebel), a Tyrian woman (used as a synonym of a termagant or false teacher): Jezabel.
  2404. Hierapolis from hieros and polis; holy city; Hierapolis, a place in Asia Minor: Hierapolis.

  2425. hikanos from hiko (hikano or hikneomai, akin to heko) (to arrive); competent (as if coming in season), i.e. ample (in amount) or fit (in character): able, + content, enough, good, great, large, long (while), many, meet, much, security, sore, sufficient, worthy.

  2436. hileos perhaps from the alternate form of haireomai; cheerful (as attractive), i.e. propitious; adverbially (by Hebraism) God be gracious!, i.e. (in averting some calamity) far be it: be it far, merciful.

  2475. Israelites from Israel; an "Israelite", i.e. descendant of Israel (literally or figuratively): Israelite.
  2476. histemi a prolonged form of a primary stao stah'-o (of the same meaning, and used for it in certain tenses); to stand (transitively or intransitively), used in various applications (literally or figuratively): abide, appoint, bring, continue, covenant, establish, hold up, lay, present, set (up), stanch, stand (by, forth, still, up). Compare tithemi.
  2477. historeo from a derivative of eido; to be knowing (learned), i.e. (by implication) to visit for information (interview): see.
  2478. ischuros from ischus; forcible (literally or figuratively): boisterous, mighty(-ier), powerful, strong(-er, man), valiant.

  2480. ischuo from ischus; to have (or exercise) force (literally or figuratively): be able, avail, can do(-not), could, be good, might, prevail, be of strength, be whole, + much work.
  2481. isos adverb from isos; likely, i.e. perhaps: it may be.
  2482. Italia probably of foreign origin; Italia, a region of Europe: Italy.

  2504. kago from kai and ego; so also the dative case kamoi kam-oy', and accusative case kame kam-eh' and (or also, even, etc.) I, (to) me: (and, even, even so, so) I (also, in like wise), both me, me also.

  2526. katho from kata and hos; according to which thing, i.e. precisely as, in proportion as: according to that, (inasmuch) as.

  2531. kathos from kata and hos; just (or inasmuch) as, that: according to, (according, even) as, how, when.
  2532. kai apparently, a primary particle, having a copulative and sometimes also a cumulative force; and, also, even, so then, too, etc.; often used in connection (or composition) with other particles or small words: and, also, both, but, even, for, if, or, so, that, then, therefore, when, yet.
