  2594. kartereo from a derivative of kratos (transposed); to be strong, i.e. (figuratively) steadfast (patient): endure.
  2595. karphos from karpho (to wither); a dry twig or straw: mote.
  2596. kata a primary particle; (prepositionally) down (in place or time), in varied relations (according to the case (genitive, dative or accusative) with which it is joined): about, according as (to), after, against, (when they were) X alone, among, and, X apart, (even, like) as (concerning, pertaining to touching), X aside, at, before, beyond, by, to the charge of, (charita-)bly, concerning, + covered, (dai-)ly, down, every, (+ far more) exceeding, X more excellent, for, from to, godly, in(-asmuch, divers, every, -to, respect of), by, after the manner of, + by any means, beyond (out of) measure, X mightily, more, X natural, of (up-)on (X part), out (of every), over against, (+ your) X own, + particularly, so, through(-oughout, -oughout every), thus, (un-)to(-gether, -ward), X uttermost, where(-by), with. In composition it retains many of these applications, and frequently denotes opposition, distribution, or intensity.
  2597. katabaino from kata and the base of basis; to descend (literally or figuratively): come (get, go, step) down, fall (down).
  2598. kataballo from kata and ballo; to throw down: cast down, lay.
  2599. katabareo from kata and bareo; to impose upon: burden.
  2600. katabasis from katabaino; a declivity: descent.
  2601. katabibazo from kata and a derivative of the base of basis; to cause to go down, i.e. precipitate: bring (thrust) down.
  2602. katabole from kataballo; a deposition, i.e. founding; figuratively, conception: conceive, foundation.
  2603. katabrabeuo from kata and brabeuo (in its original sense); to award the price against, i.e. (figuratively) to defraud (of salvation): beguile of reward.
  2604. kataggeleus from kataggello; a proclaimer: setter forth.
  2605. kataggello from kata and the base of aggelos; to proclaim, promulgate: declare, preach, shew, speak of, teach.
  2606. katagelao to laugh down, i.e. deride: laugh to scorn.
  2607. kataginosko from kata and ginosko; to note against, i.e. find fault with: blame, condemn.
  2608. katagnumi from kata and the base of rhegnumi; to rend in pieces, i.e. crack apart: break.
  2609. katago from kata and ago; to lead down; specially, to moor a vessel: bring (down, forth), (bring to) land, touch.
  2610. katagonizomai from kata and agonizomai; to struggle against, i.e. (by implication) to overcome: subdue.
  2611. katadeo from kata and deo; to tie down, i.e. bandage (a wound): bind up.
  2612. katadelos from kata intensive and delos; manifest: far more evident.
  2613. katadikazo from kata and a derivative of dike; to adjudge against, i.e. pronounce guilty: condemn.
  2614. katadioko from kata and dioko; to hunt down, i.e. search for: follow after.

  2616. katadunasteuo from kata and a derivative of dunastes; to exercise dominion against, i.e. oppress: oppress.
  2617. kataischuno from kata and aischunomai; to shame down, i.e. disgrace or (by implication) put to the blush: confound, dishonour, (be a-, make a-)shame(-d).
  2618. katakaio from kata and kaio; to burn down (to the ground), i.e. consume wholly: burn (up, utterly).
  2619. katakalupto from kata and kalupto; to cover wholly, i.e. veil: cover, hide.
  2620. katakauchaomai from kata and kauchaomai; to exult against (i.e. over): boast (against), glory, rejoice against.
  2621. katakeimai from kata and keimai; to lie down, i.e. (by implication) be sick; specially, to recline at a meal: keep, lie, sit at meat (down).
  2622. kataklao from kata and klao; to break down, i.e. divide: break.
  2623. katakleio from kata and kleio; to shut down (in a dungeon), i.e. incarcerate: shut up.
  2624. kataklerodoteo from kata and a derivative of a compound of kleros and didomi; to be a giver of lots to each, i.e. (by implication) to apportion an estate: divide by lot.

  2628. katakoloutheo from kata and akoloutheo; to accompany closely: follow (after).
  2629. katakopto from kata and kopto; to chop down, i.e. mangle: cut.

  2635. katalaleo from katalalos; to be a traducer, i.e. to slander: speak against (evil of).
  2636. katalalia from katalalos; defamation: backbiting, evil speaking.

  2640. kataleimma from kataleipo; a remainder, i.e. (by implication) a few: remnant.
  2641. kataleipo from kata and leipo; to leave down, i.e. behind; by implication, to abandon, have remaining: forsake, leave, reserve.
  2642. katalithazo from kata and lithazo; to stone down, i.e. to death: stone.
  2643. katallage from katallasso; exchange (figuratively, adjustment), i.e. restoration to (the divine) favor: atonement, reconciliation(-ing).
  2644. katallasso from kata and allasso; to change mutually, i.e. (figuratively) to compound a difference: reconcile.
  2645. kataloipos from kata and loipoy; left down (behind), i.e remaining (plural the rest): residue.
  2646. kataluma from kataluo; properly, a dissolution (breaking up of a journey), i.e. (by implication) a lodging-place: guestchamber, inn.
  2647. kataluo from kata and luo; to loosen down (disintegrate), i.e. (by implication) to demolish (literally or figuratively); specially (compare kataluma) to halt for the night: destroy, dissolve, be guest, lodge, come to nought, overthrow, throw down.
  2648. katamanthano from kata and manthano; to learn thoroughly, i.e. (by implication) to note carefully: consider.
  2649. katamartureo from kata and martureo; to testify against: witness against.
  2650. katameno from kata and meno; to stay fully, i.e. reside: abide.

  2672. kataraomai middle voice from katara; to execrate; by analogy, to doom: curse.

  2687. katastello from kata and stello; to put down, i.e. quell: appease, quiet.
  2688. katastema from kathistemi; properly, a position or condition, i.e. (subjectively) demeanor: behaviour.

  2693. katastronnumi from kata and stronnumi; to strew down, i.e. (by implication) to prostrate (slay): overthrow.

  2700. katatoxeuo from kata and a derivative of toxon; to shoot down with an arrow or other missile: thrust through.

  2745. kauchesis from kauchaomai; boasting (properly, the act; by implication, the object), in a good or a bad sense: boasting, whereof I may glory, glorying, rejoicing.
  2746. Kegchreai probably from kegchros (millet); Cenchre, a port of Corinth: Cencrea.

  2755. kenos apparently a primary word; empty (literally or figuratively): empty, (in) vain.
  2756. kenophonia from a presumed compound of kenos and phone; empty sounding, i.e. fruitless discussion: vain.
  2757. kenoo from kenos; to make empty, i.e. (figuratively) to abase, neutralize, falsify: make (of none effect, of no reputation, void), be in vain.
  2758. kentron from kenteo (to prick); a point ("centre"), i.e. a sting (figuratively, poison) or goad (figuratively, divine impulse): prick, sting.
  2759. kenturion of Latin origin; a centurion, i.e. captain of one hundred soldiers: centurion.
  2760. kenos adverb from kenos; vainly, i.e. to no purpose: in vain.
  2761. keraia feminine of a presumed derivative of the base of keras; something horn-like, i.e. (specially) the apex of a Hebrew letter (figuratively, the least particle): tittle.
  2762. kerameus from keramos; a potter: potter.
  2763. keramikos from keramos; made of clay, i.e. earthen: of a potter.

  2765. keramos probably from the base of kerannumi (through the idea of mixing clay and water); earthenware, i.e. a tile (by analogy, a thin roof or awning): tiling.
  2766. kerannumi prolonged form of a more primary kerao ker-ah'-o (which is used in certain tenses); to mingle, i.e. (by implication) to pour out (for drinking): fill, pour out. Compare mignumi.
  2767. keras from a primary kar (the hair of the head); a horn (literally or figuratively): horn.
  2768. keration neuter of a presumed derivative of keras; something horned, i.e. (specially) the pod of the carob-tree: husk.
  2769. kerdaino from kerdos; to gain (literally or figuratively): (get) gain, win.
  2770. kerdos of uncertain affinity; gain (pecuniary or genitive case): gain, lucre.
  2771. kerma from keiro; a clipping (bit), i.e. (specially) a coin: money.
  2772. kermatistes from a derivative of kerma; a handler of coins, i.e. money-broker: changer of money.
  2773. kephalaion neuter of a derivative of kephale; a principal thing, i.e. main point; specially, an amount (of money): sum.
  2774. kephalaioo from the same as kephalaion; (specially) to strike on the head: wound in the head.
  2775. kephale from the primary kapto (in the sense of seizing); the head (as the part most readily taken hold of), literally or figuratively: head.
  2776. kephalis from kephale; properly, a knob, i.e. (by implication) a roll (by extension from the end of a stick on which the manuscript was rolled): volume.
  2777. kensos of Latin origin; properly, an enrollment ("census"), i.e. (by implication) a tax: tribute.
  2778. kepos of uncertain affinity; a garden: garden.
  2779. kepouros from kepos and ouros (a warden); a garden-keeper, i.e. gardener: gardener.
  2780. kerion diminutive from keos (wax); a cell for honey, i.e. (collectively) the comb: (honey-)comb.
  2781. kerugma from kerusso; a proclamation (especially of the gospel; by implication, the gospel itself): preaching.
  2782. kerux from kerusso; a herald, i.e. of divine truth (especially of the gospel): preacher.
  2783. kerusso of uncertain affinity; to herald (as a public crier), especially divine truth (the gospel): preacher(-er), proclaim, publish.
  2784. ketos probably from the base of chasma; a huge fish (as gaping for prey): whale.
  2785. Kephas of Chaldee origin (compare keph); the Rock; Cephas (i.e. Kepha), a surname of Peter: Cephas.
  2786. kibotos of uncertain derivation; a box, i.e. the sacred ark and that of Noah: ark.
  2787. kithara of uncertain affinity; a lyre: harp.
  2788. kitharizo from kithara; to play on a lyre: harp.
  2789. kitharoidos from kithara and a derivative of the same as oide; a lyre-singer(-player), i.e. harpist: harper.
  2790. Kilikia probably of foreign origin; Cilicia, a region of Asia Minor: Cilicia.
  2791. kinamomon of foreign origin (compare qinnamown); cinnamon: cinnamon.
  2792. kinduneuo from kindunos; to undergo peril: be in danger, be (stand) in jeopardy.
  2793. kindunos of uncertain derivation; danger: peril.
  2794. kineo from kio (poetic for eimi, to go); to stir (transitively), literally or figuratively: (re-)move(-r), way.
  2795. kinesis from kineo; a stirring: moving.
  2796. Kis of Hebrew origin (Qiysh); Cis (i.e. Kish), an Israelite: Cis.
  2797. klados from klao; a twig or bough (as if broken off): branch.
  2798. klaio of uncertain affinity; to sob, i.e. wail aloud (whereas dakruo is rather to cry silently): bewail, weep.
  2799. klasis from klao; fracture (the act): breaking.
  2800. klasma from klao; a piece (bit): broken, fragment.
  2801. Klaude of uncertain derivation; Claude, an island near Crete: Clauda.
  2802. Klaudia feminine of Klaudios; Claudia, a Christian woman: Claudia.
  2803. Klaudios of Latin origin; Claudius, the name of two Romans: Claudius.
  2804. klauthmos from klaio; lamentation: wailing, weeping, X wept.
  2805. klao a primary verb; to break (specially, of bread): break.
  2806. kleis from kleio; a key (as shutting a lock), literally or figuratively: key.
  2807. kleio a primary verb; to close (literally or figuratively): shut (up).
  2808. klemma from klepto; stealing (properly, the thing stolen, but used of the act): theft.
  2809. Kleopas probably contracted from Kleopatros (compound of kleos and pater); Cleopas, a Christian: Cleopas.
  2810. kleos from a shorter form of kaleo; renown (as if being called): glory.
  2811. kleptes from klepto; a stealer (literally or figuratively): thief. Compare leistes.
  2812. klepto a primary verb; to filch: steal.
  2813. klema from klao; a limb or shoot (as if broken off): branch.

Often used in composition, in substantially the same relations of participation or proximity, and transfer or sequence.

  3257. metron an apparently primary word; a measure ("metre"), literally or figuratively; by implication, a limited portion (degree): measure.
  3258. metopon from meta and ops (the face); the forehead (as opposite the countenance): forehead.
  3259. mechri or mechris from mekos; as far as, i.e. up to a certain point (as a preposition, of extent (denoting the terminus, whereas achri refers especially to the space of time or place intervening) or conjunction): till, (un-)to, until.
  3260. me a primary particle of qualified negation (whereas ou expresses an absolute denial); (adverb) not, (conjunction) lest; also (as an interrogative implying a negative answer (whereas ou expects an affirmative one)) whether: any but (that), X forbear, + God forbid, + lack, lest, neither, never, no (X wise in), none, nor, (can-)not, nothing, that not, un(-taken), without. Often used in compounds in substantially the same relations. See also ean me, hina me, ou me, mekos, mekuno, men, me ouk.
  3261. ean me i.e. ean and me; if not, i.e. unless: X before, but, except, if, no, (if, + whosoever) not.
  3262. hina me i.e. hina and me; in order (or so) that not: albeit not, lest, that, no(-t, (-thing)).
  3263. ou me i.e. ou and me; a double negative strengthening the denial; not at all: any more, at all, by any (no) means, neither, never, no (at all), in no case (wise), nor ever, not (at all, in any wise). Compare me ouk.
  3264. medamos adverb from a compound of me and amos (somebody); by no means: not so.
  3265. mede from me and de; but not, not even; in a continued negation, nor: neither, nor (yet), (no) not (once, so much as).
  3266. medeis, including the irregular feminine medemia, and the neuter meden from me and heis; not even one (man, woman, thing): any (man, thing), no (man), none, not (at all, any man, a whit), nothing, + without delay.
  3267. medepote from mede and pote; not even ever: never.
  3268. medepo from mede and po; not even yet: not yet.
  3269. Medos of foreign origin (compare Maday); a Median, or inhabitant of Media: Mede.
  3270. meketi from me and eti; no further: any longer, (not) henceforth, hereafter, no henceforward (longer, more, soon), not any more.
  3271. mekos probably akin to megas; length (literally or figuratively) length.
  3272. mekuno from mekos; to lengthen, i.e. (middle voice) to enlarge: grow up.
  3273. melote from melon (a sheep); a sheep-skin: sheepskin.
  3274. men a stronger form of men; a particle of affirmation (only with e); assuredly: + surely.
  3275. men a primary word; a month: month.
  3276. menuo probably from the same base as massaomai and mnaomai (i.e. mao, to strive); to disclose (through the idea of mental effort and thus calling to mind), i.e. report, declare, intimate: shew, tell.
  3277. me ouk i.e. me and ou; as interrogative and negative, is it not that?: neither (followed by no), + never, not. Compare ou me.
  3278. mepote or me pote from me and pote; not ever; also if (or lest) ever (or perhaps): if peradventure, lest (at any time, haply), not at all, whether or not.
  3279. mepo from me and po; not yet: not yet.
  3280. mepos or me pos from me and pos; lest somehow: lest (by any means, by some means, haply, perhaps).
  3281. meros perhaps a primary word; a thigh: thigh.
  3282. mete from me and te; not too, i.e. (in continued negation) neither or nor; also, not even: neither, (n-)or, so as much.
  3283. meter apparently a primary word; a "mother" (literally or figuratively, immediate or remote): mother.
  3284. meti from me and the neuter of tis; whether at all: not (the particle usually not expressed, except by the form of the question).
  3285. metige from meti and ge; not at all then, i.e. not to say (the rather still): how much more.
  3286. metis or me tis from me and tis; whether any: any (sometimes unexpressed except by the simple interrogative form of the sentence).
  3287. metra from meter; the matrix: womb.
  3288. metraloias from meter and the base of halon; a mother-thresher, i.e. matricide: murderer of mothers.
  3289. metropolis from meter and polis; a mother city, i.e. "metropolis": chiefest city.
  3290. mia irregular feminine of heis; one or first: a (certain), + agree, first, one, X other.
  3291. miaino perhaps a primary verb; to sully or taint, i.e. contaminate (ceremonially or morally): defile.
  3292. miasma from miaino ("miasma"); (morally) foulness (properly, the effect): pollution.
  3293. miasmos from miaino; (morally) contamination (properly, the act): uncleanness.
  3294. migma from mignumi; a compound: mixture.
  3295. mignumi a primary verb; to mix: mingle.
  3296. mikron masculine or neuter singular of mikros (as noun); a small space of time or degree: a (little) (while).
  3297. mikros, including the comparative mikroteros apparently a primary word; small (in size, quantity, number or (figuratively) dignity): least, less, little, small.
  3298. Miletos of uncertain origin; Miletus, a city of Asia Minor: Miletus.
  3299. milion of Latin origin; a thousand paces, i.e. a "mile": mile.
  3300. mimeomai middle voice from mimos (a "mimic"); to imitate: follow.
  3301. mimetes from mimeomai; an imitator: follower.
  3302. mimnesko a prolonged form of mnaomai (from which some of the tenses are borrowed); to remind, i.e. (middle voice) to recall to mind: be mindful, remember.
  3303. miseo from a primary misos (hatred); to detest (especially to persecute); by extension, to love less: hate(-ful).
  3304. misthapodosia from misthapodotes; requital (good or bad): recompence of reward.
  3305. misthapodotes from misthoo and apodidomi; a renumerator: rewarder.
  3306. misthios from misthos; a wage-earner: hired servant.
  3307. misthos apparently a primary word; pay for service (literally or figuratively), good or bad: hire, reward, wages.
  3308. misthoo from misthos; to let out for wages, i.e. (middle voice) to hire: hire.
  3309. misthoma from misthoo; a rented building: hired house.
  3310. misthotos from misthoo; a wage-worker (good or bad): hired servant, hireling.
  3311. Mitulene for mutilene (abounding in shellfish); Mitylene (or Mytilene), a town on the island of Lesbos: Mitylene.
  3312. Michael of Hebrew origin (Miyka'el); Michael, an archangel: Michael.
  3313. mna of Latin origin; a mna (i.e. mina), a certain weight: pound.
  3314. mnaomai middle voice of a derivative of meno or perhaps of the base of massaomai (through the idea of fixture in the mind or of mental grasp); to bear in mind, i.e. recollect; by implication, to reward or punish: be mindful, remember, come (have) in remembrance. Compare mimnesko.
  3315. Mnason of uncertain origin; Mnason, a Christian: Mnason.
  3316. mneia from mnaomai or mimnesko; recollection; by implication, recital: mention, remembrance.
  3317. mnema from mnaomai; a memorial, i.e. sepulchral monument (burial-place): grave, sepulchre, tomb.
  3318. mnemeion from mneme; a remembrance, i.e. cenotaph (place of interment): grave, sepulchre, tomb.
  3319. mneme from mimnesko; memory: remembrance.
  3320. mnemoneuo from a derivative of mneme; to exercise memory, i.e. recollect; by implication, to punish; also to rehearse: make mention; be mindful, remember.
  3321. mnemosunon from mnemoneuo; a reminder (memorandum), i.e. record: memorial.
  3322. mnesteuo from a derivative of mnaomai; to give a souvenir (engagement present), i.e. betroth: espouse.
  3323. mogilalos from mogis and laleo; hardly talking, i.e. dumb (tongue-tied): having an impediment in his speech.
  3324. mogis adverb from a primary mogos (toil); with difficulty: hardly.
  3325. modios of Latin origin; a modius, i.e. certain measure for things dry (the quantity or the utensil): bushel.
  3326. moi the simpler form of emoi; to me: I, me, mine, my.
  3327. moichalis a prolonged form of the feminine of moichos; an adulteress (literally or figuratively): adulteress(-ous, -y).
  3328. moichao from moichos; (middle voice) to commit adultery: commit adultery.
  3329. moicheia from moicheuo; adultery: adultery.
  3330. moicheuo from moichos; to commit adultery: commit adultery.
  3331. moichos perhaps a primary word; a (male) paramour; figuratively, apostate: adulterer.
  3332. molis probably by variation for mogis; with difficulty: hardly, scarce(-ly), + with much work.
  3333. Moloch of Hebrew origin (Molek); Moloch (i.e. Molek), an idol: Moloch.
  3334. moluno probably from melas; to soil (figuratively): defile.
  3335. molusmos from moluno; a stain; i.e. (figuratively) immorality: filthiness.
  3336. momphe from memphomai; blame, i.e. (by implication), a fault: quarrel.
  3337. mone from meno; a staying, i.e. residence (the act or the place): abode, mansion.
  3338. monogenes from monos and ginomai; only-born, i.e. sole: only (begotten, child).
  3339. monon neuter of monos as adverb; merely: alone, but, only.
  3340. monos probably from meno; remaining, i.e. sole or single; by implication, mere: alone, only, by themselves.
  3341. monophthalmos from monos and ophthalmos; one-eyed: with one eye.
  3342. monoo from monos; to isolate, i.e. bereave: be desolate.
  3343. morphe perhaps from the base of meros (through the idea of adjustment of parts); shape; figuratively, nature: form.
  3344. morphoo from the same as morphe; to fashion (figuratively): form.
  3345. morphosis from morphoo; formation, i.e. (by implication), appearance (semblance or (concretely) formula): form.
  3346. moschopoieo from moschos and poieo; to fabricate the image of a bullock: make a calf.
  3347. moschos probably strengthened for oschos (a shoot); a young bullock: calf.
  3348. mochthos from the base of mogis; toil, i.e. (by implication) sadness: painfulness, travail.
  3349. mou the simpler form of emou; of me: I, me, mine (own), my.
  3350. mousikos from Mousa (a Muse); "musical", i.e. (as noun) a minstrel: musician.
  3351. muelos perhaps a primary word; the marrow: marrow.
  3352. mueo from the base of musterion; to initiate, i.e. (by implication) to teach: instruct.
  3353. muthos perhaps from the same as mueo (through the idea of tuition); a tale, i.e. fiction ("myth"): fable.
  3354. mukaomai from a presumed derivative of muzo ( to "moo"); to bellow (roar): roar.
  3355. mukterizo from a derivative of the base of mukaomai (meaning snout, as that whence lowing proceeds); to make mouths at, i.e. ridicule: mock.
  3356. mulikos from mulos; belonging to a mill: mill(-stone).
  3357. mulos probably ultimately from the base of molis (through the idea of hardship); a "mill", i.e. (by implication), a grinder (millstone): millstone.
  3358. mulon from mulos; a mill-house: mill.
  3359. Mura of uncertain derivation; Myra, a place in Asia Minor: Myra.
  3360. murias from murioi; a ten-thousand; by extension, a "myriad" or indefinite number: ten thousand.
  3361. murizo from muron; to apply (perfumed) unguent to: anoint.
  3362. murioi plural of an apparently primary word (properly, meaning very many); ten thousand; by extension, innumerably many: ten thousand.
  3363. muron probably of foreign origin (compare more, smurna); "myrrh", i.e. (by implication) perfumed oil: ointment.
  3364. Musia of uncertain origin; Mysia, a region of Asia Minor: Mysia.
  3365. musterion from a derivative of muo (to shut the mouth); a secret or "mystery" (through the idea of silence imposed by initiation into religious rites): mystery.
  3366. muopazo from a compound of the base of musterion and ops (the face; from optanomai); to shut the eyes, i.e. blink (see indistinctly): cannot see far off.
  3367. molops from molos ("moil"; probably akin to the base of molis) and probably ops (the face; from optanomai); a mole ("black eye") or blow-mark: stripe.
  3368. momaomai from momos; to carp at, i.e. censure (discredit): blame.
  3369. momos perhaps from memphomai; a flaw or blot, i.e. (figuratively) disgraceful person: blemish.
  3370. moraino from moros; to become insipid; figuratively, to make (passively, act) as a simpleton: become fool, make foolish, lose savour.
  3371. moria from moros; silliness, i.e. absurdity: foolishness.
  3372. morologia from a compound of moros and lego; silly talk, i.e. buffoonery: foolish talking.
  3373. moros probably from the base of musterion; dull or stupid (as if shut up), i.e. heedless, (morally) blockhead, (apparently) absurd: fool(-ish, X -ishness).
  3374. Moseus or Moses, or Mouses of Hebrew origin; (Mosheh); Moseus, Moses, or Mouses (i.e. Mosheh), the Hebrew lawgiver: Moses.
  3375. Naasson of Hebrew origin (Nachshown); Naasson (i.e. Nachshon), an Israelite: Naasson.
  3376. Naggai probably of Hebrew origin (compare Nogahh); Nang (i.e. perhaps Nogach), an Israelite: Nagge.
  3377. Nazareth or Nazaret; of uncertain derivation; Nazareth or Nazaret, a place in Palestine: Nazareth.
  3378. Nazarenos from Nazareth; a Nazarene, i.e. inhabitant of Nazareth: of Nazareth.
  3379. Nazoraios from Nazareth; a Nazoran, i.e. inhabitant of Nazareth; by extension, a Christian: Nazarene, of Nazareth.
  3380. Nathan of Hebrew origin (Nathan); Nathan, an Israelite: Nathan.
  3381. Nathanael of Hebrew origin (Nthane'l); Nathanal (i.e. Nathanel), an Israelite and Christian: Nathanael.
  3382. nai a primary particle of strong affirmation; yes: even so, surely, truth, verily, yea, yes.
  3383. Nain probably of Hebrew origin (compare na'ah); Nain, a place in Palestine: Nain.
  3384. naos from a primary naio (to dwell); a fane, shrine, temple : shrine, temple. Compare hieron.
  3385. Naoum of Hebrew origin (Nachuwm); Naum (i.e. Nachum), an Israelite: Naum.
  3386. nardos of foreign origin (compare nerd); "nard": (spike-)nard.
  3387. Narkissos a flower of the same name, from narke (stupefaction, as a "narcotic"); Narcissus, a Roman: Narcissus.

  3399. nekrosis from nekroo; decease; figuratively, impotency: deadness, dying.

  3481. xestes as if from xeo (properly, to smooth; by implication, (of friction) to boil or heat); a vessel (as fashioned or for cooking) (or perhaps by corruption from the Latin sextarius, the sixth of a modius, i.e. about a pint), i.e. (specially), a measure for liquids or solids, (by analogy, a pitcher): pot.

  3484. xulinos from xulon; wooden: of wood.
  3485. xulon from another form of the base of xestes; timber (as fuel or material); by implication, a stick, club or tree or other wooden article or substance: staff, stocks, tree, wood.
  3486. xurao from a derivative of the same as xulon (meaning a razor); to shave or "shear" the hair: shave.
  3487. ho, including the feminine he, and the neuter to in all their inflections; the definite article; the (sometimes to be supplied, at others omitted, in English idiom): the, this, that, one, he, she, it, etc.
  3488. ogdoekonta from ogdoos; ten times eight: fourscore.
  3489. ogdoos from oktos; the eighth: eighth.
  3490. ogkos probably from the same as agkale; a mass (as bending or bulging by its load), i.e. burden (hindrance): weight.
  3491. hode, including the feminine hede, and the neuter tode from ho and de; the same, i.e. this or that one (plural these or those); often used as a personal pronoun: he, she, such, these, thus.
  3492. hodeuo from hodos; to travel: journey.
  3493. hodegeo from hodegos; to show the way (literally or figuratively (teach)): guide, lead.
  3494. hodegos from hodos and hegeomai; a conductor (literally or figuratively (teacher)): guide, leader.
  3495. hodoiporeo from a compound of hodos and poreuomai; to be a wayfarer, i.e. travel: go on a journey.
  3496. hodoiporia from the same as hodoiporeo; travel: journey(-ing).
  3497. hodos apparently a primary word; a road; by implication, a progress (the route, act or distance); figuratively, a mode or means: journey, (high-)way.
  3498. odous perhaps from the base of esthio; a "tooth": tooth.
  3499. odunao from odune; to grieve: sorrow, torment.
  3500. odune from duno; grief (as dejecting): sorrow.
  3501. odurmos from a derivative of the base of duno; moaning, i.e. lamentation: mourning.
  3502. ho esti from the neuter of hos and the third person singular present indicative of eimi; which is: called, which is (make), that is (to say).
  3503. Ozias of Hebrew origin (`Uzziyah); Ozias (i.e. Uzzijah), an Israelite: Ozias.
  3504. ozo a primary verb (in a strengthened form); to scent (usually an ill "odor"): stink.
  3505. hothen from hos with the directive enclitic of source; from which place or source or cause (adverb or conjunction): from thence, (from) whence, where(-by, -fore, -upon).
  3506. othone of uncertain affinity; a linen cloth, i.e. (especially) a sail: sheet.
  3507. othonion neuter of a presumed derivative of othone; a linen bandage: linen clothes.
  3508. oikeios from oikos; domestic, i.e. (as noun), a relative, adherent: (those) of the (his own) house(-hold).
  3509. oiketes from oikeo; a fellow resident, i.e. menial domestic: (household) servant.
  3510. oikeo from oikos; to occupy a house, i.e. reside (figuratively, inhabit, remain, inhere); by implication, to cohabit: dwell. See also oikoumene.
  3511. oikema from oikeo; a tenement, i.e. (specially), a jail: prison.
  3512. oiketerion neuter of a presumed derivative of oikeo (equivalent to oikema); a residence (literally or figuratively): habitation, house.
  3513. oikia from oikos; properly, residence (abstractly), but usually (concretely) an abode (literally or figuratively); by implication, a family (especially domestics): home, house(-hold).
  3514. oikiakos from oikia; familiar, i.e. (as noun) relatives: they (them) of (his own) household.
  3515. oikodespoteo from oikodespotes; to be the head of (i.e. rule) a family: guide the house.
  3516. oikodespotes from oikos and despotes; the head of a family: goodman (of the house), householder, master of the house.
  3517. oikodomeo from the same as oikodome; to be a house-builder, i.e. construct or (figuratively) confirm: (be in) build(-er, -ing, up), edify, embolden.
  3518. oikodome feminine (abstract) of a compound of oikos and the base of doma; architecture, i.e. (concretely) a structure; figuratively, confirmation: building, edify(-ication, -ing).
  3519. oikodomia from the same as oikodome; confirmation: edifying.
  3520. oikonomeo from oikonomos; to manage (a house, i.e. an estate): be steward.
  3521. oikonomia from oikonomos; administration (of a household or estate); specially, a (religious) "economy": dispensation, stewardship.
  3522. oikonomos from oikos and the base of nomos; a house-distributor (i.e. manager), or overseer, i.e. an employee in that capacity; by extension, a fiscal agent (treasurer); figuratively, a preacher (of the Gospel): chamberlain, governor, steward.
  3523. oikos of uncertain affinity; a dwelling (more or less extensive, literal or figurative); by implication, a family (more or less related, literally or figuratively): home, house(-hold), temple.
  3524. oikoumene feminine participle present passive of oikeo (as noun, by implication, of ge); land, i.e. the (terrene part of the) globe; specially, the Roman empire: earth, world.
  3525. oikouros from oikos and ouros (a guard; be "ware"); a stayer at home, i.e. domestically inclined (a "good housekeeper"): keeper at home.
  3526. oikteiro also (in certain tenses) prolonged oiktereo from oiktos (pity); to exercise pity: have compassion on.
  3527. oiktirmos from oikteiro; pity: mercy.
  3528. oiktirmon from oikteiro; compassionate: merciful, of tender mercy.
  3529. oinopotes from oinos and a derivative of the alternate of pino; a tippler: winebibber.
  3530. oinos a primary word (or perhaps of Hebrew origin (yayin)); "wine" (literally or figuratively): wine.
  3531. oinophlugia from oinos and a form of the base of phluaros; an overflow (or surplus) of wine, i.e. vinolency (drunkenness): excess of wine.
  3532. oiomai, or (shorter) oimai middle voice apparently from hoios; to make like (oneself), i.e. imagine (be of the opinion): suppose, think.
  3533. hoios probably akin to ho, hos, and hosos; such or what sort of (as a correlation or exclamation); especially the neuter (adverbially) with negative, not so: so (as), such as, what (manner of), which.
  3534. okneo from oknos (hesitation); to be slow (figuratively, loath): delay.
  3535. okneros from okneo; tardy, i.e. indolent; (figuratively) irksome: grievous, slothful.
  3536. oktaemeros from oktos and hemera; an eight-day old person or act: the eighth day.
  3537. oktos a primary numeral; "eight": eight.
  3538. olethros from a primary ollumi (to destroy; a prolonged form); ruin, i.e. death, punishment: destruction.
  3539. oligopistos from oligos and pistis; incredulous, i.e. lacking confidence (in Christ): of little faith.
  3540. oligos of uncertain affinity; puny (in extent, degree, number, duration or value); especially neuter (adverbially) somewhat: + almost, brief(-ly), few, (a) little, + long, a season, short, small, a while.
  3541. oligopsuchos from oligos and psuche; little-spirited, i.e. faint-hearted: feebleminded.
  3542. oligoreo from a compound of oligos and ora ("care"); to have little regard for, i.e. to disesteem: despise.
  3543. olothreutes from olothreuo; a ruiner, i.e. (specially), a venomous serpent: destroyer.
  3544. olothreuo from olethros; to spoil, i.e. slay: destroy.
  3545. holokautoma from a derivative of a compound of holos and a derivative of kaio; a wholly-consumed sacrifice ("holocaust"): (whole) burnt offering.
  3546. holokleria from holokleros; integrity, i.e. physical wholeness: perfect soundness.
  3547. holokleros from holos and kleros; complete in every part, i.e. perfectly sound (in body): entire, whole.
  3548. ololuzo a reduplicated primary verb; to "howl" or "halloo", i.e. shriek: howl.
  3549. holos a primary word; "whole" or "all", i.e. complete (in extent, amount, time or degree), especially (neuter) as noun or adverb: all, altogether, every whit, + throughout, whole.
  3550. holoteles from holos and telos; complete to the end, i.e. absolutely perfect: wholly.
  3551. Olumpas probably a contraction from Olumpiodoros (Olympian-bestowed, i.e. heaven-descended); Olympas, a Christian: Olympas.
  3552. olunthos of uncertain derivation; an unripe (because out of season) fig: untimely fig.
  3553. holos adverb from holos; completely, i.e. altogether; (by analogy), everywhere; (negatively) not by any means: at all, commonly, utterly.
  3554. ombros of uncertain affinity; a thunder storm: shower.
  3555. homileo from homilos; to be in company with, i.e. (by implication) to converse: commune, talk.
  3556. homilia from homilos; companionship ("homily"), i.e. (by implication) intercourse: communication.
  3557. homilos from the base of homou and a derivative of the alternate of haireomai (meaning a crowd); association together, i.e. a multitude: company.
  3558. omma from optanomai; a sight, i.e. (by implication) the eye: eye.
  3559. omnuo, a prolonged form of a primary, but obsolete omo, for which another prolonged form omoo is used in certain tenses; to swear, i.e. take (or declare on) oath: swear.
  3560. homothumadon adverb from a compound of the base of homou and thumos; unanimously: with one accord (mind).
  3561. homoiazo from homoios; to resemble: agree.
  3562. homoiopathes from homoios and the alternate of pascho; similarly affected: of (subject to) like passions.
  3563. homoios from the base of homou; similar (in appearance or character): like, + manner.
  3564. homoiotes from homoios; resemblance: like as, similitude.
  3565. homoioo from homoios; to assimilate, i.e. compare; passively, to become similar: be (make) like, (in the) liken(-ess), resemble.
  3566. homoioma from homoioo; a form; abstractly, resemblance: made like to, likeness, shape, similitude.
  3567. homoios adverb from homoios; similarly: likewise, so.
  3568. homoiosis from homoioo; assimilation, i.e. resemblance: similitude.
  3569. homologeo from a compound of the base of homou and logos; to assent, i.e. covenant, acknowledge: con- (pro-)fess, confession is made, give thanks, promise.
  3570. homologia from the same as homologeo; acknowledgment: con- (pro-)fession, professed.
  3571. homologoumenos adverb of present passive participle of homologeo; confessedly: without controversy.
  3572. homothechnos from the base of homou and techne; a fellow-artificer: of the same craft.
  3573. homou genitive case of homos (the same; akin to hama) as adverb; at the same place or time: together.
  3574. homophron from the base of homou and phren; like-minded, i.e. harmonious: of one mind.
  3575. homos adverb from the base of homou; at the same time, i.e. (conjunctionally) notwithstanding, yet still: and even, nevertheless, though but.
  3576. onar of uncertain derivation; a dream: dream.
  3577. onarion neuter of a presumed derivative of onos; a little ass: young ass.
  3578. oneidizo from oneidos; to defame, i.e. rail at, chide, taunt: cast in teeth, (suffer) reproach, revile, upbraid.
  3579. oneidismos from oneidizo; contumely: reproach.
  3580. oneidos probably akin to the base of onoma; notoriety, i.e. a taunt (disgrace): reproach.
  3581. Onesimos from oninemi; profitable; Onesimus, a Christian: Onesimus.
  3582. Onesiphoros from a derivative of oninemi and phoros; profit-bearer; Onesiphorus, a Christian: Onespiphorus.
  3583. onikos from onos; belonging to a ass, i.e. large (so as to be turned by a ass): millstone.
  3584. oninemi a prolonged form of an apparently primary verb (onomai, to slur); for which another prolonged form (onao) is used as an alternate in some tenses (unless indeed it be identical with the base of onoma through the idea of notoriety); to gratify, i.e. (middle voice) to derive pleasure or advantage from: have joy.
  3585. onoma from a presumed derivative of the base of ginosko (compare oninemi); a "name" (literally or figuratively) (authority, character): called, (+ sur-)name(-d).
  3586. onomazo from onoma; to name, i.e. assign an appellation; by extension, to utter, mention, profess: call, name.
  3587. onos apparently a primary word; a donkey: an ass.
  3588. ontos adverb of the oblique cases of on; really: certainly, clean, indeed, of a truth, verily.
  3589. oxos from oxus; vinegar, i.e. sour wine: vinegar.
  3590. oxus probably akin to the base of akmen ("acid"); keen; by analogy, rapid: sharp, swift.
  3591. ope probably from optanomai; a hole (as if for light), i.e. cavern; by analogy, a spring (of water): cave, place.
  3592. opisthen from opis (regard; from optanomai) with enclitic of source; from the rear (as a secure aspect), i.e. at the back (adverb and preposition of place or time): after, backside, behind.
  3593. opiso from the same as opisthen with enclitic of direction; to the back, i.e. aback (as adverb or preposition of time or place; or as noun): after, back(-ward), (+ get) behind, + follow.
  3594. hoplizo from hoplon; to equip (with weapons (middle voice and figuratively)): arm self.
  3595. hoplon probably from a primary hepo (to be busy about); an implement or utensil or tool (literally or figuratively, especially, offensive for war): armour, instrument, weapon.
  3596. hopoios from hos and poios; of what kind that, i.e. how (as) great (excellent) (specially, as an indefinite correlative to the definite antecedent toioutos of quality): what manner (sort) of, such as whatsoever.
  3597. hopote from hos and pote; what(-ever) then, i.e. (of time) as soon as: when.
  3598. hopou from hos and pou; what(-ever) where, i.e. at whichever spot: in what place, where(-as, -soever), whither (+ soever).
  3599. optanomai, a (middle voice) prolonged form of the primary (middle voice) optomai; which is used for it in certain tenses; and both as alternate of horao; to gaze (i.e. with wide-open eyes, as at something remarkable; and thus differing from blepo, which denotes simply voluntary observation; and from eido, which expresses merely mechanical, passive or casual vision; while theaomai, and still more emphatically its intensive theoreo, signifies an earnest but more continued inspection; and skopeo a watching from a distance): appear, look, see, shew self.
  3600. optasia from a presumed derivative of optanomai; visuality, i.e. (concretely) an apparition: vision.
  3601. optos from an obsolete verb akin to hepso (to "steep"); cooked, i.e. roasted: broiled.
  3602. opora apparently from the base of opse and hora; properly, even-tide of the (summer) season (dog-days), i.e. (by implication) ripe fruit: fruit.
  3603. hopos from hos and pos; what(-ever) how, i.e. in the manner that (as adverb or conjunction of coincidence, intentional or actual): because, how, (so) that, to, when.
  3604. horama from horao; something gazed at, i.e. a spectacle (especially supernatural): sight, vision.
  3605. horasis from horao; the act of gazing, i.e. (externally) an aspect or (internally) an inspired appearance: sight, vision.
  3606. horatos from horao; gazed at, i.e. (by implication) capable of being seen: visible.
  3607. horao properly, to stare at (compare optanomai), i.e. (by implication) to discern clearly (physically or mentally); by extension, to attend to; by Hebraism, to experience; passively, to appear: behold, perceive, see, take heed.
  3608. orge from oregomai; properly, desire (as a reaching forth or excitement of the mind), i.e. (by analogy), violent passion (ire, or (justifiable) abhorrence); by implication punishment: anger, indignation, vengeance, wrath.
  3609. orgizo from orge; to provoke or enrage, i.e. (passively) become exasperated: be angry (wroth).
  3610. orgilos from orge; irascible: soon angry.
  3611. orguia from oregomai; a stretch of the arms, i.e. a fathom: fathom.
  3612. oregomai middle voice of apparently a prolonged form of an obsolete primary (compare oros); to stretch oneself, i.e. reach out after (long for): covet after, desire.
  3613. oreinos from oros; mountainous, i.e. (feminine by implication, of chora) the Highlands (of Juda): hill country.
  3614. orexis from oregomai; excitement of the mind, i.e. longing after: lust.
  3615. orthopodeo from a compound of orthos and pous; to be straight-footed, i.e. (figuratively) to go directly forward: walk uprightly.
  3616. orthos probably from the base of oros; right (as rising), i.e. (perpendicularly) erect (figuratively, honest), or (horizontally) level or direct: straight, upright.
  3617. orthotomeo from a compound of orthos and the base of tomoteros, to make a straight cut, i.e. (figuratively) to dissect (expound) correctly (the divine message): rightly divide.
  3618. orthrizo from orthros; to use the dawn, i.e. (by implication) to repair betimes: come early in the morning.
  3619. orthrinos from orthros; relating to the dawn, i.e. matutinal (as an epithet of Venus, especially brilliant in the early day): morning.
  3620. orthrios from orthros; in the dawn, i.e. up at day-break: early.
  3621. orthros from the same as oros; dawn (as sun-rise, rising of light); by extension, morn: early in the morning.
  3622. orthos adverb from orthos; in a straight manner, i.e. (figuratively) correctly (also morally): plain, right(-ly).
  3623. horizo from horion; to mark out or bound ("horizon"), i.e. (figuratively) to appoint, decree, specify: declare, determine, limit, ordain.
  3624. horion neuter of a derivative of an apparently primary horos (a bound or limit); a boundary-line, i.e. (by implication) a frontier (region): border, coast.
  3625. horkizo from horkos; to put on oath, i.e. make swear; by analogy, to solemnly enjoin: adjure, charge.
  3626. horkos from herkos (a fence; perhaps akin to horion); a limit, i.e. (sacred) restraint (specially, an oath): oath.
  3627. horkomosia from a compound of horkos and a derivative of omnuo; asseveration on oath: oath.
  3628. hormao from horme; to start, spur or urge on, i.e. (reflexively) to dash or plunge: run (violently), rush.
  3629. horme of uncertain affinity; a violent impulse, i.e. onset: assault.
  3630. hormema from horme; an attack, i.e. (abstractly) precipitancy: violence.
  3631. orneon neuter of a presumed derivative of ornis; a birdling: bird, fowl.
  3632. ornis probably from a prolonged form of the base of oros; a bird (as rising in the air), i.e. (specially), a hen (or female domestic fowl): hen.
  3633. horothesia from a compound of the base of horion and a derivative of tithemi; a limit-placing, i.e. (concretely) boundary-line: bound.
  3634. oros probably from an obsolete oro (to rise or "rear"; perhaps akin to airo; compare ornis); a mountain (as lifting itself above the plain): hill, mount(-ain).
  3635. orusso apparently a primary verb; to "burrow" in the ground, i.e. dig: dig.
  3636. orphanos of uncertain affinity; bereaved ("orphan"), i.e. parentless: comfortless, fatherless.
  3637. orcheomai middle voice from orchos (a row or ring); to dance (from the ranklike or regular motion): dance.
  3638. hos, including feminine he, and neuter ho probably a primary word (or perhaps a form of the article ho); the relatively (sometimes demonstrative) pronoun, who, which, what, that: one, (an-, the) other, some, that, what, which, who(-m, -se), etc. See also hou.
  3639. hosakis multiple adverb from hos; how (i.e. with an, so) many times as: as oft(-en) as.
  3640. hosios of uncertain affinity; properly, right (by intrinsic or divine character; thus distinguished from dikaios, which refers rather to human statutes and relations; from hieros, which denotes formal consecration; and from hagios, which relates to purity from defilement), i.e. hallowed (pious, sacred, sure): holy, mercy, shalt be. 342
  3641. hosiotes from hosios; piety: holiness.
  3642. hosios adverb from hosios; piously: holily.
  3643. osme from ozo; fragrance (literally or figuratively): odour, savour.
  3644. hosos by reduplication from hos; as (much, great, long, etc.) as: all (that), as (long, many, much) (as), how great (many, much), (in-)asmuch as, so many as, that (ever), the more, those things, what (great, -soever), wheresoever, wherewithsoever, which, X while, who(-soever).
  3645. hosper from hos and per; who especially: whomsoever.
  3646. osteon, or contracted ostoun of uncertain affinity; a bone: bone.

  3648. ostrakinos from ostrakon ("oyster") (a tile, i.e. terra cotta); earthen-ware, i.e. clayey; by implication, frail: of earth, earthen.
  3649. osphresis from a derivative of ozo; smell (the sense): smelling.

  3654. hotou for the genitive case of hostis (as adverb); during which same time, i.e. whilst: whiles.
  3655. ou, also (before a vowel) ouk, and (before an aspirate) ouch a primary word; the absolute negative (compare me) adverb; no or not: + long, nay, neither, never, no (X man), none, (can-)not, + nothing, + special, un(-worthy), when, + without, + yet but. See also ou me, mekos.

  3661. oudeis, including feminine oudemia, and neuter ouden from oude and heis; not even one (man, woman or thing), i.e. none, nobody, nothing: any (man), aught, man, neither any (thing), never (man), no (man), none (+ of these things), not (any, at all, -thing), nought.
  3662. oudepote from oude and pote; not even at any time, i.e. never at all: neither at any time, never, nothing at any time.

  3664. ouketi, also (separately) ouk eti from ou and eti; not yet, no longer: after that (not), (not) any more, henceforth (hereafter) not, no longer (more), not as yet (now), now no more (not), yet (not).
  3665. oukoun from ou and oun; is it not therefore that, i.e. (affirmatively) hence or so: then.
  3666. oun apparently a primary word; (adverbially) certainly, or (conjunctionally) accordingly: and (so, truly), but, now (then), so (likewise then), then, therefore, verily, wherefore.
  3667. oupo from ou and po; not yet: hitherto not, (no) as yet, not yet.
  3668. oura apparently a primary word; a tail: tail.
  3669. ouranios from ouranos; celestial, i.e. belonging to or coming from the sky: heavenly.

  3671. ouranos perhaps from the same as oros (through the idea of elevation); the sky; by extension, heaven (as the abode of God); by implication, happiness, power, eternity; specially, the Gospel (Christianity): air, heaven(-ly), sky.
  3672. Ourbanos of Latin origin; Urbanus (of the city, "urbane"), a Christian: Urbanus.
  3673. Ourias of Hebrew origin ('Uwriyah); Urias (i.e. Urijah), a Hittite: Urias.
  3674. ous apparently a primary word; the ear (physically or mentally): ear.
  3675. ousia from the feminine of on; substance, i.e. property (possessions): goods, substance.

  3677. houtos, including nominative masculine plural houtoi, nominative feminine singular haute, and nominative feminine plural hautai from the article ho and autos; the he (she or it), i.e. this or that (often with article repeated): he (it was that), hereof, it, she, such as, the same, these, they, this (man, same, woman), which, who.
  3678. houto, or (before a vowel houtos adverb from houtos; in this way (referring to what precedes or follows): after that, after (in) this manner, as, even (so), for all that, like(-wise), no more, on this fashion(-wise), so (in like manner), thus, what.
  3679. ouchi intensive of ou; not indeed: nay, not.
  3680. opheiletes from opheilo; an ower, i.e. person indebted; figuratively, a delinquent; morally, a transgressor (against God): debtor, which owed, sinner.
  3681. opheile from opheilo; indebtedness, i.e. (concretely) a sum owed; figuratively, obligation, i.e. (conjugal) duty: debt, due.
  3682. opheilema from (the alternate of) opheilo; something owed, i.e. (figuratively) a due; morally, a fault: debt.
  3683. opheilo, or (in certain tenses), its prolonged form opheileo probably from the base of ophelos (through the idea of accruing); to owe (pecuniarily); figuratively, to be under obligation (ought, must, should); morally, to fail in duty: behove, be bound, (be) debt(-or), (be) due(-ty), be guilty (indebted), (must) need(-s), ought, owe, should. See also ophelon.
  3684. ophelon first person singular of a past tense of opheilo; I ought (wish), i.e. (interjection) oh that!: would (to God).
  3685. ophelos from ophello (to heap up, i.e. accumulate or benefit); gain: advantageth, profit.
  3686. ophthalmodouleia from ophthalmos and douleia; sight-labor, i.e. that needs watching (remissness): eye-service.
  3687. ophthalmos from optanomai; the eye (literally or figuratively); by implication, vision; figuratively, envy (from the jealous side-glance): eye, sight.
  3688. ophis probably from optanomai (through the idea of sharpness of vision); a snake, figuratively, (as a type of sly cunning) an artful malicious person, especially Satan: serpent.
  3689. ophrus perhaps from optanomai (through the idea of the shading or proximity to the organ of vision); the eye-"brow" or forehead, i.e. (figuratively) the brink of a precipice: brow.
  3690. ochleo from ochlos; to mob, i.e. (by implication) to harass: vex.
  3691. ochlopoieo from ochlos and poieo; to make a crowd, i.e. raise a public disturbance: gather a company.
  3692. ochlos from a derivative of echo (meaning a vehicle); a throng (as borne along); by implication, the rabble; by extension, a class of people; figuratively, a riot: company, multitude, number (of people), people, press.
  3693. ochuroma from a remote derivative of echo (meaning to fortify, through the idea of holding safely); a castle (figuratively, argument): stronghold.
  3694. opsarion neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of optos; a relish to other food (as if cooked sauce), i.e. (specially), fish (presumably salted and dried as a condiment): fish.
  3695. opse from the same as opiso (through the idea of backwardness); (adverbially) late in the day; by extension, after the close of the day: (at) even, in the end.
  3696. opsimos from opse; later, i.e. vernal (showering): latter.
  3697. opsios from opse; late; feminine (as noun) afternoon (early eve) or nightfall (later eve): even(-ing, (-tide)).
  3698. opsis from optanomai; properly, sight (the act), i.e. (by implication) the visage, an external show: appearance, countenance, face.
  3699. opsonion neuter of a presumed derivative of the same as opsarion; rations for a soldier, i.e. (by extension) his stipend or pay: wages.
  3700. ho on kai or ho en kai or ho erchomenos a phrase combining ho with the present participle and imperfect of eimi and the present participle of erchomai by means of kai; the one being and the one that was and the one coming, i.e. the Eternal, as a divine epithet of Christ: which art (is, was), and (which) wast (is, was), and art (is) to come (shalt be).
  3701. pagideuo from pagis; to ensnare (figuratively): entangle.
  3702. pagis from pegnumi; a trap (as fastened by a noose or notch); figuratively, a trick or statagem (temptation): snare.
  3703. pathema from a presumed derivative of pathos; something undergone, i.e. hardship or pain; subjectively, an emotion or influence: affection, affliction, motion, suffering.
  3704. pathetos from the same as pathema; liable (i.e. doomed) to experience pain: suffer.
  3705. pathos from the alternate of pascho; properly, suffering ("pathos"), i.e. (subjectively) a passion (especially concupiscence): (inordinate) affection, lust.
  3706. paidagogos from pais and a reduplicated form of ago; a boy-leader, i.e. a servant whose office it was to take the children to school; (by implication, (figuratively) a tutor ("pdagogue")): instructor, schoolmaster.
  3707. paidarion neuter of a presumed derivative of pais; a little boy: child, lad.
  3708. paideia from paideuo; tutorage, i.e. education or training; by implication, disciplinary correction: chastening, chastisement, instruction, nurture.
  3709. paideutes from paideuo; a trainer, i.e. teacher or (by implication) discipliner: which corrected, instructor.
  3710. paideuo from pais; to train up a child, i.e. educate, or (by implication), discipline (by punishment): chasten(-ise), instruct, learn, teach.
  3711. paidiothen adverb (of source) from paidion; from infancy: of a child.
  3712. paidion neuter diminutive of pais; a childling (of either sex), i.e. (properly), an infant, or (by extension) a half-grown boy or girl; figuratively, an immature Christian: (little, young) child, damsel.
  3713. paidiske feminine diminutive of pais; a girl, i.e. (specially), a female slave or servant: bondmaid(-woman), damsel, maid(-en).
  3714. paizo from pais; to sport (as a boy): play.
  3715. pais perhaps from paio; a boy (as often beaten with impunity), or (by analogy), a girl, and (genitive case) a child; specially, a slave or servant (especially a minister to a king; and by eminence to God): child, maid(-en), (man) servant, son, young man.
  3716. paio a primary verb; to hit (as if by a single blow and less violently than tupto); specially, to sting (as a scorpion): smite, strike.
  3717. Pakatiane feminine of an adjective of uncertain derivation; Pacatianian, a section of Phrygia: Pacatiana.
  3718. palai probably another form for palin (through the idea of retrocession); (adverbially) formerly, or (by relatively) sometime since; (elliptically as adjective) ancient: any while, a great while ago, (of) old, in time past.
  3719. palaios from palai; antique, i.e. not recent, worn out: old.
  3720. palaiotes from palaios; antiquatedness: oldness.
  3721. palaioo from palaios; to make (passively, become) worn out, or declare obsolete: decay, make (wax) old.
  3722. pale from pallo (to vibrate; another form for ballo); wrestling: + wrestle.
  3723. paliggenesia from palin and genesis; (spiritual) rebirth (the state or the act), i.e. (figuratively) spiritual renovation; specially, Messianic restoration: regeneration.
  3724. palin probably from the same as pale (through the idea of oscillatory repetition); (adverbially) anew, i.e. (of place) back, (of time) once more, or (conjunctionally) furthermore or on the other hand: again.
  3725. pamplethei dative case (adverb) of a compound of pas and plethos; in full multitude, i.e. concertedly or simultaneously: all at once.
  3726. pampolus from pas and polus; full many, i.e. immense: very great.
  3727. Pamphulia from a compound of pas and pura; every-tribal, i.e. heterogeneous (chora being implied); Pamphylia, a region of Asia Minor: Pamphylia.
  3728. pandocheion neuter of a presumed compound of pas and a derivative of dechomai; all-receptive, i.e. a public lodging-place (caravanserai or khan): inn.
  3729. pandocheus from the same as pandocheion; an innkeeper (warden of a caravanserai): host.
  3730. paneguris from pas and a derivative of agora; a mass-meeting, i.e. (figuratively) universal companionship: general assembly.
  3731. panoiki adverb from pas and oikos; with the whole family: with all his house.
  3732. panoplia from a compound of pas and hoplon; full armor ("panoply"): all (whole) armour.
  3733. panourgia from panougos; adroitness, i.e. (in a bad sense) trickery or sophistry: (cunning) craftiness, subtilty.
  3734. panougos from pas and ergon; all-working, i.e. adroit (shrewd): crafty.
  3735. pantachothen adverb (of source) from pantachou; from all directions: from every quarter.
  3736. pantachou genitive case (as adverb of place) of a presumed derivative of pas; universally: in all places, everywhere.
  3737. panteles from pas and telos; full-ended, i.e. entire (neuter as noun, completion): + in (no) wise, uttermost.
  3738. pante adverb (of manner) from pas; wholly: always.
  3739. pantothen adverb (of source) from pas; from (i.e. on) all sides: on every side, round about.
  3740. pantokrator from pas and kratos; the all-ruling, i.e. God (as absolute and universal sovereign): Almighty, Omnipotent.
  3741. pantote from pas and hote; every when, i.e. at all times: alway(-s), ever(-more).
  3742. pantos adverb from pas; entirely; specially, at all events, (with negative, following) in no event: by all means, altogether, at all, needs, no doubt, in (no) wise, surely.
  3743. para a primary preposition; properly, near; i.e. (with genitive case) from beside (literally or figuratively), (with dative case) at (or in) the vicinity of (objectively or subjectively), (with accusative case) to the proximity with (local (especially beyond or opposed to) or causal (on account of): above, against, among, at, before, by, contrary to, X friend, from, + give (such things as they), + that (she) had, X his, in, more than, nigh unto, (out) of, past, save, sideby, in the sight of, than, (there-)fore, with. In compounds it retains the same variety of application.
  3744. parabaino from para and the base of basis; to go contrary to, i.e. violate a command: (by) transgress(-ion).
  3745. paraballo from para and ballo; to throw alongside, i.e. (reflexively) to reach a place, or (figuratively) to liken: arrive, compare.
  3746. parabasis from parabaino; violation: breaking, transgression.
  3747. parabates from parabaino; a violator: breaker, transgress(-or).
  3748. parabiazomai from para and the middle voice of biazo; to force contrary to (nature), i.e. compel (by entreaty): constrain.
  3749. parabole from paraballo; a similitude ("parable"), i.e. (symbolic) fictitious narrative (of common life conveying a moral), apothegm or adage: comparison, figure, parable, proverb.
  3750. parabouleuomai from para and the middle voice of bouleuo; to misconsult, i.e. disregard: not (to) regard(-ing).
  3751. paraggelia from paraggello; a mandate: charge, command.
  3752. paraggello from para and the base of aggelos; to transmit a message, i.e. (by implication) to enjoin: (give in) charge, (give) command(-ment), declare.
  3753. paraginomai from para and ginomai; to become near, i.e. approach (have arrived); by implication, to appear publicly: come, go, be present.
  3754. parago from para and ago; to lead near, i.e. (reflexively or intransitively) to go along or away: depart, pass (away, by, forth).
  3755. paradeigmatizo from para and deigmatizo; to show alongside (the public), i.e. expose to infamy: make a public example, put to an open shame.
  3756. paradeisos of Oriental origin (compare pardec); a park, i.e. (specially), an Eden (place of future happiness, "paradise"): paradise.
  3757. paradechomai from para and dechomai; to accept near, i.e. admit or (by implication) delight in: receive.
  3758. paradiatribe from a compound of para and diatribo; misemployment, i.e. meddlesomeness: perverse disputing.
  3759. paradidomi from para and didomi; to surrender, i.e yield up, intrust, transmit: betray, bring forth, cast, commit, deliver (up), give (over, up), hazard, put in prison, recommend.
  3760. paradoxos from para and doxa (in the sense of seeming); contrary to expectation, i.e. extraordinary ("paradox"): strange.
  3761. paradosis from paradidomi; transmission, i.e. (concretely) a precept; specially, the Jewish traditionary law: ordinance, tradition.
  3762. parazeloo from para and zeloo; to stimulate alongside, i.e. excite to rivalry: provoke to emulation (jealousy).
  3763. parathalassios from para and thalassa; along the sea, i.e. maritime (lacustrine): upon the sea coast.
  3764. paratheoreo from para and theoreo; to overlook or disregard: neglect.
  3765. paratheke from paratithemi; a deposit, i.e. (figuratively) trust: committed unto.
  3766. paraineo from para and aineo; to mispraise, i.e. recommend or advise (a different course): admonish, exhort.
  3767. paraiteomai from para and the middle voice of aiteo; to beg off, i.e. deprecate, decline, shun: avoid, (make) excuse, intreat, refuse, reject.
  3768. parakathizo from para and kathizo; to sit down near: sit.
  3769. parakaleo from para and kaleo; to call near, i.e. invite, invoke (by imploration, hortation or consolation): beseech, call for, (be of good) comfort, desire, (give) exhort(-ation), intreat, pray.
  3770. parakalupto from para and kalupto; to cover alongside, i.e. veil (figuratively): hide.
  3771. parakatatheke from a compound of para and katatithemi; something put down alongside, i.e. a deposit (sacred trust): that (thing) which is committed (un-)to (trust).
  3772. parakeimai from para and keimai; to lie near, i.e. be at hand (figuratively, be prompt or easy): be present.
  3773. paraklesis from parakaleo; imploration, hortation, solace: comfort, consolation, exhortation, intreaty.
  3774. parakletos an intercessor, consoler: advocate, comforter.
  3775. parakoe from parakouo; inattention, i.e. (by implication) disobedience: disobedience.
  3776. parakoloutheo from para and akoloutheo; to follow near, i.e. (figuratively) attend (as a result), trace out, conform to: attain, follow, fully know, have understanding.
  3777. parakouo from para and akouo; to mishear, i.e. (by implication) to disobey: neglect to hear.
  3778. parakupto from para and kupto; to bend beside, i.e. lean over (so as to peer within): look (into), stoop down.
  3779. paralambano from para and lambano; to receive near, i.e. associate with oneself (in any familiar or intimate act or relation); by analogy, to assume an office; figuratively, to learn: receive, take (unto, with).
  3780. paralegomai from para and the middle voice of lego (in its original sense); (specially), to lay one's course near, i.e. sail past: pass, sail by.
  3781. paralios from para and hals; beside the salt (sea), i.e. maritime: sea coast.
  3782. parallage from a compound of para and allasso; transmutation (of phase or orbit), i.e. (figuratively) fickleness: variableness.
  3783. paralogizomai from para and logizomai; to misreckon, i.e. delude: beguile, deceive.
  3784. paralutikos from a derivative of paraluo; as if dissolved, i.e. "paralytic": that had (sick of) the palsy.
  3785. paraluo from para and luo; to loosen beside, i.e. relax (perfect passive participle, paralyzed or enfeebled): feeble, sick of the (taken with) palsy.
  3786. parameno from para and meno; to stay near, i.e. remain (literally, tarry; or figuratively, be permanent, persevere): abide, continue.
  3787. paramutheomai from para and the middle voice of a derivative of muthos; to relate near, i.e. (by implication) encourage, console: comfort.
  3788. paramuthia from paramutheomai; consolation (properly, abstract): comfort.
  3789. paramuthion neuter of paramuthia; consolation (properly, concretely): comfort.
  3790. paranomeo from a compound of para and nomos; to be opposed to law, i.e. to transgress: contrary to law.
  3791. paranomia from the same as paranomeo; transgression: iniquity.
  3792. parapikraino from para and pikraino; to embitter alongside, i.e. (figuratively) to exasperate: provoke.
  3793. parapikrasmos from parapikraino; irritation: provocation.
  3794. parapipto from para and pipto; to fall aside, i.e. (figuratively) to apostatize: fall away.
  3795. parapleo from para and pleo; to sail near: sail by.
  3796. paraplesion neuter of a compound of para and the base of plesion (as adverb); close by, i.e. (figuratively) almost: nigh unto.
  3797. paraplesios adverb from the same as paraplesion; in a manner near by, i.e. (figuratively) similarly: likewise.
  3798. parapoeruomai from para and poreuomai; to travel near: go, pass (by).
  3799. paraptoma from parapipto; a side-slip (lapse or deviation), i.e. (unintentional) error or (wilful) transgression: fall, fault, offence, sin, trespass.
  3800. pararrhueo from para and the alternate of rheo; to flow by, i.e. (figuratively) carelessly pass (miss): let slip.
  3801. parasemos from para and the base of semaino; side-marked, i.e. labelled (with a badge (figure-head) of a ship): sign.
  3802. paraskeuazo from para and a derivative of skeuos; to furnish aside, i.e. get ready: prepare self, be (make) ready.
  3803. paraskeue as if from paraskeuazo; readiness: preparation.
  3804. parateino from para and teino (to stretch); to extend along, i.e. prolong (in point of time): continue.
  3805. paratereo from para and tereo; to inspect alongside, i.e. note insidiously or scrupulously: observe, watch.
  3806. parateresis from paratereo; inspection, i.e. ocular evidence: obervation.
  3807. paratithemi from para and tithemi; to place alongside, i.e. present (food, truth); by implication, to deposit (as a trust or for protection): allege, commend, commit (the keeping of), put forth, set before.
  3808. paratugchano from para and tugchano; to chance near, i.e. fall in with: meet with.
  3809. parautika from para and a derivative of autos; at the very instant, i.e. momentary: but for a moment.
  3810. paraphero from para and phero (including its alternate forms); to bear along or aside, i.e. carry off (literally or figuratively); by implication, to avert: remove, take away.
  3811. paraphroneo from para and phroneo; to misthink, i.e. be insane (silly): as a fool.
  3812. paraphronia from paraphroneo; insanity, i.e. foolhardiness: madness.
  3813. paracheimazo from para and cheimazo; to winter near, i.e. stay with over the rainy season: winter.
  3814. paracheimasia from paracheimazo; a wintering over: winter in.
  3815. parachrema from para and chrema (in its original sense); at the thing itself, i.e. instantly: forthwith, immediately, presently, straightway, soon.
  3816. pardalis feminine of pardos (a panther); a leopard: leopard.
  3817. pareimi from para and eimi (including its various forms); to be near, i.e. at hand; neuter present participle (singular) time being, or (plural) property: come, X have, be here, + lack, (be here) present.
  3818. pareisago from para and eisago; to lead in aside, i.e. introduce surreptitiously: privily bring in.
  3819. pareisaktos from pareisago; smuggled in: unawares brought in.
  3820. pareisduno from para and a compound of eis and duno; to settle in alongside, i.e. lodge stealthily: creep in unawares.
  3821. pareiserchomai from para and eiserchomai; to come in alongside, i.e. supervene additionally or steathily: come in privily, enter.
  3822. pareisphero from para and eisphero; to bear in alongside, i.e. introduce simultaneously: give.
  3823. parektos from para and ektos; near outside, i.e. besides: except, saving, without.
  3824. parembole from a compound of para and emballo; a throwing in beside (juxtaposition), i.e. (specially), battle-array, encampment or barracks (tower Antonia): army, camp, castle.
  3825. parenochleo from para and enochleo; to harass further, i.e. annoy: trouble.
  3826. parepidemos from para and the base of epidemeo; an alien alongside, i.e. a resident foreigner: pilgrim, stranger.
  3827. parerchomai from para and erchomai; to come near or aside, i.e. to approach (arrive), go by (or away), (figuratively) perish or neglect, (causative) avert: come (forth), go, pass (away, by, over), past, transgress.
  3828. paresis from ktetor; praetermission, i.e. toleration: remission.
  3829. parecho from para and echo; to hold near, i.e. present, afford, exhibit, furnish occasion: bring, do, give, keep, minister, offer, shew, + trouble.
  3830. paregoria from a compound of para and a derivative of agora (meaning to harangue an assembly); an address alongside, i.e. (specially), consolation: comfort.
  3831. parthenia from parthenos; maidenhood: virginity.
  3832. parthenos of unknown origin; a maiden; by implication, an unmarried daughter: virgin.
  3833. Parthos probably of foreign origin; a Parthian, i.e. inhabitant of Parthia: Parthian.
  3834. pariemi from para and hiemi (to send); to let by, i.e. relax: hang down.
  3835. paristemi, or prolonged paristano from para and histemi; to stand beside, i.e. (transitively) to exhibit, proffer, (specially), recommend, (figuratively) substantiate; or (intransitively) to be at hand (or ready), aid: assist, bring before, command, commend, give presently, present, prove, provide, shew, stand (before, by, here, up, with), yield.
  3836. Parmenas probably by contraction for Parmenides (a derivative of a compound of para and meno); constant; Parmenas, a Christian: Parmenas.
  3837. parodos from para and hodos; a by-road, i.e. (actively) a route: way.
  3838. paroikeo from para and oikeo; to dwell near, i.e. reside as a foreigner: sojourn in, be a stranger.
  3839. paroikia from paroikos; foreign residence: sojourning, X as strangers.
  3840. paroikos from para and oikos; having a home near, i.e. (as noun) a by-dweller (alien resident): foreigner, sojourn, stranger.
  3841. paroimia from a compound of para and perhaps a derivative of oiomai; apparently a state alongside of supposition, i.e. (concretely) an adage; specially, an enigmatical or fictitious illustration: parable, proverb.
  3842. paroinos from para and oinos; staying near wine, i.e. tippling (a toper): given to wine.
  3843. paroichomai from para and oichomai (to depart); to escape along, i.e. be gone: past.
  3844. paromoiazo from paromoios; to resemble: be like unto.
  3845. paromoios from para and homoios; alike nearly, i.e. similar: like.
  3846. paroxuno from para and a derivative of oxus; to sharpen alongside, i.e. (figuratively) to exasperate: easily provoke, stir.
  3847. paroxusmos from paroxuno ("paroxysm"); incitement (to good), or dispute (in anger): contention, provoke unto.
  3848. parorgizo from para and orgizo; to anger alongside, i.e. enrage: anger, provoke to wrath.
  3849. parorgismos from parorgizo; rage: wrath.
  3850. parotruno from para and otruno (to spur); to urge along, i.e. stimulate (to hostility): stir up.
  3851. parousia from the present participle of pareimi; a being near, i.e. advent (often, return; specially, of Christ to punish Jerusalem, or finally the wicked); (by implication) physically, aspect: coming, presence.
  3852. paropsis from para and the base of opsarion; a side-dish (the receptacle): platter.
  3853. parrhesia from pas and a derivative of rheo; all out-spokenness, i.e. frankness, bluntness, publicity; by implication, assurance: bold (X -ly, -ness, -ness of speech), confidence, X freely, X openly, X plainly(-ness).
  3854. parrhesiazomai middle voice from parrhesia; to be frank in utterance, or confident in spirit and demeanor: be (wax) bold, (preach, speak) boldly.
  3855. pas including all the forms of declension; apparently a primary word; all, any, every, the whole: all (manner of, means), alway(-s), any (one), X daily, + ever, every (one, way), as many as, + no(-thing), X thoroughly, whatsoever, whole, whosoever.
  3856. pascha of Chaldee origin (compare pecach); the Passover (the meal, the day, the festival or the special sacrifices connected with it): Easter, Passover.
  3857. pascho, including the forms patho, and pentho, used only in certain tenses for it apparently a primary verb; to experience a sensation or impression (usually painful): feel, passion, suffer, vex.
  3858. Patara probably of foreign origin; Patara, a place in Asia Minor: Patara.
  3859. patasso probably prolongation from paio; to knock (gently or with a weapon or fatally): smite, strike. Compare tupto.
  3860. pateo from a derivative probably of paio (meaning a "path"); to trample (literally or figuratively): tread (down, under foot).
  3861. pater apparently a primary word; a "father" (literally or figuratively, near or more remote): father, parent.
  3862. Patmos of uncertain derivation; Patmus, an islet in the Mediterranean: Patmos.
  3863. patraloias from pater and the same as the latter part of metraloias; a parricide: murderer of fathers.
  3864. patria as if feminine of a derivative of pater; paternal descent, i.e. (concretely) a group of families or a whole race (nation): family, kindred, lineage.
  3865. patriarches from patria and archo; a progenitor ("patriarch"): patriarch.
  3866. patrikos from pater; paternal, i.e. ancestral: of fathers.
  3867. patris from parasemos; a father-land, i.e. native town; (figuratively) heavenly home: (own) country.
  3868. Patrobas perhaps a contraction for Patrobios (a compound of pater and bios); father's life; Patrobas, a Christian: Patrobas.
  3869. patroparadotos from pater and a derivative of paradidomi (in the sense of handing over or down); traditionary: received by tradition from fathers.
  3870. patroios from pater; paternal, i.e. hereditary: of fathers.
  3871. Paulos of Latin origin; (little; but remotely from a derivative of pauo, meaning the same); Paulus, the name of a Roman and of an apostle: Paul, Paulus.
  3872. pauo a primary verb ("pause"); to stop (transitively or intransitively), i.e. restrain, quit, desist, come to an end: cease, leave, refrain.
  3873. Paphos of uncertain derivation; Paphus, a place in Cyprus: Paphos.
  3874. pachuno from a derivative of pegnumi (meaning thick); to thicken, i.e. (by implication) to fatten (figuratively, stupefy or render callous): wax gross.
  3875. pede ultimately from pous; a shackle for the feet: fetter.
  3876. pedinos from a derivative of pous (meaning the ground); level (as easy for the feet): plain.
  3877. pezeuo from the same as peze; to foot a journey, i.e. travel by land: go afoot.
  3878. peze dative case feminine of a derivative of pous (as adverb); foot-wise, i.e. by walking: a- (on) foot.
  3879. peitharcheo from a compound of peitho and archo; to be persuaded by a ruler, i.e. (genitive case) to submit to authority; by analogy, to conform to advice: hearken, obey (magistrates).
  3880. peithos from peitho; persuasive: enticing.
  3881. peitho a primary verb; to convince (by argument, true or false); by analogy, to pacify or conciliate (by other fair means); reflexively or passively, to assent (to evidence or authority), to rely (by inward certainty): agree, assure, believe, have confidence, be (wax) conflent, make friend, obey, persuade, trust, yield.
  3882. peinao from the same as penes (through the idea of pinching toil; "pine"); to famish (absolutely or comparatively); figuratively, to crave: be an hungered.
  3883. peira from the base of peran (through the idea of piercing); a test, i.e. attempt, experience: assaying, trial.
  3884. peirazo from peira; to test (objectively), i.e. endeavor, scrutinize, entice, discipline: assay, examine, go about, prove, tempt(-er), try.
  3885. peirasmos from peirazo; a putting to proof (by experiment (of good), experience (of evil), solicitation, discipline or provocation); by implication, adversity: temptation, X try.
  3886. peirao from peira; to test (subjectively), i.e. (reflexively) to attempt: assay.
  3887. peismone from a presumed derivative of peitho; persuadableness, i.e. credulity: persuasion.
  3888. pelagos of uncertain affinity; deep or open sea, i.e. the main: depth, sea.
  3889. pelekizo from a derivative of plesso (meaning an axe); to chop off (the head), i.e. truncate: behead.
  3890. pemptos from pente; fifth: fifth.
  3891. pempo apparently a primary verb; to dispatch (from the subjective view or point of departure, whereas hiemi (as a stronger form of eimi) refers rather to the objective point or terminus ad quem, and stello denotes properly, the orderly motion involved), especially on a temporary errand; also to transmit, bestow, or wield: send, thrust in.
  3892. penes from a primary peno (to toil for daily subsistence); starving, i.e. indigent: poor. Compare ptochos.
  3893. penthera feminine of pentheros; a wife's mother: mother in law, wife's mother.
  3894. pentheros of uncertain affinity; a wife's father: father in law.
  3895. pentheo from penthos; to grieve (the feeling or the act): mourn, (be-)wail.
  3896. penthos strengthened from the alternate of pascho; grief: mourning, sorrow.
  3897. pentichros prolongation from the base of penes; necessitous: poor.
  3898. pentakis multiplicative adverb from pente; five times: five times.
  3899. pentakischilioi from pentakis and chilioi; five times a thousand: five thousand.
  3900. pentakosioi from pente and hekaton; five hundred: five hundred.
  3901. pente a primary number; "five": five.
  3902. pentekaidekatos from pente and kai and dekatos; five and tenth: fifteenth.
  3903. pentekonta multiplicative of pente; fifty: fifty.
  3904. pentekoste feminine of the ordinal of pentekonta; fiftieth (hemera being implied) from Passover, i.e. the festival of "Pentecost": Pentecost.
  3905. pepoithesis from the perfect of the alternate of pascho; reliance: confidence, trust.
  3906. per from the base of peran; an enclitic particle significant of abundance (thoroughness), i.e. emphasis; much, very or ever: (whom-)soever.
  3907. peran apparently accusative case of an obsolete derivative of peiro (to "pierce"); through (as adverb or preposition), i.e. across: beyond, farther (other) side, over.
  3908. peras from the same as peran; an extremity: end, ut-(ter-)most participle.
  3909. Pergamos from purgos; fortified; Pergamus, a place in Asia Minor: Pergamos.
  3910. Perge probably from the same as Pergamos; a tower; Perga, a place in Asia Minor: Perga.
  3911. peri from the base of peran; properly, through (all over), i.e. around; figuratively with respect to; used in various applications, of place, cause or time (with the genitive case denoting the subject or occasion or superlative point; with the accusative case the locality, circuit, matter, circumstance or general period): (there-)about, above, against, at, on behalf of, X and his company, which concern, (as) concerning, for, X how it will go with, ((there-, where-)) of, on, over, pertaining (to), for sake, X (e-)state, (as) touching, (where-)by (in), with. In comparative, it retains substantially the same meaning of circuit (around), excess (beyond), or completeness (through).
  3912. periago from peri and ago; to take around (as a companion); reflexively, to walk around: compass, go (round) about, lead about.
  3913. periaireo from peri and haireomai (including its alternate); to remove all around, i.e. unveil, cast off (anchor); figuratively, to expiate: take away (up).
  3914. periastrapto from peri and astrapto; to flash all around, i.e. envelop in light: shine round (about).
  3915. periballo from peri and ballo; to throw all around, i.e. invest (with a palisade or with clothing): array, cast about, clothe(-d me), put on.
