  3916. periblepo from peri and blepo; to look all around: look (round) about (on).
  3917. peribolaion neuter of a presumed derivative of periballo; something thrown around one, i.e. a mantle, veil: covering, vesture.
  3918. perideo from peri and deo; to bind around one, i.e. enwrap: bind about.
  3919. periergazomai from peri and ergazomai; to work all around, i.e. bustle about (meddle): be a busybody.
  3920. periergos from peri and ergon; working all around, i.e. officious (meddlesome, neuter plural magic): busybody, curious arts.
  3921. perierchomai from peri and erchomai (including its alternate); to come all around, i.e. stroll, vacillate, veer: fetch a compass, vagabond, wandering about.
  3922. periecho from peri and echo; to hold all around, i.e. include, clasp (figuratively): + astonished, contain, after (this manner).
  3923. perizonnumi from peri and zonnumi; to gird all around, i.e. (middle voice or passive) to fasten on one's belt (literally or figuratively): gird (about, self).
  3924. perithesis from peritithemi; a putting all around, i.e. decorating oneself with: wearing.
  3925. periistemi from peri and histemi; to stand all around, i.e. (near) to be a bystander, or (aloof) to keep away from: avoid, shun, stand by (round about).
  3926. perikatharma from a compound of peri and kathairo; something cleaned off all around, i.e. refuse (figuratively): filth.
  3927. perikalupto from peri and kalupto; to cover all around, i.e. entirely (the face, a surface): blindfold, cover, overlay.
  3928. perikeimai from peri and keimai; to lie all around, i.e. inclose, encircle, hamper (literally or figuratively): be bound (compassed) with, hang about.
  3929. perikephalaia feminine of a compound of peri and kephale; encirclement of the head, i.e. a helmet: helmet.
  3930. perikrates from peri and kratos; strong all around, i.e. a master (manager): + come by.
  3931. perikrupto from peri and krupto; to conceal all around, i.e. entirely: hide.
  3932. perikukloo from peri and kukloo; to encircle all around, i.e. blockade completely: compass round.
  3933. perilampo from peri and lampo; to illuminate all around, i.e. invest with a halo: shine round about.
  3934. perileipo from peri and leipo; to leave all around, i.e. (passively) survive: remain.
  3935. perilupos from peri and lupe; grieved all around, i.e. intensely sad: exceeding (very) sorry(-owful).
  3936. perimeno from peri and meno; to stay around, i.e. await: wait for.
  3937. perix adverb from peri; all around, i.e. (as an adjective) circumjacent: round about.
  3938. perioikeo from peri and oikeo; to reside around, i.e. be a neighbor: dwell round about.
  3939. perioikos from peri and oikos; housed around, i.e. neighboring (used elliptically as a noun): neighbour.
  3940. periousios from the present participle feminine of a compound of peri and eimi; being beyond usual, i.e. special (one's own): peculiar.
  3941. perioche from periecho; a being held around, i.e. (concretely) a passage (of Scripture, as circumscribed): place.
  3942. peripateo from peri and pateo; to tread all around, i.e. walk at large (especially as proof of ability); figuratively, to live, deport oneself, follow (as a companion or votary): go, be occupied with, walk (about).
  3943. peripeiro from peri and the base of peran; to penetrate entirely, i.e. transfix (figuratively): pierce through.
  3944. peripipto from peri and pipto; to fall into something that is all around, i.e. light among or upon, be surrounded with: fall among (into).
  3945. peripoieomai middle voice from peri and poieo; to make around oneself, i.e. acquire (buy): purchase.
  3946. peripoiesis from peripoieomai; acquisition (the act or the thing); by extension, preservation: obtain(-ing), peculiar, purchased, possession, saving.
  3947. perirrhegnumi from peri and rhegnumi; to tear all around, i.e. completely away: rend off.
  3948. perispao from peri and spao; to drag all around, i.e. (figuratively) to distract (with care): cumber.
  3949. perisseia from perisseuo; surplusage, i.e. superabundance: abundance(-ant, (-ly)), superfluity.
  3950. perisseuma from perisseuo; a surplus, or superabundance: abundance, that was left, over and above.
  3951. perisseuo from perissos; to superabound (in quantity or quality), be in excess, be superfluous; also (transitively) to cause to superabound or excel: (make, more) abound, (have, have more) abundance (be more) abundant, be the better, enough and to spare, exceed, excel, increase, be left, redound, remain (over and above).
  3952. perissos from peri (in the sense of beyond); superabundant (in quantity) or superior (in quality); by implication, excessive; adverbially (with ek) violently; neuter (as noun) preeminence: exceeding abundantly above, more abundantly, advantage, exceedingly, very highly, beyond measure, more, superfluous, vehement(-ly).
  3953. perissoteron neuter of perissoteros (as adverb); in a more superabundant way: more abundantly, a great deal, far more.
  3954. perissoteros comparative of perissos; more superabundant (in number, degree or character): more abundant, greater (much) more, overmuch.
  3955. perissoteros adverb from perissoteros; more superabundantly: more abundant(-ly), X the more earnest, (more) exceedingly, more frequent, much more, the rather.
  3956. perissos adverb from perissos; superabundantly: exceedingly, out of measure, the more.
  3957. peristera of uncertain derivation; a pigeon: dove, pigeon.
  3958. peritemno from peri and the base of tomoteros; to cut around, i.e. (specially) to circumcise: circumcise.
  3959. peritithemi from peri and tithemi; to place around; by implication, to present: bestow upon, hedge round about, put about (on, upon), set about.
  3960. peritome from peritemno; circumcision (the rite, the condition or the people, literally or figuratively): X circumcised, circumcision.
  3961. peritrepo from peri and the base of trope; to turn around, i.e. (mentally) to craze: + make mad.
  3962. peritrecho from peri and trecho (including its alternate); to run around, i.e. traverse: run through.
  3963. periphero from peri and phero; to convey around, i.e. transport hither and thither: bear (carry) about.
  3964. periphroneo from peri and phroneo; to think beyond, i.e. depreciate (contemn): despise.
  3965. perichoros from peri and chora; around the region, i.e. circumjacent (as noun, with ge implied vicinity): country (round) about, region (that lieth) round about.
  3966. peripsoma from a comparative of peri and psao (to rub); something brushed all around, i.e. off-scrapings (figuratively, scum): offscouring.
  3967. perpereuomai middle voice from perperos (braggart; perhaps by reduplication of the base of peran); to boast: vaunt itself.
  3968. Persis a Persian woman; Persis, a Christian female: Persis.
  3969. perusi adverb from peras; the by-gone, i.e. (as noun) last year: + a year ago.
  3970. peteinon neuter of a derivative of petomai; a flying animal, i.e. bird: bird, fowl.
  3971. petomai, or prolongation petaomai, or contracted ptaomai middle voice of a primary verb; to fly: fly(-ing).
  3972. petra feminine of the same as Petros; a (mass of) rock (literally or figuratively): rock.
  3973. Petros apparently a primary word; a (piece of) rock (larger than lithos); as a name, Petrus, an apostle: Peter, rock. Compare Kephas.
  3974. petrodes from petra and eidos; rock-like, i.e. rocky: stony.
  3975. peganon from pegnumi; rue (from its thick or fleshy leaves): rue.
  3976. pege probably from pegnumi (through the idea of gushing plumply); a fount (literally or figuratively), i.e. source or supply (of water, blood, enjoyment) (not necessarily the original spring): fountain, well.
  3977. pegnumi a prolonged form of a primary verb (which in its simpler form occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); to fix ("peg"), i.e. (specially) to set up (a tent): pitch.
  3978. pedalion neuter of a (presumed) derivative of pedon (the blade of an oar; from the same as pede); a "pedal", i.e. helm: rudder.
  3979. pelikos a quantitative form (the feminine) of the base of pou; how much (as an indefinite), i.e. in size or (figuratively) dignity: how great (large).
  3980. pelos perhaps a primary word; clay: clay.
  3981. pera of uncertain affinity; a wallet or leather pouch for food: scrip.
  3982. pechus of uncertain affinity; the fore-arm, i.e. (as a measure) a cubit: cubit.
  3983. piazo probably another form of biazo; to squeeze, i.e. seize (gently by the hand (press), or officially (arrest), or in hunting (capture)): apprehend, catch, lay hand on, take. Compare piezo.
  3984. piezo another form for piazo; to pack: press down.
  3985. pithanologia from a compound of a derivative of peitho and logos; persuasive language: enticing words.
  3986. pikraino from pikros; to embitter (literally or figuratively): be (make) bitter.
  3987. pikria from pikros; acridity (especially poison), literally or figuratively: bitterness.
  3988. pikros perhaps from pegnumi (through the idea of piercing); sharp (pungent), i.e. acrid (literally or figuratively): bitter.
  3989. pikros adverb from pikros; bitterly, i.e. (figuratively) violently: bitterly.
  3990. Pilatos of Latin origin; close-pressed, i.e. firm; Pilatus, a Roman: Pilate.
  3991. pimpremi; a reduplicated and prolonged form of a primary preo which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); to fire, i.e. burn (figuratively and passively, become inflamed with fever): be (X should have) swollen.
  3992. pinakidion diminutive of pinax; a tablet (for writing on): writing table.
  3993. pinax apparently a form of plax; a plate: charger, platter.
  3994. pino, a prolonged form of pio, which (together with another form) poo occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses; to imbibe (literally or figuratively): drink.
  3995. piotes from pion (fat; perhaps akin to the alternate of pino through the idea of repletion); plumpness, i.e. (by implication) richness (oiliness): fatness.
  3996. piprasko, a reduplicated and prolonged form of prao; (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); contracted from perao (to traverse; from the base of peran); to traffic (by travelling), i.e. dispose of as merchandise or into slavery (literally or figuratively): sell.
  3997. pipto, a reduplicated and contracted form of peto; (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); probably akin to petomai through the idea of alighting; to fall (literally or figuratively): fail, fall (down), light on.
  3998. Pisidia probably of foreign origin; Pisidia, a region of Asia Minor: Pisidia.
  3999. pisteuo from pistis; to have faith (in, upon, or with respect to, a person or thing), i.e. credit; by implication, to entrust (especially one's spiritual well-being to Christ): believe(-r), commit (to trust), put in trust with.
  4000. pistikos from pistis; trustworthy, i.e. genuine (unadulterated): spike-(nard).
  4001. pistis from peitho; persuasion, i.e. credence; moral conviction (of religious truth, or the truthfulness of God or a religious teacher), especially reliance upon Christ for salvation; abstractly, constancy in such profession; by extension, the system of religious (Gospel) truth itself: assurance, belief, believe, faith, fidelity.
  4002. pistos from peitho; objectively, trustworthy; subjectively, trustful: believe(-ing, -r), faithful(-ly), sure, true.
  4003. pistoo from pistos; to assure: assure of.
  4004. planao from plane; to (properly, cause to) roam (from safety, truth, or virtue): go astray, deceive, err, seduce, wander, be out of the way.
  4005. plane feminine of planos (as abstractly); objectively, fraudulence; subjectively, a straying from orthodoxy or piety: deceit, to deceive, delusion, error.
  4006. planetes from planos; a rover ("planet"), i.e. (figuratively) an erratic teacher: wandering.
  4007. planos of uncertain affinity; roving (as a tramp), i.e. (by implication) an impostor or misleader; --deceiver, seducing.
  4008. plax from plasso; a moulding-board, i.e. flat surface ("plate", or tablet, literally or figuratively): table.
  4009. plasma from plasso; something moulded: thing formed.
  4010. plasso a primary verb; to mould, i.e. shape or fabricate: form.
  4011. plastos from plasso; moulded, i.e. (by implication) artificial or (figuratively) fictitious (false): feigned.
  4012. plateia feminine of platus; a wide "plat" or "place", i.e. open square: street.
  4013. platos from platus; width: breadth.
  4014. platuno from platus; to widen (literally or figuratively): make broad, enlarge.
  4015. platus from plasso; spread out "flat" ("plot"), i.e. broad: wide.
  4016. plegma from pleko; a plait (of hair): broidered hair.
  4017. pleistos irregular superlative of polus; the largest number or very large: very great, most.
  4018. pleion, or neuter pleion, or pleon comparative of polus; more in quantity, number, or quality; also (in plural) the major portion: X above, + exceed, more excellent, further, (very) great(-er), long(-er), (very) many, greater (more) part, + yet but.
  4019. pleko a primary word; to twine or braid: plait.
  4020. pleonazo from pleion; to do, make or be more, i.e. increase (transitively or intransitively); by extension, to superabound: abound, abundant, make to increase, have over.
  4021. pleonekteo from pleonektes; to be covetous, i.e. (by implication) to over-reach: get an advantage, defraud, make a gain.
  4022. pleonektes from pleion and echo; holding (desiring) more, i.e. eager for gain (avaricious, hence a defrauder): covetous.
  4023. pleonexia from pleonektes; avarice, i.e. (by implication) fraudulency, extortion: covetous(-ness) practices, greediness.
  4024. pleura of uncertain affinity; a rib, i.e. (by extension) side: side.
  4025. pleo, another form for pleuo plyoo'-o; which is used as an alternate in certain tenses; probably a form of pluno (through the idea of plunging through the water); to pass in a vessel: sail. See also pletho.
  4026. plege from plesso; a stroke; by implication, a wound; figuratively, a calamity: plague, stripe, wound(-ed).
  4027. plethos from pletho; a fulness, i.e. a large number, throng, populace: bundle, company, multitude.
  4028. plethuno from another form of plethos; to increase (transitively or intransitively): abound, multiply.
  4029. pletho, a prolonged form of a primary pleo (which appears only as an alternate in certain tenses and in the reduplicated form pimplemi); to "fill" (literally or figuratively (imbue, influence, supply)); specially, to fulfil (time): accomplish, full (come), furnish.
  4030. plektes from plesso; a smiter, i.e. pugnacious (quarrelsome): striker.
  4031. plemmura prolonged from pletho; flood-tide, i.e. (by analogy) a freshet: flood.
  4032. plen from pleion; moreover (besides), i.e. albeit, save that, rather, yet: but (rather), except, nevertheless, notwithstanding, save, than.
  4033. pleres from pletho; replete, or covered over; by analogy, complete: full.
  4034. plerophoreo from pleres and phoreo; to carry out fully (in evidence), i.e. completely assure (or convince), entirely accomplish: most surely believe, fully know (persuade), make full proof of.
  4035. plerophoria from plerophoreo; entire confidence: (full) assurance.
  4036. pleroo from pleres; to make replete, i.e. (literally) to cram (a net), level up (a hollow), or (figuratively) to furnish (or imbue, diffuse, influence), satisfy, execute (an office), finish (a period or task), verify (or coincide with a prediction), etc.: accomplish, X after, (be) complete, end, expire, fill (up), fulfil, (be, make) full (come), fully preach, perfect, supply.
  4037. pleroma from pleroo; repletion or completion, i.e. (subjectively) what fills (as contents, supplement, copiousness, multitude), or (objectively) what is filled (as container, performance, period): which is put in to fill up, piece that filled up, fulfilling, full, fulness.
  4038. plesion neuter of a derivative of pelas (near); (adverbially) close by; as noun, a neighbor, i.e. fellow (as man, countryman, Christian or friend): near, neighbour.
  4039. plesmone from a presumed derivative of pletho; a filling up, i.e. (figuratively) gratification: satisfying.
  4040. plesso apparently another form of plasso (through the idea of flattening out); to pound, i.e. (figuratively) to inflict with (calamity): smite. Compare tupto.
  4041. ploiarion neuter of a presumed derivative of ploion; a boat: boat, little (small) ship.
  4042. ploion from pleo; a sailer, i.e. vessel: ship(-ing).
  4043. ploos from pleo; a sail, i.e. navigation: course, sailing, voyage.
  4044. plousios from ploutos; wealthy; figuratively, abounding with: rich.
  4045. plousios adverb from plousios; copiously: abundantly, richly.
  4046. plouteo from ploutizo; to be (or become) wealthy (literally or figuratively): be increased with goods, (be made, wax) rich.
  4047. ploutizo from ploutos; to make wealthy (figuratively): en- (make) rich.
  4048. ploutos from the base of pletho; wealth (as fulness), i.e. (literally) money, possessions, or (figuratively) abundance, richness, (specially), valuable bestowment: riches.
  4049. pluno a prolonged form of an obsolete pluo (to "flow"); to "plunge", i.e. launder clothing: wash. Compare louo, nipto.
  4050. pneuma from pneo; a current of air, i.e. breath (blast) or a breeze; by analogy or figuratively, a spirit, i.e. (human) the rational soul, (by implication) vital principle, mental disposition, etc., or (superhuman) an angel, demon, or (divine) God, Christ's spirit, the Holy Spirit: ghost, life, spirit(-ual, -ually), mind. Compare psuche.
  4051. pneumatikos from pneuma; non-carnal, i.e. (humanly) ethereal (as opposed to gross), or (dmoniacally) a spirit (concretely), or (divinely) supernatural, regenerate, religious: spiritual. Compare psuchikos.
  4052. pneumatikos adverb from pneumatikos; non-physically, i.e. divinely, figuratively: spiritually.
  4053. pneo a primary word; to breathe hard, i.e. breeze: blow. Compare psucho.
  4054. pnigo strengthened from pneo; to wheeze, i.e. (causative, by implication) to throttle or strangle (drown): choke, take by the throat.
  4055. pniktos from pnigo; throttled, i.e. (neuter concretely) an animal choked to death (not bled): strangled.
  4056. pnoe from pneo; respiration, a breeze: breath, wind.
  4057. poderes from pous and another element of uncertain affinity; a dress (esthes implied) reaching the ankles: garment down to the foot.
  4058. pothen from the base of posis with enclitic adverb of origin; from which (as interrogative) or what (as relative) place, state, source or cause: whence.
  4059. poieo apparently a prolonged form of an obsolete primary; to make or do (in a very wide application, more or less direct): abide, + agree, appoint, X avenge, + band together, be, bear, + bewray, bring (forth), cast out, cause, commit, + content, continue, deal, + without any delay, (would) do(-ing), execute, exercise, fulfil, gain, give, have, hold, X journeying, keep, + lay wait, + lighten the ship, make, X mean, + none of these things move me, observe, ordain, perform, provide, + have purged, purpose, put, + raising up, X secure, shew, X shoot out, spend, take, tarry, + transgress the law, work, yield. Compare prasso.
  4060. poiema from poieo; a product, i.e. fabric (literally or figuratively): thing that is made, workmanship.
  4061. poiesis from poieo; action, i.e. performance (of the law): deed.
  4062. poietes from poieo; a performer; specially, a "poet"; --doer, poet.
  4063. poikilos of uncertain derivation; motley, i.e. various in character: divers, manifold.
  4064. poimaino from poimen; to tend as a shepherd of (figuratively, superviser): feed (cattle), rule.
  4065. poimen of uncertain affinity; a shepherd (literally or figuratively): shepherd, pastor.
  4066. poimne contraction from poimaino; a flock (literally or figuratively): flock, fold.
  4067. poimnion neuter of a presumed derivative of poimne; a flock, i.e. (figuratively) group (of believers): flock.
  4068. poios from the base of pou and hoios; individualizing interrogative (of character) what sort of, or (of number) which one: what (manner of), which.
  4069. polemeo from polemos; to be (engaged) in warfare, i.e. to battle (literally or figuratively): fight, (make) war.
  4070. polemos from pelomai (to bustle); warfare (literally or figuratively; a single encounter or a series): battle, fight, war.
  4071. polis probably from the same as polemos, or perhaps from polus; a town (properly, with walls, of greater or less size): city.
  4072. politarches from polis and archo; a town-officer, i.e. magistrate: ruler of the city.
  4073. politeia from polites ("polity"); citizenship; concretely, a community: commonwealth, freedom.
  4074. politeuma from politeuomai; a community, i.e. (abstractly) citizenship (figuratively): conversation.
  4075. politeuomai middle voice of a derivative of polites; to behave as a citizen (figuratively): let conversation be, live.
  4076. polites from polis; a townsman: citizen.
  4077. pollakis multiplicative adverb from polus; many times, i.e. frequently: oft(-en, -entimes, -times).
  4078. pollaplasion from polus and probably a derivative of pleko; manifold, i.e. (neuter as noun) very much more: manifold more.
  4079. polulogia from a compound of polus and logos; loquacity, i.e. prolixity: much speaking.
  4080. polumeros adverb from a compound of polus and meros; in many portions, i.e. variously as to time and agency (piecemeal): at sundry times.
  4081. polupoikilos from polus and poikilos; much variegated, i.e. multifarious: manifold.
  4082. polus including the forms from the alternate pollos; (singular) much (in any respect) or (plural) many; neuter (singular) as adverbial, largely; neuter (plural) as adverb or noun often, mostly, largely: abundant, + altogether, common, + far (passed, spent), (+ be of a) great (age, deal, -ly, while), long, many, much, oft(-en (-times)), plenteous, sore, straitly. Compare pleistos, pleion.
  4083. polusplagchnos from polus and splagchnon (figuratively); extremely compassionate: very pitiful.
  4084. poluteles from polus and telos; extremely expensive: costly, very precious, of great price.
  4085. polutimos from polus and time; extremely valuable: very costly, of great price.
  4086. polutropos adverb from a compound of polus and tropos; in many ways, i.e. variously as to method or form: in divers manners.
  4087. poma from the alternate of pino; a beverage: drink.
  4088. poneria from poneros; depravity, i.e. (specially), malice; plural (concretely) plots, sins: iniquity, wickedness.
  4089. poneros from a derivative of ponos; hurtful, i.e. evil (properly, in effect or influence, and thus differing from kakos, which refers rather to essential character, as well as from sapros, which indicates degeneracy from original virtue); figuratively, calamitous; also (passively) ill, i.e. diseased; but especially (morally) culpable, i.e. derelict, vicious, facinorous; neuter (singular) mischief, malice, or (plural) guilt; masculine (singular) the devil, or (plural) sinners: bad, evil, grievous, harm, lewd, malicious, wicked(-ness). See also poneroteros.
  4090. poneroteros comparative of poneros; more evil: more wicked.
  4091. ponos from the base of penes; toil, i.e. (by implication) anguish: pain.
  4092. Pontikos from Pontos; a Pontican, i.e. native of Pontus: born in Pontus.
  4093. Pontios of Latin origin; apparently bridged; Pontius, a Roman: Pontius.
  4094. Pontos of Latin origin; a sea; Pontus, a region of Asia Minor: Pontus.
  4095. Poplios of Latin origin; apparently "popular"; Poplius (i.e. Publius), a Roman: Publius.
  4096. poreia from poreuomai; travel (by land); figuratively (plural) proceedings, i.e. career: journey(-ing), ways.
  4097. poreuomai middle voice from a derivative of the same as peira; to traverse, i.e. travel (literally or figuratively; especially to remove (figuratively, die), live, etc.); --depart, go (away, forth, one's way, up), (make a, take a) journey, walk.
  4098. portheo prolongation from pertho (to sack); to ravage (figuratively): destroy, waste.
  4099. porismos from a derivative of poros (a way, i.e. means); furnishing (procuring), i.e. (by implication) money-getting (acquisition): gain.
  4100. Porkios of Latin origin; apparently swinish; Porcius, a Roman: Porcius.
  4101. porneia from porneuo; harlotry (including adultery and incest); figuratively, idolatry: fornication.
  4102. porneuo from porne; to act the harlot, i.e. (literally) indulge unlawful lust (of either sex), or (figuratively) practise idolatry: commit (fornication).
  4103. porne feminine of pornos; a strumpet; figuratively, an idolater: harlot, whore.
  4104. pornos from pernemi (to sell; akin to the base of piprasko); a (male) prostitute (as venal), i.e. (by analogy) a debauchee (libertine): fornicator, whoremonger.
  4105. porrho adverb from pro; forwards, i.e. at a distance: far, a great way off. See also porrhothen.
  4106. porrhothen from porrho with adverbial enclitic of source; from far, or (by implication) at a distance, i.e. distantly: afar off.
  4107. porrhotero adverb comparative of porrho; further, i.e. a greater distance: farther.
  4108. porphura of Latin origin; the "purple" mussel, i.e. (by implication) the red-blue color itself, and finally a garment dyed with it: purple.
  4109. porphurous from porphura; purpureal, i.e. bluish red: purple.
  4110. porphuropolis feminine of a compound of porphura and poleo; a female trader in purple cloth: seller of purple.
  4111. posakis multiplicative from posos; how many times: how oft(-en).
  4112. posis from the alternate of pino; a drinking (the act), i.e. (concretely) a draught: drink.
  4113. posos from an absolute pos (who, what) and hos; interrogative pronoun (of amount) how much (large, long or (plural) many): how great (long, many), what.
  4114. potamos probably from a derivative of the alternate of pino (compare potos); a current, brook or freshet (as drinkable), i.e. running water: flood, river, stream, water.
  4115. potamophoretos from potamos and a derivative of phoreo; river-borne, i.e. overwhelmed by a stream: carried away of the flood.
  4116. potapos apparently from pote and the base of pou; interrogatively, whatever, i.e. of what possible sort: what (manner of).
  4117. pote from the base of pou and te; indefinite adverb, at some time, ever: afore-(any, some-)time(-s), at length (the last), (+ n-)ever, in the old time, in time past, once, when.
  4118. pote from the base of pou and te; interrogative adverb, at what time: + how long, when.
  4119. poteron neuter of a comparative of the base of pou; interrogative as adverb, which (of two), i.e. is it this or that: whether.
  4120. poterion neuter of a derivative of the alternate of pino; a drinking-vessel; by extension, the contents thereof, i.e. a cupful (draught); figuratively, a lot or fate: cup.
  4121. potizo from a derivative of the alternate of pino; to furnish drink, irrigate: give (make) to drink, feed, water.
  4122. Potioloi of Latin origin; little wells, i.e. mineral springs; Potioli (i.e. Puteoli), a place in Italy: Puteoli.
  4123. potos from the alternate of pino; a drinking-bout or carousal: banqueting.
  4124. pou genitive case of an indefinite pronoun pos (some) otherwise obsolete (compare posos); as adverb of place, somewhere, i.e. nearly: about, a certain place.
  4125. pou genitive case of an interrogative pronoun pos (what) otherwise obsolete (perhaps the same as pou used with the rising slide of inquiry); as adverb of place; at (by implication, to) what locality: where, whither.
  4126. Poudes of Latin origin; modest; Pudes (i.e. Pudens), a Christian: Pudens.
  4127. pous a primary word; a "foot" (figuratively or literally): foot(-stool).
  4128. pragma from prasso; a deed; by implication, an affair; by extension, an object (material): business, matter, thing, work.
  4129. pragmateia from pragmateuomai; a transaction, i.e. negotiation: affair.
  4130. pragmateuomai from pragma; to busy oneself with, i.e. to trade: occupy.
  4131. praitorion of Latin origin; the prtorium or governor's courtroom (sometimes including the whole edifice and camp): (common, judgment) hall (of judgment), palace, prtorium.
  4132. praktor from a derivative of prasso; a practiser, i.e. (specially), an official collector: officer.
  4133. praxis from prasso; practice, i.e. (concretely) an act; by extension, a function: deed, office, work.
  4134. praios a form of praus, used in certain parts; gentle, i.e. humble: meek.
  4135. praiotes from praios; gentleness, by implication, humility: meekness.
  4136. prasia perhaps from prason (a leek, and so an onion-patch); a garden plot, i.e. (by implication, of regular beds) a row (repeated in plural by Hebraism, to indicate an arrangement): in ranks.
  4137. prasso a primary verb; to "practise", i.e. perform repeatedly or habitually (thus differing from poieo, which properly refers to a single act); by implication, to execute, accomplish, etc.; specially, to collect (dues), fare (personally): commit, deeds, do, exact, keep, require, use arts.
  4138. praus apparently a primary word; mild, i.e. (by implication) humble: meek. See also praios.
  4139. prautes from praus; mildness, i.e. (by implication) humility: meekness.
  4140. prepo apparently a primary verb; to tower up (be conspicuous), i.e. (by implication) to be suitable or proper (third person singular present indicative, often used impersonally, it is fit or right): become, comely.
  4141. pesbeia from presbeuo; seniority (eldership), i.e. (by implication) an embassy (concretely, ambassadors): ambassage, message.
  4142. presbeuo from the base of presbuteros; to be a senior, i.e. (by implication) act as a representative (figuratively, preacher): be an ambassador.
  4143. presbuterion neuter of a presumed derivative of presbuteros; the order of elders, i.e. (specially), Israelite Sanhedrin or Christian "presbytery": (estate of) elder(-s), presbytery.
  4144. presbuteros comparative of presbus (elderly); older; as noun, a senior; specially, an Israelite Sanhedrist (also figuratively, member of the celestial council) or Christian "presbyter": elder(-est), old.
  4145. presbutes from the same as presbuteros; an old man: aged (man), old man.
  4146. presbutis feminine of presbutes; an old woman: aged woman.
  4147. prenes from pro; leaning (falling) forward ("prone"), i.e. head foremost: headlong.
  4148. prizo a strengthened form of a primary prio (to saw); to saw in two: saw asunder.
  4149. prin adverb from pro; prior, sooner: before (that), ere.
  4150. Priska of Latin origin; feminine of Priscus, ancient; Priska, a Christian woman: Prisca. See also Priscilla.
  4151. Priscilla diminutive of Priska; Priscilla (i.e. little Prisca), a Christian woman: Priscilla.
  4152. pro a primary preposition; "fore", i.e. in front of, prior (figuratively, superior) to: above, ago, before, or ever. In the comparative, it retains the same significations.
  4153. proago from pro and ago; to lead forward (magisterially); intransitively, to precede (in place or time (participle, previous)): bring (forth, out), go before.
  4154. proaireomai from pro and haireomai; to choose for oneself before another thing (prefer), i.e. (by implication) to propose (intend): purpose.
  4155. proaitiaomai from pro and a derivative of aitia; to accuse already, i.e. previously charge: prove before.
  4156. proakouo from pro and akouo; to hear already,i.e. anticipate: hear before.
  4157. proamartano from pro and hamartano; to sin previously (to conversion): sin already, heretofore sin.
  4158. proaulion neuter of a presumed compound of pro and aule; a forecourt, i.e. vestibule (alley-way): porch.
  4159. probaino from pro and the base of basis; to walk forward, i.e. advance (literally, or in years): + be of a great age, go farther (on), be well stricken.
  4160. proballo from pro and ballo; to throw forward, i.e. push to the front, germinate: put forward, shoot forth.
  4161. probatikos from probaton; relating to sheep, i.e. (a gate) through which they were led into Jerusalem: sheep (market).
  4162. probaton probably neuter of a presumed derivative of probaino; something that walks forward (a quadruped), i.e. (specially), a sheep (literally or figuratively): sheep(-fold).
  4163. probibazo from pro and a reduplicated form of biazo; to force forward, i.e. bring to the front, instigate: draw, before instruct.
  4164. problepo from pro and blepo; to look out beforehand, i.e. furnish in advance: provide.
  4165. proginomai from pro and ginomai; to be already, i.e. have previousy transpired: be past.
  4166. proginosko from pro and ginosko; to know beforehand, i.e. foresee: foreknow (ordain), know (before).
  4167. prognosis from proginosko; forethought: foreknowledge.
  4168. progonos from proginomai; an ancestor, (grand-)parent: forefather, parent.
  4169. prographo from pro and grapho; to write previously; figuratively, to announce, prescribe: before ordain, evidently set forth, write (afore, aforetime).
  4170. prodelos from pro and delos; plain before all men, i.e. obvious: evident, manifest (open) beforehand.
  4171. prodidomi from pro and didomi; to give before the other party has given: first give.
  4172. prodotes from prodidomi (in the sense of giving forward into another's (the enemy's) hands); a surrender: betrayer, traitor.
  4173. prodromos from the alternate of protrecho; a runner ahead, i.e. scout (figuratively, precursor): forerunner.
  4174. proeido from pro and eido; foresee: foresee, saw before.
  4175. proelpizo from pro and elpizo; to hope in advance of other confirmation: first trust.
  4176. proepo from pro and epo; to say already, to predict: forewarn, say (speak, tell) before. Compare proereo.
  4177. proenarchomai from pro and enarchomai; to commence already: begin (before).
  4178. proepaggellomai middle voice from pro and epaggello; to promise of old: promise before.
  4179. proereo from pro and ereo; used as alternate of proepo; to say already, predict: foretell, say (speak, tell) before.
  4180. proerchomai from pro and erchomai (including its alternate); to go onward, precede (in place or time): go before (farther, forward), outgo, pass on.
  4181. proetoimazo from pro and hetoimazo; to fit up in advance (literally or figuratively): ordain before, prepare afore.
  4182. proeuaggelizomai middle voice from pro and euaggelizo; to announce glad news in advance: preach before the gospel.
  4183. proechomai middle voice from pro and echo; to hold oneself before others, i.e. (figuratively) to excel: be better.
  4184. proegeomai from pro and hegeomai; to lead the way for others, i.e. show deference: prefer.
  4185. prothesis from protithemai; a setting forth, i.e. (figuratively) proposal (intention); specially, the show-bread (in the Temple) as exposed before God: purpose, shew(-bread).
  4186. prothesmios from pro and a derivative of tithemi; fixed beforehand, i.e. (feminine with hemera implied) a designated day: time appointed.
  4187. prothumia from prothumos; predisposition, i.e. alacrity: forwardness of mind, readiness (of mind), ready (willing) mind.
  4188. prothumos from pro and thumos; forward in spirit, i.e. predisposed; neuter (as noun) alacrity: ready, willing.
  4189. prothumos adverb from prothumos; with alacrity: willingly.
  4190. proistemi from pro and histemi; to stand before, i.e. (in rank) to preside, or (by implication) to practise: maintain, be over, rule.
  4191. prokaleomai middle voice from pro and kaleo; to call forth to oneself (challenge), i.e. (by implication) to irritate: provoke.
  4192. prokataggello from pro and kataggello; to anounce beforehand, i.e. predict, promise: foretell, have notice, (shew) before.
  4193. prokatartizo from pro and katartizo; to prepare in advance: make up beforehand.
  4194. prokeimai from pro and keimai; to lie before the view, i.e. (figuratively) to be present (to the mind), to stand forth (as an example or reward): be first, set before (forth).
  4195. prokerusso from pro and kerusso; to herald (i.e. proclaim) in advance: before (first) preach.
  4196. prokope from prokopto; progress, i.e. advancement (subjectively or objectively): furtherance, profit.
  4197. prokopto from pro and kopto; to drive forward (as if by beating), i.e. (figuratively and intransitively) to advance (in amount, to grow; in time, to be well along): increase, proceed, profit, be far spent, wax.
  4198. prokrima from a compound of pro and krino; a prejudgment (prejudice), i.e. prepossession: prefer one before another.
  4199. prokuroo from pro and kuroo; to ratify previously: confirm before.
  4200. prolambano from pro and lambano; to take in advance, i.e. (literally) eat before others have an opportunity; (figuratively) to anticipate, surprise: come aforehand, overtake, take before.
  4201. prolego from pro and lego; to say beforehand, i.e. predict, forewarn: foretell, tell before.
  4202. promarturomai from pro and marturomai; to be a witness in advance i.e. predict: testify beforehand.
  4203. promeletao from pro and meletao; to premeditate: meditate before.
  4204. promerimnao from pro and merimnao; to care (anxiously) in advance: take thought beforehand.
  4205. pronoeo from pro and noieo; to consider in advance, i.e. look out for beforehand (actively, by way of maintenance for others; middle voice by way of circumspection for oneself): provide (for).
  4206. pronoia from pronoeo; forethought, i.e. provident care or supply: providence, provision.
  4207. proorao from pro and horao; to behold in advance, i.e. (actively) to notice (another) previously, or (middle voice) to keep in (one's own) view: foresee, see before.
  4208. proorizo from pro and horizo; to limit in advance, i.e. (figuratively) predetermine: determine before, ordain, predestinate.
  4209. propascho from pro and pascho; to undergo hardship previously: suffer before.
  4210. propempo from pro and pempo; to send forward, i.e. escort or aid in travel: accompany, bring (forward) on journey (way), conduct forth.
  4211. propetes from a compound of pro and pipto; falling forward, i.e. headlong (figuratively, precipitate): heady, rash(-ly).
  4212. proporeuomai from pro and poreuomai; to precede (as guide or herald): go before.
  4213. pros a strengthened form of pro; a preposition of direction; forward to, i.e. toward (with the genitive case, the side of, i.e. pertaining to; with the dative case, by the side of, i.e. near to; usually with the accusative case, the place, time, occasion, or respect, which is the destination of the relation, i.e. whither or for which it is predicated): about, according to, against, among, at, because of, before, between, (where-)by, for, X at thy house, in, for intent, nigh unto, of, which pertain to, that, to (the end that), X together, to (you) -ward, unto, with(-in). In the comparative case, it denotes essentially the same applications, namely, motion towards, accession to, or nearness at.
  4214. prosabbaton from pro and sabbaton; a fore-sabbath, i.e. the Sabbath-eve: day before the sabbath. Compare paraskeue.
  4215. prosagoreuo from pros and a derivative of agora (mean to harangue); to address, i.e. salute by name: call.
  4216. prosago from pros and ago; to lead towards, i.e. (transitively) to conduct near (summon, present), or (intransitively) to approach: bring, draw near.
  4217. prosagoge from prosago (compare agoge); admission: access.
  4218. prosaiteo from pros and aiteo; to ask repeatedly (importune), i.e. solicit: beg.
  4219. prosanabaino from pros and anabaino; to ascend farther, i.e. be promoted (take an upper (more honorable) seat): go up.
  4220. prosanalisko from pros and analisko; to expend further: spend.
  4221. prosanapleroo from pros and anapleroo; to fill up further, i.e. furnish fully: supply.
  4222. prosanatithemi from pros and anatithemai; to lay up in addition, i.e. (middle voice and figuratively) to impart or (by implication) to consult: in conference add, confer.
  4223. prosapeileo from pros and apeileo; to menace additionally: i.e. threaten further.
  4224. prosdapanao from pros and dapanao; to expend additionally: spend more.
  4225. prosdeomai from pros and deomai; to require additionally, i.e. want further: need.
  4226. prosdechomai from pros and dechomai; to admit (to intercourse, hospitality, credence, or (figuratively) endurance); by implication, to await (with confidence or patience): accept, allow, look (wait) for, take.
  4227. prosdokao from pros and dokeuo (to watch); to anticipate (in thought, hope or fear); by implication, to await: (be in) expect(-ation), look (for), when looked, tarry, wait for.
  4228. prosdokia from prosdokao; apprehension (of evil); by implication, infliction anticipated: expectation, looking after.
  4229. proseao from pros and eao; to permit further progress: suffer.
  4230. proseggizo from pros and eggizo; to approach near: come nigh.
  4231. prosedreuo from a compound of pros and the base of hedraios; to sit near, i.e. attend as a servant: wait at.
  4232. prosergazomai from pros and ergazomai; to work additionally, i.e. (by implication) acquire besides: gain.
  4233. proserchomai from pros and erchomai (including its alternate); to approach, i.e. (literally) come near, visit, or (figuratively) worship, assent to: (as soon as he) come (unto), come thereunto, consent, draw near, go (near, to, unto).
  4234. proseuche from proseuchomai; prayer (worship); by implication, an oratory (chapel): X pray earnestly, prayer.
  4235. proseuchomai from pros and euchomai; to pray to God, i.e. supplicate, worship: pray (X earnestly, for), make prayer.
  4236. prosecho from pros and echo; (figuratively) to hold the mind (nous implied) towards, i.e. pay attention to, be cautious about, apply oneself to, adhere to: (give) attend(-ance, -ance at, -ance to, unto), beware, be given to, give (take) heed (to unto); have regard.
  4237. proseloo from pros and a derivative of helos; to peg to, i.e. spike fast: nail to.
  4238. proselutos from the alternate of proserchomai; an arriver from a foreign region, i.e. (specially), an acceder (convert) to Judaism ("proselyte"): proselyte.
  4239. proskairos from pros and kairos; for the occasion only, i.e. temporary: dur-(eth) for awhile, endure for a time, for a season, temporal.
  4240. proskaleomai middle voice from pros and kaleo; to call toward oneself, i.e. summon, invite: call (for, to, unto).
  4241. proskartereo from pros and kartereo; to be earnest towards, i.e. (to a thing) to persevere, be constantly diligent, or (in a place) to attend assiduously all the exercises, or (to a person) to adhere closely to (as a servitor): attend (give self) continually (upon), continue (in, instant in, with), wait on (continually).
  4242. proskarteresis from proskartereo; persistancy: perseverance.
  4243. proskephalaion neuter of a presumed compound of pros and kephale; something for the head, i.e. a cushion: pillow.
  4244. proskleroo from pros and kleroo; to give a common lot to, i.e. (figuratively) to associate with: consort with.
  4245. prosklisis from a compound of pros and klino; a leaning towards, i.e. (figuratively) proclivity (favoritism): partiality.
  4246. proskollao from pros and kollao; to glue to, i.e. (figuratively) to adhere: cleave, join (self).
  4247. proskomma from proskopto; a stub, i.e. (figuratively) occasion of apostasy: offence, stumbling(-block, (-stone)).
  4248. proskope from proskopto; a stumbling, i.e. (figuratively and concretely) occasion of sin: offence.
  4249. proskopto from pros and kopto; to strike at, i.e. surge against (as water); specially, to stub on, i.e. trip up (literally or figuratively): beat upon, dash, stumble (at).
  4250. proskulio from pros and kulioo; to roll towards, i.e. block against: roll (to).
  4251. proskuneo from pros and a probable derivative of kuon (meaning to kiss, like a dog licking his master's hand); to fawn or crouch to, i.e. (literally or figuratively) prostrate oneself in homage (do reverence to, adore): worship.
  4252. proskunetes from proskuneo; an adorer: worshipper.
  4253. proslaleo from pros and laleo; to talk to, i.e. converse with: speak to (with).
  4254. proslambano from pros and lambano; to take to oneself, i.e. use (food), lead (aside), admit (to friendship or hospitality): receive, take (unto).
  4255. proslepsis from proslambano; admission: receiving.
  4256. prosmeno from pros and meno; to stay further, i.e. remain in a place, with a person; figuratively, to adhere to, persevere in: abide still, be with, cleave unto, continue in (with).
  4257. prosormizo from pros and a derivative of the same as horme (meaning to tie (anchor) or lull); to moor to, i.e. (by implication) land at: draw to the shore.
  4258. prosopheilo from pros and opheilo; to be indebted additionally: over besides.
  4259. prosochthizo from pros and a form of ochtheo (to be vexed with something irksome); to feel indignant at: be grieved at.
  4260. prospeinos from pros and the same as peinao; hungering further, i.e. intensely hungry: very hungry.
  4261. prospegnumi from pros and pegnumi; to fasten to, i.e. (specially), to impale (on a cross): crucify.
  4262. prospipto from pros and pipto; to fall towards, i.e. (gently) prostrate oneself (in supplication or homage), or (violently) to rush upon (in storm): beat upon, fall (down) at (before).
  4263. prospoieomai middle voice from pros and poieo; to do forward for oneself, i.e. pretend (as if about to do a thing): make as though.
  4264. prosporeuomai from pros and poreuomai; to journey towards, i.e. approach (not the same as proporeuomai): go before.
  4265. prosregnumi from pros and rhegnumi; to tear towards, i.e. burst upon (as a tempest or flood): beat vehemently against (upon).
  4266. prostasso from pros and tasso; to arrange towards, i.e. (figuratively) enjoin: bid, command.
  4267. prostatis feminine of a derivative of proistemi; a patroness, i.e. assistant: succourer.
  4268. prostithemi from pros and tithemi; to place additionally, i.e. lay beside, annex, repeat: add, again, give more, increase, lay unto, proceed further, speak to any more.
  4269. prostrecho from pros and trecho (including its alternate); to run towards, i.e. hasten to meet or join: run (thither to, to).
  4270. prosphagion neuter of a presumed derivative of a compound of pros and phago; something eaten in addition to bread, i.e. a relish (specially, fish; compare opsarion): meat.
  4271. prosphatos from pro and a derivative of sphazo; previously (recently) slain (fresh), i.e. (figuratively) lately made: new.
  4272. prosphatos adverb from prosphatos; recently: lately.
  4273. prosphero from pros and phero (including its alternate); to bear towards, i.e. lead to, tender (especially to God), treat: bring (to, unto), deal with, do, offer (unto, up), present unto, put to.
  4274. prosphiles from a presumed compound of pros and phileo; friendly towards, i.e. acceptable: lovely.
  4275. prosphora from prosphero; presentation; concretely, an oblation (bloodless) or sacrifice: offering (up).
  4276. prosphoneo from pros and phoneo; to sound towards, i.e. address, exclaim, summon: call unto, speak (un-)to.
  4277. proschusis from a comparative of pros and cheo (to pour); a shedding forth, i.e. affusion: sprinkling.
  4278. prospsauo from pros and psauo (to touch); to impinge, i.e. lay a finger on (in order to relieve): touch.
  4279. prosopolepteo from prosopoleptes; to favor an individual, i.e. show partiality: have respect to persons.
  4280. prosopoleptes from prosopon and lambano; an accepter of a face (individual), i.e. (specially), one exhibiting partiality: respecter of persons.
  4281. prosopolepsia from prosopoleptes; partiality, i.e. favoritism: respect of persons.
  4282. prosopon from pros and ops (the visage, from optanomai); the front (as being towards view), i.e. the countenance, aspect, appearance, surface; by implication, presence, person: (outward) appearance, X before, countenance, face, fashion, (men's) person, presence.
  4283. protasso from pro and tasso; to pre-arrange, i.e. prescribe: before appoint.
  4284. proteino from pro and teino (to stretch); to protend, i.e. tie prostrate (for scourging): bind.
  4285. proteron neuter of proteros as adverb (with or without the article); previously: before, (at the) first, former.
  4286. proteros comparative of pro; prior or previous: former.
  4287. protithemai middle voice from pro and tithemi; to place before, i.e. (for oneself) to exhibit; (to oneself) to propose (determine): purpose, set forth.
  4288. protrepomai middle voice from pro and the base of trope; to turn forward for oneself, i.e. encourage: exhort.
  4289. protrecho from pro and trecho (including its alternate); to run forward, i.e. outstrip, precede: outrun, run before.
  4290. prouparcho from pro and huparcho; to exist before, i.e. (adverbially) to be or do something previously: + be before(-time).
  4291. prophasis from a compound of pro and phaino; an outward showing, i.e. pretext: cloke, colour, pretence, show.
  4292. prophero from pro and phero; to bear forward, i.e. produce: bring forth.
  4293. propheteia from prophetes ("prophecy"); prediction (scriptural or other): prophecy, prophesying.
  4294. propheteuo from prophetes; to foretell events, divine, speak under inspiration, exercise the prophetic office: prophesy.
  4295. prophetes from a compound of pro and phemi; a foreteller ("prophet"); by analogy, an inspired speaker; by extension, a poet: prophet.
  4296. prophetikos from prophetes; pertaining to a foreteller ("prophetic"): of prophecy, of the prophets.
  4297. prophetis feminine of prophetes; a female foreteller or an inspired woman: prophetess.
  4298. prophthano from pro and phthano; to get an earlier start of, i.e. anticipate: prevent.
  4299. procheirizomai middle voice from pro and a derivative of cheir; to handle for oneself in advance, i.e. (figuratively) to purpose: choose, make.
  4300. procheirotoneo from pro and cheirotoneo; to elect in advance: choose before.
  4301. Prochoros from pro and choros; before the dance; Prochorus, a Christian: Prochorus.
  4302. prumna feminine of prumnus (hindmost); the stern of a ship: hinder part, stern.
  4303. proi adverb from pro; at dawn; by implication, the day-break watch: early (in the morning), (in the) morning.
  4304. proia feminine of a derivative of proi as noun; day-dawn: early, morning.
  4305. proimos from proi; dawning, i.e. (by analogy) autumnal (showering, the first of the rainy season): early.
  4306. proinos from proi; pertaining to the dawn, i.e. matutinal: morning.
  4307. prora feminine of a presumed derivative of pro as noun; the prow, i.e. forward part of a vessel: forepart(-ship).
  4308. proteuo from protos; to be first (in rank or influence): have the preeminence.
  4309. protokathedria from protos and kathedra; a sitting first (in the front row), i.e. preeminence in council: chief (highest, uppermost) seat.
  4310. protoklisia from protos and klisia; a reclining first (in the place of honor) at the dinner-bed, i.e. preeminence at meals: chief (highest, uppermost) room.
  4311. proton neuter of protos as adverb (with or without ho); firstly (in time, place, order, or importance): before, at the beginning, chiefly (at, at the) first (of all).
  4312. protos contracted superlative of pro; foremost (in time, place, order or importance): before, beginning, best, chief(-est), first (of all), former.
  4313. protostates from protos and histemi; one standing first in the ranks, i.e. a captain (champion): ringleader.
  4314. prototokia from prototokos; primogeniture (as a privilege): birthright.
  4315. prototokos from protos and the alternate of tikto; first-born (usually as noun, literally or figuratively): firstbegotten(-born).
  4316. ptaio a form of pipto; to trip, i.e. (figuratively) to err, sin, fail (of salvation): fall, offend, stumble.
  4317. pterna of uncertain derivation; the heel (figuratively): heel.
  4318. pterugion neuter of a presumed derivative of pterux; a winglet, i.e. (figuratively) extremity (top corner): pinnacle.
  4319. pterux from a derivative of petomai (meaning a feather); a wing: wing.
  4320. ptenon contraction for peteinon; a bird: bird.
  4321. ptoeo probably akin to the alternate of pipto (through the idea of causing to fall) or to petomai (through that of causing to fly away); to scare: frighten.
  4322. ptoesis from ptoeo; alarm: amazement.
  4323. Ptolemais from Ptolemaios (Ptolemy, after whom it was named); Ptolemais, a place in Palestine: Ptolemais.
  4324. ptuon from ptuo; a winnowing-fork (as scattering like spittle): fan.
  4325. pturo from a presumed derivative of ptuo (and thus akin to ptoeo); to frighten: terrify.
  4326. ptusma from ptuo; saliva: spittle.
  4327. ptusso probably akin to petannumi (to spread; and thus apparently allied to petomai through the idea of expansion, and to ptuo through that of flattening; compare pateo); to fold, i.e. furl a scroll: close.
  4328. ptuo a primary verb (compare ptusso); to spit: spit.
  4329. ptoma from the alternate of pipto; a ruin, i.e. (specially), lifeless body (corpse, carrion): dead body, carcase, corpse.
  4330. ptosis from the alternate of pipto; a crash, i.e. downfall (literally or figuratively): fall.
  4331. ptocheia from ptocheuo; beggary, i.e. indigence (literally or figuratively): poverty.
  4332. ptocheuo from ptochos; to be a beggar, i.e. (by implication) to become indigent (figuratively): become poor.
  4333. ptochos from ptosso (to crouch); akin to ptoeo and the alternate of pipto); a beggar (as cringing), i.e. pauper (strictly denoting absolute or public mendicancy, although also used in a qualified or relative sense; whereas penes properly means only straitened circumstances in private), literally (often as noun) or figuratively (distressed): beggar(-ly), poor.
  4334. pugme from a primary pux (the fist as a weapon); the clenched hand, i.e. (only in dative case as adverb) with the fist (hard scrubbing): oft.
  4335. Puthon from Putho (the name of the region where Delphi, the seat of the famous oracle, was located); a Python, i.e. (by analogy, with the supposed diviner there) inspiration (soothsaying): divination.
  4336. puknos from the same as skenopoios; clasped (thick), i.e. (figuratively) frequent; neuter plural (as adverb) frequently: often(-er).
  4337. pukteo from a derivative of the same as pugme; to box (with the fist), i.e. contend (as a boxer) at the games (figuratively): fight.
  4338. pule apparently a primary word; a gate, i.e. the leaf or wing of a folding entrance (literally or figuratively): gate.
  4339. pulon from pule; a gate-way, door-way of a building or city; by implication, a portal or vestibule: gate, porch.
  4340. punthanomai middle voice prolonged from a primary putho (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); to question, i.e. ascertain by inquiry (as a matter of information merely; and thus differing from erotao, which properly means a request as a favor; and from aiteo, which is strictly a demand for something due; as well as from zeteo, which implies a search for something hidden; and from deomai, which involves the idea of urgent need); by implication, to learn (by casual intelligence): ask, demand, enquire, understand.
  4341. pur a primary word; "fire" (literally or figuratively, specially, lightning): fiery, fire.
  4342. pura from pur; a fire (concretely): fire.
  4343. purgos apparently a primary word ("burgh"); a tower or castle: tower.
  4344. puresso from pura; to be on fire, i.e. (specially), to have a fever: be sick of a fever.
  4345. puretos from puresso; inflamed, i.e. (by implication) feverish (as noun, fever): fever.
  4346. purinos from pura; fiery, i.e. (by implication) flaming: of fire.
  4347. puroo from pur; to kindle, i.e. (passively) to be ignited, glow (literally), be refined (by implication), or (figuratively) to be inflamed (with anger, grief, lust): burn, fiery, be on fire, try.
  4348. purrhazo from purrhos; to redden (intransitively): be red.
  4349. purrhos from pur; fire-like, i.e. (specially), flame- colored: red.
  4350. purosis from puroo; ignition, i.e. (specially), smelting (figuratively, conflagration, calamity as a test): burning, trial.
  4351. po another form of the base of pos; an enclitic particle of indefiniteness; yet, even; used only in the comparative. See medepo, mepo, oudepo, oupo, popote.
  4352. poleo probably ultimately from pelomai (to be busy, to trade); to barter (as a pedlar), i.e. to sell: sell, whatever is sold.
  4353. polos apparently a primary word; a "foal" or "filly", i.e. (specially), a young ass: colt.
  4354. popote from po and pote; at any time, i.e. (with negative particle) at no time: at any time, + never (to any man), + yet, never man.
  4355. poroo apparently from poros (a kind of stone); to petrify, i.e. (figuratively) to indurate (render stupid or callous): blind, harden.
  4356. porosis from poroo; stupidity or callousness: blindness, hardness.
  4357. pos adverb from the base of pou; an enclitic particle of indefiniteness of manner; somehow or anyhow; used only in composition: haply, by any (some) means, perhaps. See ei pos, mepos. Compare pos.
  4358. pos adverb from the base of pou; an interrogative particle of manner; in what way? (sometimes the question is indirect, how?); also as exclamation, how much!: how, after (by) what manner (means), that. (Occasionally unexpressed in English).
  4359. Rhaab of Hebrew origin (Rachab); Raab (i.e. Rachab), a Canaanitess: Rahab. See also Rhachab.
  4360. rhabbi of Hebrew origin (rab with pronominal suffix); my master, i.e Rabbi, as an official title of honor: Master, Rabbi.
  4361. rhabboni, or rhabbouni of Chaldee origin; corresponding to rhabbi: Lord, Rabboni.
  4362. rhabdizo from rhabdos; to strike with a stick, i.e. bastinado: beat (with rods).
  4363. rhabdos from the base of rhapizo; a stick or wand (as a cudgel, a cane or a baton of royalty): rod, sceptre, staff.
  4364. rhabdouchos from rhabdos and echo; a rod- (the Latin fasces) holder, i.e. a Roman lictor (constable or executioner): serjeant.
  4365. Rhagau of Hebrew origin (R`uw); Ragau (i.e. Reu), a patriarch: Ragau.
  4366. rhaidiourgema from a comparative of rhaidios (easy, i.e. reckless) and ergon; easy-going behavior, i.e. (by extension) a crime: lewdness.
  4367. rhaidiourgia from the same as rhaidiourgema; recklessness, i.e. (by extension) malignity: mischief.
  4368. rhaka of Chaldee origin (compare reyq); O empty one, i.e. thou worthless (as a term of utter vilification): Raca.
  4369. rhakos from rhegnumi; a "rag," i.e. piece of cloth: cloth.
  4370. Rhama of Hebrew origin (Ramah); Rama (i.e. Ramah), a place in Palestine: Rama.
  4371. rhantizo from a derivative of rhaino (to sprinkle); to render besprinkled, i.e. asperse (ceremonially or figuratively): sprinkle.
  4372. rhantismos from rhantizo; aspersion (ceremonially or figuratively): sprinkling.
  4373. rhapizo from a derivative of a primary rhepo (to let fall, "rap"); to slap: smite (with the palm of the hand). Compare tupto.
  4374. rhapisma from rhapizo; a slap: (+ strike with the) palm of the hand, smite with the hand.
  4375. rhaphis from a primary rhapto (to sew; perhaps rather akin to the base of rhapizo through the idea of puncturing); a needle: needle.
  4376. Rhachab from the same as Rhaab; Rachab, a Canaanitess: Rachab.
  4377. Rhachel of Hebrew origin (Rachel); Rachel, the wife of Jacob: Rachel.
  4378. Rhebekka of Hebrew origin (Ribqah); Rebecca (i.e. Ribkah), the wife of Isaac: Rebecca.
  4379. rheda of Latin origin; a rheda, i.e. four-wheeled carriage (wagon for riding): chariot.
  4380. Rhemphan by incorrect transliteration for a word of Hebrew origin (Kiyuwn); Remphan (i.e. Kijun), an Egyptian idol: Remphan.
  4381. rheo a primary verb; for some tenses of which a prolonged form rheuo is used; to flow ("run"; as water): flow.
  4382. rheo, for certain tenses of which a prolonged form ereo is used; and both as alternate for epo perhaps akin (or identical) with rheo (through the idea of pouring forth); to utter, i.e. speak or say: command, make, say, speak (of). Compare lego.
  4383. Rhegion of Latin origin; Rhegium, a place in Italy: Rhegium.
  4384. rhegma from rhegnumi; something torn, i.e. a fragment (by implication and abstractly, a fall): ruin.
  4385. rhegnumi or rhesso both prolonged forms of rheko (which appears only in certain forms, and is itself probably a strengthened form of agnumi (see in katagnumi)) to "break," "wreck" or "crack", i.e. (especially) to sunder (by separation of the parts; katagnumi being its intensive (with the preposition in composition), and thrauo a shattering to minute fragments; but not a reduction to the constituent particles, like luo) or disrupt, lacerate; by implication, to convulse (with spasms); figuratively, to give vent to joyful emotions: break (forth), burst, rend, tear.
  4386. rhema from rheo; an utterance (individually, collectively or specially),; by implication, a matter or topic (especially of narration, command or dispute); with a negative naught whatever: + evil, + nothing, saying, word.
  4387. Rhesa probably of Hebrew origin (apparently for Rphayah); Resa (i.e. Rephajah), an Israelite: Rhesa.
  4388. rhetor from rheo; a speaker, i.e. (by implication) a forensic advocate: orator.
  4389. rhetos adverb from a derivative of rheo; out-spokenly, i.e. distinctly: expressly.
  4390. rhiza apparently a primary word; a "root" (literally or figuratively): root.
  4391. rhizoo from rhiza; to root (figuratively, become stable): root.
  4392. rhipe from rhipto; a jerk (of the eye, i.e. (by analogy) an instant): twinkling.
  4393. rhipizo from a derivative of rhipto (meaning a fan or bellows); to breeze up, i.e. (by analogy) to agitate (into waves): toss.
  4394. rhipteo from a derivative of rhipto; to toss up: cast off.
  4395. rhipto a primary verb (perhaps rather akin to the base of rhapizo, through the idea of sudden motion); to fling (properly, with a quick toss, thus differing from ballo, which denotes a deliberate hurl; and from teino (see in ekteino), which indicates an extended projection); by qualification, to deposit (as if a load); by extension, to disperse: cast (down, out), scatter abroad, throw.
  4396. Rhoboam of Hebrew origin (Rchab`am); Roboam (i.e. Rechobam), an Israelite: Roboam.
  4397. Rhode probably for rhode (a rose); Rode, a servant girl: Rhoda.
  4398. Rhodos probably from rhodon (a rose); Rhodus, an island of the Mediterranean: Rhodes.
  4399. rhoizedon adverb from a derivative of rhoizos (a whir); whizzingly, i.e. with a crash: with a great noise.
  4400. rhomphaia probably of foreign origin; a sabre, i.e. a long and broad cutlass (any weapon of the kind, literally or figuratively): sword.
  4401. Rhouben of Hebrew origin (R'uwben); Ruben (i.e. Reuben), an Israelite: Reuben.
  4402. Rhouth of Hebrew origin (Ruwth); Ruth, a Moabitess: Ruth.
  4403. Rhouphos of Latin origin; red; Rufus, a Christian: Rufus.
  4404. rhume prolongation from rhoumai in its original sense; an alley or avenue (as crowded): lane, street.
  4405. rhoumai middle voice of an obsolete verb, akin to rheo (through the idea of a current; compare rhusis); to rush or draw (for oneself), i.e. rescue: deliver(-er).
  4406. rhuparia from rhuparos; dirtiness (morally): turpitude.
  4407. rhuparos from rhupos; dirty, i.e. (relatively) cheap or shabby; morally, wicked: vile.
  4408. rhupos of uncertain affinity; dirt, i.e. (morally) depravity: filth.
  4409. rhupoo from rhupos; to soil, i.e. (intransitively) to become dirty (morally): be filthy.
  4410. rhusis from rhoumai in the sense of its congener rheo; a flux (of blood): issue.
  4411. rhutis from rhoumai; a fold (as drawing together), i.e. a wrinkle (especially on the face): wrinkle.
  4412. Rhomaikos from Rhomaios; Romaic, i.e. Latin: Latin.
  4413. Rhomaios from Rhome; Roman, i.e. Roman (as noun): Roman, of Rome.
  4414. Rhomaisti adverb from a presumed derivative of Rhome; Romaistically, i.e. in the Latin language: Latin.
  4415. Rhome from the base of rhonnumi; strength; Roma, the capital of Italy: Rome.
  4416. rhonnumi prolongation from rhoomai (to dart; probably akin to rhoumai); to strengthen, i.e. (impersonal passive) have health (as a parting exclamation, good-bye): farewell.
  4417. sabachthani of Chaldee or (shbaq with pronominal suffix); thou hast left me; sabachthani (i.e. shebakthani), a cry of distress: sabachthani.
  4418. sabaoth of Hebrew origin (tsaba' in feminine plural); armies; sabaoth (i.e. tsebaoth), a military epithet of God: sabaoth.
  4419. sabbatismos from a derivative of sabbaton; a "sabbatism", i.e. (figuratively) the repose of Christianity (as a type of heaven): rest.
  4420. sabbaton of Hebrew origin (shabbath); the Sabbath (i.e. Shabbath), or day of weekly repose from secular avocations (also the observance or institution itself); by extension, a se'nnight, i.e. the interval between two Sabbaths; likewise the plural in all the above applications: sabbath (day), week.
  4421. sagene from a derivative of satto (to equip) meaning furniture, especially a pack-saddle (which in the East is merely a bag of netted rope); a "seine" for fishing: net.
  4422. Saddoukaios probably from Sadok; a Sadducan (i.e. Tsadokian), or follower of a certain heretical Israelite: Sadducee.
  4423. Sadok of Hebrew origin (Tsadowq); Sadoc (i.e. Tsadok), an Israelite: Sadoc.
  4424. saino akin to seio; to wag (as a dog its tail fawningly), i.e. (generally) to shake (figuratively, disturb): move.
  4425. sakkos of Hebrew origin (saq); "sack"-cloth, i.e. mohair (the material or garments made of it, worn as a sign of grief): sackcloth.
  4426. Sala of Hebrew origin (Shelach); Sala (i.e. Shelach), a patriarch : Sala.
  4427. Salathiel of Hebrew origin (Sh'altiy'el); Salathiel (i.e. Shealtiel), an Israelite: Salathiel.
  4428. Salamis probably from salos (from the surge on the shore); Salamis, a place in Cyprus: Salamis.
  4429. Saleim probably from the same as saleuo; Salim, a place in Palestine: Salim.
  4430. saleuo from salos; to waver, i.e. agitate, rock, topple or (by implication) destroy; figuratively, to disturb, incite: move, shake (together), which can(-not) be shaken, stir up.
  4431. Salem of Hebrew origin (Shalem); Salem (i.e. Shalem), a place in Palestine: Salem.
  4432. Salmon of Hebrew origin (Salmown); Salmon, an Israelite: Salmon.
  4433. Salmone perhaps of similar origin to Salamis; Salmone, a place in Crete: Salmone.
  4434. salos probably from the base of saino; a vibration, i.e. (specially), billow: wave.
  4435. salpigx perhaps from salos (through the idea of quavering or reverberation); a trumpet: trump(-et).
  4436. salpizo from salpigx; to trumpet, i.e. sound a blast (literally or figuratively): (which are yet to) sound (a trumpet).
  4437. salpistes from salpizo; a trumpeter: trumpeter.
  4438. Salome probably of Hebrew origin (feminine from shalowm); Salome (i.e. Shelomah), an Israelitess: Salome.
  4439. Samareia of Hebrew origin (Shomrown); Samaria (i.e. Shomeron), a city and region of Palestine: Samaria.
  4440. Samareites from Samareia; a Samarite, i.e. inhabitant of Samaria: Samaritan.
  4441. Samareitis feminine of Samareites; a Samaritess, i.e. woman of Samaria: of Samaria.
  4442. Samothraike from Samos and Thraike (Thrace); Samo-thrace (Samos of Thrace), an island in the Mediterranean: Samothracia.
  4443. Samos of uncertain affinity; Samus, an island of the Mediterranean: Samos.
  4444. Samouel of Hebrew origin (Shmuw'el); Samuel (i.e. Shemuel), an Israelite: Samuel.
  4445. Sampson of Hebrew origin (Shimshown); Sampson (i.e. Shimshon), an Israelite: Samson.
  4446. sandalion neuter of a derivative of sandalon (a "sandal"; of uncertain origin); a slipper or sole-pad: sandal.
  4447. sanis of uncertain affinity; a plank: board.
  4448. Saoul of Hebrew origin (Sha'uwl); Saul (i.e. Shaul), the Jewish name of Paul: Saul. Compare Saulos.
  4449. sapros from sepo; rotten, i.e. worthless (literally or morally): bad, corrupt. Compare poneros.
  4450. Sappheire feminine of sappheiros; Sapphire, an Israelitess: Sapphira.
  4451. sappheiros of Hebrew origin (cappiyr); a "sapphire" or lapis-lazuli gem: sapphire.
  4452. sargane apparently of Hebrew origin (sarag); a basket (as interwoven or wicker-work: basket.
  4453. Sardeis plural of uncertain derivation; Sardis, a place in Asia Minor: Sardis.
  4454. sardinos from the same as sardios; sardine (lithos being implied), i.e. a gem, so called: sardine.
  4455. sardios properly, an adjective from an uncertain base; sardian (lithos being implied), i.e. (as noun) the gem so called: sardius.
  4456. sardonux from the base of sardios and onux (the nail of a finger; hence the "onyx" stone); a "sardonyx", i.e. the gem so called: sardonyx.
  4457. Sarepta of Hebrew origin (Tsarphath); Sarepta (i.e. Tsarephath), a place in Palestine: Sarepta.
  4458. sarkikos from sarx; pertaining to flesh, i.e. (by extension) bodily, temporal, or (by implication) animal, unregenerate: carnal, fleshly.
  4459. sarkinos from sarx; similar to flesh, i.e. (by analogy) soft: fleshly.
  4460. sarx probably from the base of saroo; flesh (as stripped of the skin), i.e. (strictly) the meat of an animal (as food), or (by extension) the body (as opposed to the soul (or spirit), or as the symbol of what is external, or as the means of kindred), or (by implication) human nature (with its frailties (physically or morally) and passions), or (specially), a human being (as such): carnal(-ly, + -ly minded), flesh(-ly).
  4461. Sarouch of Hebrew origin (Sruwg); Saruch (i.e. Serug), a patriarch: Saruch.
  4462. saroo from a derivative of sairo (to brush off; akin to suro); meaning a broom; to sweep: sweep.
  4463. Sarrha of Hebrew origin (Sarah); Sarra (i.e. Sarah), the wife of Abraham: Sara, Sarah.
  4464. Saron of Hebrew origin (Sharown); Saron (i.e. Sharon), a district of Palestine: Saron.
  4465. Satan of Hebrew origin (satan); Satan, i.e. the devil: Satan. Compare Satanas.
  4466. Satanas of Chaldee origin corresponding to ma`bad (with the definite affix); the accuser, i.e. the devil: Satan.
  4467. saton of Hebrew origin (c'ah); a certain measure for things dry: measure.
  4468. Saulos of Hebrew origin, the same as Saoul; Saulus (i.e. Shaul), the Jewish name of Paul: Saul.
  4469. sbennumi a prolonged form of an apparently primary verb; to extinguish (literally or figuratively): go out, quench.
  4470. se accusative case singular of su; thee: thee, thou, X thy house.
  4471. seautou, genitive case from se and autos, also dative case of the same, seautoi, and accusative case seauton, likewise contracted sautou, sautoi, and sauton, respectively; of (with, to) thyself: thee, thine own self, (thou) thy(-self).
  4472. sebazomai middle voice from a derivative of sebomai; to venerate, i.e. adore: worship.
  4473. sebasma from sebazomai; something adored, i.e. an object of worship (god, altar, etc): devotion, that is worshipped.
  4474. sebastos from sebazomai; venerable (august), i.e. (as noun) a title of the Roman Emperor, or (as adjective) imperial: Augustus(-').
  4475. sebomai middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to revere, i.e. adore: devout, religious, worship.
  4476. seira probably from suro through its congener eiro (to fasten; akin to haireomai); a chain (as binding or drawing): chain.
  4477. seismos from seio; a commotion, i.e. (of the air) a gale, (of the ground) an earthquake: earthquake, tempest.
  4478. seio apparently a primary verb; to rock (vibrate, properly, sideways or to and fro), i.e. (generally) to agitate (in any direction; cause to tremble); figuratively, to throw into a tremor (of fear or concern): move, quake, shake.
  4479. Sekoundos of Latin origin; "second"; Secundus, a Christian: Secundus.
  4480. Seleukeia from Seleukos (Seleucus, a Syrian king); Seleuceia, a place in Syria: Seleucia.
  4481. selene from selas (brilliancy; probably akin to the alternate of haireomai, through the idea of attractiveness); the moon: moon.
  4482. seleniazomai middle voice or passive from a presumed derivative of selene; to be moon-struck, i.e. crazy: be a lunatic.
  4483. Semei of Hebrew origin (Shim`iy); Semei (i.e. Shimi), an Israelite: Semei.
  4484. semidalis probably of foreign origin; fine wheaten flour: fine flour.
  4485. semnos from sebomai; venerable, i.e. honorable: grave, honest.
  4486. semnotes from semnos; venerableness, i.e. probity: gravity, honesty.
  4487. Sergios of Latin origin; Sergius, a Roman: Sergius.
  4488. Seth of Hebrew origin (Sheth); Seth (i.e. Sheth), a patriarch: Seth.
  4489. Sem of Hebrew origin (Shem); Sem (i.e. Shem), a patriarch: Sem.
  4490. semaino from sema (a mark; of uncertain derivation); to indicate: signify.
  4491. semeion neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of semaino; an indication, especially ceremonially or supernaturally: miracle, sign, token, wonder.
  4492. semeioo from semeion; to distinguish, i.e. mark (for avoidance): note.
  4493. semeron neuter (as adverb) of a presumed compound of the article ho (t changed to s) and hemera; on the (i.e. this) day (or night current or just passed); generally, now (i.e. at present, hitherto): this (to-)day.
  4494. sepo apparently a primary verb; to putrefy, i.e. (figuratively) perish: be corrupted.
  4495. serikos from Ser (an Indian tribe from whom silk was procured; hence the name of the silk-worm); Seric, i.e. silken (neuter as noun, a silky fabric): silk.
  4496. ses apparently of Hebrew origin (cac); a moth: moth.
  4497. setobrotos from ses and a derivative of bibrosko; moth-eaten: motheaten.
  4498. sthenoo from sthenos (bodily vigor; probably akin to the base of histemi); to strengthen, i.e. (figuratively) confirm (in spiritual knowledge and power): strengthen.
  4499. siagon of uncertain derivation; the jaw-bone, i.e. (by implication) the cheek or side of the face: cheek.
  4500. sigao from sige; to keep silent (transitively or intransitively): keep close (secret, silence), hold peace.
  4501. sige apparently from sizo (to hiss, i.e. hist or hush); silence: silence. Compare siopao.
  4502. sidereos from sideros; made of iron: (of) iron.
  4503. sideros of uncertain derivation; iron: iron.
  4504. Sidon of Hebrew origin (Tsiydown); Sidon (i.e. Tsidon), a place in Palestine: Sidon.
  4505. Sidonios from Sidon; a Sidonian, i.e. inhabitant of Sidon: of Sidon.
  4506. sikarios of Latin origin; a dagger-man or assassin; a freebooter (Jewish fanatic outlawed by the Romans): murderer. Compare phoneus.
  4507. sikera of Hebrew origin (shekar); an intoxicant, i.e. intensely fermented liquor: strong drink.
  4508. Silas contraction for Silouanos; Silas, a Christian: Silas.
  4509. Silouanos of Latin origin; "silvan"; Silvanus, a Christian: Silvanus. Compare Silas.
  4510. Siloam of Hebrew origin (Shiloach); Siloam (i.e. Shiloach), a pool of Jerusalem: Siloam.
  4511. simikinthion of Latin origin; a semicinctium or half-girding, i.e. narrow covering (apron): apron.
  4512. Simon of Hebrew origin (Shim`own); Simon (i.e. Shimon), the name of nine Israelites: Simon. Compare Sumeon.
  4513. Sina of Hebrew origin (Ciynay); Sina (i.e. Sinai), a mountain in Arabia: Sina.
  4514. sinapi perhaps from sinomai (to hurt, i.e. sting); mustard (the plant): mustard.
  4515. sindon of uncertain (perhaps foreign) origin; byssos, i.e. bleached linen (the cloth or a garment of it): (fine) linen (cloth).
  4516. siniazo from sinion (a sieve); to riddle (figuratively): sift.
  4517. siteutos from a derivative of sitos; grain-fed, i.e. fattened: fatted.
  4518. sitistos from a derivative of sitos; grained, i.e. fatted: fatling.
  4519. sitometron from sitos and metron; a grain-measure, i.e. (by implication) ration (allowance of food): portion of meat.
  4520. sitos, also plural irregular neuter sita of uncertain derivation; grain, especially wheat: corn, wheat.
  4521. Sion of Hebrew origin (Tsiyown); Sion (i.e. Tsijon), a hill of Jerusalem; figuratively, the Church (militant or triumphant): Sion.
  4522. siopao from siope (silence, i.e. a hush; properly, muteness, i.e. involuntary stillness, or inability to speak; and thus differing from sige, which is rather a voluntary refusal or indisposition to speak, although the terms are often used synonymously); to be dumb (but not deaf also, like kophos properly); figuratively, to be calm (as quiet water): dumb, (hold) peace.
  4523. skandalizo from skandalon; to entrap, i.e. trip up (figuratively, stumble (transitively) or entice to sin, apostasy or displeasure): (make to) offend.
  4524. skandalon ("scandal"); probably from a derivative of kampto; a trap-stick (bent sapling), i.e. snare (figuratively, cause of displeasure or sin): occasion to fall (of stumbling), offence, thing that offends, stumblingblock.
  4525. skapto apparently a primary verb; to dig: dig.
  4526. skaphe a "skiff" (as if dug out), or yawl (carried aboard a large vessel for landing): boat.
  4527. skelos apparently from skello (to parch; through the idea of leanness); the leg (as lank): leg.
  4528. skepasma from a derivative of skepas (a covering; perhaps akin to the base of skopos through the idea of noticeableness); clothing: raiment.
  4529. Skeuas apparently of Latin origin; left-handed; Scevas (i.e. Scvus), an Israelite: Sceva.
  4530. skeue from skeuos; furniture, i.e. spare tackle: tackling.
  4531. skeuos of uncertain affinity; a vessel, implement, equipment or apparatus (literally or figuratively [specially, a wife as contributing to the usefulness of the husband]): goods, sail, stuff, vessel.
  4532. skene apparently akin to skeuos and skia; a tent or cloth hut (literally or figuratively): habitation, tabernacle.
  4533. skenopegia from skenos and pegnumi; the Festival of Tabernacles (so called from the custom of erecting booths for temporary homes): tabernacles.
  4534. skenopoios from skene and poieo; a manufacturer of tents: tent-maker.
  4535. skenos from skene; a hut or temporary residence, i.e. (figuratively) the human body (as the abode of the spirit): tabernacle.
  4536. skenoo from skenos; to tent or encamp, i.e. (figuratively) to occupy (as a mansion) or (specially), to reside (as God did in the Tabernacle of old, a symbol of protection and communion): dwell.
  4537. skenoma from skenoo; an encampment, i.e. (figuratively) the Temple (as God's residence), the body (as a tenement for the soul): tabernacle.
  4538. skia apparently a primary word; "shade" or a shadow (literally or figuratively (darkness of error or an adumbration)): shadow.
  4539. skirtao akin to skairo (to skip); to jump, i.e. sympathetically move (as the quickening of a fetus): leap (for joy).
  4540. sklerokardia feminine of a compound of skleros and kardia; hard-heartedness, i.e. (specially), destitution of (spiritual) perception: hardness of heart.
  4541. skleros from the base of skelos; dry, i.e. hard or tough (figuratively, harsh, severe): fierce, hard.
  4542. sklerotes from skleros; callousness, i.e. (figuratively) stubbornness: hardness.
  4543. sklerotrachelos from skleros and trachelos; hardnaped, i.e. (figuratively) obstinate: stiffnecked.
  4544. skleruno from skleros; to indurate, i.e. (figuratively) render stubborn: harden.
  4545. skolios from the base of skelos; warped, i.e. winding; figuratively, perverse: crooked, froward, untoward.
  4546. skolops perhaps from the base of skelos and optanomai; withered at the front, i.e. a point or prickle (figuratively, a bodily annoyance or disability): thorn.
  4547. skopeo from skopos; to take aim at (spy), i.e. (figuratively) regard: consider, take heed, look at (on), mark. Compare optanomai.
