  4548. skopos from skeptomai (to peer about ("skeptic"); perhaps akin to skapto through the idea of concealment; compare skepasma); a watch (sentry or scout), i.e. (by implication) a goal: mark.
  4549. skorpizo apparently from the same as skorpios (through the idea of penetrating); to dissipate, i.e. (figuratively) put to flight, waste, be liberal: disperse abroad, scatter (abroad).
  4550. skorpios probably from an obsolete skerpo (perhaps strengthened from the base of skopos and meaning to pierce); a "scorpion" (from its sting): scorpion.
  4551. skoteinos from skotos; opaque, i.e. (figuratively) benighted: dark, full of darkness.
  4552. skotia from skotos; dimness, obscurity (literally or figuratively): dark(-ness).
  4553. skotizo from skotos; to obscure (literally or figuratively): darken.
  4554. skotos from the base of skia; shadiness, i.e. obscurity (literally or figuratively): darkness.
  4555. skotoo from skotos; to obscure or blind (literally or figuratively): be full of darkness.
  4556. skubalon neuter of a presumed derivative of eis and kuon and ballo; what is thrown to the dogs, i.e. refuse (ordure): dung.
  4557. Skuthes probably of foreign origin; a Scythene or Scythian, i.e. (by implication) a savage: Scythian.
  4558. skuthropos from skuthros (sullen) and a derivative of optanomai; angry-visaged, i.e. gloomy or affecting a mournful appearance: of a sad countenance.
  4559. skullo apparently a primary verb; to flay, i.e. (figuratively) to harass: trouble(self).
  4560. skulon neuter from skullo; something stripped (as a hide), i.e. booty: spoil.
  4561. skolekobrotos from skolex and a derivative of bibrosko; worm-eaten, i.e. diseased with maggots: eaten of worms.
  4562. skolex of uncertain derivation; a grub, maggot or earth-worm: worm.
  4563. smaragdinos from smaragdos; consisting of emerald: emerald.
  4564. smaragdos of uncertain derivation; the emerald or green gem so called: emerald.
  4565. smurna apparently strengthened for muron; myrrh: myrrh.
  4566. Smurna the same as smurna; Smyrna, a place in Asia Minor: Smyrna.
  4567. Smurnaios from Smurna; a Smyrnan: in Smyrna.
  4568. smurnizo from Smurna; to tincture with myrrh, i.e. embitter (as a narcotic): mingle with myrrh.
  4569. Sodoma plural of Hebrew origin (Cdom); Sodoma (i.e. Sedom), a place in Palestine: Sodom.
  4570. soi dative case of su; to thee: thee, thine own, thou, thy.
  4571. Solomon of Hebrew origin (Shlomoh); Solomon (i.e. Shelomoh), the son of David: Solomon.
  4572. soros probably akin to the base of soreuo; a funereal receptacle (urn, coffin), i.e. (by analogy) a bier: bier.
  4573. sos from su; thine: thine (own), thy (friend).
  4574. sou genitive case of su; of thee, thy: X home, thee, thine (own), thou, thy.
  4575. soudarion of Latin origin; a sudarium (sweat-cloth), i.e. towel (for wiping the perspiration from the face, or binding the face of a corpse): handkerchief, napkin.
  4576. Sousanna of Hebrew origin (shuwshan feminine); lily; Susannah (i.e. Shoshannah), an Israelitess: Susanna.
  4577. sophia from sophos; wisdom (higher or lower, worldly or spiritual): wisdom.
  4578. sophizo from sophos; to render wise; in a sinister acceptation, to form "sophisms", i.e. continue plausible error: cunningly devised, make wise.
  4579. sophos akin to saphes (clear); wise (in a most general application): wise. Compare phronimos.
  4580. Spania probably of foreign origin; Spania, a region of Europe: Spain.
  4581. sparasso prolongation from spairo (to grasp; apparently strengthened from spao through the idea of spasmodic contraction); to mangle, i.e. convluse with epilepsy: rend, tear.
  4582. sparganoo from sparganon (a strip; from a derivative of the base of sparasso meaning to strap or wrap with strips); to swathe (an infant after the Oriental custom): wrap in swaddling clothes.
  4583. spatalao from spatale (luxury); to be voluptuous: live in pleasure, be wanton.
  4584. spao a primary verb; to draw: draw (out).
  4585. speira of immediate Latin origin, but ultimately a derivative of haireomai in the sense of its cognate heilisso; a coil (spira, "spire"), i.e. (figuratively) a mass of men (a Roman military cohort; also (by analogy) a squad of Levitical janitors): band.
  4586. speiro probably strengthened from spao (through the idea of extending); to scatter, i.e. sow (literally or figuratively): sow(- er), receive seed.
  4587. spekoulator of Latin origin; a speculator, i.e. military scout (spy or (by extension) life-guardsman): executioner.
  4588. spendo apparently a primary verb; to pour out as a libation, i.e. (figuratively) to devote (one's life or blood, as a sacrifice) ("spend"): (be ready to) be offered.
  4589. sperma from speiro; something sown, i.e. seed (including the male "sperm"); by implication, offspring; specially, a remnant (figuratively, as if kept over for planting): issue, seed.
  4590. spermologos from sperma and lego; a seed-picker (as the crow), i.e. (figuratively) a sponger, loafer (specially, a gossip or trifler in talk): babbler.
  4591. speudo probably strengthened from pous; to "speed" ("study"), i.e. urge on (diligently or earnestly); by implication, to await eagerly: (make, with) haste unto.
  4592. spelaion neuter of a presumed derivative of speos (a grotto); a cavern; by implication, a hiding-place or resort: cave, den.
  4593. spilas of uncertain derivation; a ledge or reef of rock in the sea: spot (by confusion with spilos).
  4594. spiloo from spilos; to stain or soil (literally or figuratively): defile, spot.
  4595. spilos of uncertain derivation; a stain or blemish, i.e. (figuratively) defect, disgrace: spot.
  4596. splagchnizomai middle voice from splagchnon; to have the bowels yearn, i.e. (figuratively) feel sympathy, to pity: have (be moved with) compassion.
  4597. splagchnon probably strengthened from splen (the "spleen"); an intestine (plural); figuratively, pity or sympathy: bowels, inward affection, + tender mercy.
  4598. spoggos perhaps of foreign origin; a "sponge": spunge.
  4599. spodos of uncertain derivation; ashes: ashes.
  4600. spora from speiro; a sowing, i.e. (by implication) parentage: seed.
  4601. sporimos from sporos; sown, i.e. (neuter plural) a planted field: corn(-field).
  4602. sporos from speiro; a scattering (of seed), i.e. (concretely) seed (as sown): seed (X sown).
  4603. spoudazo from spoude; to use speed, i.e. to make effort, be prompt or earnest: do (give) diligence, be diligent (forward), endeavour, labour, study.
  4604. spoudaios from spoude; prompt, energetic, earnest: diligent.
  4605. spoudaioteron neuter of spoudaioteros as adverb; more earnestly than others), i.e. very promptly: very diligently.
  4606. spoudaioteros comparative of spoudaios; more prompt, more earnest: more diligent (forward).
  4607. spoudaioteros adverb from spoudaioteros; more speedily, i.e. sooner than otherwise: more carefully.
  4608. spoudaios adverb from spoudaios; earnestly, promptly: diligently, instantly.
  4609. spoude from speudo; "speed", i.e. (by implication) despatch, eagerness, earnestness: business, (earnest) care(-fulness), diligence, forwardness, haste.
  4610. spuris from speiro (as woven); a hamper or lunch-receptacle: basket.
  4611. stadion, or masculine (in plural) stadios from the base of histemi (as fixed); a stade or certain measure of distance; by implication, a stadium or race-course: furlong, race.
  4612. stamnos from the base of histemi (as stationary); a jar or earthen tank: pot.
  4613. stasis from the base of histemi; a standing (properly, the act), i.e. (by analogy) position (existence); by implication, a popular uprising; figuratively, controversy: dissension, insurrection, X standing, uproar.
  4614. stater from the base of kauchesis; a stander (standard of value), i.e. (specially), a stater or certain coin: piece of money.
  4615. stauros from the base of histemi; a stake or post (as set upright), i.e. (specially), a pole or cross (as an instrument of capital punishment); figuratively, exposure to death, i.e. self-denial; by implication, the atonement of Christ: cross.
  4616. stauroo from stauros; to impale on the cross; figuratively, to extinguish (subdue) passion or selfishness: crucify.
  4617. staphule probably from the base of stephanos; a cluster of grapes (as if intertwined): grapes.
  4618. stachus from the base of histemi; a head of grain (as standing out from the stalk): ear (of corn).
  4619. Stachus the same as stachus; Stachys, a Christian: Stachys.
  4620. stege strengthened from a primary tegos (a "thatch" or "deck" of a building); a roof: roof.
  4621. stego from stege; to roof over, i.e. (figuratively) to cover with silence (endure patiently): (for-)bear, suffer.
  4622. steiros a contraction from stereos (as stiff and unnatural); "sterile": barren.
  4623. stello probably strengthened from the base of histemi; properly, to set fast ("stall"), i.e. (figuratively) to repress (reflexively, abstain from associating with): avoid, withdraw self.
  4624. stemma from the base of stephanos; a wreath for show: garland.
  4625. stenagmos from stenazo; a sigh: groaning.
  4626. stenazo from stenos; to make (intransitively, be) in straits, i.e. (by implication) to sigh, murmur, pray inaudibly: with grief, groan, grudge, sigh.
  4627. stenos probably from the base of histemi; narrow (from obstacles standing close about): strait.
  4628. stenochoreo from the same as stenochoria; to hem in closely, i.e. (figuratively) cramp: distress, straiten.
  4629. stenochoria from a compound of stenos and chora; narrowness of room, i.e. (figuratively) calamity: anguish, distress.
  4630. stereos from histemi; stiff, i.e. solid, stable (literally or figuratively): stedfast, strong, sure.
  4631. stereoo from stereos; to solidify, i.e. confirm (literally or figuratively): establish, receive strength, make strong.
  4632. stereoma from stereoo; something established, i.e. (abstractly) confirmation (stability): stedfastness.
  4633. Stephanas probably contraction for stephanotos (crowned; from stephanoo); Stephanas, a Christian: Stephanas.
  4634. stephanos from an apparently primary stepho (to twine or wreathe); a chaplet (as a badge of royalty, a prize in the public games or a symbol of honor generally; but more conspicuous and elaborate than the simple fillet, diadema), literally or figuratively: crown.
  4635. Stephanos the same as stephanos; Stephanus, a Christian: Stephen.
  4636. stephanoo from stephanos; to adorn with an honorary wreath (literally or figuratively): crown.
  4637. stethos from histemi (as standing prominently); the (entire external) bosom, i.e. chest: breast.
  4638. steko from the perfect tense of histemi; to be stationary, i.e. (figuratively) to persevere: stand (fast).
  4639. sterigmos from sterizo; stability (figuratively): stedfastness.
  4640. sterizo from a presumed derivative of histemi (like stereos); to set fast, i.e. (literally) to turn resolutely in a certain direction, or (figuratively) to confirm: fix, (e-)stablish, stedfastly set, strengthen.
  4641. stigma from a primary stizo (to "stick", i.e. prick); a mark incised or punched (for recognition of ownership), i.e. (figuratively) scar of service: mark.
  4642. stigme feminine of stigma; a point of time, i.e. an instant: moment.
  4643. stilbo apparently a primary verb; to gleam, i.e. flash intensely: shining.
  4644. stoa probably from histemi; a colonnade or interior piazza: porch.
  4645. stoibas from a primary steibo (to "step" or "stamp"); a spread (as if tramped flat) of loose materials for a couch, i.e. (by implication) a bough of a tree so employed: branch.
  4646. stoicheion neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of stoicheo; something orderly in arrangement, i.e. (by implication) a serial (basal, fundamental, initial) constituent (literally), proposition (figuratively): element, principle, rudiment.
  4647. stoicheo from a derivative of steicho (to range in regular line); to march in (military) rank (keep step), i.e. (figuratively) to conform to virtue and piety: walk (orderly).
  4648. stole from stello; equipment, i.e. (specially), a "stole" or long-fitting gown (as a mark of dignity): long clothing (garment), (long) robe.
  4649. stoma probably strengthened from a presumed derivative of the base of tomoteros; the mouth (as if a gash in the face); by implication, language (and its relations); figuratively, an opening (in the earth); specially, the front or edge (of a weapon): edge, face, mouth.
  4650. stomachos from stoma; an orifice (the gullet), i.e. (specially), the "stomach": stomach.
  4651. strateia from strateuomai; military service, i.e. (figuratively) the apostolic career (as one of hardship and danger): warfare.
  4652. strateuma from strateuomai; an armament, i.e. (by implication) a body of troops (more or less extensive or systematic): army, soldier, man of war.
  4653. strateuomai middle voice from the base of stratia; to serve in a military campaign; figuratively, to execute the apostolate (with its arduous duties and functions), to contend with carnal inclinations: soldier, (go to) war(-fare).
  4654. strategos from the base of stratia and ago or hegeomai; a general, i.e. (by implication or analogy) a (military) governor (prtor), the chief (prfect) of the (Levitical) temple-wardens: captain, magistrate.
  4655. stratia feminine of a derivative of stratos (an army; from the base of stronnumi, as encamped); camp-likeness, i.e. an army, i.e. (figuratively) the angels, the celestial luminaries: host.
  4656. stratiotes from a presumed derivative of the same as stratia; a camper-out, i.e. a (common) warrior (literally or figuratively): soldier.
  4657. stratologeo from a compound of the base of stratia and lego (in its original sense); to gather (or select) as a warrior, i.e. enlist in the army: choose to be a soldier.
  4658. stratopedarches from stratopedon and archo; a ruler of an army, i.e. (specially), a from stratopedon and archo; a ruler of an army, i.e. prfect: captain of the guard.
  4659. stratopedon from the base of stratia and the same as pedinos; a camping-ground, i.e. (by implication) a body of troops: army.
  4660. strebloo from a derivative of strepho; to wrench, i.e. (specially), to torture (by the rack), but only figuratively, to pervert: wrest.
  4661. strepho strengthened from the base of trope; to twist, i.e. turn quite around or reverse (literally or figuratively): convert, turn (again, back again, self, self about).
  4662. streniao from a presumed derivative of strenos; to be luxurious: live deliciously.
  4663. strenos akin to stereos; a "straining", "strenuousness" or "strength", i.e. (figuratively) luxury (voluptuousness): delicacy.
  4664. strouthion diminutive of strouthos (a sparrow); a little sparrow: sparrow.
  4665. stronnumi, or simpler stronnuo, prolongation from a still simpler stroo, (used only as an alternate in certain tenses) (probably akin to stereos through the idea of positing); to "strew," i.e. spread (as a carpet or couch): make bed, furnish, spread, strew.
  4666. stugnetos from a derivative of an obsolete apparently primary stugo (to hate); hated, i.e. odious: hateful.
  4667. stugnazo from the same as stugnetos; to render gloomy, i.e. (by implication) glower (be overcast with clouds, or sombreness of speech): lower, be sad.
  4668. stulos from stuo (to stiffen; properly akin to the base of histemi); a post ("style"), i.e. (figuratively) support: pillar.
  4669. Stoikos from stoa; a "Stoic" (as occupying a particular porch in Athens), i.e. adherent of a certin philosophy: Stoick.
  4670. su the personal pronoun of the second person singular; thou: thou. See also se, soi, sou; and for the plural humas, humeis, humin, humon.
  4671. suggeneia from suggenes; relationship, i.e. (concretely) relatives: kindred.
  4672. suggenes from sun and genos; a relative (by blood); by extension, a fellow countryman: cousin, kin(-sfolk, -sman).
  4673. suggnome from a compound of sun and ginosko; fellow knowledge, i.e. concession: permission.
  4674. sugkathemai from sun and kathemai; to seat oneself in company with: sit with.
  4675. sugkathizo from sun and kathizo; to give (or take) a seat in company with: (make) sit (down) together.
  4676. sugkakopatheo from sun and kakopatheo; to suffer hardship in company with: be partaker of afflictions.
  4677. sugkakoucheo from sun and kakoucheo; to maltreat in company with, i.e. (passively) endure persecution together: suffer affliction with.
  4678. sugkaleo from sun and kaleo; to convoke: call together.
  4679. sugkalupto from sun and kalupto; to conceal altogether: cover.
  4680. sugkampto from sun and kampto; to bend together, i.e. (figuratively) to afflict: bow down.
  4681. sugkatabaino from sun and katabaino; to descend in company with: go down with.
  4682. sugkatathesis from sugkatatithemai; a deposition (of sentiment) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) accord with: agreement.
  4683. sugkatatithemai middle from sun and katatithemi; to deposit (one's vote or opinion) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to accord with: consent.
  4684. sugkatapsephizo from sun and a compound of kata and psephizo; to count down in company with, i.e. enroll among: number with.
  4685. sugkerannumi from sun and kerannumi; to commingle, i.e. (figuratively) to combine or assimilate: mix with, temper together.
  4686. sugkineo from sparasso and kineo; to move together, i.e. (specially), to excite as a mass (to sedition): stir up.
  4687. sugkleio from sun and kleio; to shut together, i.e. include or (figuratively) embrace in a common subjection to: conclude, inclose, shut up.
  4688. sugkleronomos from sun and kleronomos; a co-heir, i.e. (by analogy) participant in common: fellow (joint)-heir, heir together, heir with.
  4689. sugkoinoneo from sun and koinoneo; to share in company with, i.e. co-participate in: communicate (have fellowship) with, be partaker of.
  4690. sugkoinonos from sun and koinonos; a co-participant: companion, partake(-r, -r with).
  4691. sugkomizo from sun and komizo; to convey together, i.e. collect or bear away in company with others: carry.
  4692. sugkrino from sun and krino; to judge of one thing in connection with another, i.e. combine (spiritual ideas with appropriate expressions) or collate (one person with another by way of contrast or resemblance): compare among (with).
  4693. sugkupto from sun and kupto; to stoop altogether, i.e. be completely overcome by: bow together.
  4694. sugkuria from a comparative of sun and kureo (to light or happen; from the base of kurios); concurrence, i.e. accident: chance.
  4695. sugchairo from sun and chairo; to sympathize in gladness, congratulate: rejoice in (with).
  4696. sugcheo or sugchuno from sun and cheo (to pour) or its alternate; to commingle promiscuously, i.e. (figuratively) to throw (an assembly) into disorder, to perplex (the mind): confound, confuse, stir up, be in an uproar.
  4697. sugchraomai from sun and chraomai; to use jointly, i.e. (by implication) to hold intercourse in common: have dealings with.
  4698. sugchusis from sugcheo; commixture, i.e. (figuratively) riotous disturbance: confusion.
  4699. suzao from sun and zao; to continue to live in common with, i.e. co-survive (literally or figuratively): live with.
  4700. suzeugnumi from sun and the base of zeugos; to yoke together, i.e. (figuratively) conjoin (in marriage): join together.
  4701. suzeteo from sun and zeteo; to investigate jointly, i.e. discuss, controvert, cavil: dispute (with), enquire, question (with), reason (together).
  4702. suzetesis from suzeteo; mutual questioning, i.e. discussion: disputation(-ting), reasoning.
  4703. suzetetes from suzeteo; a disputant, i.e. sophist: disputer.
  4704. suzugos from suzeugnumi; co-yoked, i.e. (figuratively) as noun, a colleague; probably rather as a proper name; Syzygus, a Christian: yokefellow.
  4705. suzoopoieo from sun and zoopoieo; to reanimate conjointly with (figuratively): quicken together with.
  4706. sukaminos of Hebrew origin (shaqam) in imitation of sukomoraia; a sycamore-fig tree: sycamine tree.
  4707. suke from sukon; a fig-tree: fig tree.
  4708. sukomoraia from sukon and moron (the mulberry); the "sycamore"-fig tree: sycamore tree. Compare sukaminos.
  4709. sukon apparently a primary word; a fig: fig.
  4710. sukophanteo from a compound of sukon and a derivative of phaino; to be a fig-informer (reporter of the law forbidding the exportation of figs from Greece), "sycophant", i.e. (genitive and by extension) to defraud (exact unlawfully, extort): accuse falsely, take by false accusation.
  4711. sulagogeo from the base of sulao and (the reduplicated form of) ago; to lead away as booty, i.e. (figuratively) seduce: spoil.
  4712. sulao from a derivative of sullo (to strip; probably akin to haireomai; compare skulon); to despoil: rob.
  4713. sullaleo from sun and laleo; to talk together, i.e. converse: commune (confer, talk) with, speak among.
  4714. sullambano from sun and lambano; to clasp, i.e. seize (arrest, capture); specially, to conceive (literally or figuratively); by implication, to aid: catch, conceive, help, take.
  4715. sullego from sun and lego in its original sense; to collect: gather (together, up).
  4716. sullogizomai from sun and logizomai; to reckon together (with oneself), i.e. deliberate: reason with.
  4717. sullupeo from sun and lupeo; to afflict jointly, i.e. (passive) sorrow at (on account of) someone: be grieved.
  4718. sumbaino from sun and the base of basis; to walk (figuratively, transpire) together, i.e. concur (take place): be(-fall), happen (unto).
  4719. sumballo from sun and ballo; to combine, i.e. (in speaking) to converse, consult, dispute, (mentally) to consider, (by implication) to aid, (personally) to join, attack: confer, encounter, help, make, meet with, ponder.
  4720. sumbasileuo from sun and basileuo; to be co-regent (figuratively): reign with.
  4721. sumbibazo from sun and bibazo (to force; causative (by reduplication) of the base of basis); to drive together, i.e. unite (in association or affection), (mentally) to infer, show, teach: compact, assuredly gather, intrust, knit together, prove.
  4722. sumbouleuo from sun and bouleuo; to give (or take) advice jointly, i.e. recommend, deliberate or determine: consult, (give, take) counsel (together).
  4723. sumboulion neuter of a presumed derivative of sumboulos; advisement; specially, a deliberative body, i.e. the provincial assessors or lay-court: consultation, counsel, council.
  4724. sumboulos from sun and boule; a consultor, i.e. adviser: counsellor.
  4725. Sumeon from the same as Simon; Symeon (i.e. Shimon), the name of five Israelites: Simeon, Simon.
  4726. summathetes from a compound of sun and manthano; a co-learner (of Christianity): fellow disciple.
  4727. summartureo from sun and martureo; to testify jointly, i.e. corroborate by (concurrent) evidence: testify unto, (also) bear witness (with).
  4728. summerizomai middle voice from sun and merizo; to share jointly, i.e. participate in: be partaker with.
  4729. summetochos from sun and metochos; a co-participant: partaker.
  4730. summimetes from a presumed compound of sun and mimeomai; a co-imitator, i.e. fellow votary: follower together.
  4731. summorphos from sun and morphe; jointly formed, i.e. (figuratively) similar: conformed to, fashioned like unto.
  4732. summorphoo from summorphos; to render like, i.e. (figuratively) to assimilate: make conformable unto.
  4733. sumpatheo from sumpathes; to feel "sympathy" with, i.e. (by implication) to commiserate: have compassion, be touched with a feeling of.
  4734. sumpathes from sumpascho; having a fellow-feeling ("sympathetic"), i.e. (by implication) mutually commiserative: having compassion one of another.
  4735. sumparaginomai from sun and paraginomai; to be present together, i.e. to convene; by implication, to appear in aid: come together, stand with.
  4736. sumparakaleo from sun and parakaleo; to console jointly: comfort together.
  4737. sumparalambano from sun and paralambano; to take along in company: take with.
  4738. sumparameno from sun and parameno; to remain in company, i.e. still live: continue with.
  4739. sumpareimi from sun and pareimi; to be at hand together, i.e. now present: be here present with.
  4740. sumpascho from sun and pascho (including its alternate); to experience pain jointly or of the same kind (specially, persecution; to "sympathize"): suffer with.
  4741. sumpempo from sun and pempo; to despatch in company: send with.
  4742. sumperilambano from sun and a compound of peri and lambano; to take by enclosing altogether, i.e. earnestly throw the arms about one: embrace.
  4743. sumpino from sun and pino; to partake a beverage in company: drink with.
  4744. sumpleroo from sun and pleroo; to implenish completely, i.e. (of space) to swamp (a boat), or (of time) to accomplish (passive, be complete): (fully) come, fill up.
  4745. sumpnigo from sun and pnigo; to strangle completely, i.e. (literally) to drown, or (figuratively) to crowd: choke, throng.
  4746. sumpolites from sun and polites; a native of the same town, i.e. (figuratively) co-religionist (fellow-Christian): fellow- citizen.
  4747. sumporeuomai from sun and poreuomai; to journey together; by implication, to assemble: go with, resort.
  4748. sumposion neuter of a derivative of the alternate of sumpino; a drinking-party ("symposium"), i.e. (by extension) a room of guests: company.
  4749. sumpresbuteros from sun and presbuteros; a co-presbyter: presbyter, also an elder.
  4750. sumphero from sun and phero (including its alternate); to bear together (contribute), i.e. (literally) to collect, or (figuratively) to conduce; especially (neuter participle as a noun) advantage: be better for, bring together, be expedient (for), be good, (be) profit(-able for).
  4751. sumphemi from sun and phemi; to say jointly, i.e. assent to: consent unto.
  4752. sumphuletes from sun and a derivative of phule; a co-tribesman, i.e. native of the same country: countryman.
  4753. sumphutos from sun and a derivative of phuo; grown along with (connate), i.e. (figuratively) closely united to: planted together.
  4754. sumphuo from sun and phuo; passive, to grow jointly: spring up with.
  4755. sumphoneo from sumphonos; to be harmonious, i.e. (figuratively) to accord (be suitable, concur) or stipulate (by compact): agree (together, with).
  4756. sumphonesis from sumphoneo; accordance: concord.
  4757. sumphonia from sumphonos; unison of sound ("symphony"), i.e. a concert of instruments (harmonious note): music.
  4758. sumphonos from sun and phone; sounding together (alike), i.e. (figuratively) accordant (neuter as noun, agreement): consent.
  4759. sumpsephizo from sun and psephizo; to compute jointly: reckon.
  4760. sumpsuchos from sun and psuche; co-spirited, i.e. similar in sentiment: like-minded.
  4761. sun a primary preposition denoting union; with or together (but much closer than meta or para), i.e. by association, companionship, process, resemblance, possession, instrumentality, addition, etc.: beside, with. In composition it has similar applications, including completeness.
  4762. sunago from sun and ago; to lead together, i.e. collect or convene; specially, to entertain (hospitably): + accompany, assemble (selves, together), bestow, come together, gather (selves together, up, together), lead into, resort, take in.
  4763. sunagoge from (the reduplicated form of) sunago; an assemblage of persons; specially, a Jewish "synagogue" (the meeting or the place); by analogy, a Christian church: assembly, congregation, synagogue.
  4764. sunagonizomai from sun and agonizomai; to struggle in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to be a partner (assistant): strive together with.
  4765. sunathleo from sun and athleo; to wrestle in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to seek jointly: labour with, strive together for.
  4766. sunathroizo from sun and athroizo (to hoard); to convene: call (gather) together.
  4767. sunairo from sun and airo; to make up together, i.e. (figuratively) to compute (an account): reckon, take.
  4768. sunaichmalotos from sun and aichmalotos; a co-captive: fellowprisoner.
  4769. sunakoloutheo from sun and akoloutheo; to accompany: follow.
  4770. sunalizo from sun and halizo (to throng); to accumulate, i.e. convene: assemble together.
  4771. sunanabaino from sun and anabaino; to ascend in company with: come up with.
  4772. sunanakeimai from sun and anakeimai; to recline in company with (at a meal): sit (down, at the table, together) with (at meat).
  4773. sunanamignumi from sun and a compound of ana and mignumi; to mix up together, i.e. (figurative) associate with: (have, keep) company (with).
  4774. sunanapauomai middle from sun and anapano; to recruit oneself in company with: refresh with.
  4775. sunantao from sun and a derivative of anti; to meet with; figuratively, to occur: befall, meet.
  4776. sunantesis from sunantao; a meeting with: meet.
  4777. sunantilambanomai from sun and antilambanomai; to take hold of opposite together, i.e. co-operate (assist): help.
  4778. sunapago from sun and apago; to take off together, i.e. transport with (seduce, passively, yield): carry (lead) away with, condescend.
  4779. sunapothnesko from sun and apothnesko; to decease (literally) in company with, or (figuratively), similarly to: be dead (die) with.
  4780. sunapollumi from sun and apollumi; to destroy (middle voice or passively, be slain) in company with: perish with.
  4781. sunapostello from sun and apostello; to despatch (on an errand) in company with: send with.
  4782. sunarmologeo from sun and a derivative of a compound of harmos and lego (in its original sense of laying); to render close-jointed together, i.e. organize compactly: be fitly framed (joined) together.
  4783. sunarpazo from sun and harpazo; to snatch together, i.e. seize: catch.
  4784. sunauxano from sun and auzano; to increase (grow up) together: grow together.
  4785. sundesmos from sun and desmon; a joint tie, i.e. ligament, (figuratively) uniting principle, control: band, bond.
  4786. sundeo from sun and deo; to bind with, i.e. (passively) be a fellow-prisoner (figuratively): be bound with.
  4787. sundoxazo from sun and doxazo; to exalt to dignity in company (i.e. similarly) with: glorify together.
  4788. sundoulos from sun and doulos; a co-slave, i.e. servitor or ministrant of the same master (human or divine): fellowservant.
  4789. sundrome from (the alternate of) suntrecho; a running together, i.e. (riotous) concourse: run together.
  4790. sunegeiro from sun and egeiro; to rouse (from death) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to revivify (spirtually) in resemblance to: raise up together, rise with.
  4791. sunedrion neuter of a presumed derivative of a compound of sun and the base of hedraios; a joint session, i.e. (specially), the Jewish Sanhedrin; by analogy, a subordinate tribunal: council.
  4792. suneidesis from a prolonged form of suneido; co-perception, i.e. moral consciousness: conscience.
  4793. suneido from sun and eido; to see completely; used (like its primary) only in two past tenses, respectively meaning to understand or become aware, and to be conscious or (clandestinely) informed of: consider, know, be privy, be ware of.
  4794. suneimi from sun and eimi (including its various inflections); to be in company with, i.e. present at the time: be with.
  4795. suneimi from sun and eimi (to go); to assemble: gather together.
  4796. suneiserchomai from sun and eiserchomai; to enter in company with: go in with, go with into.
  4797. sunekdemos from sun and the base of ekdemeo; a co-absentee from home, i.e. fellow-traveller: companion in travel, travel with.
  4798. suneklektos from a compound of sun and eklegomai; chosen in company with, i.e. co-elect (fellow Christian): elected together with.
  4799. sunelauno from sun and elauno; to drive together, i.e. (figuratively) exhort (to reconciliation): + set at one again.
  4800. sunepimartureo from sun and epimartureo; to testify further jointly, i.e. unite in adding evidence: also bear witness.
  4801. sunepomai middle voice from sun and a primary hepo (to follow); to attend (travel) in company with: accompany.
  4802. sunergeo from sunergos; to be a fellow-worker, i.e. co-operate: help (work) with, work(-er) together.
  4803. sunergos from a presumed compound of sun and the base of ergon; a co-laborer, i.e. coadjutor: companion in labour, (fellow-)helper(-labourer, -worker), labourer together with, workfellow.
  4804. sunerchomai from sun and erchomai; to convene, depart in company with, associate with, or (specially), cohabit (conjugally): accompany, assemble (with), come (together), come (company, go) with, resort.
  4805. sunesthio from sun and esthio (including its alternate); to take food in company with: eat with.
  4806. sunesis from suniemi; a mental putting together, i.e. intelligence or (concretely) the intellect: knowledge, understanding.
  4807. sunetos from suniemi; mentally put (or putting) together, i.e. sagacious: prudent. Compare phronimos.
  4808. suneudokeo from sun and eudokeo; to think well of in common, i.e. assent to, feel gratified with: allow, assent, be pleased, have pleasure.
  4809. suneuocheo from sun and a derivative of a presumed compound of eu and a derivative of echo (meaning to be in good condition, i.e. (by implication) to fare well, or feast); to entertain sumptuously in company with, i.e. (middle voice or passive) to revel together: feast with.
  4810. sunephistemi from sun and ephistemi; to stand up together, i.e. to resist (or assault) jointly: rise up together.
  4811. sunecho from sun and echo; to hold together, i.e. to compress (the ears, with a crowd or siege) or arrest (a prisoner); figuratively, to compel, perplex, afflict, preoccupy: constrain, hold, keep in, press, lie sick of, stop, be in a strait, straiten, be taken with, throng.
  4812. sunedomai middle voice from sun and the base of hedone; to rejoice in with oneself, i.e. feel satisfaction concerning: delight.
  4813. sunetheia from a compound of sun and ethos; mutual habituation, i.e. usage: custom.
  4814. sunelikiotes from sun and a derivative of helikia; a co-aged person, i.e. alike in years: equal.
  4815. sunthapto from sun and thapto; to inter in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to assimilate spiritually (to Christ by a sepulture as to sin): bury with.
  4816. sunthlao from sun and thlao (to crush); to dash together, i.e. shatter: break.
  4817. sunthlibo from sun and thlibo; to compress, i.e. crowd on all sides: throng.
  4818. sunthrupto from sun and thrupto (to crumble); to crush together, i.e. (figuratively) to dispirit: break.
  4819. suniemi from sun and hiemi (to send); to put together, i.e. (mentally) to comprehend; by implication, to act piously: consider, understand, be wise.
  4820. sunistao, or (strengthened) sunistano, or sunistemi from sun and histemi (including its collateral forms); to set together, i.e. (by implication) to introduce (favorably), or (figuratively) to exhibit; intransitively, to stand near, or (figuratively) to constitute: approve, commend, consist, make, stand (with).
  4821. sunodeuo from sun and hodeuo; to travel in company with: journey with.
  4822. sunodia from a compound of sun and hodos ("synod"); companionship on a journey, i.e. (by implication), a caravan: company.
  4823. sunoikeo from sun and oikeo; to reside together (as a family): dwell together.
  4824. sunoikodomeo from sun and oikodomeo; to construct, i.e. (passively) to compose (in company with other Christians, figuratively): build together.
  4825. sunomileo from sun and homileo; to converse mutually: talk with.
  4826. sunomoreo from sun and a derivative of a compound of the base of homou and the base of horion; to border together, i.e. adjoin: join hard.
  4827. sunoche from sunecho; restraint, i.e. (figuratively) anxiety: anguish, distress.
  4828. suntasso from sun and tasso; to arrange jointly, i.e. (figuratively) to direct: appoint.
  4829. sunteleia from sunteleo; entire completion, i.e. consummation (of a dispensation): end.
  4830. sunteleo from sun and teleo; to complete entirely; generally, to execute (literally or figuratively): end, finish, fulfil, make.
  4831. suntemno from sun and the base of tomoteros; to contract by cutting, i.e. (figuratively) do concisely (speedily): (cut) short.
  4832. suntereo from sun and tereo; to keep closely together, i.e. (by implication) to conserve (from ruin); mentally, to remember (and obey): keep, observe, preserve.
  4833. suntithemai middle voice from sun and tithemi; to place jointly, i.e. (figuratively) to consent (bargain, stipulate), concur: agree, assent, covenant.
  4834. suntomos adverb from a derivative of suntemno; concisely (briefly): a few words.
  4835. suntrecho from sun and trecho (including its alternate); to rush together (hastily assemble) or headlong (figuratively): run (together, with).
  4836. suntribo from sun and the base of tribos; to crush completely, i.e. to shatter (literally or figuratively): break (in pieces), broken to shivers (+ -hearted), bruise.
  4837. suntrimma from suntribo; concussion or utter fracture (properly, concretely), i.e. complete ruin: destruction.
  4838. suntrophos from sun and trophos (in a passive sense); a fellow-nursling, i.e. comrade: brought up with.
  4839. suntugchano from sun and tugchano; to chance together, i.e. meet with (reach): come at.
  4840. Suntuche from suntugchano; an accident; Syntyche, a Christian female: Syntyche.
  4841. sunupokrinomai from sun and hupokrinomai; to act hypocritically in concert with: dissemble with.
  4842. sunupourgeo from sun and a derivative of a compound of hupo and the base of ergon; to be a co-auxiliary, i.e. assist: help together.
  4843. sunodino from sun and odino; to have (parturition) pangs in company (concert, simultaneously) with, i.e. (figuratively) to sympathize (in expectation of relief from suffering): travail in pain together.
  4844. sunomosia from a compound of sun and omnuo; a swearing together, i.e. (by implication) a plot: comspiracy.
  4845. Surakousai plural of uncertain derivation; Syracuse, the capital of Sicily: Syracuse.
  4846. Suria probably of Hebrew origin (Tsor); Syria (i.e. Tsyria or Tyre), a region of Asia: Syria.
  4847. Suros from the same as Suria; a Syran (i.e. probably Tyrian), a native of Syria: Syrian.
  4848. Surophoinissa feminine of a compound of Suros and the same as Phoinike; a Syro-phnician woman, i.e. a female native of Phnicia in Syria: Syrophenician.
  4849. surtis from suro; a shoal (from the sand drawn thither by the waves), i.e. the Syrtis Major or great bay on the north coast of Africa: quicksands.
  4850. suro probably akin to haireomai; to trail: drag, draw, hale.
  4851. susparasso from sun and sparasso; to rend completely, i.e. (by analogy) to convulse violently: throw down.
  4852. sussemon neuter of a compound of sun and the base of semaino; a sign in common, i.e. preconcerted signal: token.
  4853. sussomos from sun and soma; of a joint body, i.e. (figuratively) a fellow-member of the Christian community: of the same body.
  4854. sustasiastes from a compound of sun and a derivative of stasis; a fellow-insurgent: make insurrection with.
  4855. sustatikos from a derivative of sunistao; introductory, i.e. recommendatory: of commendation.
  4856. sustauroo from sun and stauroo; to impale in company with (literally or figuratively): crucify with.
  4857. sustello from sun and stello; to send (draw) together, i.e. enwrap (enshroud a corpse for burial), contract (an interval): short, wind up.
  4858. sustenazo from sun and stenazo; to moan jointly, i.e. (figuratively) experience a common calamity: groan together.
  4859. sustoicheo from sun and stoicheo; to file together (as soldiers in ranks), i.e. (figuratively) to correspond to: answer to.
  4860. sustratiotes from sun and stratiotes; a co-campaigner, i.e. (figuratively) an associate in Christian toil: fellowsoldier.
  4861. sustrepho from sun and strepho; to twist together, i.e. collect (a bundle, a crowd): gather.
  4862. sustrophe from sustrepho; a twisting together, i.e. (figuratively) a secret coalition, riotous crowd: + band together, concourse.
  4863. suschematizo from sun and a derivative of schema; to fashion alike, i.e. conform to the same pattern (figuratively): conform to, fashion self according to.
  4864. Suchar of Hebrew origin (shekar); Sychar (i.e. Shekar), a place in Palestine: Sychar.
  4865. Suchem of Hebrew origin (Shkem); Sychem (i.e. Shekem), the name of a Canaanite and of a place in Palestine: Sychem.
  4866. sphage from sphazo; butchery (of animals for food or sacrifice, or (figuratively) of men (destruction)): slaughter.
  4867. sphagion neuter of a derivative of sphage; a victim (in sacrifice): slain beast.
  4868. sphazo a primary verb; to butcher (especially an animal for food or in sacrifice) or (generally) to slaughter, or (specially), to maim (violently): kill, slay, wound.
  4869. sphodra neuter plural of sphodros (violent; of uncertain derivation) as adverb; vehemently, i.e. in a high degree, much: exceeding(-ly), greatly, sore, very.
  4870. sphodros adverb from the same as sphodra; very much: exceedingly.
  4871. sphragizo from sphragis; to stamp (with a signet or private mark) for security or preservation (literally or figuratively); by implication, to keep secret, to attest: (set a, set to) seal up, stop.
  4872. sphragis probably strengthened from phrasso; a signet (as fencing in or protecting from misappropriation); by implication, the stamp impressed (as a mark of privacy, or genuineness), literally or figuratively: seal.
  4873. sphuron neuter of a presumed derivative probably of the same as sphaira (a ball, "sphere"; compare the feminine sphura, a hammer); the ankle (as globular): ancle bone.
  4874. schedon neuter of a presumed derivative of the alternate of echo as adverb; nigh, i.e. nearly: almost.
  4875. schema from the alternate of echo; a figure (as a mode or circumstance), i.e. (by implication) external condition: fashion.
  4876. schizo apparently a primary verb; to split or sever (literally or figuratively): break, divide, open, rend, make a rent.
  4877. schisma from schizo; a split or gap ("schism"), literally or figuratively: division, rent, schism.
  4878. schoinion diminutive of schoinos (a rush or flag-plant; of uncertain derivation); a rushlet, i.e. grass-withe or tie (generally): small cord, rope.
  4879. scholazo from schole; to take a holiday, i.e. be at leisure for (by implication, devote oneself wholly to); figuratively, to be vacant (of a house): empty, give self.
  4880. schole probably feminine of a presumed derivative of the alternate of echo; properly, loitering (as a withholding of oneself from work) or leisure, i.e. (by implication) a "school" (as vacation from physical employment): school.
  4881. sozo from a primary sos (contraction for obsolete saos, "safe"); to save, i.e. deliver or protect (literally or figuratively): heal, preserve, save (self), do well, be (make) whole.
  4882. soma from sozo; the body (as a sound whole), used in a very wide application, literally or figuratively: bodily, body, slave.
  4883. somatikos from soma; corporeal or physical: bodily.
  4884. somatikos adverb from somatikos; corporeally or physically: bodily.
  4885. Sopatros from the base of sozo and pater; of a safe father; Sopatrus, a Christian: Sopater. Compare Sosipatros.
  4886. soreuo from another form of soros; to pile up (literally or figuratively): heap, load.
  4887. Sosthenes from the base of sozo and that of sthenoo; of safe strength; Sosthenes, a Christian: Sosthenes.
  4888. Sosipatros prolongation for Sopatros; Sosipatrus, a Christian: Sosipater.
  4889. soter from sozo; a deliverer, i.e. God or Christ: saviour.
  4890. soteria feminine of a derivative of soter as (properly, abstract) noun; rescue or safety (physically or morally): deliver, health, salvation, save, saving.
  4891. soterion neuter of the same as soteria as (properly, concretely) noun; defender or (by implication) defence: salvation.
  4892. sophroneo from sophron; to be of sound mind, i.e. sane, (figuratively) moderate: be in right mind, be sober (minded), soberly.
  4893. sophronizo from sophron; to make of sound mind, i.e. (figuratively) to discipline or correct: teach to be sober.
  4894. sophronismos from sophronizo; discipline, i.e. self-control: sound mind.
  4895. sophronos adverb from sophron; with sound mind, i.e. moderately: soberly.
  4896. sophrosune from sophron; soundness of mind, i.e. (literally) sanity or (figuratively) self-control: soberness, sobriety.
  4897. sophron from the base of sozo and that of phren; safe (sound) in mind, i.e. self-controlled (moderate as to opinion or passion): discreet, sober, temperate.
  4898. Tabernai plural of Latin origin; huts or wooden-walled buildings; Tabern: taverns.
  4899. Tabitha of Chaldee origin (compare tsbiyah); the gazelle; Tabitha (i.e. Tabjetha), a Christian female: Tabitha.
  4900. tagma from tasso; something orderly in arrangement (a troop), i.e. (figuratively) a series or succession: order.
  4901. taktos from tasso; arranged, i.e. appointed or stated: set.
  4902. talaiporeo from talaiporos; to be wretched, i.e. realize one's own misery: be afflicted.
  4903. talaiporia from talaiporos; wretchedness, i.e. calamity: misery.
  4904. talaiporos from the base of talanton and a derivative of the base of peira; enduring trial, i.e. miserable: wretched.
  4905. talantiaios from talanton; talent-like in weight: weight of a talent.
  4906. talanton neuter of a presumed derivative of the original form of tlao (to bear; equivalent to phero); a balance (as supporting weights), i.e. (by implication) a certain weight (and thence a coin or rather sum of money) or "talent": talent.
  4907. talitha of Chaldee origin (compare taleh); the fresh, i.e. young girl; talitha (O maiden): talitha.
  4908. tameion neuter contraction of a presumed derivative of tamias (a dispenser or distributor; akin to temno, to cut); a dispensary or magazine, i.e. a chamber on the ground-floor or interior of an Oriental house (generally used for storage or privacy, a spot for retirement): secret chamber, closet, storehouse.
  4909. taxis from tasso; regular arrangement, i.e. (in time) fixed succession (of rank or character), official dignity: order.
  4910. tapeinos of uncertain derivation; depressed, i.e. (figuratively) humiliated (in circumstances or disposition): base, cast down, humble, of low degree (estate), lowly.
  4911. tapeinophrosune from a compound of tapeinos and the base of phren; humiliation of mind, i.e. modesty: humbleness of mind, humility (of mind, loneliness (of mind).
  4912. tapeinoo from tapeinos; to depress; figuratively, to humiliate (in condition or heart): abase, bring low, humble (self).
  4913. tapeinosis from tapeinoo; depression (in rank or feeling): humiliation, be made low, low estate, vile.
  4914. tarasso of uncertain affinity; to stir or agitate (roil water): trouble.
  4915. tarache feminine from tarasso; disturbance, i.e. (of water) roiling, or (of a mob) sedition: trouble(-ing).
  4916. tarachos masculine from tarasso; a disturbance, i.e. (popular) tumult: stir.
  4917. Tarseus from Tarsos; a Tarsean, i.e. native of Tarsus: of Tarsus.
  4918. Tarsos perhaps the same as tarsos (a flat basket); Tarsus, a place in Asia Minor: Tarsus.
  4919. tartaroo from Tartaros (the deepest abyss of Hades); to incarcerate in eternal torment: cast down to hell.
  4920. tasso a prolonged form of a primary verb (which latter appears only in certain tenses); to arrange in an orderly manner, i.e. assign or dispose (to a certain position or lot): addict, appoint, determine, ordain, set.
  4921. tauros apparently a primary word (compare towr, "steer"); a bullock: bull, ox.
  4922. tauta nominative or accusative case neuter plural of houtos; these things: + afterward, follow, + hereafter, X him, the same, so, such, that, then, these, they, this, those, thus.
  4923. tauta neuter plural of ho and autos as adverb; in the same way: even thus, (manner) like, so.
  4924. tautais, and tautas dative case and accusative case feminine plural respectively of houtos; (to or with or by, etc.) these: hence, that, then, these, those.
  4925. taute, and tauten, and tautes dative case, accusative case and genitive case respectively of the feminine singular of houtos; (towards or of) this: her, + hereof, it, that, + thereby, the (same), this (same).
  4926. taphe feminine from thapto; burial (the act): X bury.
  4927. taphos masculine from thapto; a grave (the place of interment): sepulchre, tomb.
  4928. tacha as if neuter plural of tachus (adverbially); shortly, i.e. (figuratively) possibly: peradventure(-haps).
  4929. tacheos adverb from tachus; briefly, i.e. (in time) speedily, or (in manner) rapidly: hastily, quickly, shortly, soon, suddenly.
  4930. tachinos from tachos; curt, i.e. impending: shortly, swift.
  4931. tachion neuter singular of the comparative of tachus (as adverb); more swiftly, i.e. (in manner) more rapidly, or (in time) more speedily: out (run), quickly, shortly, sooner.
  4932. tachista neuter plural of the superlative of tachus (as adverb); most quickly, i.e. (with hos prefixed) as soon as possible: + with all speed.
  4933. tachos from the same as tachus; a brief space (of time), i.e. (with en prefixed) in haste: + quickly, + shortly, + speedily.
  4934. tachu neuter singular of tachus (as adverb); shortly, i.e. without delay, soon, or (by surprise) suddenly, or (by implication, of ease) readily: lightly, quickly.
  4935. tachus of uncertain affinity; fleet, i.e. (figuratively) prompt or ready: swift.
  4936. te a primary particle (enclitic) of connection or addition; both or also (properly, as correlation of kai): also, and, both, even, then, whether. Often used in composition, usually as the latter participle.
  4937. teichos akin to the base of tikto; a wall (as formative of a house): wall.
  4938. tekmerion neuter of a presumed derivative of tekmar (a goal or fixed limit); a token (as defining a fact), i.e. criterion of certainty: infallible proof.
  4939. teknion diminutive of teknon; an infant, i.e. (plural figuratively) darlings (Christian converts): little children.
  4940. teknogoneo from a compound of teknon and the base of ginomai; to be a child-bearer, i.e. parent (mother): bear children.
  4941. teknogonia from the same as teknogoneo; childbirth (parentage), i.e. (by implication) maternity (the performance of maternal duties): childbearing.
  4942. teknon from the base of timoria; a child (as produced): child, daughter, son.
  4943. teknotropheo from a compound of teknon and trepho; to be a childrearer, i.e. fulfil the duties of a female parent: bring up children.
  4944. tekton from the base of timoria; an artificer (as producer of fabrics), i.e. (specially), a craftsman in wood: carpenter.
  4945. teleios from telos; complete (in various applications of labor, growth, mental and moral character, etc.); neuter (as noun, with ho) completeness: of full age, man, perfect.
  4946. teleiotes from teleios; (the state) completeness (mentally or morally): perfection(-ness).
  4947. teleioo from teleios; to complete, i.e. (literally) accomplish, or (figuratively) consummate (in character): consecrate, finish, fulfil, make) perfect.
  4948. teleios adverb from teleios; completely, i.e. (of hope) without wavering: to the end.
  4949. teleiosis from phusioo; (the act) completion, i.e. (of prophecy) verification, or (of expiation) absolution: perfection, performance.
  4950. teleiotes from teleioo; a completer, i.e. consummater: finisher.
  4951. telesphoreo from a compound of telos and phero; to be a bearer to completion (maturity), i.e. to ripen fruit (figuratively): bring fruit to perfection.
  4952. teleutao from a presumed derivative of teleo; to finish life (by implication, of bios), i.e. expire (demise): be dead, decease, die.
  4953. teleute from teleutao; decease: death.
  4954. teleo from telos; to end, i.e. complete, execute, conclude, discharge (a debt): accomplish, make an end, expire, fill up, finish, go over, pay, perform.
  4955. telos from a primary tello (to set out for a definite point or goal); properly, the point aimed at as a limit, i.e. (by implication) the conclusion of an act or state (termination (literally, figuratively or indefinitely), result (immediate, ultimate or prophetic), purpose); specially, an impost or levy (as paid): + continual, custom, end(-ing), finally, uttermost. Compare phoros.
  4956. telones from telos and oneomai; a tax-farmer, i.e. collector of public revenue: publican.
  4957. telonion neuter of a presumed derivative of telones; a tax-gatherer's place of business: receipt of custom.
  4958. teras of uncertain affinity; a prodigy or omen: wonder.
  4959. Tertios of Latin origin; third; Tertius, a Christian: Tertius.
  4960. Tertullos of uncertain derivation; Tertullus, a Roman: Tertullus.
  4961. tessarakonta the decade of tessares; forty: forty.
  4962. tessarakontaetes from tessarakonta and etos; of forty years of age: (+ full, of) forty years (old).
  4963. tessares, or neuter tessara a plural number; four: four.
