  4966. tetartos ordinal from tessares; fourth: four(-th).
  4967. tetragonos from tessares and gonia; four-cornered, i.e. square: foursquare.
  4968. tetradion neuter of a presumed derivative of tetras (a tetrad; from tessares); a quaternion or squad (picket) of four Roman soldiers: quaternion.
  4969. tetrakischilioi from the multiplicative adverb of tessares and chilioi; four times a thousand: four thousand.
  4970. tetrakosioi, or neuter tetrakosia plural from tessares and hekaton; four hundred: four hundred.
  4971. tetramenon neuter of a compound of tessares and men; a four months' space: four months.
  4972. tetraploos from tessares and a derivative of the base of pleistos; quadruple: fourfold.
  4973. tetrapous from tessares and pous; a quadruped: fourfooted beast.
  4974. tetrarcheo from tetrarches; to be a tetrarch: (be) tetrarch.
  4975. tetrarches from tessares and archo; the ruler of a fourth part of a country ("tetrarch"): tetrarch.
  4976. tephroo from tephra (ashes); to incinerate, i.e. consume: turn to ashes.
  4977. techne from the base of tikto; art (as productive), i.e. (specially), a trade, or (generally) skill: art, craft, occupation.
  4978. technites from techne; an artisan; figuratively, a founder (Creator): builder, craftsman.
  4979. teko apparently a primary verb; to liquefy: melt.
  4980. telaugos adverb from a compound of a derivative of telos and auge; in a far-shining manner, i.e. plainly: clearly.
  4981. telikoutos, or feminine telikaute from a compound of ho with helikos and houtos; such as this, i.e. (in (figurative) magnitude) so vast: so great, so mighty.
  4982. tereo from teros (a watch; perhaps akin to theoreo); to guard (from loss or injury, properly, by keeping the eye upon; and thus differing from phulasso, which is properly to prevent escaping; and from koustodia, which implies a fortress or full military lines of apparatus), i.e. to note (a prophecy; figuratively, to fulfil a command); by implication, to detain (in custody; figuratively, to maintain); by extension, to withhold (for personal ends; figuratively, to keep unmarried); by extension, to withhold (for personal ends; figuratively, to keep unmarried): hold fast, keep(- er), (pre-, re-)serve, watch.
  4983. teresis from tereo; a watching, i.e. (figuratively) observance, or (concretely) a prison: hold.
  4984. Tiberias from Tiberios; Tiberias, the name of a town and a lake in Palestine: Tiberias.
  4985. Tiberios of Latin origin; probably pertaining to the river Tiberis or Tiber; Tiberius, a Roman emperor: Tiberius.
  4986. tithemi, a prolonged form of a primary theo (which is used only as alternate in certain tenses); to place (in the widest application, literally and figuratively; properly, in a passive or horizontal posture, and thus different from histemi, which properly denotes an upright and active position, while keimai is properly reflexive and utterly prostrate): + advise, appoint, bow, commit, conceive, give, X kneel down, lay (aside, down, up), make, ordain, purpose, put, set (forth), settle, sink down.
  4987. tikto a strengthened form of a primary teko tek'-o (which is used only as alternate in certain tenses); to produce (from seed, as a mother, a plant, the earth, etc.), literally or figuratively: bear, be born, bring forth, be delivered, be in travail.
  4988. tillo perhaps akin to the alternate of haireomai, and thus to suro; to pull off: pluck.
  4989. Timaios probably of Chaldee origin (compare tame'); Timus (i.e. Timay), an Israelite: Timus.
  4990. timao from timios; to prize, i.e. fix a valuation upon; by implication, to revere: honour, value.
  4991. time from tino; a value, i.e. money paid, or (concretely and collectively) valuables; by analogy, esteem (especially of the highest degree), or the dignity itself: honour, precious, price, some.
  4992. timios, including the comparative timioteros, and the superlative timiotatos from time; valuable, i.e. (objectively) costly, or (subjectively) honored, esteemed, or (figuratively) beloved: dear, honourable, (more, most) precious, had in reputation.
  4993. timiotes from timios; expensiveness, i.e. (by implication) magnificence: costliness.
  4994. Timotheos from time and theos; dear to God; Timotheus, a Christian: Timotheus, Timothy.
  4995. Timon from time; valuable; Timon, a Christian: Timon.
  4996. timoreo from a comparative of time and ouros (a guard); properly, to protect one's honor, i.e. to avenge (inflict a penalty): punish.
  4997. timoria from timoreo; vindication, i.e. (by implication) a penalty: punishment.
  4998. tino, strengthened for a primary tio (which is only used as an alternate in certain tenses) to pay a price, i.e. as a penalty: be punished with.
  4999. tis an enclitic indefinite pronoun; some or any person or object: a (kind of), any (man, thing, thing at all), certain (thing), divers, he (every) man, one (X thing), ought, + partly, some (man, -body, - thing, -what), (+ that no-)thing, what(-soever), X wherewith, whom(-soever), whose(-soever).
  5000. tis probably emphatic of tis; an interrogative pronoun, who, which or what (in direct or indirect questions): every man, how (much), + no(-ne, thing), what (manner, thing), where (-by, -fore, -of, -unto, - with, -withal), whether, which, who(-m, -se), why.
  5001. titlos of Latin origin; a titulus or "title" (placard): title.
  5002. Titos of Latin origin but uncertain significance; Titus, a Christian: Titus.
  5003. toi probably for the dative case of ho; an enclitic particle of asseveration by way of contrast; in sooth: (used only with other particles in the comparative, as kaitoige, mentoi, toigaroun, toinun, etc.)
  5004. toigaroun from toi and gar and oun; truly for then, i.e. consequently: there-(where-)fore.
  5005. toinun from toi and nun; truly now, i.e. accordingly: then, therefore.
  5006. toiosde (including the other inflections); from a derivative of toi and de; such-like then, i.e. so great: such.
  5007. toioutos (including the other inflections); from toi and houtos; truly this, i.e. of this sort (to denote character or individuality): like, such (an one).
  5008. toichos another form of teichos; a wall: wall.
  5009. tokos from the base of tikto; interest on money loaned (as a produce): usury.
  5010. tolmao from tolma (boldness; probably itself from the base of telos through the idea of extreme conduct); to venture (objectively or in act; while tharrheo is rather subjective or in feeling); by implication, to be courageous: be bold, boldly, dare, durst.
  5011. tolmeroteron neuter of the compound of a derivative of the base of tolmao (as adverb); more daringly, i.e. with greater confidence than otherwise: the more boldly.
  5012. tolmetes from tolmao; a daring (audacious) man: presumptuous.
  5013. tomoteros comparative of a derivative of the primary temno (to cut; more comprehensive or decisive than kopto, as if by a single stroke; whereas that implies repeated blows, like hacking); more keen: sharper.
  5014. toxon from the base of tikto; a bow (apparently as the simplest fabric): bow.
  5015. topazion neuter of a presumed derivative (alternately) of topazos (a "topaz"; of uncertain origin); a gem, probably the chrysolite: topaz.
  5016. topos apparently a primary word; a spot (general in space, but limited by occupancy; whereas chora is a large but participle locality), i.e. location (as a position, home, tract, etc.); figuratively, condition, opportunity; specially, a scabbard: coast, licence, place, X plain, quarter, + rock, room, where.
  5017. tosoutos from tosos (so much; apparently from ho and hos) and houtos (including its variations); so vast as this, i.e. such (in quantity, amount, number of space): as large, so great (long, many, much), these many.
  5018. tote from (the neuter of) ho and hote; the when, i.e. at the time that (of the past or future, also in consecution): that time, then.
  5019. tou properly, the genitive case of ho; sometimes used for toutou; of this person: his.
  5020. tounantion contraction for the neuter of ho and enantion; on the contrary: contrariwise.
  5021. tounoma contraction for the neuter of ho and onoma; the name (is): named.
  5022. toutesti contraction for touto and esti; that is: that is (to say).
  5023. touto neuter singular nominative or accusative case of houtos; that thing: here (-unto), it, partly, self(-same), so, that (intent), the same, there(-fore, -unto), this, thus, where(-fore).
  5024. toutois dative case plural masculine or neuter of houtos; to (for, in, with or by) these (persons or things): such, them, there(-in, -with), these, this, those.
  5025. touton accusative case singular masculine of houtos; this (person, as objective of verb or preposition): him, the same, that, this.
  5026. toutou genitive case singular masculine or neuter of houtos; of (from or concerning) this (person or thing): here(-by), him, it, + such manner of, that, thence(-forth), thereabout, this, thus.
  5027. toutous accusative case plural masculine of houtos; these (persons, as objective of verb or preposition): such, them, these, this.
  5028. toutoi dative case singular masculine or neuter of houtos; to (in, with or by) this (person or thing): here(-by, -in), him, one, the same, there(-in), this.
  5029. touton genitive case plural masculine or neuter of houtos; of (from or concerning) these (persons or things): such, their, these (things), they, this sort, those.
  5030. tragos from the base of trogo; a he-goat (as a gnawer): goat.
  5031. trapeza probably contracted from tessares and peze; a table or stool (as being four-legged), usually for food (figuratively, a meal); also a counter for money (figuratively, a broker's office for loans at interest): bank, meat, table.
  5032. trapezites from trapeza; a money-broker or banker: exchanger.
  5033. trauma from the base of titrosko (to wound; akin to the base of thrauo, tribos, trizo, etc.); a wound: wound.
  5034. traumatizo from trauma; to inflict a wound: wound.
  5035. trachelizo from trachelos; to seize by the throat or neck, i.e. to expose the gullet of a victim for killing (generally, to lay bare): opened.
  5036. trachelos probably from trecho (through the idea of mobility); the throat (neck), i.e. (figuratively) life: neck.
  5037. trachus perhaps strengthened from the base of rhegnumi (as if jagged by rents); uneven, rocky (reefy): rock, rough.
  5038. Trachonitis from a derivative of trachus; rough district; Trachonitis, a region of Syria: Trachonitis.
  5039. treis, or neuter tria a primary (plural) number; "three": three.
  5040. tremo strengthened from a primary treo (to "dread", "terrify"); to "tremble" or fear: be afraid, trembling.
  5041. trepho a primary verb (properly, threpho; but perhaps strengthened from the base of trope through the idea of convolution); properly, to stiffen, i.e. fatten (by implication, to cherish (with food, etc.), pamper, rear): bring up, feed, nourish.
  5042. trecho apparently a primary verb (properly, threcho; compare thrix); which uses dremo drem'-o (the base of dromos) as alternate in certain tenses; to run or walk hastily (literally or figuratively): have course, run.
  5043. triakonta the decade of treis; thirty: thirty.
  5044. triakosioi plural from treis and hekaton; three hundred: three hundred.
  5045. tribolos from treis and belos; properly, a crow-foot (three-pronged obstruction in war), i.e. (by analogy) a thorny plant (caltrop): brier, thistle.
  5046. tribos from tribo (to "rub"; akin to teiro, truo, and the base of tragos, trauma); a rut or worn track: path.
  5047. trietia from a compound of treis and etos; a three years' period (triennium): space of three years.
  5048. trizo apparently a primary verb; to creak (squeak), i.e. (by analogy) to grate the teeth (in frenzy): gnash.
  5049. trimenon neuter of a compound of treis and men as noun; a three months' space: three months.
  5050. tris adverb from treis; three times: three times, thrice.
  5051. tristegon neuter of a compound of treis and stege as noun; a third roof (story): third loft.
  5052. trischilioi from tris and chilioi; three times a thousand: three thousand.
  5053. tritos ordinal from treis; third; neuter (as noun) a third part, or (as adverb) a (or the) third time, thirdly: third(-ly).
  5054. trichinos from thrix; hairy, i.e. made of hair (mohair): of hair.
  5055. tromos from tremo; a "trembling", i.e. quaking with fear: + tremble(-ing).
  5056. trope from an apparently primary trepo to turn; a turn ("trope"), i.e. revolution (figuratively, variation): turning.
  5057. tropos from the same as trope; a turn, i.e. (by implication) mode or style (especially with preposition or relative prefix as adverb, like); figuratively, deportment or character: (even) as, conversation, (+ like) manner, (+ by any) means, way.
  5058. tropophoreo from tropos and phoreo; to endure one's habits: suffer the manners.
  5059. trophe from trepho; nourishment (literally or figuratively); by implication, rations (wages): food, meat.
  5060. Trophimos from trophe; nutritive; Trophimus, a Christian: Trophimus.
  5061. trophos from trepho; a nourisher, i.e. nurse: nurse.
  5062. trochia from trochos; a track (as a wheel-rut), i.e. (figuratively) a course of conduct: path.
  5063. trochos from trecho; a wheel (as a runner), i.e. (figuratively) a circuit of physical effects: course.
  5064. trublion neuter of a presumed derivative of uncertain affinity; a bowl: dish.
  5065. trugao from a derivative of trugo (to dry) meaning ripe fruit (as if dry); to collect the vintage: gather.
  5066. trugon from truzo (to murmur; akin to trizo, but denoting a duller sound); a turtle-dove (as cooing): turtle-dove.
  5067. trumalia from a derivative of truo (to wear away; akin to the base of trauma, tribos and trogo); an orifice, i.e. needle's eye: eye. Compare trupema.
  5068. trupema from a derivative of the base of trumalia; an aperture, i.e. a needle's eye: eye.
  5069. Truphaina from truphe; luxurious; Tryphna, a Christian woman: Tryphena.
  5070. truphao from truphe; to indulge in luxury: live in pleasure.
  5071. truphe from thrupto (to break up or (figuratively) enfeeble, especially the mind and body by indulgence); effeminacy, i.e. luxury or debauchery: delicately, riot.
  5072. Truphosa from truphe; luxuriating; Tryphosa, a Christian female: Tryphosa.
  5073. Troas from Tros (a Trojan); the Troad (or plain of Troy), i.e. Troas, a place in Asia Minor: Troas.
  5074. Trogullion of uncertain derivation; Trogyllium, a place in Asia Minor: Trogyllium.
  5075. trogo probably strengthened from a collateral form of the base of trauma and tribos through the idea of corrosion or wear; or perhaps rather of a base of trugon and trizo through the idea of a craunching sound; to gnaw or chew, i.e. (generally) to eat: eat.
  5076. tugchano probably for an obsolete tucho (for which the middle voice of another alternate teucho (to make ready or bring to pass) is used in certain tenses; akin to the base of tikto through the idea of effecting; properly, to affect; or (specially), to hit or light upon (as a mark to be reached), i.e. (transitively) to attain or secure an object or end, or (intransitively) to happen (as if meeting with); but in the latter application only impersonal (with ei), i.e. perchance; or (present participle) as adjective, usual (as if commonly met with, with ou, extraordinary), neuter (as adverb) perhaps; or (with another verb) as adverb, by accident (as it were): be, chance, enjoy, little, obtain, X refreshself, + special. Compare tupto.
  5077. tumpanizo from a derivative of tupto (meaning a drum, "tympanum"); to stretch on an instrument of torture resembling a drum, and thus beat to death: torture.
  5078. tupos from tupto; a die (as struck), i.e. (by implication) a stamp or scar; by analogy, a shape, i.e. a statue, (figuratively) style or resemblance; specially, a sampler ("type"), i.e. a model (for imitation) or instance (for warning): en-(ex-)ample, fashion, figure, form, manner, pattern, print.
  5079. tupto a primary verb (in a strengthened form); to "thump", i.e. cudgel or pummel (properly, with a stick or bastinado), but in any case by repeated blows; thus differing from paio and patasso, which denote a (usually single) blow with the hand or any instrument, or plesso with the fist (or a hammer), or rhapizo with the palm; as well as from tugchano, an accidental collision); by implication, to punish; figuratively, to offend (the conscience): beat, smite, strike, wound.
  5080. Turannos a provincial form of the derivative of the base of kurios; a "tyrant"; Tyrannus, an Ephesian: Tyrannus.
  5081. turbazo from turbe (Latin turba, a crowd; akin to thorubos); to make "turbid", i.e. disturb: trouble.
  5082. Turios from Turos; a Tyrian, i.e. inhabitant of Tyrus: of Tyre.
  5083. Turos of Hebrew origin (Tsor): Tyrus (i.e. Tsor), a place in Palestine: Tyre.
  5084. tuphlos from, tuphoo; opaque (as if smoky), i.e. (by analogy) blind (physically or mentally): blind.
  5085. tuphloo from tuphlos; to make blind, i.e. (figuratively) to obscure: blind.
  5086. tuphoo from a derivative of tupho; to envelop with smoke, i.e. (figuratively) to inflate with self-conceit: high-minded, be lifted up with pride, be proud.
  5087. tupho apparently a primary verb; to make a smoke, i.e. slowly consume without flame: smoke.
  5088. tuphonikos from a derivative of tupho; stormy (as if smoky): tempestuous.
  5089. Tuchikos from a derivative of tugchano; fortuitous, i.e. fortunate; Tychicus, a Christian: Tychicus.
  5090. huakinthinos from huakinthos; "hyacinthine" or "jacinthine", i.e. deep blue: jacinth.
  5091. huakinthos of uncertain derivation; the "hyacinth" or "jacinth", i.e. some gem of a deep blue color, probably the zirkon: jacinth.
  5092. hualinos from hualos; glassy, i.e. transparent: of glass.
  5093. hualos perhaps from the same as huetos (as being transparent like rain); glass: glass.
  5094. hubrizo from hubris; to exercise violence, i.e. abuse: use despitefully, reproach, entreat shamefully (spitefully).
  5095. hubris from huper; insolence (as over-bearing), i.e. insult, injury: harm, hurt, reproach.
  5096. hubristes from hubrizo; an insulter, i.e. maltreater: despiteful, injurious.
  5097. hugiaino from hugies; to have sound health, i.e. be well (in body); figuratively, to be uncorrupt (true in doctrine): be in health, (be safe and) sound, (be) whole(-some).
  5098. hugies from the base of auzano; healthy, i.e. well (in body); figuratively, true (in doctrine): sound, whole.
  5099. hugros from the base of huetos; wet (as if with rain), i.e. (by implication) sappy (fresh): green.
  5100. hudria from hudor; a water-jar, i.e. receptacle for family supply: water-pot.
  5101. hudropoteo from a compound of hudor and a derivative of pino; to be a water-drinker, i.e. to abstain from vinous beverages: drink water.
  5102. hudropikos from a compound of hudor and a derivative of optanomai (as if looking watery); to be "dropsical": have the dropsy.
  5103. hudor, and genitive case, hudatos, etc. from the base of huetos; water (as if rainy) literally or figuratively: water.
  5104. huetos from a primary huo (to rain); rain, especially a shower: rain.
  5105. huiothesia from a presumed compound of huios and a derivative of tithemi; the placing as a son, i.e. adoption (figuratively, Christian sonship in respect to God): adoption (of children, of sons).
  5106. huios apparently a primary word; a "son" (sometimes of animals), used very widely of immediate, remote or figuratively, kinship: child, foal, son.
  5107. hule perhaps akin to xulon; a forest, i.e. (by implication) fuel: matter.
  5108. humas accusative case of humeis; you (as the objective of a verb or preposition): ye, you (+ -ward), your (+ own).
  5109. humeis irregular plural of su; you (as subjective of verb): ye (yourselves), you.
  5110. Humenaios from Humen (the god of weddings); "hymenal"; Hymenus, an opponent of Christianity: Hymenus.
  5111. humeteros from humeis; yours, i.e. pertaining to you: your (own).
  5112. humin irregular dative case of humeis; to (with or by) you: ye, you, your(-selves).
  5113. humneo from humnos; to hymn, i.e. sing a religious ode; by implication, to celebrate (God) in song: sing a hymn (praise unto).
  5114. humnos apparently from a simpler (obsolete) form of hudeo (to celebrate; probably akin to aido; compare `abowt); a "hymn" or religious ode (one of the Psalms): hymn.
  5115. humon genitive case of humeis; of (from or concerning) you: ye, you, your (own, -selves).
  5116. hupago from hupo and ago; to lead (oneself) under, i.e. withdraw or retire (as if sinking out of sight), literally or figuratively: depart, get hence, go (a-)way.
  5117. hupakoe from hupakouo; attentive hearkening, i.e. (by implication) compliance or submission: obedience, (make) obedient, obey(-ing).
  5118. hupakouo from hupo and akouo; to hear under (as a subordinate), i.e. to listen attentively; by implication, to heed or conform to a command or authority: hearken, be obedient to, obey.
  5119. hupandros from hupo and aner; in subjection under a man, i.e. a married woman: which hath an husband.
  5120. hupantao from hupo and a derivative of anti; to go opposite (meet) under (quietly), i.e. to encounter, fall in with: (go to) meet.
  5121. hupantesis from hupantao; an encounter or concurrence (with eis for infinitive, in order to fall in with): meeting.
  5122. huparxis from huparcho; existency or proprietorship, i.e. (concretely) property, wealth: goods, substance.
  5123. huparchonta neuter plural of present participle active of huparcho as noun; things extant or in hand, i.e. property or possessions: goods, that which one has, things which (one) possesseth, substance, that hast.
  5124. huparcho from hupo and archomai; to begin under (quietly), i.e. come into existence (be present or at hand); expletively, to exist (as copula or subordinate to an adjective, participle, adverb or preposition, or as an auxiliary to a principal (verb): after, behave, live.
  5125. hipeiko from hupo and eiko (to yield, be "weak"); to surrender: submit self.
  5126. hupenantios from hupo and enantios; under (covertly) contrary to, i.e. opposed or (as noun) an opponent: adversary, against.
  5127. huper a primary preposition; "over", i.e. (with the genitive case) of place, above, beyond, across, or causal, for the sake of, instead, regarding; with the accusative case superior to, more than: (+ exceeding, abundantly) above, in (on) behalf of, beyond, by, + very chiefest, concerning, exceeding (above, -ly), for, + very highly, more (than), of, over, on the part of, for sake of, in stead, than, to(-ward), very. In the comparative, it retains many of the above applications.
  5128. huperairomai middle voice from huper and airo; to raise oneself over, i.e. (figuratively) to become haughty: exalt self, be exalted above measure.
  5129. huperakmos from huper and the base of akmen; beyond the "acme", i.e. figuratively (of a daughter) past the bloom (prime) of youth: + pass the flower of (her) age.
  5130. huperano from huper and ano; above upward, i.e. greatly higher (in place or rank): far above, over.
  5131. huperauxano from huper and auzano; to increase above ordinary degree: grow exceedingly.
  5132. huperbaino from huper and the base of basis; to transcend, i.e. (figuratively) to overreach: go beyond.
  5133. huperballontos adverb from present participle active of huperballo; excessively: beyond measure.
  5134. huperballo from huper and ballo; to throw beyod the usual mark, i.e. (figuratively) to surpass (only active participle supereminent): exceeding, excel, pass.
  5135. huperbole from huperballo; a throwing beyond others, i.e. (figuratively) supereminence; adverbially (with eis or kata) pre- eminently: abundance, (far more) exceeding, excellency, more excellent, beyond (out of) measure.
  5136. hupereido from huper and eido; to overlook, i.e. not punish: wink at.
  5137. huperekeina from huper and the neuter plural of ekeinos; above those parts, i.e. still farther: beyond.
  5138. huperekteino from huper and ekteino; to extend inordinately: stretch beyond.
  5139. huperekchuno from huper and the alternate form of ekcheo; to pour out over, i.e. (passively) to overflow: run over.
  5140. huperentugchano from huper and entugchano; to intercede in behalf of: make intercession for.
  5141. huperecho from huper and echo; to hold oneself above, i.e. (figuratively) to excel; participle (as adjective, or neuter as noun) superior, superiority: better, excellency, higher, pass, supreme.
  5142. huperephania from huperephanos; haughtiness: pride.
  5143. huperephanos from huper and phaino; appearing above others (conspicuous), i.e. (figuratively) haughty: proud.
  5144. hupernikao from huper and nikao; to vanquish beyond, i.e. gain a decisive victory: more than conquer.
  5145. huperogkos from huper and ogkos; bulging over, i.e. (figuratively) insolent: great swelling.
  5146. huperoche from huperecho; prominence, i.e. (figuratively) superiority (in rank or character): authority, excellency.
  5147. huperperisseuo from huper and perisseuo; to super-abound: abound much more, exceeding.
  5148. huperperissos from huper and perissos; superabundantly, i.e. exceedingly: beyond measure.
  5149. huperpleonazo from huper and pleonazo; to superabound: be exceeding abundant.
  5150. huperupsoo from huper and hupsoo; to elevate above others, i.e. raise to the highest position: highly exalt.
  5151. huperphroneo from huper and phroneo; to esteem oneself overmuch, i.e. be vain or arrogant: think more highly.
  5152. huperoion neuter of a derivative of huper; a higher part of the house, i.e. apartment in the third story: upper chamber (room).
  5153. hupecho from hupo and echo; to hold oneself under, i.e. endure with patience: suffer.
  5154. hupekoos from hupakouo; attentively listening, i.e. (by implication) submissive: obedient.
  5155. hupereteo from huperetes; to be a subordinate, i.e. (by implication) subserve: minister (unto), serve.
  5156. huperetes from hupo and a derivative of eresso (to row); an under-oarsman, i.e. (generally) subordinate (assistant, sexton, constable): minister, officer, servant.
  5157. hupnos from an obsolete primary (perhaps akin to hupo through the idea of subsilience); sleep, i.e. (figuratively) spiritual torpor: sleep.
  5158. hupo a primary preposition; under, i.e. (with the genitive case) of place (beneath), or with verbs (the agency or means, through); (with the accusative case) of place (whither (underneath) or where (below) or time (when (at)): among, by, from, in, of, under, with. In the comparative, it retains the same general applications, especially of inferior position or condition, and specially, covertly or moderately.
  5159. hupoballo from hupo and ballo; to throw in stealthily, i.e. introduce by collusion: suborn.
  5160. hupogrammos from a compound of hupo and grapho; an underwriting, i.e. copy for imitation (figuratively): example.
  5161. hupodeigma from hupodeiknumi; an exhibit for imitation or warning (figuratively, specimen, adumbration): en-(ex-)ample, pattern.
  5162. hupodeiknumi from hupo and deiknuo; to exhibit under the eyes, i.e. (figuratively) to exemplify (instruct, admonish): show, (fore-)warn.
  5163. hupodechomai from hupo and dechomai; to admit under one's roof, i.e. entertain hospitably: receive.
  5164. hupodeo from hupo and deo; to bind under one's feet, i.e. put on shoes or sandals: bind on, (be) shod.
  5165. hupodema from hupodeo; something bound under the feet, i.e. a shoe or sandal: shoe.
  5166. hupodikos from hupo and dike; under sentence, i.e. (by implication) condemned: guilty.
  5167. hupozugion neuter of a compound of hupo and zugos; an animal under the yoke (draught-beast), i.e. (specially), a donkey: ass.
  5168. hupozonnumi from hupo and zonnumi; to gird under, i.e. frap (a vessel with cables across the keel, sides and deck): undergirt.
  5169. hupokato from hupo and kato; down under, i.e. beneath: under.
  5170. hupokrinomai middle voice from hupo and krino; to decide (speak or act) under a false part, i.e. (figuratively) dissemble (pretend): feign.
  5171. hupokrisis from hupokrinomai; acting under a feigned part, i.e. (figuratively) deceit ("hypocrisy"): condemnation, dissimulation, hypocrisy.
  5172. hupokrites from hupokrinomai; an actor under an assumed character (stage-player), i.e. (figuratively) a dissembler ("hypocrite": hypocrite.
  5173. hupolambano from hupo and lambano; to take from below, i.e. carry upward; figuratively, to take up, i.e. continue a discourse or topic; mentally, to assume (presume): answer, receive, suppose.
  5174. hupoleipo from hupotrecho and leipo; to leave under (behind), i.e. (passively) to remain (survive): be left.
  5175. hupolenion neuter of a presumed compound of hupo and lenos; vessel or receptacle under the press, i.e. lower wine-vat: winefat.
  5176. hupolimpano a prolonged form for hupoleipo; to leave behind, i.e. bequeath: leave.
  5177. hupomeno from hupo and meno; to stay under (behind), i.e. remain; figuratively, to undergo, i.e. bear (trials), have fortitude, persevere: abide, endure, (take) patient(-ly), suffer, tarry behind.
  5178. hupomimnesko from hupo and mimnesko; to remind quietly, i.e. suggest to the (middle voice, one's own) memory: put in mind, remember, bring to (put in) remembrance.
  5179. hupomnesis from hupomimnesko; a reminding or (reflexively) recollection: remembrance.
  5180. hupomone from hupomeno; cheerful (or hopeful) endurance, constancy: enduring, patience, patient continuance (waiting).
  5181. huponoeo from hupo and noieo; to think under (privately), i.e. to surmise or conjecture: think, suppose, deem.
  5182. huponoia from huponoeo; suspicion: surmising.
  5183. hupopleo from hupo and pleo; to sail under the lee of: sail under.
  5184. hupopneo from hupo and pneo; to breathe gently, i.e. breeze: blow softly.
  5185. hupopodion neuter of a compound of hupo and pous; something under the feet, i.e. a foot-rest (figuratively): footstool.
  5186. hupostasis from a compound of hupo and histemi; a setting under (support), i.e. (figuratively) concretely, essence, or abstractly, assurance (objectively or subjectively): confidence, confident, person, substance.
  5187. hupostello from hupo and stello; to withhold under (out of sight), i.e. (reflexively) to cower or shrink, (figuratively) to conceal (reserve): draw (keep) back, shun, withdraw.
  5188. hupostole from hupostello; shrinkage (timidity), i.e. (by implication) apostasy: draw back.
  5189. hupostrepho from hupo and strepho; to turn under (behind), i.e. to return (literally or figuratively): come again, return (again, back again), turn back (again).
  5190. hupostronnumi from hupo and stronnumi; to strew underneath (the feet as a carpet): spread.
  5191. hupotage from hupotasso; subordination: subjection.
  5192. hupotasso from hupo and tasso; to subordinate; reflexively, to obey: be under obedience (obedient), put under, subdue unto, (be, make) subject (to, unto), be (put) in subjection (to, under), submit self unto.
  5193. hupotithemi from hupo and tithemi; to place underneath, i.e. (figuratively) to hazard, (reflexively) to suggest: lay down, put in remembrance.
  5194. hupotrecho from hupo and trecho (including its alternate); to run under, i.e. (specially), to sail past: run under.
  5195. hupotuposis from a compound of hupo and a derivative of tupos; typification under (after), i.e. (concretely) a sketch (figuratively) for imitation: form, pattern.
  5196. hupophero from hupo and phero; to bear from underneath, i.e. (figuratively) to undergo hardship: bear, endure.
  5197. hupochoreo from hupo and choreo; to vacate down, i.e. retire quietly: go aside, withdraw self.
  5198. hupopiazo from a compound of hupo and a derivative of optanomai; to hit under the eye (buffet or disable an antagonist as a pugilist), i.e. (figuratively) to tease or annoy (into compliance), subdue (one's passions): keep under, weary.
  5199. hus apparently a primary word; a hog ("swine"): sow.
  5200. hussopos of foreign origin ('ezowb); "hyssop": hyssop.
  5201. hustereo from husteros; to be later, i.e. (by implication) to be inferior; generally, to fall short (be deficient): come behind (short), be destitute, fail, lack, suffer need, (be in) want, be the worse.
  5202. husterema from hustereo; a deficit; specially, poverty: that which is behind, (that which was) lack(-ing), penury, want.
  5203. husteresis from hustereo; a falling short, i.e. (specially), penury: want.
  5204. husteron neuter of husteros as adverb; more lately, i.e. eventually: afterward, (at the) last (of all).
  5205. husteros comparative from hupo (in the sense of behind); later: latter.
  5206. huphantos from huphaino to weave; woven, i.e. (perhaps) knitted: woven.
  5207. hupselos from hupsos; lofty (in place or character): high(-er, -ly) (esteemed).
  5208. hupselophroneo from a compound of hupselos and phren; to be lofty in mind, i.e. arrogant: be highminded.
  5209. hupsistos superlative from the base of hupsos; highest, i.e. (masculine singular) the Supreme (God), or (neuter plural) the heavens: most high, highest.
  5210. hupsos from a derivative of huper; elevation, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, (specially), the sky, or (figuratively) dignity: be exalted, height, (on) high.
  5211. hupsoo from hupsos; to elevate (literally or figuratively): exalt, lift up.
  5212. hupsoma from hupsoo; an elevated place or thing, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, or (by implication) a barrier (figuratively): height, high thing.
  5213. phagos from phago; a glutton: gluttonous.
  5214. phago a primary verb (used as an alternate of esthio in certain tenses); to eat (literally or figuratively): eat, meat.
  5215. phaino prolongation for the base of phos; to lighten (shine), i.e. show (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative): appear, seem, be seen, shine, X think.
  5216. Phalek of Hebrew origin (Peleg); Phalek (i.e. Peleg), a patriarch: Phalec.
  5217. phaneros from phaino; shining, i.e. apparent (literally or figuratively); neuter (as adverb) publicly, externally: abroad, + appear, known, manifest, open (+ -ly), outward (+ -ly).
  5218. phaneroo from phaneros; to render apparent (literally or figuratively): appear, manifestly declare, (make) manifest (forth), shew (self).
  5219. phaneros adverb from phaneros; plainly, i.e. clearly or publicly: evidently, openly.
  5220. phanerosis from phaneroo; exhibition, i.e. (figuratively) expression, (by extension) a bestowment: manifestation.
  5221. phanos from phaino; a lightener, i.e. light; lantern: lantern.
  5222. Phanouel of Hebrew origin (Pnuw'el); Phanuel (i.e. Penuel), an Israelite: Phanuel.
  5223. phantazo from a derivative of phaino; to make apparent, i.e. (passively) to appear (neuter participle as noun, a spectacle): sight.
  5224. phantasia from a derivative of phantazo; (properly abstract) a (vain) show ("fantasy"): pomp.
  5225. phantasma from phantazo; (properly concrete) a (mere) show ("phantasm"), i.e. spectre: spirit.
  5226. pharagx properly, strengthened from the base of peran or rather of rhegnumi; a gap or chasm, i.e. ravine (winter-torrent): valley.
  5227. Pharao of foreign origin (Par`oh); Pharao (i.e. Pharoh), an Egyptian king: Pharaoh.
  5228. Phares of Hebrew origin (Perets); Phares (i.e. Perets), an Israelite: Phares.
  5229. Pharisaios of Hebrew origin (compare parash); a separatist, i.e. exclusively religious; a Pharisean, i.e. Jewish sectary: Pharisee.
  5230. pharmakeia from pharmakeus; medication ("pharmacy"), i.e. (by extension) magic (literally or figuratively): sorcery, witchcraft.
  5231. pharmakeus from pharmakon (a drug, i.e. spell-giving potion); a druggist ("pharmacist") or poisoner, i.e. (by extension) a magician: sorcerer.
  5232. pharmakos the same as pharmakeus: sorcerer.
  5233. phasis from phemi (not the same as "phase", which is from phaino); a saying, i.e. report: tidings.
  5234. phasko prolongation from the same as phemi; to assert: affirm, profess, say.
  5235. phatne from pateomai (to eat); a crib (for fodder): manager, stall.
  5236. phaulos apparently a primary word; "foul" or "flawy", i.e. (figuratively) wicked: evil.
  5237. pheggos probably akin to the base of phos (compare phtheggomai); brilliancy: light.
  5238. pheidomai of uncertain affinity; to be chary of, i.e. (subjectively) to abstain or (objectively) to treat leniently: forbear, spare.
  5239. pheidomenos adverb from participle of pheidomai; abstemiously, i.e. stingily: sparingly.
  5240. phelones by transposition for a derivative probably of phaino (as showing outside the other garments); a mantle (surtout): cloke.
  5241. phero a primary verb -- for which other, and apparently not cognate ones are used in certain tenses only; namely, oio oy'-o; and enegko en-eng'-ko; to "bear" or carry (in a very wide application, literally and figuratively, as follows): be, bear, bring (forth), carry, come, + let her drive, be driven, endure, go on, lay, lead, move, reach, rushing, uphold.
  5242. pheugo apparently a primary verb; to run away (literally or figuratively); by implication, to shun; by analogy, to vanish: escape, flee (away).
  5243. Phelix of Latin origin; happy; Phelix (i.e. Felix), a Roman: Felix.
  5244. pheme from phemi; a saying, i.e. rumor ("fame"): fame.
  5245. phemi properly, the same as the base of phos and phaino; to show or make known one's thoughts, i.e. speak or say: affirm, say. Compare lego.
  5246. Phestos of Latin derivation; festal; Phestus (i.e. Festus), a Roman: Festus.
  5247. phthano apparently a primary verb; to be beforehand, i.e. anticipate or precede; by extension, to have arrived at: (already) attain, come, prevent.
  5248. phthartos from phtheiro; decayed, i.e. (by implication) perishable: corruptible.
  5249. phtheggomai probably akin to pheggos and thus to phemi; to utter a clear sound, i.e. (generally) to proclaim: speak.
  5250. phtheiro probably strengthened from phthio (to pine or waste); properly, to shrivel or wither, i.e. to spoil (by any process) or (generally) to ruin (especially figuratively, by moral influences, to deprave): corrupt (self), defile, destroy.
  5251. phthinoporinos from derivative of phthino (to wane; akin to the base of phtheiro) and opora (meaning late autumn); autumnal (as stripped of leaves): whose fruit withereth.
  5252. phthoggos from phtheggomai; utterance, i.e. a musical note (vocal or instrumental): sound.
  5253. phthoneo from phthonos; to be jealous of: envy.
  5254. phthonos probably akin to the base of phtheiro; ill-will (as detraction), i.e. jealousy (spite): envy.
  5255. phthora from phtheiro; decay, i.e. ruin (spontaneous or inflicted, literally or figuratively): corruption, destroy, perish.
  5256. phiale of uncertain affinity; a broad shallow cup ("phial"): vial.
  5257. philagathos from philos and agathos; fond to good, i.e. a promoter of virtue: love of good men.
  5258. Philadelpheia from Philadelphos (the same as philadelphos), a king of Pergamos; Philadelphia, a place in Asia Minor: Philadelphia.
  5259. philadelphia from philadelphos; fraternal affection: brotherly love (kindness), love of the brethren.
  5260. philadelphos from philos and adephos; fond of brethren, i.e. fraternal: love as brethren.
  5261. philandros from philos and aner; fond of man, i.e. affectionate as a wife: love their husbands.
  5262. philanthropia from the same as philanthropos; fondness of mankind, i.e. benevolence ("philanthropy"): kindness, love towards man.
  5263. philanthropos adverb from a compound of philos and anthropos; fondly to man ("philanthropically"), i.e. humanely: courteously.
  5264. philarguria from philarguros; avarice: love of money.
  5265. philarguros from philos and arguros; fond of silver (money), i.e. avaricious: covetous.
  5266. philautos from philos and autos; fond of self, i.e. selfish: lover of own self.
  5267. phileo from philos; to be a friend to (fond of (an individual or an object)), i.e. have affection for (denoting personal attachment, as a matter of sentiment or feeling; while agapao is wider, embracing especially the judgment and the deliberate assent of the will as a matter of principle, duty and propriety: the two thus stand related very much as thelo and boulomai, or as thumos and nous respectively; the former being chiefly of the heart and the latter of the head); specially, to kiss (as a mark of tenderness): kiss, love.
  5268. philedonos from philos and hedone; fond of pleasure, i.e. voluptuous: lover of pleasure.
  5269. philema from phileo; a kiss: kiss.
  5270. Philemon from phileo; friendly; Philemon, a Christian: Philemon.
  5271. Philetos from phileo; amiable; Philetus, an opposer of Christianity: Philetus.
  5272. philia from philos; fondness: friendship.
  5273. Philippesios from Philippoi; a Philippesian (Philippian), i.e. native of Philippi: Philippian.
  5274. Philippoi plural of Philippos; Philippi, a place in Macedonia: Philippi.
  5275. Philippos from philos and hippos; fond of horses; Philippus, the name of four Israelites: Philip.
  5276. philotheos from philos and theos; fond of God, i.e. pious: lover of God.
  5277. Philologos from philos and logos; fond of words, i.e. talkative (argumentative, learned, "philological"); Philologus, a Christian: Philologus.
  5278. philoneikia from philoneikos; quarrelsomeness, i.e. a dispute: strife.
  5279. philoneikos from philos and neikos (a quarrel; probably akin to nikos); fond of strife, i.e. disputatious: contentious.
  5280. philonexia from philoxenos; hospitableness: entertain stranger, hospitality.
  5281. philoxenos from philos and xenos; fond of guests, i.e. hospitable: given to (lover of, use) hospitality.
  5282. philoproteuo from a compound of philos and protos; to be fond of being first, i.e. ambitious of distinction: love to have the preeminence.
  5283. philos properly, dear, i.e. a friend; actively, fond, i.e. friendly (still as a noun, an associate, neighbor, etc.): friend.
  5284. philosophia from philosophos; "philosophy", i.e. (specially), Jewish sophistry: philosophy.
  5285. philosophos from philos and sophos; fond of wise things, i.e. a "philosopher": philosopher.
  5286. philostorgos from philos and storge (cherishing one's kindred, especially parents or children); fond of natural relatives, i.e. fraternal towards fellow Christian: kindly affectioned.
  5287. philoteknos from philos and teknon; fond of one's children, i.e. maternal: love their children.
  5288. philotimeomai middle voice from a compound of philos and time; to be fond of honor, i.e. emulous (eager or earnest to do something): labour, strive, study.
  5289. philophronos adverb from philophron; with friendliness of mind, i.e. kindly: courteously.
  5290. philophron from philos and phren; friendly of mind, i.e. kind: courteous.
  5291. phimoo from phimos (a muzzle); to muzzle: muzzle.
  5292. Phlegon active participle of the base of phlox; blazing; Phlegon, a Christian: Phlegon.
  5293. phlogizo from phlox; to cause a blaze, i.e. ignite (figuratively, to inflame with passion): set on fire.
  5294. phlox from a primary phlego (to "flash" or "flame"); a blaze: flame(-ing).
  5295. phluareo from phluaros; to be a babbler or trifler, i.e. (by implication) to berate idly or mischievously: prate against.
  5296. phluaros from phluo (to bubble); a garrulous person, i.e. prater: tattler.
  5297. phoberos from phobos; frightful, i.e. (objectively) formidable: fearful, terrible.
  5298. phobeo from phobos; to frighten, i.e. (passively) to be alarmed; by analogy, to be in awe of, i.e. revere: be (+ sore) afraid, fear (exceedingly), reverence.
  5299. phobetron neuter of a derivative of phobeo; a frightening thing, i.e. terrific portent: fearful sight.
  5300. phobos from a primary phebomai (to be put in fear); alarm or fright: be afraid, + exceedingly, fear, terror.
  5301. Phoibe feminine of phoibos (bright; probably akin to the base of phos); Phbe, a Christian woman: Phebe.
  5302. Phoinike from phoinix; palm-country; Phnice (or Phnicia), a region of Palestine: Phenice, Phenicia.
  5303. phoinix of uncertain derivation; a palm-tree: palm (tree).
  5304. Phoinix probably the same as phoinix; Phnix, a place in Crete: Phenice.
  5305. phoneus from phonos; a murderer (always of criminal (or at least intentional) homicide; which anthropoktonos does not necessarily imply; while sikarios is a special term for a public bandit): murderer.
  5306. phoneuo from phoneus; to be a murderer (of): kill, do murder, slay.
  5307. phonos from an obsolete primary pheno (to slay); murder: murder, + be slain with, slaughter.
  5308. phoreo from phoros; to have a burden, i.e. (by analogy) to wear as clothing or a constant accompaniment: bear, wear.
  5309. Phoron of Latin origin; a forum or market-place; only in comparative with Appios; a station on the Appian road: forum.
  5310. phoros from phero; a load (as borne), i.e. (figuratively) a tax (properly, an individual assessment on persons or property; whereas telos is usually a general toll on goods or travel): tribute.
  5311. phortizo from phortos; to load up (properly, as a vessel or animal), i.e. (figuratively) to overburden with ceremony (or spiritual anxiety): lade, by heavy laden.
  5312. phortion diminutive of phortos; an invoice (as part of freight), i.e. (figuratively) a task or service: burden.
  5313. phortos from phero; something carried, i.e. the cargo of a ship: lading.
  5314. Phortounatos of Latin origin; "fortunate"; Fortunatus, a Christian: Fortunatus.
  5315. phragellion neuter of a derivative from the base of phragelloo; a whip, i.e. Roman lash as a public punishment: scourge.
  5316. phragelloo from a presumed equivalent of the Latin flagellum; to whip, i.e. lash as a public punishment: scourge.
  5317. phragmos from phrasso; a fence, or inclosing barrier (literally or figuratively): hedge (+ round about), partition.
  5318. phrazo probably akin to phrasso through the idea of defining; to indicate (by word or act), i.e. (specially), to expound: declare.
  5319. phrasso apparently a strengthening form of the base of phren; to fence or inclose, i.e. (specially), to block up (figuratively, to silence): stop.
  5320. phrear of uncertain derivation; a hole in the ground (dug for obtaining or holding water or other purposes), i.e. a cistern or well; figuratively, an abyss (as a prison): well, pit.
  5321. phrenapatao from phrenapates; to be a mind-misleader, i.e. delude: deceive.
  5322. phrenapates from phren and apate; a mind-misleader, i.e. seducer: deceiver.
  5323. phren probably from an obsolete phrao (to rein in or curb; compare phrasso); the midrif (as a partition of the body), i.e. (figuratively and by implication, of sympathy) the feelings (or sensitive nature; by extension (also in the plural) the mind or cognitive faculties): understanding.
  5324. phrisso apparently a primary verb; to "bristle" or chill, i.e. shudder (fear): tremble.
  5325. phroneo from phren; to exercise the mind, i.e. entertain or have a sentiment or opinion; by implication, to be (mentally) disposed (more or less earnestly in a certain direction); intensively, to interest oneself in (with concern or obedience): set the affection on, (be) care(-ful), (be like-, + be of one, + be of the same, + let this) mind(-ed), regard, savour, think.
  5326. phronema from phroneo; (mental) inclination or purpose: (be, + be carnally, + be spiritually) mind(-ed).
  5327. phronesis from phroneo; mental action or activity, i.e. intellectual or moral insight: prudence, wisdom.
  5328. phronimos from phren; thoughtful, i.e. sagacious or discreet (implying a cautious character; while sophos denotes practical skill or acumen; and sunetos indicates rather intelligence or mental acquirement); in a bad sense conceited (also in the comparative): wise(-r).
  5329. phronimos adverb from phronimos; prudently: wisely.
  5330. phrontizo from a derivative of phren; to exercise thought, i.e. be anxious: be careful.
  5331. phroureo from a compound of pro and horao; to be a watcher in advance, i.e. to mount guard as a sentinel (post spies at gates); figuratively, to hem in, protect: keep (with a garrison). Compare tereo.
  5332. phruasso akin to bruo, brucho; to snort (as a spirited horse), i.e. (figuratively) to make a tumult: rage.
  5333. phruganon neuter of a presumed derivative of phrugo (to roast or parch; akin to the base of phlox); something desiccated, i.e. a dry twig: stick.
  5334. Phrugia probably of foreign origin; Phrygia, a region of Asia Minor: Phrygia.
  5335. Phugellos probably from pheugo; fugitive; Phygellus, an apostate Christian: Phygellus.
  5336. phuge from pheugo; a fleeing, i.e. escape: flight.
  5337. phulake from phulasso; a guarding or (concretely, guard), the act, the person; figuratively, the place, the condition, or (specially), the time (as a division of day or night), literally or figuratively: cage, hold, (im-)prison(-ment), ward, watch.
  5338. phulakizo from phulax; to incarcerate: imprison.
  5339. phulakterion neuter of a derivative of phulasso; a guard-case, i.e. "phylactery" for wearing slips of Scripture texts: phylactery.
  5340. phulax from phulasso; a watcher or sentry: keeper.
  5341. phulasso probably from phule through the idea of isolation; to watch, i.e. be on guard (literally of figuratively); by implication, to preserve, obey, avoid: beward, keep (self), observe, save. Compare tereo.
  5342. phule from phuo (compare phullon); an offshoot, i.e. race or clan: kindred, tribe.
  5343. phullon from the same as phule; a sprout, i.e. leaf: leaf.
  5344. phurama from a prolonged form of phuro (to mix a liquid with a solid; perhaps akin to phuo through the idea of swelling in bulk), mean to knead; a mass of dough: lump.
  5345. phusikos from phusis; "physical", i.e. (by implication) instinctive: natural. Compare psuchikos.
  5346. phusikos adverb from phusikos; "physically", i.e. (by implication) instinctively: naturally.
  5347. phusioo from phusis in the primary sense of blowing; to inflate, i.e. (figuratively) make proud (haughty): puff up.
  5348. phusis from phuo; growth (by germination or expansion), i.e. (by implication) natural production (lineal descent); by extension, a genus or sort; figuratively, native disposition, constitution or usage: (man-)kind, nature(-al).
  5349. phusiosis from phusioo; inflation, i.e. (figuratively) haughtiness: swelling.
  5350. phuteia from phuteuo; trans-planting, i.e. (concretely) a shrub or vegetable: plant.
  5351. phuteuo from a derivative of phuo; to set out in the earth, i.e. implant; figuratively, to instil doctrine: plant.
  5352. phuo a primary verb; probably originally, to "puff" or blow, i.e. to swell up; but only used in the implied sense, to germinate or grow (sprout, produce), literally or figuratively: spring (up).
  5353. pholeos of uncertain derivative; a burrow or lurking-place: hole.
  5354. phoneo from phone; to emit a sound (animal, human or instrumental); by implication, to address in words or by name, also in imitation: call (for), crow, cry.
  5355. phone probably akin to phaino through the idea of disclosure; a tone (articulate, bestial or artificial); by implication, an address (for any purpose), saying or language: noise, sound, voice.
  5356. phos from an obsolete phao (to shine or make manifest, especially by rays; compare phaino, phemi); luminousness (in the widest application, natural or artificial, abstract or concrete, literal or figurative): fire, light.
  5357. phoster from phos; an illuminator, i.e. (concretely) a luminary, or (abstractly) brilliancy: light.
  5358. phosphoros from phos and phero; light-bearing ("phosphorus"), i.e. (specially), the morning-star (figuratively): day star.
  5359. photeinos from phos; lustrous, i.e. transparent or well-illuminated (figuratively): bright, full of light.
  5360. photizo from phos; to shed rays, i.e. to shine or (transitively) to brighten up (literally or figuratively): enlighten, illuminate, (bring to, give) light, make to see.
  5361. photismos from photizo; illumination (figuratively): light.
  5362. chairo a primary verb; to be "cheer"ful, i.e. calmly happy or well-off; impersonally, especially as salutation (on meeting or parting), be well: farewell, be glad, God speed, greeting, hall, joy(- fully), rejoice.
  5363. chalaza probably from chalao; hail: hail.
  5364. chalao from the base of chasma; to lower (as into a void): let down, strike.
  5365. Chaldaios probably of Hebrew or (Kasdiy); a Chaldan (i.e. Kasdi), or native or the region of the lower Euphrates: Chaldan.
  5366. chalepos perhaps from chalao through the idea of reducing the strength; difficult, i.e. dangerous, or (by implication) furious: fierce, perilous.
  5367. chalinagogeo from a compound of chalinos and the reduplicated form of ago; to be a bit-leader, i.e. to curb (figuratively): bridle.
  5368. chalinos from chalao; a curb or head-stall (as curbing the spirit): bit, bridle.
  5369. chalkeos from chalkos; coppery: brass.
  5370. chalkeus from chalkos; a copper-worker or brazier: coppersmith.
  5371. chalkedon from chalkos and perhaps eidos; copper-like, i.e. "chalcedony": chalcedony.
  5372. chalkion diminutive from chalkos; a copper dish: brazen vessel.
  5373. chalkolibanon neuter of a compound of chalkos and libanos (in the implied mean of whiteness or brilliancy); burnished copper, an alloy of copper (or gold) and silver having a brilliant lustre: fine brass.
  5374. chalkos perhaps from chalao through the idea of hollowing out as a vessel (this metal being chiefly used for that purpose); copper (the substance, or some implement or coin made of it): brass, money.
  5375. chamai adverb perhaps from the base of chasma through the idea of a fissure in the soil; earthward, i.e. prostrate: on (to) the ground.
  5376. Chanaan of Hebrew origin (Kna`an); Chanaan (i.e. Kenaan), the early name of Palestine: Chanaan.
  5377. Chanaanaios from Chanaan; a Chanaanan (i.e. Kenaanite), or native of gentile Palestine: of Canaan.
  5378. chara from chairo; cheerfulness, i.e. calm delight: gladness, X greatly, (X be exceeding) joy(-ful, -fully, -fulness, -ous).
  5379. charagma from the same as charax; a scratch or etching, i.e. stamp (as a badge of servitude), or scupltured figure (statue): graven, mark.
  5380. charakter from the same as charax; a graver (the tool or the person), i.e. (by implication) engraving (("character"), the figure stamped, i.e. an exact copy or (figuratively) representation): express image.
  5381. charax from charasso (to sharpen to a point; akin to grapho through the idea of scratching); a stake, i.e. (by implication) a palisade or rampart (military mound for circumvallation in a siege): trench.
  5382. charizomai middle voice from charis; to grant as a favor, i.e. gratuitously, in kindness, pardon or rescue: deliver, (frankly) forgive, (freely) give, grant.
  5383. charin accusative case of charis as preposition; through favor of, i.e. on account of: be-(for) cause of, for sake of, +fore, X reproachfully.
  5384. charis from chairo; graciousness (as gratifying), of manner or act (abstract or concrete; literal, figurative or spiritual; especially the divine influence upon the heart, and its reflection in the life; including gratitude): acceptable, benefit, favour, gift, grace(- ious), joy, liberality, pleasure, thank(-s, -worthy).
  5385. charisma from charizomai; a (divine) gratuity, i.e. deliverance (from danger or passion); (specially), a (spiritual) endowment, i.e. (subjectively) religious qualification, or (objectively) miraculous faculty: (free) gift.
  5386. charitoo from charis; to grace, i.e. indue with special honor: make accepted, be highly favoured.
  5387. Charrhan of Hebrew origin (Charan); Charrhan (i.e. Charan), a place in Mesopotamia: Charran.
  5388. chartes from the same as charax; a sheet ("chart") of writing-material (as to be scribbled over): paper.
  5389. chasma from a form of an obsolete primary chao (to "gape" or "yawn"); a "chasm" or vacancy (impassable interval): gulf.
  5390. cheilos from a form of the same as chasma; a lip (as a pouring place); figuratively, a margin (of water): lip, shore.
  5391. cheimazo from the same as cheimon; to storm, i.e. (passively) to labor under a gale: be tossed with tempest.
  5392. cheimarrhos from the base of cheimon and rheo; a storm-runlet, i.e. winter-torrent: brook.
  5393. cheimon from a derivative of cheo (to pour; akin to the base of chasma through the idea of a channel), meaning a storm (as pouring rain); by implication, the rainy season, i.e. winter: tempest, foul weather, winter.
  5394. cheir perhaps from the base of cheimon in the sense of its congener the base of chasma (through the idea of hollowness for grasping); the hand (literally or figuratively (power); especially (by Hebraism) a means or instrument): hand.
  5395. cheiragogeo from cheiragogos; to be a hand-leader, i.e. to guide (a blind person): lead by the hand.
  5396. cheiragogos from cheir and a reduplicated form of ago; a hand-leader, i.e. personal conductor (of a blind person): some to lead by the hand.
  5397. cheirographon neuter of a compound of cheir and grapho; something hand-written ("chirograph"), i.e. a manuscript (specially, a legal document or bond (figuratively)): handwriting.
  5398. cheiropoietos from cheir and a derivative of poieo; manufactured, i.e. of human construction: made by (make with) hands.
  5399. cheirotoneo from a comparative of cheir and teino (to stretch); to be a hand-reacher or voter (by raising the hand), i.e. (generally) to select or appoint: choose, ordain.
  5400. cheiron irregular comparative of kakos; from an obsolete equivalent cheres (of uncertain derivation); more evil or aggravated (physically, mentally or morally): sorer, worse.
  5401. cheroubim plural of Hebrew origin (kruwb); "cherubim" (i.e. cherubs or kerubim): cherubims.
  5402. chera feminine of a presumed derivative apparently from the base of chasma through the idea of deficiency; a widow (as lacking a husband), literally or figuratively: widow.
  5403. chthes of uncertain derivation; "yesterday"; by extension, in time past or hitherto: yesterday.
  5404. chilias from chilioi; one thousand ("chiliad"): thousand.
  5405. chiliarchos from chilioi and archo; the commander of a thousand soldiers ("chiliarch"; i.e. colonel: (chief, high) captain.
  5406. chilioi plural of uncertain affinity; a thousand: thousand.
  5407. Chios of uncertain derivation; Chios, an island in the Mediterranean: Chios.
  5408. chiton of foreign origin (kthoneth); a tunic or shirt: clothes, coat, garment.
  5409. chion perhaps akin to the base of chasma (chalao) or cheimon (as descending or empty); snow: snow.
  5410. chlamus of uncertain derivation; a military cloak: robe.
  5411. chleuazo from a derivative probably of cheilos; to throw out the lip, i.e. jeer at: mock.
  5412. chliaros from chlio (to warm); tepid: lukewarm.
  5413. Chloe feminine of apparently a primary word; "green"; Chlo, a Christian female: Chloe.
  5414. chloros from the same as Chloe; greenish, i.e. verdant, dun-colored: green, pale.
  5415. chi xi stigma the 22nd, 14th and an obsolete letter (stigma as a cross) of the Greek alphabet (intermediate between the 5th and 6th), used as numbers; denoting respectively 600, 60 and 6; 666 as a numeral: six hundred threescore and six.
  5416. choikos from choos; dusty or dirty (soil-like), i.e. (by implication) terrene: earthy.
  5417. choinix of uncertain derivation; a chnix or certain dry measure: measure.
  5418. choiros of uncertain derivation; a hog: swine.
  5419. cholao from chole; to be bilious, i.e. (by implication) irritable (enraged, "choleric"): be angry.
  5420. chole feminine of an equivalent perhaps akin to the same as Chloe (from the greenish hue); "gall" or bile, i.e. (by analogy) poison or an anodyne (wormwood, poppy, etc.): gall.
  5421. choos from the base of cheimon; a heap (as poured out), i.e. rubbish; loose dirt: dust.
  5422. Chorazin of uncertain derivation; Chorazin, a place in Palestine: Chorazin.
  5423. choregeo from a compound of choros and ago; to be a dance-leader, i.e. (generally) to furnish: give, minister.
  5424. choros of uncertain derivation; a ring, i.e. round dance ("choir": dancing.
  5425. chortazo from chortos; to fodder, i.e. (generally) to gorge (supply food in abundance): feed, fill, satisfy.
  5426. chortasma from chortazo; forage, i.e. food: sustenance.
  5427. chortos apparently a primary word; a "court" or "garden", i.e. (by implication, of pasture) herbage or vegetation: blade, grass, hay.
  5428. Chouzas of uncertain origin; Chuzas, an officer of Herod: Chuza.
  5429. chraomai middle voice of a primary verb (perhaps rather from cheir, to handle); to furnish what is needed; (give an oracle, "graze" (touch slightly), light upon, etc.), i.e. (by implication) to employ or (by extension) to act towards one in a given manner: entreat, use. Compare chrao; chre.
  5430. chrao probably the same as the base of chraomai; to loan: lend.
  5431. chreia from the base of chraomai or chre; employment, i.e. an affair; also (by implication) occasion, demand, requirement or destitution: business, lack, necessary(-ity), need(-ful), use, want.
  5432. chreopheiletes from a derivative of chrao and opheiletes; a loan-ower, i.e. indebted person: debtor.
  5433. chre third person singular of the same as chraomai or chrao used impersonally; it needs (must or should) be: ought.
  5434. chreizo from chreia; to make (i.e. have) necessity, i.e. be in want of: (have) need.
  5435. chrema something useful or needed, i.e. wealth, price: money, riches.
  5436. chrematizo from chrema; to utter an oracle (compare the original sense of chraomai), i.e. divinely intimate; by implication, (compare the secular sense of chreia) to constitute a firm for business, i.e. (generally) bear as a title: be called, be admonished (warned) of God, reveal, speak.
  5437. chrematismos from chrematizo; a divine response or revelation: answer of God.
  5438. chresimos from chresis; serviceable: profit.
  5439. chresis from chraomai; employment, i.e. (specially), sexual intercourse (as an occupation of the body): use.
  5440. chresteuomai middle voice from chrestos; to show oneself useful, i.e. act benevolently: be kind.
  5441. chrestologia from a compound of chrestos and lego; fair speech, i.e. plausibility: good words.
  5442. chrestos from chraomai; employed, i.e. (by implication) useful (in manner or morals): better, easy, good(-ness), gracious, kind.
  5443. chrestotes from chrestos; usefulness, i.e. morally, excellence (in character or demeanor): gentleness, good(-ness), kindness.
  5444. chrisma from chrio; an unguent or smearing, i.e. (figuratively) the special endowment ("chrism") of the Holy Spirit: anointing, unction.
  5445. Christianos from Christos; a Christian, i.e. follower of Christ: Christian.
  5446. Christos from chrio; anointed, i.e. the Messiah, an epithet of Jesus: Christ.
  5447. chrio probably akin to chraomai through the idea of contact; to smear or rub with oil, i.e. (by implication) to consecrate to an office or religious service: anoint.
  5448. chronizo from chronos; to take time, i.e. linger: delay, tarry.
  5449. chronos of uncertain derivation; a space of time (in general, and thus properly distinguished from kairos, which designates a fixed or special occasion; and from aion, which denotes a particular period) or interval; by extension, an individual opportunity; by implication, delay: + years old, season, space, (X often-)time(-s), (a) while.
  5450. chronotribeo from a presumed compound of chronos and the base of tribos; to be a time-wearer, i.e. to procrastinate (linger): spend time.
  5451. chruseos from chrusos; made of gold: of gold, golden.
  5452. chrusion diminutive of chrusos; a golden article, i.e. gold plating, ornament, or coin: gold.
  5453. chrusodaktulios from chrusos and daktulios; gold-ringed, i.e. wearing a golden finger-ring or similar jewelry: with a gold ring.
  5454. chrusolithos from chrusos and lithos; gold-stone, i.e. a yellow gem ("chrysolite"): chrysolite.
  5455. chrusoprasos from chrusos and prason (a leek); a greenish-yellow gem ("chrysoprase"): chrysoprase.
  5456. chrusos perhaps from the base of chraomai (through the idea of the utility of the metal); gold; by extension, a golden article, as an ornament or coin: gold.
  5457. chrusoo from chrusos; to gild, i.e. bespangle with golden ornaments: deck.
  5458. chros probably akin to the base of chraomai through the idea of handling; the body (properly, its surface or skin): body.
  5459. cholos apparently a primary word; "halt", i.e. limping: cripple, halt, lame.
  5460. chora feminine of a derivative of the base of chasma through the idea of empty expanse; room, i.e. a space of territory (more or less extensive; often including its inhabitants): coast, county, fields, ground, land, region. Compare topos.
  5461. choreo from chora; to be in (give) space, i.e. (intransitively) to pass, enter, or (transitively) to hold, admit (literally or figuratively): come, contain, go, have place, (can, be room to) receive.
  5462. chorizo from chora; to place room between, i.e. part; reflexively, to go away: depart, put asunder, separate.
  5463. chorion diminutive of chora; a spot or plot of ground: field, land, parcel of ground, place, possession.
  5464. choris adverb from chora; at a space, i.e. separately or apart from (often as preposition): beside, by itself, without.
  5465. choros of Latin origin; the north-west wind: north west.
  5466. psallo probably strengthened from psao (to rub or touch the surface; compare psocho); to twitch or twang, i.e. to play on a stringed instrument (celebrate the divine worship with music and accompanying odes): make melody, sing (psalms).
  5467. psalmos from psallo; a set piece of music, i.e. a sacred ode (accompanied with the voice, harp or other instrument; a "psalm"); collectively, the book of the Psalms: psalm. Compare oide.
  5468. pseudadelphos from pseudes and adephos; a spurious brother, i.e. pretended associate: false brethren.
  5469. pseudapostolos from pseudes and apostolos; a spurious apostle, i.e. pretended pracher: false teacher.
  5470. pseudes from pseudomai; untrue, i.e. erroneous, deceitful, wicked: false, liar.
  5471. pseudodidaskalos from pseudes and didaskalos; a spurious teacher, i.e. propagator of erroneous Christian doctrine: false teacher.
  5472. pseudologos from pseudes and lego; mendacious, i.e. promulgating erroneous Christian doctrine: speaking lies.
  5473. pseudomai middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to utter an untruth or attempt to deceive by falsehood: falsely, lie.
  5474. pseudomartur from pseudes and a kindred form of martus; a spurious witness, i.e. bearer of untrue testimony: false witness.
  5475. pseudomartureo from pseudomartur; to be an untrue testifier, i.e. offer falsehood in evidence: be a false witness.
  5476. pseudomarturia from pseudomartur; untrue testimony: false witness.
  5477. pseudoprophetes from pseudes and prophetes; a spurious prophet, i.e. pretended foreteller or religious impostor: false prophet.
  5478. pseudos from pseudomai; a falsehood: lie, lying.
  5479. pseudochristos from pseudes and Christos; a spurious Messiah: false Christ.
  5480. pseudonumos from pseudes and onoma; untruly named: falsely so called.
  5481. pseusma from pseudomai; a fabrication, i.e. falsehood: lie.
  5482. pseustes from pseudomai; a falsifier: liar.
  5483. pselaphao from the base of psallo (compare psephos); to manipulate, i.e. verify by contact; figuratively, to search for: feel after, handle, touch.
  5484. psephizo from psephos; to use pebbles in enumeration, i.e. (generally) to compute: count.
  5485. psephos from the same as pselaphao; a pebble (as worn smooth by handling), i.e. (by implication, of use as a counter or ballot) a verdict (of acquittal) or ticket (of admission); a vote: stone, voice.
  5486. psithurismos from a derivative of psithos (a whisper; by implication, a slander; probably akin to pseudomai); whispering, i.e. secret detraction: whispering.
  5487. psithuristes from the same as psithurismos; a secret calumniator: whisperer.
  5488. psichion diminutive from a derivative of the base of psallo (meaning a crumb); a little bit or morsel: crumb.
  5489. psuche from psucho; breath, i.e. (by implication) spirit, abstractly or concretely (the animal sentient principle only; thus distinguished on the one hand from pneuma, which is the rational and immortal soul; and on the other from zoe, which is mere vitality, even of plants: these terms thus exactly correspond respectively to the Hebrew nephesh, ruwach and chay): heart (+ -ily), life, mind, soul, + us, + you.
  5490. psuchikos from psuche; sensitive, i.e. animate (in distinction on the one hand from pneumatikos, which is the higher or renovated nature; and on the other from phusikos, which is the lower or bestial nature): natural, sensual.
  5491. psuchos from psucho; coolness: cold.
  5492. psuchros from psuchos; chilly (literally or figuratively): cold.
  5493. psucho a primary verb; to breathe (voluntarily but gently, thus differing on the one hand from pneo, which denotes properly a forcible respiration; and on the other from the base of aer, which refers properly to an inanimate breeze), i.e. (by implication, of reduction of temperature by evaporation) to chill (figuratively): wax cold.
  5494. psomizo from the base of psomion; to supply with bits, i.e. (generally) to nourish: (bestow to) feed.
  5495. psomion diminutive from a derivative of the base of psocho; a crumb or morsel (as if rubbed off), i.e. a mouthful: sop.
  5496. psocho prolongation from the same base as psallo; to triturate, i.e. (by analogy) to rub out (kernels from husks with the fingers or hand): rub.
  5497. omega the last letter of the Greek alphabet, i.e. (figuratively) the finality: Omega.
  5498. o a primary interjection; as a sign of the vocative case, O; as a note of exclamation, oh: O.
  5499. o, including the oblique forms, as well as es; e; etc. the subjunctive of eimi; (may, might, can, could, would, should, must, etc.; also with ei and its comparative, as well as with other particles) be: + appear, are, (may, might, should) be, X have, is, + pass the flower of her age, should stand, were.
  5500. Obed of Hebrew origin (`Owbed); Obed, an Israelite: Obed.
  5501. hode from an adverb form of hode; in this same spot, i.e. here or hither: here, hither, (in) this place, there.
  5502. oide from aido; a chant or "ode" (the general term for any words sung; while humnos denotes especially a religious metrical composition, and psalmos still more specially, a Hebrew cantillation): song.
  5503. odin akin to odune; a pang or throe, especially of childbirth: pain, sorrow, travail.
  5504. odino from odin; to experience the pains of parturition (literally or figuratively): travail in (birth).
  5505. omos perhaps from the alternate of phero; the shoulder (as that on which burdens are borne): shoulder.
  5506. on, including the feminine ousa; and the neuter on present participle of eimi; being: be, come, have.
  5507. oneomai middle voice from an apparently primary onos (a sum or price); to purchase (synonymous with the earlier pimpremi): buy.
  5508. oon apparently a primary word; an "egg": egg.
  5509. hora apparently a primary word; an "hour" (literally or figuratively): day, hour, instant, season, X short, (even-)tide, (high) time.
  5510. horaios from hora; belonging to the right hour or season (timely), i.e. (by implication) flourishing (beauteous (figuratively)): beautiful.
  5511. oruomai middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to "roar": roar.
  5512. hos probably adverb of comparative from hos; which how, i.e. in that manner (very variously used, as follows): about, after (that), (according) as (it had been, it were), as soon (as), even as (like), for, how (greatly), like (as, unto), since, so (that), that, to wit, unto, when(-soever), while, X with all speed.
  5513. hosanna of Hebrew origin (yasha` and na'); oh save!; hosanna (i.e. hoshia-na), an exclamation of adoration: hosanna.
  5514. hosautos from hos and an adverb from autos; as thus, i.e. in the same way: even so, likewise, after the same (in like) manner.
  5515. hosei from hos and ei; as if: about, as (it had been, it were), like (as).
  5516. Hosee of Hebrew origin (Howshea`); Hosee (i.e. Hoshea), an Israelite: Osee.
  5517. hosper from hos and per; just as, i.e. exactly like: (even, like) as.
  5518. hosperei from hosper and ei; just as if, i.e. as it were: as.
  5519. hoste from hos and te; so too, i.e. thus therefore (in various relations of consecution, as follow): (insomuch) as, so that (then), (insomuch) that, therefore, to, wherefore.
  5520. otion diminutive of ous; an earlet, i.e. one of the ears, or perhaps the lobe of the ear: ear.
  5521. opheleia from a derivative of the base of ophelimos; usefulness, i.e. benefit: advantage, profit.
  5522. opheleo from the same as opheleia; to be useful, i.e. to benefit: advantage, better, prevail, profit.
  5523. ophelimos from a form of ophelos; helpful or serviceable, i.e. advantageous: profit(-able).
